president kurt waldheim acknowledged thursday that he had considered resigning, and canceled his scheduled speech at the main ceremony on the 50th anniversary of the day adolf hitler annexed austria
he said he would address the nation on television instead. leading politicians have said a speech by waldheim, who concealed his germany army service and has been accused of war crimes, was not the way to lead national reflection on atrocities of the nazi past
the speech on march 11, the day of the nazi ``anschluss'' in 1938, was decided upon last month as a means of avoiding a political showdown over whether to invite the 69-year-old president to address a joint session of parliament on that day
during an interview late thursday on austrian state television, waldheim was asked if he had considered quitting before his term ends in 1992
naturally i thought of it,'' he said. ``otherwise i wouldn`t be a human being. i'd have to be a piece of wood.''
he again rejected the notion of resigning, which has been suggested or demanded from all political quarters
that would only make things worse,'' waldheim said, adding that he has a ``clear conscience'' about his past. he was elected in june 1986 to a six-year term
austria is governed by a coalition of the socialists, led by chancellor franz vranitzky, and the conservative people's party, which backed waldheim for president in the 1986 election. people's party leader alois mock, who is deputy chancellor and foreign minister, is among his fervent supporters
accusations arose during the presidential campaign about waldheim's service as a german army lieutenant in the balkans, and the united states put the former u.n. secretary-general on a ``watch list'' of undesirable aliens last year
in september, at waldheim's request, vranitzky's government appointed an international panel of historians to investigate his wartime activities. it concluded in a report this month that he knew atrocities were being committed in ``close proximity'' to him and did nothing to stop them, and left the question of personal guilt open
in an interview broadcast thursday evening on state radio, waldheim said he felt the president should promote reconciliation, and ``it was a result of this feeling of my duty as federal president that i took this personal initiative'' not to speak
asked whether it was ``painful'' for him to cancel the speech, waldheim responded: ``it wasn't very painful, since i will be present at the ceremony.''
waldheim's office said in a statement earlier thursday: ``in the interest of efforts aimed at a harmonious remembrance ceremony, the president will not speak at this event.'' the statement did not specify a day for the televised address, but mock said later that waldheim would deliver it on march 10, the day before the ceremony
his office said waldheim would attend the unveiling of a plaque honoring members of austria's prewar parliament who were victims of the nazis. the statement added that he hopes to promote the ``peaceful development of our nation.''
leaders of the anti-waldheim movement had said thousands of protesters would mass outside the hofburg palace, former seat of the hapsburg emperors, if waldheim spoke at the anniversary ceremony. it is to be held in the palace, which houses the presidential offices
organizers of the program, including vranitzky, met with waldheim on thursday to discuss his participation. date of burial to sunday and date he died to thursday. no pickup.</note>
former prime minister mamdouh salem died thursday in london while undergoing treatment from an undisclosed illness. he was 70
the state-run middle east news agency said salem would be given a military funeral sunday in cairo
the agency said president hosni mubarak praised salem, saying egypt would remember him for his ``nationalism, his good manners, his self-respect and sacrifices for the majority interest and good.''
salem was prime minister from 1975 to 1978. when then-foreign minister ibrahim kamel resigned in 1978 to protest the signing of the u.s.-sponsored camp david accords between egypt and israel, late president anwar sadat appointed a new government. the peace treaty was signed a year later
salem was a personal aide to sadat and to mubarak, who succeeded sadat in 1981
born in 1918 in the mediterranean port of alexandria, salem was governor of asiut, gharbiya and alexandria from 1967 to 1971, when he was appointed interior minister
a federal judge thursday upheld the national collegiate athletic association's drug-testing program, ruling against a student athlete who contended the taking of urine samples violated her privacy
u.s. district judge walter mcgovern said any violation of privacy is outweighed by the ncaa's interest in protecting students' health, reducing drug use and ensuring fair competition
the american civil liberties union, which filed the suit on behalf of university of washington runner betsy o'halloran and another athlete who later joined the case, will probably appeal, said the aclu's kathleen taylor
under ncaa rules, students must sign a consent form before the regular season begins allowing random testing
the testing does not actually occur until post-season playoff time, but students like ms. o'halloran who refuse to sign are prohibited from regular-season competition
ms. o'halloran, a cross-country and track athlete, had sued the university over its mandatory testing program, but last month uw revised its program so that screening was voluntary and required only of athletes suspected of drug use
the claim against the university was then dismissed, with the claim against the ncaa program and the university's participation in it remaining
however, uw athletes are still required to sign an ncaa consent form
ms. o'halloran had asked mcgovern to grant her a preliminary injunction allowing her to compete for the uw women's track team this spring
but mcgovern denied the request, saying any harm done to her by being barred from competition was outweighed by the potentially greater harm to the ncaa
competent athletes might use banned drugs in violation of ncaa rules, and the public interest in fair competition without the use of drugs would not be served,'' mcgovern said
ms. o'halloran has not been able to compete during the fall cross-country season and will not participate in track this spring because she will not sign the consent form, ms. taylor said
ms. taylor said the aclu was surprised by the decision, especially in light of a feb. 11 federal appeals court decision prohibiting drug testing of railway workers without specific suspicion against a particular individual
the ncaa's laudable goal of reducing drug use among student athletes must be carried out in a less degrading and intrusive manner,'' ms. taylor said
more than president hosni mubarak's efforts to bring peace to the middle east, egyptians are talking these days about shortages of cooking oil and sugar. it's angry talk
cooking oil and sugar are important items on the egyptian menu, used extensively by peasants who make up half the nation's 51 million people
cooking oil is added to beans, which are eaten at breakfast and dinner, and used to fry vegetables, especially eggplant and potatoes, the usual peasant lunch
as for sugar, egyptians consume so much in tea, pastries and candy that the health ministry has begun a television campaign in an effort to persuade people that more than six lumps a day is harmful
the shortages have been assailed in the news media and heatedly discussed in coffee shops
the subject has come up in the shura council, a government body of experts in various fields who give advice to mubarak and to the people's assembly, the national legislature
and in the people's assembly itself, prime minister atef sedki was taken to task because of his cabinet ministers had denied that the shortages exist. sedki admitted they were not being entirely candid, but he assured the assembly that egypt once again will get by
food shortages are nothing new to egypt. the country must import 60 percent of what it eats and it doesn't have the money to pay for all it needs. in addition, it increasingly has more mouths than it can feed, as the population explodes at a rate of 1 million every nine months
that coupled with stagnant food production has transformed the country from the food exporter it was three decades ago to the importer it is today. the nation, facing a foreign debt of $44 billion, doesn't have the money to pay for it all
nobody has a ready solution. increasing food production isn't easy because only about 4 percent of the country's land area, the nile river valley, is fertile, and little money is available to reclaim and cultivate the desert
egypt is among the world's biggest producers of cotton, which is the source of most cooking oil used in the country, but it must import more than 80 percent of its needs _ at a cost of $250 million a year
we import 500,000 tons of cooking oil, at the cost of $500 a ton,'' said rifaat saadawy, an official in charge of oil imports at the industry ministry
so the cooking oil crisis is connected with the foreign exchange crisis, and any shortage in foreign currency means a shortage of providing cooking oil for local consumption.''
similarily, despite expanses of sugar cane in central egypt, the country's farmers produce only about half the nation's needs, forcing imports of 700,000 tons for almost $158 million last year
a further complication is that many stable foods are distributed through expensive subsidy and ration systems. under pressure from the international monetary fund and at the urging of the united states, the government has been trying to reduce the subsidy systems' burden on the national treasury
for the past two years, it has tapered off the number of subsidized items available at government stores or purchased with ration cards from private markets. but the items taken off the list cost much more
despite the cutbacks, the government spent $2.2 billion in the 1986-87 fiscal year on subsidies for food and other items. that's only $675 million less than the subsidy bill in 1983-84 and remains much higher than levels washington and the imf want
the government does not want to eliminate or sharply reduce subsidies because it fears a recurrence of food riots in which more than 70 people were killed in 1977
for peasants like nawal mohamedein, who lives at el-faronia, 30 miles north of cairo, the system is not working
the official price of a one-kilogram (2.2-pound) bottle of oil was 80 piasters (36 cents,) but now it is not available in the shops,'' she said. ``i buy it off the black market for 3.5 pounds ($1.60) a bottle. it has limited our food to next to nothing.''
she said she now has to serve bread and cheese for the midday meal in place of the usual eggplant and potatoes
jazz legend lionel hampton announced that a $20,000 grant the national endowment for the arts is giving to a foundation under his control will be channeled to a music school named in his honor
hampton spoke wednesday to the moscow chamber of commerce while visiting the panhandle college town to headline the university of idaho's jazz festival and receive an honorary degree
i always enjoy coming out here because this is a place where high school students, college students, professional people and educators and jazz musicians can come together in a common cause to listen and improve the great art we foster,'' hampton said
dozens of the world's top jazz performers have come out of hampton's bands. but he said he has gotten the most pleasure from having the university's lionel hampton school of music named after him, which he said is ``like going to heaven.''
hampton started his career in the 1920s. when he joined benny goodman's quartet in 1936, he broke a color barrier that had kept black musicians out of american entertainment's front ranks
wheel of fortune'' host pat sajak says that just because cbs is giving him a talk show opposite nbc's ``tonight show'' doesn't mean he's taking on johnny carson
if you're going to do a late-night show, that's a fact of life, that mr. carson is going to be there. we can't worry about that. we have to worry about doing the best show we can,'' sajak said at a news conference wednesday
cbs entertainment president kim lemasters confirmed plans for the show, which he said would be 90 minutes compared with carson's hour and would debut next january
there is no attempt on our part here to compete with johnny carson,'' lemasters said. ``mr. carson is a tradition, he is much-beloved and a brilliant performer in what he does, and that's not our aim. our aim is that the environment in late night can stand more than just one talk-show format.''
sajak will continue indefinitely as host of the nighttime version of ``wheel of fortune,'' the nation's no. 1 syndicated show. his contract for the nbc daytime version of the show expires in december
rock singer alice cooper returned to his hometown for a weekend concert and mentioned that he also will be running for governor _ on the wild party ticket
more than 80 people already have entered the special may 17 election prompted by a recall petition campaign against impeached gov. evan mecham. cooper, who says he bought his first automobile from mecham's pontiac dealership in nearby glendale, said he will join the throng seeking to unseat the conservative republican
i'm definitely a write-in candidate,'' cooper said wednesday. ``hey, i'm a native. i'm a registered voter. i represent the wild party and i even have a campaign slogan: `alice cooper _ a troubled man for troubled times.'''
cooper, 39, was born vincent furnier, a minister's son. he gained fame with outrageous makeup and such hits as ``school's out.'' his phoenix concert saturday night is scheduled to end the american leg of a year-long comeback tour
hugh hefner's former live-in girlfriend upped the ante in her ``palimony'' suit against the playboy magazine publisher, saying she now wants $35 million to prevent him from ruining other young lives
celebrity divorce lawyer marvin mitchelson filed an amended complaint wednesday for carrie leigh adding fraud and deceit to her previous accusations that hefner abandoned promises to support and father her child
hefner attorney anthony michael glassman said the fraud and deceit claims were unfounded. he called the lawsuit revision a publicity stunt
miss leigh's suit now seeks $20 million in punitive damages ``to dissuade him from maintaining his long-enjoyed practice of seducing teen-age girls, supporting them for a few years and then discarding them.''
the initial complaint filed feb. 11 in superior court sought an estimated $5 million-plus, but the amendment adds the punitive amount and says lost career earnings and benefits amount to $15 million. miss leigh, 24, claims she gave up a modeling career in 1983 to serve as a companion at the playboy mansion to hefner, 61
mitchelson said the relationship ended with the arrival at the mansion of jessica hahn, whose sexual encounter with ptl minister jim bakker led to the evangelist's fall from grace
a pickup truck driver who crashed through the front gate of sean penn's and madonna's home was placed on three years' probation and ordered to pay the couple $3,000 for damages
steven stillbower, 33, of anaheim, pleaded no contest wednesday to misdemeanor counts of vandalism and peeking into the window of the celebrity couple's home
in addition to placing him on probation and ordering restitution to actor penn and his pop singer wife, municipal court judge lawrence mira fined stillbower $2,000
after stillbower crashed his pickup truck jan. 7, penn placed him under citizen's arrest. state law permits a person to make a citizen's arrest for a misdemeanor committed in his presence
the government's ban on political activity by opposition organizations was the most extensive crackdown in 10 years. here is a chronology of previous efforts to restrict political opposition:
1955 _ a national peoples congress was broken up and 156 black leaders, including nelson mandela of the african national congress , and pan-africanist congress leader zeph mothopeng were charged with treason. all were acquitted after lengthy trials
march 21, 1960 _ the anc and pac called for peaceful protests against laws requiring blacks to have passes to enter white areas. police gunfire killed 69 blacks at a rally in the sharpeville township
march 30, 1960 _ national state of emergency was declared, granting police wide powers to prohibit gatherings, search people and premises, and resort to force. new powers of detention without trial were introduced and after the emergency ended, many of the new powers became law
april 1960 _ parliament outlawed the anc and pac
1961-62 _ anc and pac military wings were formed and a sabotage campaign began
aug. 5, 1962 _ nelson mandela was arrested and, in 1964, sentenced to life in prison for treason and sabotage
june 16, 1976 _ an estimated 13,000 black students demonstrated in soweto to protest a requirement that lessons be taught in the afrikaans language. police killed several students, touching off riots and boycotts that sweep south africa for more than a year, claiming 575 lives by official count
sept. 12, 1977 _ steve biko, founder of the black consciousness movement, died in police detention
oct. 19, 1977 _ government banned 18 organizations plus the two largest black newspapers, and detained 47 black leaders
may 1978 _ the azanian people organization was formed to replace the black consciousness organizations banned after biko's death
aug. 20, 1983 _ the united democratic front was launched to organize opposition to a planned tri-cameral parliament including representation for all race groups except the black majority. over the next four years, the udf became the largest legal anti-apartheid group
september 1983 _ riots broke out in sharpeville, touching off three years of widespread violence claiming 2,500 black lives
feb. 19, 1985 _ police began arresting udf leaders on treason charges. more than 22 were arrested
july 20, 1985 _ president p.w. botha declared a state of emergency in 36 black cities and towns, the first such declaration since 1960. the emergency decrees covered about half the country. in the first week, 1,000 activists were detained
december 1985 _ the congress of south african trade unions was formed to consolidate labor and political activity of black unions
march 7, 1986 _ the government lifted the state of emergency, saying conditions have improved
june 4, 1986 _ the government banned all meetings related to 10th anniversary of soweto riots
june 12, 1986 _ more than 1,000 anti-apartheid activists were detained in pre-dawn raids. botha imposed a nationwide state of emergency, with broad press curbs, wide powers for police and restrictions on many forms of protests and statements. an estimated 30,000 people were detained
oct. 9, 1986 _ government banned the udf from receiving funds from outside the country
nov. 7, 1986 _ new orders were issued restricting activities of white opponents, prohibiting them from participating in certain organizations, publishing statements or attending rallies
december 1986 _ the press was banned from reporting many anti-government statements or being within sight of protest activity
may 6, 1987 _ the headquarters of congress of south african trade unions was blown up on election day. the conservative party made big gains, becoming the official parliamentary opposition on campaign against any apartheid reform
august 1987 _ national union of mineworkers, cosatu affiliate, staged the most costly strike in country's history
aug. 27, 1987 _ new curbs were announced to suppress anti-government press, by threatening shutdown or in-house censors. seven newspapers were warned about articles government considers objectionable
october 1987 _ universities were told that funds will be cut if they don't stop campus protests. anc leader govan mbeki was released after 24 years in prison
december 1987 _ the government restricted mbeki to port elizabeth, banning him from talking to press or addressing rallies
feb. 24, 1988 _ the government banned political activity of 18 organizations, including cosatu, udf and azapo. ams moved.</note>
laszlo g. versenyi, a williams college philosophy professor called ``a reincarnation of socrates'' by secretary of education william bennett, died tuesday of cancer at age 59
versenyi began teaching at williams in 1958 and received numerous academic awards, including a senior fellowship from the national endowment for the humanities in 1970 and grants from the american council of learned societies
he wrote numerous articles and four books on philosophy and ancient greek thought, and used the socratic method of questioning and logic in his freshman classes. in addition to greek philosophy, versenyi also taught courses on 20th century german existentialist martin heidegger
charles l. banks, a retired marine brigadier general and winner of medals of valor in two wars, died monday of cancer. he was 73
banks became a marine corps officer after graduating from the virginia military institute in 1936 and fought with edson's raiders on guadalcanal early in world war ii. he received the navy cross for his actions in the marine breakout at chosin reservoir in korea. upon his 1959 retirement banks also received two legions of merit and the silver star. rockies</head>
a quake stronger than the oct. 1 temblor that caused severe damage in los angeles is likely to occur east of the rockies in the next two decades, so buildings in the area should be fortified, experts said
the prediction is based on the history and geology of the region, said robert ketter, director of the national center for earthquake engineering research at the state university of new york at buffalo
the california quake, which killed eight people and measured 5.9 on the richter scale, left an estimated $358 million in destruction in the los angeles area, damaging more than 10,400 buildings and leaving about 2,200 people homeless
i feel comfortable there will be a magnitude of 6 or higher within the next 20 years'' somewhere in the united states east of the rocky mountain foothills, said ketter
ketter, who called the california quake relatively modest, spoke wednesday during a break in a conference on earthquake hazards and construction design in the united states east of the rockies
despite the low probability of a serious quake in any one place east of the rockies, the region's relatively dense population and older buildings make for a ``very serious problem'' in risk from earthquakes, he said
robert whitman, a civil engineering professor at the massachusetts institute of technology, called ketter's prediction reasonable
the last major quake east of the rockies struck charleston, s.c., in 1886, reaching an estimated richter reading of 7 and making itself felt as far away as chicago, conference organizers say. other damaging quakes hit new york city in 1884, anna, ohio, in 1937, western tennessee in 1843 and giles county, va., in 1897
the most severe earthquakes in the nation's history struck new madrid, mo., in 1811 and 1812, ketter said. having an estimated magnitude of 8.3 to 8.5 on the richter scale, the quakes were strong enough to ring church bells in washington, d.c., ketter said
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs
an earthquake of magnitude 3.5 can cause slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6 severe damage. a 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage
the san francisco earthquake of 1906, which occurred before the richter scale was devised, has been estimated at 8.3 on the richter scale
earthquakes east of the rockies result from pressure exerted by the floor of the atlantic ocean acting on geological areas of weakness, speakers at the conference said. because of geology, ketter said, an earthquake of a given strength can shake an area 100 times larger in this region than on the west coast
we cannot rule out the possibility of a very large earthquake occuring practically anywhere'' in the region, said whitman, who called on architects and engineers to encourage earthquake-resistant construction
cities and states should adopt the earthquake provisions of model building codes, he said. studies suggest that quake-resistant designs add only about 1 percent to the cost of most new buildings, he said
the more important challenge is what should be done to make existing buildings more quake-resistant, he said. while it would be politically difficult to require upgrading to meet the standards of new construction, he said, steps short of that would be acceptable
substantial upgradings of masonry buildings have been done for $5 to $6 per square foot in los angeles and $5 to $10 per square foot elsewhere, he said. for buildings with other types of construction, upgrading can cost $10 to $20 per square foot, he said
the conference is sponsored by ketter's institute and the new york academy of sciences, and co-sponsored by the national science foundation and the earthquake engineering research institute, a professional society for earthquake engineering
robert packwood, u.s. senator and fugitive from a quorum call, thought he was safe, hiding behind a locked door in his senate office
but henry giugni, senate sergeant-at-arms and former vice and motorcycle cop, knew he would get his man
i had to take him in,'' he explained
i thoughti was safe,'' packwood recalled. ``but it's the little things that trip you up.''
it was as unlikely a scene _ and a night _ as could be recalled by senate historians, parliamentarians and press corps observers
it was the night, as sen. john kerry, d-mass., put it, where ``the entire republican party in the united states senate ... vanished into the night.''
it was the night senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., wanted to keep the senate in session through dawn's early light to draw attention to a republican filibuster that previously had been quietly played out during daytime hours off and on over many months
if the republicans didn't want a vote on a campaign finance bill, they would have to keep talking. republicans didn't want to keep talking, so they attempted to keep a quorum off the senate floor, forcing the senate to quit for the night
they huddled in the cloakroom outside the chamber
then byrd got tough. he asked for a vote directing the sergeant-at-arms to ``reques attendance of absent senators.''
the republicans were so requested
but they stayed behind the cloakroom door
byrd upped the ante
he asked that the senate approve a motion to instruct the sergeant-at-arms to ``arrest the absent senators and bring them to the chamber.''
with 45 democratic votes, the motion carried
and the chase was on
kerry said the sergeant-at-arms' orders resulted in ``a lot of senators running off into the corridors at night,'' chased by giugni and a team of five plainclothes detectives
giugni spotted idaho republicans steve symms and james mcclure down in a basement corridor where symms has a ``hideaway'' office
at about the same moment, symms and mcclure spotted the sergeant-at-arms
we took off. henry was alone,'' symms said. he fled down the corridor
i didn't want to be the first one caught,'' he said
mcclure's press secretary, h.d. palmer, said his boss ``blew out of there. he was a fugitive from bobby byrd's chain gang.''
giugni's position was a tough one. he works for the senators in a capitol where senators' wishes are law. ``i had to do my job ... i had a list. i went into the hideaways, then the russell building'' where some senators have their offices
giugni got lucky
packwood had just holed up in his office. ``i thought i was safe, i had been forewarned by my staff that henry was going around looking,'' packwood recalled. after all, he was locked behind a bolted door, and senators locked behind bolted doors in their well-guarded office buildings are usually very, very safe
packwood forgot the cleaning lady had seen him enter his office
and giugni, five years on the honolulu police force under his ample belt, remembered to ask
moments later, giugni and his gang of five, armed with a passkey, threw themselves at another door as the oregon senator was trying to slam and bolt it shut
there were three of them on one side. their mass beat my mass,'' packwood said
giugni was diplomatic. ``it was a misunderstanding. i thought we were helping him open the door,'' he later joked, packwood at his side
the senator was hauled out of his office, across the capitol, put in an elevator, and, finally, physically picked up and deposited feet first into the senate chamber
once there, giugni had his man and the senate had its reluctant quorum of 51 senators
the arrest warrant carried with it indignities, but no penalties
but packwood wasn't taking any chances
i'm asking gerald ford for a pardon.''
the chairman of president reagan's aids commission is drawing praise from one of the administration's more vocal congressional critics for his first round of recommendations on combating the deadly disease
the praise came after retired navy adm. james d. watkins, promoted to the helm of the struggling commission last september, said wednesday the federal government should spend an additional $1 billion a year to fight aids among intravenous drug abusers alone
approval of such an ambitious undertaking would virtually double the $1.3 billion reagan has requested for all public health service spending on aids in fiscal 1989 _ including research and prevention measures aimed at the entire population
admiral watkins has compiled a first-rate set of recommendations that begin to deal with the aids epidemic responsibly and in detail,'' said rep. henry a. waxman, d-calif., who has been frequent critic of the administration during his health subcommittee's 19 hearings on aids
i hope that president reagan will attend to these recommendations of his commission and will amend his budget and come to the congress to support them and the spending they require,''' said waxman
watkins, who said he was making his recommendations to the full commission public at the same time he sent them to the white house, acknowledged that his call for sharply higher federal spending might be less than well received at the office of management and budget
but he said there is no doubt aids is spreading most rapidly among the nation's estimated 1.3 million intravenous drug abusers, and their sexual partners, and that efforts to stem the disease must concentrate on them
he expessed confidence the commission will adopt his recommendations _ which also call on state and local governments to increase their drug program spending by about $1 billion a year _ and formally pass them to the white house in early march
it is not in our charter to worry about the political impact,'' said watkins
a final report is due at the white house june 24 and watkins promised it will get into such controversial areas as aids testing. the panel would be ``at loggerheads with ourselves'' if it tried to deal with them without further testimony and deliberation, he said
watkins also made a number of recommendations in the health care area, including more training for doctors and federal backing for home care for dying aids patients who may not require full-time hospitalization
many physicians are severely lacking in knowledge about aids and there are signs that medical schools have not yet built up a curriculum to educate doctors about aids treatment,'' watkins said
he also cited a growing nursing shortage, saying an additional 500,000 nurses will be needed throughout the health care system by 1991
the report called for more financial support for the food and drug administration as well
asked his reaction to the possibility of presidential candidates, particularly democrats, using his recommendations to ``zing the white house'' for not doing more earlier, watkins replied:
how do you avoid politicizing something in an election year? if they all adopt this and say `let's get on with it,' that's the kind of politicization i like.''
