and if you'll remember, back in those days, almost every other day there was speculation that the health of the khomeini was failing to where there might be this contest for a new government
their objection was _ what we had done _ we'd gotten this request and in dealing with it, in this conversation with these private individuals _ we pointed out our feelings about terrorism and so forth
they agreed with us
and the thing was that they _ the hezbollah, as we know, is philosophically attuned to iran
the idea was that they could perhaps influence the hezbollah to give up some of our hostages
and indeed, as the talks went on, they did
we got two of them free
but their objection was that if and when this became known, as it would be, it would be made to appear that we were trading hostages for _ or arms for hostages
now, we were _ we were getting these arms to these individuals because we felt that maybe they could influence the hezbollah
we weren't dealing with the kidnappers at all
and this was what the whole situation was
but it turned out that george and cap, and those who had doubts, were right in that when it did become known, by way of a henchman of the ayatollah, then everyone just automatically said that _ and to this day are saying it was arms for hostages
q. on the issue of george bush and his role though, this has become one of the major issues between the vice president and senator dole. now, although you have to remain neutral, as the author of the 11th commandment, thou shalt not criticize one's fellow republicans, do you have any advice for these two men, and aren't you getting a little concerned that they might be hurting the republican chances by their very bitter political feud?
a. well, whether i am concerned or not, i am not going to comment on things like that
i am going to say that they know my feelings, all of them, about the 11th commandment
q. no advice at all to them?
a. jerry
q. mr. president, the resignation of secretary of the navy webb has ignited a controversy about the _ your build-up of the united states navy. and the question is, are you satisfied with the budget cuts in the military have not damaged our national security, and are you still committed to a 600-ship navy at a time when the soviets are not cutting their navy?
q. i am committed to the 600-ship navy, and i want you to know, jerry, that from the very beginning since i've been here, the congress has cut my request for defense every time
and sometimes, they have tried to pretend that that is in an effort to reduce the deficit spending and so forth
but in a five-year period, the congress cut my defense budgets a total of $125 billion at the same time that they increased my request for domestic programs by $250 billion
and this _ this budget which is now being attributed to me _ no, this isn't as low as they originally wanted to cut it
but it was as high as we could get it in the negotiations for the present budget
and it has been harmful, but let me tell you that in 1980 when we came here, the navy had 479 vessels. and by 1987, we had 568. and by next year it will be 580
and so what has happened is that there will be a little delay in the achieving of the 600-ship navy
but i can't help but remind, or tell all of you _ when i was campaigning in 1980 and knew the state of our defenses, i was faced with a question _ and some of you will recall _ i did a lot of campaigning on question-and-answer basis
at almost every gathering, there would be a question _ well, if i came to a choice between deficit spending and build-up of our defense structure, which would i choose?
and every time, i said, in responsibility, i would have to choose the build-up of our defenses
and every time, in every audience in america that i said that to, gave me an applause that was almost an ovation for saying that
q. the second part of the question was, is it a threat to the national security that the navy is not going to have 600 ships _ on the schedule that you had in mind?
a. i don't think right at the moment, and with the way we're progressing in various treaties and so forth, i don't believe that the threat is that immediate
and _ but because very shortly, we will achieve our 600
we want 15 carriers and their squadrons, and we've just launched the 15th carrier, 100 nuclear-powered attack submarines and four battleships, and we're achieving them
q. mr. president, you must certify by march 1 whether panama has been cracking down on drug trafficking through that country, or whether aid to panama should be continued to be suspended. what are you going to do?
a. well, i can't give you the answer yet because we're still working on that and still collecting the facts as to what their effort has been at trying to intercept the drugs and join us in that campaign
but, as you said, march 1 we will be giving the answer
q. sir, if i could follow up, some officials in your administration have suggested that if noriega would step down and go into exile, that you would stop the prosecution of him on drug charges. would you consider that kind of deal?
a. no, and i'm not going to comment on something of this kind
this man has been indicted by a federal grand jury, and so i'm not going to make any comment of that kind, nor have we made any advances or suggestions of that kind to the government of panama
what we would like to see is a return to democracy and a civilian government in panama, and not this domination by literally a military dictator
q. mr. president, federal reserve chairman alan greenspan today objected to pressure from the administration regarding the formulation of monetary policy, such as contained in the budget and the economic report and a treasury letter to federal reserve board members. don't you have confidence in your appointee to the fed, alan greenspan, as chairman?
a. yes, i do, and i'm going to have to find out what this is all about that you're talking about. because nothing of that kind had been directed to me
q. mr. president, back to the contra aid question _ in your opening statement you seemed to suggest that the sandinistas are taking advantage of congress not coming through with contra aid to withdraw some of the concessions that had made. with congress about to consider new humanitarian aid, both the democratic and republican plan, is it worth it to pass humanitarian aid without military aid?
a. well, i think the only comment that i can make there is that anything that will keep the freedom fighters as a pressure on the sandinistas is worth doing
just as when we tried to pass our own bill and narrowly failed, you could see that the military aid was down the road a ways _ it was not necessary right now
the other aid _ humanitarian aid _ is more imminent
and so, if we'll _ if we can get that, that's fine, and then we'll take our chances on the other in trying to get it
but they do still have some military store for a limited period of time
q. if i may follow up on that point, sir, in the two plans that are being considered, the democrats want the defense department to deliver whatever stores and supplies are authorized. the republican plan would give that responsibility to the cia. do you favor either course?
a. i certainly would favor the cia
i think that involving our military when there is no need to is very rash and foolish because you would be putting our military into a combat situation and this is what we've been trying to avoid in central america all the way
q. in that regard, mr. president, i'd like to ask you about the latest hostage situation. do you think it was responsible for your administration to allow a marine lieutenant colonel, william higgins, to operate in southern lebanon at a time when eight americans were already being held in that country and when your own state department was recommending against travel there _ and, considering the ramifications of the abduction of william buckley earlier?
a. i don't think that you can use that as a measure of where officers can be assigned to duty
they're in a dangerous business to begin with, and this _ we are a part of the united nations and we have obligations to the u.n. with regard to the unifil force that has been there for a number of years now, and this particular officer happened to volunteer when there was a vacancy at that spot _ volunteered for that
and i think we have to have the confidence _ and i do have the confidence in men like him that someone would have a hard time getting secrets that could harm this country from a person of that kind
q. mr. president?
a. no, i was _
q. mr. president, to follow up on bill's question earlier, democratic national chairman paul kirk this morning called your administration the sleaziest and most corrupt in recent american history. even if you have full confidence in people like ed meese, that they will be cleared, do you have any concern that all these charges and all these investigations are going to be used effectively by the democrats against all the republican candidates in 1988?
a. i don't know whether they're going to be used effectively or not
i know they're going to be used; they have been for quite some considerable time now
as a matter of fact, if anyone listened for more than 15 minutes to their candidates, he would decide that we're in an economic slump, we're burdened by inflation, high interest rates and unemployment, when, at the moment, none of those things are true
and we have a higher percentage of our potential employee pool employed than ever in our history, and are continuing the longest expansion, economic expansion in our history
and tomorrow morning, i think you'll find a little good news, along about 8:30 a.m. tomorrow morning, is going to be released with regard to the economy
so i just think that, you know, the kids will play _ (laughter) _ and as long as they want to do that, but i hope it'll easily be forgotten
q. mr. president, the budget that you have proposed to congress would cut _ would eliminate three housing programs for the homeless. it would make deep cuts in an emergency food program, and it would end a job training program for the homeless. do you believe that the problem of the homeless is less pressing now than just a year ago when you signed legislation from congress to create these programs?
a. no, but i do know that we're doing a great many things and we also are keeping track of the extent to which the private sector is joining in and helping on this, and this budget is the result of long, long weeks of negotiation with the democrats and ourselves, and i think that we're meeting the problems
again, i also have to say this _ that sometimes, our budget in programs can reflect another program we've had going, which is a management program, and we have had a team for a considerable period of time now that has been actually investigating the management practices of government programs as compared to the way they're done in the private sector
and there are millions and millions of dollars that are being saved so that something that maybe looks smaller does not mean that the people in need are going to get less, it means that we're able to provide that with less administrative overhead
when i came here from a governorship, as a governor, i had seen federal programs administered in our state in which it was costing the federal government $2 for every dollar that reached a needy person
this is something we've been trying to change, and we've made some progress in it
q. mr. president, just to follow up on the budget, the chairman of your council of economic advisers told us last week that the deficit might have a good side if it forces your successor and congress to make choices in social programs _ do you _ is that _ do you see a good side to the deficit?
a. i have said that i think that there is a great reform that is needed throughout many of those programs, and it is a reform to where we can get these programs to where their goal will be to remove people from dependency and make them independent of government help instead of doing what we've been doing for too many years now, and that is, actually involving them in dependency to the place where they never can get out _ we've made them permanently dependent on government _ and we're trying to change that, correct that
q. thank you
a. thank you, helen. i'm going to run for it now
president reagan says the nicaraguan government, emboldened by house rejection of more aid to the contra rebels, now appears determined to ``crush its opposition and threaten its neighbors.''
at a news conference wednesday night, reagan said the house rejection of his $36.2 million contra aid proposal removed the pressure on the sandinistas and encouraged them to reject a cease-fire proposal offered by a mediator during peace talks in guatemala city
in addition, he said that while congress was voting to withdraw support from the contras, the soviets have doubled military aid to the sandinistas this year compared with a comparable period in 1987
the nicaraguan embassy took immediate exception to reagan's allegation that the sadninstas had rebuffed the cease-fire proposal. it maintained the government had ``responded positively to the proposal, saying that it was constructive and that it had several points we could work with.''
reagan ``misstated the truth,'' said embassy spokeswoman sarali porta, accusing the administration of harboring ``a commitment to prevent the achievement of a cease-fire.''
reagan spoke shortly after rep. tony coelho, d-calif., disclosed that a vote on a ``humanitarian'' aid package for the contras, originally scheduled for today, will be postponed until next week
he said house members had asked for a delay to allow them more time to evaluate a democratic plan and a rival republican proposal
the $30.5 million democratic package included $14.6 million for food, clothing, medicine and shelter for the rebels and a like amount for medical aid for children who are victims of nicaragua's seven-year civil war
the plan's author, rep. david bonior, d-mich., said it had the tacit approval of costa rican president oscar arias, author of a central america peace initiative. coelho predicted victory for the proposal by a comfortable margin
republicans criticized the democratic plan as too weak to keep the rebels alive as a fighting force. they proposed an alternative that would keep the cia in business as the delivery agent for the aid, and give reagan a chance to trigger a guaranteed vote on further military help for the rebels sometime after may 1
the democratic plan would put responsibility for delivery of the aid in the hands of the defense department, which would presumably enlist private contractors to continue air drops to the rebels similar to those now supervised by the cia. it would bar any delivery of weapons
at his news conference, reagan expressed a strong opposition to direct deliveries by the u.s. military
you would be putting our military into a combat situation and this is what we've been trying to avoid in central america all the way,'' he said
the cease-fire proposal reagan said the sandinistas had rejected called for the contras to accept a truce in exchange for four major political concessions by the government, including unrestricted press freedom and a total, unconditional amnesty
it was not clear why reagan had said the sandinistas had rejected the proposal. on monday, the state department stopped short of making that accusation, saying only that a sandinista delay in responding to the proposal had prompted the mediator, cardinal miguel obando y bravo, to suspend the talks
on saturday, nicaraguan president daniel ortega had said the cardinal's proposal ``was not rejected.''
here are highlights of president reagan's news conference wednesday night, his first in four months:
reagan asked again for aid to the contra rebels fighting the nicaraguan government. he said the soviet union had doubled military assistance for the leftist regime in the first two months of this year over 1987 levels but provided no figures or other substantiation
the president criticized the democrats for what he called their gloom and doom statements about the economy. ``at the moment none of those things are true,'' he said
reagan said ``we've never let up and we never will'' in efforts to win freedom for american hostages in lebanon. he said if republican presidential contender pat robertson knew anything of their whereabouts, as robertson insisted he once did, it was ``very strange'' that ``he kept it to himself.''
the president confirmed anew that vice president george bush expressed reservations during the iran-contra affair, but he refused to say precisely what bush had told him
reagan said he had ``every confidence'' in the personal integrity of embattled attorney general edwin meese iii but could not comment on reports of the investigation of meese's role in a proposed middle east oil pipeline
he refused to criticize israeli action against arab protesters on the occupied west bank and gaza strip. he said he hoped israelis and arabs would ``rid themselves of old ideas and stances that cannot work'' and begin serious peace negotiations
the president said he had not decided whether to tell congress that aid should be resumed to panama. he has to certify that panama is helping in anti-drug efforts. gen. manuel noriega, panama's military leader, has been indicted on u.s. drug-trafficking charges
the effort by secretary of state george p. shultz to revive america's middle east peace campaign has been greeted by a chorus of skepticism and scorn from arab commentators
a successful visit could trigger a final effort by the outgoing reagan administration to champion arab-israeli peace talks
but shultz's tour, which begins today, seems just as likely to inflame israeli-palestinian violence in the occupied lands, where leaflets distributed last weekend called for massive protests against shultz
rarely in recent years has a ranking u.s. official on a middle east peace mission faced such universal public skepticism in the government-influenced arab press
these trips will bring no results,'' said egyptian columnist moussa sabry, who is close to president hosni mubarak
syria's state-run damascus radio branded shultz's visit ``nothing but a political airlift to rescue israel and gain time.''
an editorial in the english-language jordan times said the u.s. mission has been ``greeted throughout the middle east with a combination of skepticism and laughs.''
government officials in pro-western egypt and jordan welcomed the renewed u.s. interest in middle east peace, spurred by 11 weeks of israeli-palestinian clashes in which more than 60 palestinians have been killed
but jordan's king hussein, increasingly disillusioned with american policy over the last two years, has not announced plans to meet shultz in amman
however, the two could meet in london next week on shultz's way back to washington. hussein is considered indispensable to any u.s. plan to end the 40-year-old arab-israeli conflict
arab leaders generally have become increasingly despondent about u.s. efforts following the failure of a string of american missions to the region in the last decade
mubarak warned that the u.s. proposals ``must stay away from any words or provisions that were in the camp david agreements'' signed by egypt, israel and the united states in 1978
hard-line arab states have made it clear they oppose any partial solutions, such as those the americans have in mind
the u.s. suggestions leaked so far resemble a juiced-up camp david: a period of limited self-government for palestinians in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip followed by talks on a final settlement
the arab world is exhilarated by what palestinians call ``the uprising'' and palestinians are in no mood to compromise on their demand for some form of statehood _ a status no formal american or israeli plan has conceded
the essential quality of the national rights of the palestinians ... is not up for bargaining, negotiations or compromise,'' wrote jordan times editor rami khouri
the americans have not formally announced their ideas, but what is known so far leaves some room for negotiation
there is no word of conditions for talks on a final settlement, supposed to start by december. u.s. officials have not defined the international conference they say could launch arab-israeli talks in april
arab states insist on a conference attended by all parties to the conflict, as well as the five permanent members of the u.n. security council, and talks aimed at a final _ not interim _ solution
but shultz's ability to compromise is limited by washington's ally, israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who resists calls to accelerate the camp david process or to surrender the occupied territories, a universal arab demand
the palestinian unrest has reasserted the palestine liberation organization's role as their spokesman, damaging u.s. and israeli efforts to find ``alternative'' palestinian leaders to talk with
the growth in plo prestige occurs just as the united states is trying to defy the united nations by forcing closure of the plo mission to the world body in new york
the plo returned the american snubs by ordering palestinians in the west bank and gaza strip to boycott the shultz visit, threatening to rob shultz of contact with the people at the heart of the conflict
the plo's increased strength, coupled with washington's refusal to meet with it, bolsters the middle east role of the soviet union, a staunch backer of the organization
at the same time, the shift of the conflict to one between israelis and palestinians has moved america's main arab friends, egypt and jordan, a few steps toward the sidelines
the result makes it more difficult for the americans and israelis to prevent the soviets from taking a role in any peace talks, something the united states has accepted grudgingly and shamir still rejects
john rice has covered middle east affairs since 1984 as the ap's correspondent in amman
new screening techniques to further safeguard blood donations from the aids virus are being studied by the american association of blood banks
the aabb announced wednesday that the new study was prompted by reports that ``have raised concerns about the safety of blood transfusions administered to over 4 million people in the united states annually.''
a study published feb. 25 in the new england journal of medicine traced 13 units of blood infected by the aids virus back to seven people who donated blood even though they had been recently exposed to the virus
blood banks and hospitals routinely test donated blood for the human immune virus which causes aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome. but the hiv tests are able only to detect antibodies which may not develop until long after the exposure to the virus. the aabb said wednesday its study will test for the hiv antigen, a marker that may appear in the blood of an infected person before the antibodies
the results of this study will determine if an antigen test would be useful in detecting individuals in early stages of infection who donate blood,'' the statement said. it added that no tests for the antigen have yet been licensed
dr. paul j. schmidt, the aabb president, said current tests are ``nearly'' 99 percent sensitive, but do not detect people recently exposed to hiv
we expected that there would be some infection developing in transfusion recipients,'' he said. ``we are working on solutions to the problem of detecting persons even earlier in this infectious state, and on how to discourage them from donating blood.''
schmidt added: ``the risk from not getting a needed transfusion is infinitely greater than the risk of getting one.''
aids is a fatal disease that is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from infected pregnant women to their offspring
the federal centers for disease control estimates that at least 1,350 americans have been infected by the aids virus from transfusions of blood or blood products since 1981. about 900 patients have died
a rigorous blood-screen program now has reduced the presence of the virus in blood supplies to an estimated one unit in 50,000
as of feb. 15, aids had been diagnosed in 53,814 americans, of whom more than half, 30,158, have died, according to the cdc. no one is known to have recovered from aids
aids kills by destroying the immune system, leaving patients susceptible to a host of opportunistic infections
blood banks now screen donor candidates for aids risk factors, but the aabb said it would review these procedures to determine if they should be tightened
the aabb is the world's largest organization of blood banks and transfusion services, with 2,500 members. it accredits blood banks and transfusion services and sets standards for agencies collecting nearly half the nation's donated blood
people often grow overweight because their fuel efficient bodies are better at storing up fat than burning off calories, not because they are gluttonous slobs, according to research published today
the studies provide scientific backing for an obvious fact of life for many overweight people: they simply need less food than their svelte friends
overeating certainly may contribute to obesity, but the two reports in the new england journal of medicine demonstrate that people's metabolisms also play a crucial role
in one of the studies, researchers found that fat babies _ all of whom had overweight mothers _ were already expending less energy than other infants when they were just 3 months old
the other found that grownups with slow metabolisms put on weight much more quickly than do other people
previous studies have shown that fat people often use up relatively low amounts of calories when resting. but it was unclear whether their metabolism was low because they are fat, or whether they were they fat because their metabolism was low
the new work suggests that low metabolism causes obesity, not the other way around
it means that some people have to eat less than others to maintain their weight. it's like they always said, but nobody ever believed,'' said dr. clifton bogardus of the national institutes of health
he said he hopes the research will help convince doctors that ``everyone who is fat isn't that way just because they are gluttonous slobs. they have something wrong.''
bogardus of phoenix, ariz., was a co-author of the adult study, conducted on 221 pima indians, who have a high rate of obesity. the researchers measured their subjects' energy expenditure while resting and while living for 24 hours in a small room
they found that those whose 24-hour energy expenditure was low were four times more likely than those with high metabolisms to gain at least 17 pounds during the following two years. they also found that low and high metabolisms tend to run in families
in the infant study, doctors studied six babies who were born to lean mothers and 12 born to overweight women. they used a newly developed urine test called the doubly labeled water method to measure the infants' energy expenditure while living at home
at 3 months, all of the babies were normal sized. but by age 1, six of the fat mothers' babies had become overweight. total energy expenditure at 3 months was 21 percent lower in the infants who later became fat
the researchers theorize that these babies have an inherited tendency to be fat. their bodies have a high ``set point,'' or weight goal. they try to reach this point by taking in more energy or using up less
the study's director, dr. susan b. roberts of massachusetts institute of technology, said she believes that the fat babies ate no more than the normal ones. they therefore put on weight to reach their set point by being less active
that would be a logical thing to do in small infants, because their food intake is largely controlled by their mothers, so they didn't have the option of going to the fridge and having another sandwich,'' she said. ``but in adults, who have the option of going to the fridge, high food intake may also contribute to the maintenance of being overweight.''
dr. william i. bennett, a diet expert at harvard medical school, said, ``what's being shown here is that there is some broad pattern of vulnerability to weight gain. they are starting to get awfully close to showing that there is a set of genes'' that controls obesity
the government has been overcharged more than $1 billion for development of the stealth bomber, according to a lawsuit against northrop corp., the company building the secret plane
the lawsuit was filed wednesday in u.s. district court here on behalf of four current and former northrop employees who could collect part of any damages awarded to the government if the suit were successful
the lawsuit, which was sealed under procedures followed in such cases, accuses northrop of double-billing, false billing and misrepresented charges, said robert kilborne, the attorney representing the employees
northrop spokesman tony cantafio refused comment, citing a company policy against responding publicly to lawsuits
the air force office of special investitations has launched its own investigation into the allegations, a standard step in such cases, said maj. kathleen mccollom, a spokeswoman for the office
kilborne refused to reveal the names of his clients, identifying them only as an internal auditor, a former controller, a former avionics engineer and a former test equipment engineer
the lawsuit alleges that northrop destroyed internal audits that turned up evidence of improper charges on development of the bomber
the plane, dubbed stealth because it is designed to be difficult to detect on enemy radar, is under development at the company's plants in pico rivera and palmdale
the audit documented $400 million in overcharges and estimated those charges amounted to $1 billion by 1987, kilborne said
the los angeles times reported in today's editions the overcharges alleged in the lawsuit amount to more than $2 billion
the lawsuit was brought under the federal false claims act, which allows citizens to sue on behalf of the government and share in any damage award. the justice department must join in the suit for it to go forward, and the suit remains sealed up to 60 days while that decision is made
it was filed by kilborne, who with his law partner, herbert hafif of claremont has brought three other such suits against northrop in connection with its work on the mx missile program. in october, the justice department moved to dismiss one of those suits after failing to substantiate the allegations
here are some facts and figures on south korea:
the land _ a small, mountainous country about the size of indiana or england, south korea occupies the southern half of the korean peninsula jutting out into the sea of japan and the yellow sea. its only border is with north korea, but it is ringed by nearby china, the soviet union and japan. the country of 41 million people has hot humid summers and very cold winters
government _ south korea is a republic with a strong presidential system under which the presidency iniates most government programs and the prime minister and cabinet ministers traditionally have had little power. the unicameral national assembly is playing a growing role
history _ korea's history can be traced to at least the 1st century b.c. small, rival kingdoms fought for control of the korean peninsula over the centuries, with china often dominating the area. japan seized the country in 1910 and proclaimed it a province
u.s. and soviet forces ended the harsh japanese colonial occupation in 1945, dividing the country along the 38th parallel. south korea and north korea were formed and the two nations fought the korean war when the communist north invaded in 1950. forces from the united states and other nations intervened on the side of the south as china sent troops to fight with the north and the soviet union provided supplies
south korea and north korea remain bitter enemies with hundreds of thousands of troops poised along their border. about 40,000 u.s. troops remain in the south under a mutual defense pact
economy _ the export-fueled economy has helped transform south korea into one of the economic powers of asia and allowed it to make a remarkable recovery from the devastation of the korean war. south korea exports a wide range of electronic goods, automobiles, ships, textiles and clothing. its main export market is the united states. contests</head>
to home-state backers, sen. paul simon's decision to forgo a big super tuesday push has an important virtue _ it beats seeing him drop out
simon advocates in illinois contacted wednesday lauded simon's decision to stay in the race following disappointing showings in the latest contests
the illinois senator announced his new strategy in washington, saying that because of a lack of campaign money, there was little he could do in the 20 states that vote on super tuesday, march 8
he is on the ballot in all the super tuesday primaries, but he said he will do little or no campaigning in those states _ except for the nationally televised debates that are a major feature of the next two weeks
and, of course, he'll have a big edge in the illinois primary, which is a week after super tuesday
simon, meeting here with about 150 supporters, many of them delegate candidates and elected officials, offered assurances that he's in the race to stay
so, there is no misunderstanding, i am on the ballot in every state. we are in every district, and we are going to contest and fight for every delegate and every vote,'' simon said to cheers and whistles
some of simon's democratic rivals suggested that a candidate who's not campaigning in the super tuesday contests poses little threat
i have always believed that to win the nomination and to ultimately win the presidency you can't have a regional strategy and you can't run in just one part of the country and not others,'' said rep. richard gephardt
and tennessee sen. albert gore, who is concentrating on the southern states, was asked whether any contender could afford to sit out super tuesday
no,'' he said
simon's backers were undaunted, though
we urged him to take a midwestern industrial strategy,'' said state sen. vince demuzio, d-carlinville, state democratic chairman
some supporters held out hope that simon still has a chance to win the democratic nomination for president despite the lack of a first-place finish in any of the early primaries and caucuses
others said simon has leverage to fashion the party ticket in case there is no clear winner by the beginning of the democratic national convention in atlanta _ leverage that would be lost if simon were to drop out now
simon himself cited ``growing evidence that for the first time in recent history there will be no first-ballot winner at the democratic convention.''
one delegate candidate, state sen. patrick welch, d-peru, also said some politicians in illinois, seeking to be simon delegates but facing their own races for offices from the county to state legislative levels, don't want to be embarrassed with losses in the delegate races
his (simon's) campaign recruited a lot of elected individuals to use their political operations to get simon elected,'' welch said. ``this works both ways.''
simon also acknowledged he has had some pressure from illinois delegate candidates to stay in the race so they could get to the convention
there are people in illinois who want to go to the convention and who are simon delegates,'' he said at a news conference. but, he said, ``this is not just an illinois strategy. it is a strategy to win.''
state sen. dawn clark netsch, d-chicago, said she is among candidates for simon-committed delegates who were dismayed when simon announced, after a third-place showing in new hampshire, that he would drop out of the race if he did not win in either minnesota or south dakota. he later took back that statement and placed fourth in both races tuesday
simon came in second in iowa's feb. 8 caucuses and third in new hampshire's feb. 16 primary
mrs. netsch said she knew of no delegate candidate whose only concern was getting to the convention
there may be some individuals who feel that way,'' she said, but ``i can't imagine someone who is angry or upset only because their ticket to the convention has gone down the drain.''
sen. alan dixon, d-ill., said he had counseled simon not to waste resources in the super tuesday states
whatever he gets (in delegates on) super tuesday, fine, but don't spend any money,'' dixon said
i firmly believe that he'll run first in illinois,'' dixon said. ``he'll pick up a large bloc of delegates there, and i think that will give him a bump _ the kind of a bump that (rep. richard) gephardt got coming out of iowa.''
rep. lane evans, d-ill., said simon's support may have waned but is still deep. simon's campaign plunged into debt before the new hampshire primary, but he has collected close to half a million dollars in the past two weeks
a judge deliberated on the 65-year-old puzzle of president warren g. harding's untimely death before concluding, ``it's a mystery to me.''
the ``ruling'' by judge george t. choppelas came after an uproarious session wednesday of the mock court of historical review, which considered suggestions that harding's wife killed him in 1923
but the ``spirit'' of harding's widow, testifying in a standing-room-only city hall courtroom, said ``madame x,'' her fortuneteller, told her that vice president calvin coolidge killed the 29th president
it was the 50th session of the just-for-fun court that since 1975 has taken up such weighty questions as ``who invented the fortune cookie?'' and ``is chicken soup jewish penicillin?''
harding, whose administration was torn apart by such corruption scandals as teapot dome, died at age 57 on aug. 2, 1923, in san francisco's palace hotel. no autopsy was performed, and his body was whisked back to washington for burial
attorney frank winston, arguing that florence harding killed her husband, opened by ordering the courtroom to pay no attention to his opponent, u.s. attorney joseph p. russoniello
we'll set the record straight,'' snarled winston, drawing snorts of derision from russoniello
hmmm,'' said the judge, raising an eyebrow
i stand for truth, justice and the american way!'' announced the government prosecutor
history can be tedious at times,'' sighed choppelas, a municipal court judge
russoniello, arguing that the widow did not kill her husband, claimed mrs. harding hated coolidge and would hardly have done anything to speed him into the presidency
coolidge was ``a scoundrel,'' testified the ``widow,'' played by attorney diane elan wick, president of the lawyers club of san francisco
police chief frank jordan, who was ``sworn in'' and promised to testify truthfully ``to the limit of my instability,'' affirmed that local officials did not investigate harding's death
it's a mystery to me,'' choppelas concluded
the tokyo stock exchange's key nikkei average closed above the 25,000-point level for the first time since the october stock crash today, while the dollar rose marginally against the japanese yen
the 225-share nikkei stock average rose 132.01 points, or 0.50 percent, in active trading to finish the day at 25,100.66
sato yamashita of goldman sachs in tokyo said the market was upbeat, although there was no special driving force behind its rally
it's generating its own momentum,'' he said
last october, on the day after a plunge of more than 500 points in wall street's dow jones industrial average, the nikkei index fell more than 3,800 points, from 25,746.56 to 21,910.08
on tokyo's foreign exchange market today the dollar closed at 128.80 yen, up a slight 0.05 yen from its close on wednesday. spot volume totaled $13.3 billion
a dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo said wednesday's release of fourth-quarter u.s. trade figures showing that the nation's trade deficit had declined from the previous quarter had no major effect on the tokyo market
everyone's just ignoring the report,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity
the u.s. foreign trade deficit stood at $40.2 billion for the october-december 1987 quarter, down $200 million from the july-september period, u.s. commerce officials said wednesday. the trade deficit with japan, however, increased by $1.3 billion dollars to $15 billion dollars
bob dole is playing catch-up in south carolina and it helps to talk textiles and tobacco and have strom thurmond at his side
hopping from airport to airport on wednesday, dole was battling to become competitive in a state where vice president george bush and former television evangelist pat robertson were conceded to have a large lead
in the battle for the 1988 republican presidential nomination, south carolina has a unique role. its primary is march 5, three days before super tuesday when republican voters in 17 states will express their presidential choices in primaries or caucuses
the threshold to super tuesday,'' was how the kansas senator referred to south carolina at columbia, his first stop
each of dole's four stops followed the same pattern
first, his state campaign chairman introduced thurmond, the state's senior senator
in the beginning, i thought i'd remain neutral,'' said thurmond, describing all the republican candidates as ``friends of mine.''
but, he went on, ``people came to me and wanted to know where i stood.''
so this week he announced he was supporting dole
thurmond called dole ``the head man among the republicans in the senate,'' a man who rose from humble beginnings, the son of hard-working parents
in other words,'' he told people crowded into the florence airport ``they're not of the so-called elite, they weren't born with silver spoons in their mouths.'' that's the kind of reference dole often uses to contrast his background to that of bush
thurmond found other, more practical aspects of dole's background to recommend the kansan to south carolina voters
bob dole supported the textile bill,'' said thurmond, pointing out that 300,000 textile industry jobs across the country had been lost to foreign competition and that 126 textile plants had closed in south carolina
the south carolina senator said that 45 percent of the jobs in his state were in the textile industry
the legislation he referred to would limit imports
we have a textile bill up now,'' he said ``and he (dole) is obligated _ not obligated _ he has promised to support that and we are proud of that.''
as republican leader of the senate, dole can play a significant role in determining whether textile import legislation can come to a vote in congress, certainly more of a role than bush or robertson could hope to play
florence also is tobacco country and dole was asked his view on tobacco subsidies
he talked about his role in passage of the current subsidy program which he described as operating at no cost to the taxpayers
a lot of people think, why are you subsidizing tobacco,'' he said
those people are farmers, too,'' he went on ``and they've got a right to, make a living. i've supported the tobacco program in every vote since i've been in congress and i'm going to continue to do so.''
to guarantee the comfort of secretary of state george p. shultz, the holy city saved him the best hotel room in town, stocked up on exotic fruits and made him chocolates shaped like the dove of peace
a white sculpture of a dove with a 12-foot wing span hangs in the lobby of hilton hotel where the secretary will stay
when he arrives today for a five-day middle east shuttle to launch a new peace initiative, shultz will occupy the 20th floor royal suite in the hotel, which dominates the northwestern outskirts of jerusalem. his entourage will fill about 160 rooms, hotel officials said
when you open the doors leading to the balcony, you see really a stunning view of jerusalem, with the whole old city spread before you,'' alon ben-gurion, the hotel's deputy manager, told israel's army radio
dina doron, who will be responsible for the reception, said the rooms have been decorated with orchids and other plants
ben-gurion said a cook ``was flown from germany especially for the occasion to make some sweets, chocolates in the form of doves.''
shultz ... likes very much seafood, and he usually tries local dishes, so we brought a selection of mediterranean fish. he also likes beer, and usually drinks local beer. during his last visit he drank (israeli) maccabee beer,'' he said
and, of course, the local fruits, all the exotic fruits that we have today in israel, like strawberries, kiwi, and oranges,'' ben-gurion added
the army radio reported that the hotel's pool has been heated to the temperature of 79 degrees preferred by shultz and that several couples have been invited to play tennis with the secretary of state
but other sights shultz is likely to encounter in jerusalem are bound to be less peaceful
airport police said special riot units were called in and will stay on duty through tuesday as shultz conducts his mission
jerusalem's police force was doubled to 3,000 to forestall palestinian protests during the shultz visit, said city spokeswoman sivana meryn
an army spokesman said israeli police approached the army with a request for extra manpower in jerusalem and the military agreed. in the mixed arab-jewish abu tor neighborhood, troops were seen checking the identities of arab teen-agers
it was apparently the first time troops were used in the holy city since israel united it after capturing the arab east jerusalem from jordan in the 1967 middle east war
the space shuttle program took another step toward america's return to space with the apparently successful fourth test of a joint on the redesigned booster rocket, a nasa official says
flaws deliberately built into the nozzle-to-case joint for wednesday's test allowed hot gases to reach the joint's primary o-ring seal. but the o-ring stopped the gases from reaching the secondary or final seal, said royce mitchell, nasa solid rocket motor manager
it will prove that we can give up two of our seals, or two of our lines of defense against this hot gas, and still have a good, safe motor,'' mitchell said following the six-second test at morton thiokol inc.'s wasatch operations plant 25 miles west of here
all indications are it's a good test, but we've got another couple of these to go and, of course, our next motor test will be in april,'' mitchell said, adding that a complete analysis of the joint's performance was not expected for several weeks
the solid-fuel rocket booster has undergone extensive redesign since the jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle challenger that killed the seven-member crew. the disaster was blamed on a faulty seal in a booster joint that allowed hot gases to escape and ignite the fuel tank
wednesday's test, delayed two hours by replacement of a computer board, was the fourth of six nozzle joint environment simulator experiments and one of hundreds of booster component tests
the initially favorable results showed the shuttle program is moving slowly but surely toward resumption of flights, mitchell said
we are maintaining our schedule for the august launch of discovery,'' he said. ``it's a very conservative approach.''
the test was designed to evaluate the main seal's ability to contain any gases that might leak through bonded adhesive insulation and a rubber-like ``wiper'' o-ring during launch, said thiokol spokesman rocky raab
engineers made a quarter-inch-by-five-hundredths-inch hole through the insulation and disabled the wiper ring, creating two flaws that assured a gas path to the primary seal
the double defects simulated coincidental manufacturing defects in the insulation and wiper o-ring, a ``worst possible case'' that likely could never occur, raab said. it also subjected the joint to more severe conditions than previous tests
the next test will increase the pressure because the primary o-ring will be purposely flawed to permit gases to reach the secondary o-ring, mitchell said. the final test will simulate complete failure
engineers concluded after the third nozzle-joint test oct. 8 that the o-ring system withstood gas pressure after a single flaw was built into the joint, which connects the nozzle to the body of the segmented booster rocket
however, during a full-scale test dec. 23, a ``blow hole'' was detected in the joint's adhesive sealant, a defect nasa had not built into the test
blow holes can occur during assembly of the 126-foot-long rocket, ``so it happens here at the factory, if it happens,'' raab said
while the blow hole was not considered a major problem, the failure of a nozzle boot ring during the december test prompted nasa officials to delay the scheduled june 2 resumption of shuttle flights
raab said the test wednesday simulated ``the most difficult portion of the environment for the o-rings, that is the first one second'' of launch
in addition to the final two nozzle-to-case tests scheduled before shuttle flights resume, nasa and thiokol will conduct several more joint environment simulator tests of the booster rocket and three more full-scale horizontal tests, in april, june and july
the birth control device known as the cervical cap appears headed for regulatory approval after seven years of testing
the device, already used by women in great britain and several other countries, received the green light wednesday by the food and drug administration's obstetrics-gynecology devices advisory panel
the unanimous recommendation was non-binding, but the fda usually follows the advice of such panels of outside experts it maintains to help assess clinical studies
the cervical cap is medically similar to the diaphragms already used by an estimated 3 million u.s. women, but it was not widely used in the united states in 1977 when congress ordered fda to strengthen its regulation of birth control and other medical devices
diaphragms and condoms were given ``grandfather'' fda approval at that time without the stringent testing subsequently required of new medical devices
in the testing financed by the national institutes of health, the cap has been available to about 50,000 women in 29 states and the district of columbia
rather than covering the entire roof of the vagina as a diaphragm does, the cap fits over the tip of the cervix and thus allows for more sensitivity during intercourse
another advantage is that it can remain in place longer than the diaphragm without additional application of spermicide, which is recommended for use with the cap as it is with the diaphragm
although many women typically wore the cap for three days at a time in the clinical trials, the panel decided to recommend that it remain in place no longer than two days at a time. similar recommendations for the diaphragm say it should not stay in place more than 24 hours
the cap was found to be 94.6 percent effective in preventing pregnancy when worn for every instance of intercourse compared to 96.4 percent for the diaphragm
survey forms on which doctors admitted helping with mercy killings of terminally ill patients have been burned to protect the doctors from possible criminal prosecution, a ``right-to-die'' group said
the survey responses, including 20 signed forms from doctors who said they had helped patients, were destroyed because of a ``witch hunt'' for a doctor who described a mercy killing in a medical journal, said derek humphry, executive director of the hemlock society
some people have noticed evidence buried in the survey of what i would call compassionate crimes,'' humphry said tuesday. ``we decided to destroy the evidence before there is any official inquiry, and therefore not break any law. we would not want to get these kindly doctors into trouble.''
the society, which promotes euthanasia, or mercy killing, last week released results of the survey showing 51 percent of california doctors responding would practice euthanasia where they considered it appropriate
asked if they had ever helped a patient die, 79 of 588 doctors responded positively, and 20 of those put their names on their responses, humphrey said. of those doctors who had taken the life of a patient, 15 said they had done it once, 35 said they had done it two or three times and 29 said they had done it more than three times, he said
the society's news release didn't describe how the doctors surveyed were selected or how representative they are
humphry said concern over possible prosecution was prompted by calls for criminal charges against a doctor who wrote anonymously in the jan. 8 issue of the journal of the american medical association of a mercy killing
the letter to the editor, titled ``it's over, debbie,'' prompted calls for prosecution from new york mayor edward koch among others. the district attorney in cook county, ill., where the journal is published, is seeking the name of the letter writer, but the journal has resisted
the hemlock society, which claims 23,000 members, is based in los angeles
violent palestinian riots have spilled onto canvas and into lyrics as many israeli artists and intellectuals rebel against government policy in the occupied territories
the intellectual rebellion has galvanized the dovish camp but so far has had no noticeable effect on the middle-of-the road voter whose support will determine what path israel follows in the peace process in elections this november
one hundred writers, actors, singers and other well-known figures in the arts published an advertisement in israeli newspapers last week calling for an end to army brutality against the palestinians
on saturday, more than 100 artists and photographers are scheduled to take part in a protest exhibition, many of them displaying works made since the unrest broke out
it is not as much the occupation that worries me as what has happened to us,'' said nira yitzhaki, an art gallery owner who is organizing the exhibition. ``we have lost our humanity.''
six art galleries will host the show under the banner: ``we favor immediate talks with the palestinians and an end to the occupation.''
representatives of more than 10 groups of writers, playwrights, students and university academics are co-ordinating a protest campaign
playwrights are mounting a vigil outside prime minister yitzhak shamir's home, calling for negotiations with palestinian leaders
a growing number of israelis in the arts, many of them leaders in their fields, have started to protest the 20-year-long occupation and the harsh army crackdown on palestinian demonstrators
according to u.n. figures, more than 60 palestinians have been killed since violence began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, which israel captured from jordan and egypt during the 1967 middle east war
some of the more popular entertainers could be putting their careers on the line by taking sides in israel's highly polarized and emotional debate
among them is cee heiman, an up-and-coming rock 'n' roll singer who recently cut her first record
during an appearance last saturday at an avant-garde theatre run by the left-wing mapam party, heiman sang the first israeli protest song of the current palestinian uprising
the song, ``shooting and crying,'' has some tough lyrics
the window in my home is broken and tel aviv rushes in,'' sang heiman. ``even its smell has changed. boys play with lead and girls with dolls of steel. life looks different in the shadow of the filth.''
we shoot and cry, laugh and burn. whenever did we learn how to bury people alive. we shoot and cry, laugh and burn. when did we forget there was a time our children were also killed.''
but aharon appelfeld, a holocaust survivor and one of israel's internationally known writers, said the intellectuals are contributing to the discord which is ripping israeli society apart
instead of being a moderating influence, the intellectuals are adding to the extremism,'' he said in an interview. ``i'm very afraid of the polarization and they keep fanning the flames.''
appelfeld, author of such books as ``badenheim, 1939'' and ``the age of wonders'' said he agreed israel should not rule over the palestinians but disliked the way the intellectuals were presenting their arguments
they are saying that in the present situation the arabs are the good guys and the jews the bad ones,'' he said. ``the arabs want to negotiate with us and we don't want to. but this is not true
most israelis feel that the arabs still do not accept us in this region,'' appelfeld said. ``we want to hear voices from the other side telling us we are welcome, telling us they won't throw us into the sea.''
he warned that the arguments used by israeli intellectuals were alienating the silent majority of israelis who strive for peace but have genuine and legitimate concerns
the mainly ashkenazi (european-origin) intellectuals have not found a way to reach the religious community or the sephardis (who come from arabic-speaking countries),'' appelfeld said. ``they are not rabble. they are people with genuine fears and they must be understood.''
i am very afraid that two large camps may be formed which could reach the point of civil war,'' said appelfeld. ``it's our job not to light that fire. that's a heavy responsibility.''
david walter says customers will have to wade for a table at the restaurant he hopes to moor off this gulf coast resort
walter has applied to the u.s. army corps of engineers for a permit allowing him to moor a 50-foot-long oil field jack-up boat converted into a restaurant and bar
the restaurant would sit in the surf within 50 feet of the beach in about 3 feet of water, he said recently
the eatery would be jacked up on four legs and would face the beach. customers would wade through the water and walk up a ramp to enter the restaurant
you have to wear something you can get wet,'' walter said. shoes aren't required
walter said he expects his customers to be ``the bathing suit people'' who lie on the beach, and hopes to do business from may 15 to sept. 15
he said the restaurant initially won't be open at night for safety reasons. he also has yet to work out a menu, but said the food will be ``nothing elaborate.''
if the establishment is not successful, walter said, he can just ``push two levers and move the boat off and drive away.''
no posie tweets from the bright lights allowed
in ``boontling'' dialect, that means no flower children from a big city will be accepted in the four- to eight-week course in boontling that will be offered this summer to children in boonville
jack june, a 65-year resident of boonville, is one of about a dozen ``true literates'' of the unusual dialect spoken only in the little village about 180 miles north of san francisco
i'd like to see it (the course), but not if it's half-eesled. if it's half-eesled, just shy it. does more harm than good,'' june said
half eesled,'' loosely translated, means ``half-baked.''
the mendocino county convention and visitors' bureau has approved a $1,000 grant to be used as seed money for the pilot program
officials said the boontling program may blossom into a prototype for eventual use in addition to english in boonville schools
soviet soldiers have started loading shorter-range ss-12 nuclear missiles onto railroad cars in preparation for the rockets' removal from czechoslovakia, the official news agency said today
the loading was taking place in the moravian town of hranice, the news agency ctk added
according to the report, the missiles were transported during the night from a nearby military zone to the railway station where the loading operation began
czechoslovakia announced wednesday that the soviet rockets would be removed before the u.s. congress votes on ratification of the superpowers' missile treaty signed last december in washington
ctk added that the first of the missiles would leave hranice for the soviet union this evening
foreign ministry spokesman dusan rovensky said wednesday evening that under an agreement between czechoslovakia and the soviet union, ``the withdrawal of soviet army rocket units armed with operational-tactical missiles from czechoslovak territory will start on feb. 25.''
ctk said the removal of the soviet missiles was being watched by 60 reporters, but it was not known if any western journalists were invited
a farewell meeting between hranice citizens and soviet soldiers was scheduled for the afternoon, ctk noted
hranice, with a population of 12,500, has been singled out by czechoslovak officials as the only place in the country where soviet missiles had been stationed
the step of the soviet government, the removal of operational-tactical shorter-range missiles before ratification of the soviet-american agreement, is further proof of the sincerity, concreteness and constructive approach of the soviet peace policy to nuclear disarmament and the creation of a more secure world,'' ctk said
the withdrawal coincides with the 40th anniversary of communist rule in czechoslovakia
communist party leader milos jakes condemned the social reforms that were crushed by soviet-led troops 20 years ago, and said the nation will maintain central planning of the economy
speaking at a celebration wednesday marking the 40th anniversary of the communist takeover in czechoslovakia, jakes gave little indication he is about to favor economic and political reforms similar to those being tried in the soviet union, poland, hungary and bulgaria
the 65-year-old jakes also ruled out all non-communist opposition
jakes took over party leadership last december from gustav husak, now 75, who was chairman of the solemn meeting on wednesday
jakes' hourlong speech to 500 party members in prague's hradcany castle did not essentially differ from the cautious conservatism husak displayed during his 18-year tenure
the speech preceded celebrations that will include a mass rally today in prague's old town square, scene of a triumphant speech by then-communist party leader klement gottwald on feb. 21, 1948
jakes asserted that an economic restructuring process was under way concerning ``a new framework of the sphere of action for central bodies.''
but he hastened to add, ``these measures are in no way meant as steps toward weakening the role of the centrally managed economy.''
he revealed that part of the ministerial bureaucracy will be reassigned to productive work, and, in an apparent allusion to reform-minded neighboring hungary, said: ``there is no threat of unemployment in czechoslovakia.''
jakes attacked the communists who, under the leadership of alexander dubcek, tried in 1968 to introduce some reforms resembling those recently instituted or proposed by mikhail s. gorbachev in the soviet union
as head of the party's chief disciplinary body from 1968 to 1977, jakes was responsible for purging 500,000 people from the communist party after the invasion. jakes denied there is a need to reassess the official view of 1968
he also rejected any comparison between dubcek's reforms and gorbachev's innovations. the party chief lauded the ``assistance'' czechoslovakia received from the soviet union and its allies to obliterate dubcek's reform efforts
the communists received nearly 40 percent of the vote in elections in 1946, but assumed sole power only after a series of political maneuvers from feb. 20-25, 1948. czechoslovakia was the last country in eastern europe to turn communist, setting the seal on kremlin domination of the region
it was no communist coup, as it's always described by hostile propaganda,'' jakes said of the 1948 takeover. ``it was the will of the people.''
he also issued a warning to the charter 77 human rights movement and other non-conformists who are banned from public life in czechoslovakia
the broadening of democratization in no case means the creation of space for the legalization of political opposition which, as all experiences to date show, cannot be other than anti-socialist,'' said jakes
rock 'n' roll singer frank zappa has pledged to register fans at his concert here tonight to vote, and the league of women voters couldn't be happier
the alliance prompted one elderly league member to joke that he would turn down the volume on his hearing aid during the concert, said pittsburgh league president marsha bingler
i consider that an upbeat comment,'' said ms. bingler. ``the gentleman who said that is about 70 years old. he does have trouble with his hearing
i've had no one in the league say anything other than that this is a worthwhile effort,'' she said. ``the league encourages the widest participation in the electoral process.''
zappa said 400 people registered at his recent concert in boston, and about 380 registered at a stop in hartford, conn
the only way to change what is going on is to vote,'' he said. ``unless young people get involved, their decisions will be made by people older than them who don't know or don't care.'' heptachlor</head>
a federal judge has told the environmental protection agency it has until april 15 to ban the sale and commercial use of products containing an anti-termite pesticide believed to cause cancer
u.s. district judge louis oberdorfer ruled wednesday that the epa had acted illegally by allowing 197 holders of federal pesticide licenses to sell existing stocks of products containing the pesticides chlordane and heptachlor
oberdorfer said the epa failed to take into account whether continued sale or use of the products ``would pose any unreasonable risk to man or the environment.''
last year, velsicol chemical corp., the nation's only manufacturer of chlordane and heptachlor, agreed to stop selling the chemical while it tries to find an acceptable method of applying the pesticide
but the epa's agreement with velsicol did not cover products containing chlordane made by other companies for the retail market
the agency estimates these companies have 1,700 pounds of chlordane products in their stocks compared with the 110,000 pounds in velsicol's inventory
a federally imposed waiting period for would-be gun buyers would save lives by letting violence-prone customers cool down, say olice officials
representatives of national, state and local police wednesday urged the house judiciary subcommitee on crime to advance legislation requiring a waiting period after any request to buy a handgun
the crime panel is considering a number of bills that would require a delay of at least seven days between the time a buyer enters a gun store and when the customer gets the weapon
also under consideration are plans to require background checks of would-be buyers, including comparison of their fingerprints to fbi records
both ideas were strongly opposed by pro-gun groups and some members of congress as ineffective against violent crimes and unfair to legitimate gun buyers. the national rifle association called the plan ``irrelevant, useless, costly and unconstitutional.''
up to 1 million taxpayers will receive federal refunds as much as three weeks earlier this year by having a professional file their tax returns directly into the irs computer
already this year, 119,494 returns have been filed electronically _ compared with 77,612 for the entire filing season in 1987. if the taxpayers choose, their refunds will be deposited directly into their bank account
although the number of electronic returns are up considerably this year, the volume of ordinary, paper returns filed so far is 6.7 percent below last year's pace. however, the gap _ which officials blame partially on the new tax law _ is closing each week
through feb. 19, the internal revenue service said wednesday, 23.55 million returns had been filed, compared with 25.24 million a year ago. the irs has processed 9.74 million of this year's returns, up slightly from 9.72 million last year
the inventory of unprocessed returns totaled 13.8 million last week, compared with 15.5 million a year ago
the average refund is bigger this year: $782 compared with $727. by the time all 107 million individual returns are filed this year, the irs estimates, nearly 80 percent will qualify for refunds averaging about $1,000
the election of a dynamic tycoon as president and a thaw in greek-turkish relations has raised hopes for a settlement of ethnic disputes on this mediterranean island
the cyprus question has long soured relations between greece and turkey, two nato allies, posing a potentially serious weakness in the atlantic alliance's vulnerable southern flank
george vassiliou, 56, a self-made millionaire, was elected cyprus' president for a five-year term feb. 21. he ran as an independent with the powerful communist party his main backer on a platform of ``time for change.''
he vowed to be flexible and work for ``quick results'' to reunite cyprus, partitioned since turkey invaded in 1974 and occupied the northern third of the island
as leader of the 500,000-strong greek cypriot majority, vassiliou has said he is prepared to meet with rauf denktash, president of the breakaway turkish cypriot republic proclaimed in the north in 1983 and recognized only by turkey
but vassiliou must overcome deep distrust and military buildups on both sides which u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar has warned could trigger a new confrontation
vassiliou, a political newcomer, is widely viewed as more flexible than his predecessor, spyros kyprianou. but vassiliou remains committed to the withdrawal of some 30,000 turkish troops and 50,000 turkish settlers from the north and the return of 200,000 greek cypriot refugees
turkey and denktash insist the troops are needed to protect the 120,000 turkish cypriots
hints by the turkish government that it might be prepared to pull out some troops in advance of any agreement fueled hopes of progress
it is not clear what concessions vassiliou is prepared to make
negotiations under u.n. auspices have been deadlocked for three years because of kyprianou's hard line
kyprianou had the rug pulled from under him two weeks before the election, when greek prime minister andreas papandreou, who for years refused to negotiate with turkey, changed his mind
papandreou conferred with turkish prime minister turgut ozal in the swiss resort of davos in late january. the meeting ended with a ``no war'' agreement and an announced determination to settle all outstanding differences peacefully
apart from the cyprus problem, what has brought brought greece and turkey to the brink of war repeatedly in recent years is the issue of territorial waters and underwater oilfields in the aegean sea
greece and turkey sought to patch together a settlement of the cyprus problem in 1958 in what greek cypriots refer to as ``the ignominious, imposed zurich agreement.''
this laid the groundwork for independence from britain two years later. under that agreement, the island's constitution gave the turkish cypriot minority, 17 percent of the population, equal political status with the greek cypriots
the agreement also made britain, greece and turkey guarantor powers with the right to intervene
that is widely seen by greek cypriots as sowing the seeds for turkey's subsequent invasion on the pretext of protecting turkish cypriots after a short-lived coup by supporters of union with greece plotted with the colonels' junta then in power in athens
alex efty has been cyprus correspondent for the associated press for 30 years
after a prolonged warm spell, relations between britain and ireland appear to be going into a dangerous free fall over a spate of incidents involving the conduct of british security forces in northern ireland
so severe is the strain that fears are being voiced for the survival of the 1985 anglo-irish agreement, the accord that gave dublin a say in the running of northern ireland and was responsible for the relative amity that existed between britain and ireland until the beginning of the year
the harmony was jolted on jan. 25. the british government announced that, having investigated the shooting of six unarmed roman catholics by northern ireland police in 1982, authorities uncovered evidence of a conspiracy to pervert the course of justice _ yet no policemen would be prosecuted
matters grew worse the same week when a british court rejected the appeal of six irishmen who claim they were wrongly convicted of a 1974 bombing attack in mainland britain that killed 21 people
the irish government said that despite the ruling, it continued to believe a miscarriage of justice may have occurred
that dispute was quickly followed by a new one as ireland accused london of failing to abide by the conditions dublin has set for extraditing irish republican army suspects to britain
next, the british government announced it was making its tough anti-terrorism law, which requires annual parliamentary renewal, permanent. many irish believe the law tars them with the brush of the ira. only after outcry in ireland did britain restore parliament's right to review the law annually
tempers grew worse on sunday when aidan mcanespie, a 23-year-old catholic and supporter of the outlawed ira's legal political wing, sinn fein, was shot dead from an army observation tower as he was walking through a security checkpoint on the ireland-northern ireland border
the army expressed regret and the soldier who fired the shot was charged wednesday with unlawful killing
the royal ulster constabulary said it was investigating the shooting, but irish prime minister charles haughey ordered his own force to investigate, too
this outraged the british, who saw it as a gesture of disdain for the royal ulster constabulary's efforts. prime minister margaret thatcher pointedly warned the irish to keep their investigation to their own side of the border
she also voiced annoyance at dublin's behavior on the extradition issue
but then, on tuesday, the army dropped a new bombshell. it announced that pvt. ian thain, the only british soldier ever jailed for life for killing a civilian in northern ireland, was free on parole and back in his regiment, having served only three years of his term
even the conservative daily telegraph, which usually takes britain's side in disputes with britain, called it an act of ``stunning insensitivity.''
among northern ireland's catholic minority, angry reactions came not just from sinn fein militants, but from moderates like cardinal tomas o fiaich, head of ireland's roman catholic church. he called mcanespie's death ``murder,'' and said thain's release ``add insult to injury.''
a british official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the incidents were ``a spasm'' in anglo-irish relations, not a pattern. he said britain's critics were failing to take into account that the security forces in northern ireland were up against a terrorist organization in a civil war that has claimed more than 2,500 lives since 1969
but merlyn rees, a former northern ireland secretary, warned that the anglo-irish agreement was ``tottering.''
in dublin, the irish press commented: ``there is an alarming but unmistakable pattern emerging from the behavior of the british government toward our government. it is almost as if it is trying to provoke mr. haughey into a rash decision.''
so far the irish prime minister has kept cool and refrained from anti-british rhetoric. most important, perhaps, is his clear determination to carry on fighting the ira
police have uncovered several large ira arms caches north and south of the border, including one on wednesday night near dublin that contained explosives, grenades and two dozen assault rifles
the irish press editorialized that it was britain's system of justice that had alienated northern ireland's catholics and pushed some of them into the ira's embrace
it was that alienation that was supposed to be tackled by the anglo-irish agreement, the paper said, adding: ``that hope is fading by the week.''
