democrat mike dukakis and vice president george bush appear to be the favorites in the march 8 super tuesday primary elections and caucuses, according to the denver post-gallup poll
the poll showed dukakis as the runaway favorite in his home state of massachusetts, with 61 percent of the voters saying they favor their governor. thirteen percent said they supported richard gephardt; 7 percent sen. paul simon; 6 percent for jesse jackson; 3 percent for sen. albert gore, and 2 percent for gary hart, according to the poll
democrats in the 13 southern states holding primaries or caucuses on march 8 give dukakis 26 percent; gore 18 percent; jackson 16 percent; gephardt 12 percent; hart 11 percent and simon 6 percent, the poll results show
the poll showed that while bush still is the solid gop favorite in the south and in massachusetts, sen. bob dole has made significant gains during the past month of campaigning
bush is favored by 54 percent of the republicans most likely to vote in the southern states march 8, while dole has the backing of 33 percent the poll shows
the poll was conducted by the gallup organization of princeton, n.j., on feb. 19-21 through telephone interviews with 1729 registered republicans and democrats in the southern states, massachusetts an oklahoma
in the gop races, the poll's margin of error was plus or minus 6 percent, and in the democratic contests, the margin was 5 percent
