in london, the dollar rose against the british pound. it cost $1.76135 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7640 late wednesday
bullion dealers said gold remained weak after falling through several technical resistance points on wednesday
gold opened in london at a bid price of $433.20 a troy ounce and at mid-morning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $433.95. both were down from wednesday's late bid of $434.70
in zurich, the bid price was $433.40, down from $434.70 late wednesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold fell $7.85 to close at a bid $436.35
silver was quoted in london today a bid price of $6.20 a troy ounce, down from wednesday's $6.26
undersecretary of state michael armacost today discussed with pakistan's president recent moves toward a soviet troop withdrawal from afghanistan, officials said
armacost also met for nearly two hours with afghan moslem guerrilla leaders in pakistan in what a u.s. embassy official said was a ``frank and open'' exchange wednesday
he was scheduled to travel next to india for similar talks before flying back to washington
armacost's swing through the region follows secretary of state george p. shultz' trip to moscow this week, where shultz discussed the soviets' pledge to begin leaving afghanistan by may 15, depending on the outcome of the next round of u.n.-sponsored peace talks in geneva
pakistan, a participant in the geneva talks, has added a condition that a military settlement to the fighting in afghanistan be coupled with a political settlement to ensure afghan stability during a soviet troop pullout
washington has said only that a political solution would be ``desirable'' and indicated it is willing to settle for an agreement on a timetable for a soviet pullout in exchange for a halt in u.s. military aid to the guerrillas
the rebel alliance, under chairman yunis khalis, reportedly reiterated its vow to armacost that the guerrillas will continue fighting until they install themselves as an all-moslem government in kabul
one of the more extremist resistance leaders, gulbaddin hekmatyar of the hezb-i-islami party, on wednesday accused washington of betraying the guerrilla cause by striking a secret deal with moscow on ending the war
pakistani president mohammad zia ul-haq has said pakistan will not sign any accord with the present kabul government, headed by communist leader najib
pakistan, in addition to serving as headquarters for the guerrillas, also shelters about 3.5 million refugees from the 9-year-old afghan civil war
the past weeks have seen hectic diplomatic activity in all countries involved in the afghan conflict to prepare for the next, and possibly final, round of geneva talks between pakistan and afghanistan, scheduled to begin march 2
magistrates fined an unemployed hairdresser $525 for smuggling an australian rat nicknamed napoleon into england
linda squire, 21, hid the 5-week-old black and white rodent in her sweater during the 32-hour flight from perth, australia, to london
she did not declare the rat to customs officers at london's gatwick airport, and police later arrested her at her home in dawlish in southwest england, said prosecutor david bick
miss squires bought the rat in a perth pet shop for $2.60 at the end of an 11-month trip to australia
because she could not afford to put it in quarantine for the mandatory six months, the rat was cremated by a local vet
the racketeering conviction of seven members of the westies has put the murderous manhattan gang out of business, a federal prosecutor says
a federal jury convicted the seven wednesday of taking part in the westies' violent dealings, including seven murders, three attempted murders and four kidnappings
an eighth defendant was acquitted of all charges, but still faces a state murder charge in an unrelated case
in addition to racketeering, several of the seven, including westies boss james ``jimmy'' coonan, also were found guilty of various crimes ranging from attempted murder and loansharking to drug dealing and tax evasion
but the key verdict was the jury's decision that the westies did exist, that it constituted a racketeering enterprise and that the convicted defendants had participated in activities to further the gang's criminal goals
the group has been incapacitated and put out of business,'' said assistant u.s. attorney mary lee warren
during the nearly five-month trial, defense lawyers contended there was no such organization as the westies. even former gang members testifying for the prosecution conceded the name ``westies'' was created by the police and the news media to describe irish-american hoodlums on manhattan's west side
ms. warren and the other prosecutor, david brodsky, claimed the six men and two women on trial were the violent core of the westies, which seized control of a neighborhood once known as hell's kitchen on the edge of manhattan's theater district near times square
for 20 years, they claimed, the gang maintained its rule ``with horrible and ghoulish acts of murder.''
witnesses testified that in at least three murders, the victim's body was cut up and disposed of in what ms. warren called ``the nightmarish signature crime of the westies.''
most of those murders and murder plots were not separate charges in the indictment, but listed as acts in furtherance of the racketeering enterprise. to be convicted of racketeering, each defendant had to have committed at least two of the 28 racketeering acts charged
the 14-count indictment also listed 10 alleged co-racketeers who were not named as defendants because they had been slain
several witnesss also testified that the westies forged an alliance with the gambino organized crime family, said to be the largest, most powerful mafia group in the country
the verdict was reached on the eighth day of deliberations
coonan was convicted of attempted murder, murder conspiracy, loansharking, extortion and income tax evasion, among other crimes. his wife was convicted of loansharking and tax charges
the jury also found that coonan participated in most of the racketeering acts charged against him, including seven murders
a trial on any single act in this indictment would have resulted in an acquittal,'' said his lawyer, gerald shargel. ``it's just a matter of the government, piling it all together. that's the nightmare of rico (the racketeer influenced corrupt organizations act).''
in addition to coonan and his 44-year-old wife, edna, both of hazlet, n.j., the others convicted of racketeering and racketeering conspiracy were: william ``indian'' bokun, 30; james ``jimmy mack'' mcelroy, 42; richard ``muggsy'' ritter, 50; thomas collins, 53, and his wife florence, 52, all of manhattan
only john halo, 36, of new york was acquitted on all charges. he still faces trial for the june 1985 fatal shooting of his 21-year-old nephew
u.s. district judge whitman knapp scheduled sentencing for april 18. all seven face up to 20 years apiece on both racketeering and racketeering conspiracy
villagers in northern ghana shot guns and arrows at police who came to discuss a chieftaincy dispute, leaving two officers dead and 20 wounded, ghana radio reported
the villagers in karaga fled when police sent reinforcements from nearby accra, said the report, which was monitored wednesday in abidjan
police found the bodies of police inspector p.c.k. dotsey and sgt. mandoh kokomba, who were killed saturday when a police squad arrived for talks with village elders and to arrest several villagers for recent assaults against police officers, the radio said
it quoted kwesi nkansa, the northern region police commissioner
the radio did not give details about the chieftaincy dispute, or when the reinforcements arrived to discover the bodies
nkansa told ghana radio that only one villager, a man in his 70s, was arrested and 15 others were being sought
a man who said he put a rattlesnake over the shoulder of a 21-month-old girl to show her it would not hurt her was convicted of manslaughter in the child's death from snakebite
darrell wessendorf, 24, faces a possible one- to 15-year prison sentence for the may 8, 1987, death of stevie luren kirkwood of la verkin
wessendorf had been charged with second-degree murder, which carries a possible sentence of five years to life. he had pleaded innocent by reason of insanity
wessendorf had caused a ``grave risk of death'' by bringing the snake so close to the girl and ``engaging in activities that eventually caused the reptile to bite the child,'' district judge j. phillip eves said wednesday
wessendorf, a former page, ariz., resident, said he was trying to show the girl that the snake would not hurt her when it bit her on the shoulder
he said he showed her the snake that he had found on a nearby road and partially placed it over her shoulder. the child's mother entered the room and screamed, causing wessendorf to flinch and the snake to bite the child, he said
defense attorney j. macarthur wright argued that only 0.2 percent of those bitten by rattlesnakes die and that those bitten often are not treated. he said the judge had to ``make a distinction here on what constitutes a grave risk of death.''
eves set sentencing for april 11
an 84-year-old woman was killed when a stray bullet from youths target-shooting nearby shattered her kitchen window and struck her in the chest, authorities said
neighbors expressed anger that the youths were allowed to go free after the shooting
rose cudigan died at ami valley medical center in el cajon less than two hours after being shot wednesday morning. her husband, raymond, who was standing near her in the kitchen when she was struck, was not injured and summoned help
three youths admitted they had been target shooting with a .22 caliber rifle about 100 yards away from the cudigans' home in the lakeview neighborhood of lakeside, said san diego county sheriff's sgt. danny goodrich
no charges were filed pending further investigation, and the teen-agers later were released to the custody of their parents
i'm mad and i'm bitter,'' neighbor sharon dudley said. ``we've lost a wonderful neighbor and the suspects are free.''
neighbors said youths had fired guns in the area before
the (deputies) told me they had no evidence, that i'd have to get a restraining order against those boys to stop them from firing their guns. what good is a piece of paper?'' dudley said
lt. bill baxter said the entire case may ``simply be handed to the district attorney for a review and final determination on any charges.''
under the state penal code, discharging a firearm at an inhabited dwelling is a felony, punishable by three, five or seven years in state prison, or by six months to a year in county jail. to 71.5.</note>
secretary of education william j. bennett said today that college entrance test scores ``are in a dead stall'' and the public is still not getting its money's worth from the schools
in saying that i am disappointed, i think i speak for the american people,'' said bennett in his annual report card on the states
bennett was delivering that verdict at a news conference where he was also releasing two wall charts nearly six feet wide crammed with statistics ranking the states on test scores, dropout rates, how much they pay teachers and other measures
it was the fifth straight year that an education secretary has released the controversial wall charts. bennett's predecessor, t.h. bell, initiated the practice
john weiss, executive director of fairtest, a cambridge, mass., group that is critical of standardized tests, said, ``it makes no sense to use a faulty thermometer to measure the nation's educational health.''
bennett said the school reform movement is alive and yielding positive results in some states, but ``there is still too much resistance to sensible and needed reform,'' including accountability measures and merit pay
this year, for the first time, the wall chart includes a list of seven states (arkansas, georgia, kentucky, new jersey, ohio, south carolina and texas) with laws allowing state officials to intervene in ``academically bankrupt'' school districts
it also lists the percentage of high scorers on the scholastic aptitude test and american college testing program, and the percentage of high school graduates who took advanced placement exams
the college entrance test scores were not new. they were made public last fall
bennett lamented that they ``are in a dead stall. the 1987 scores are basically unchanged from last year. the act average dipped by 0.1 point to 18.7, and the sat remained the same _ 906.'' the act is graded on a scale of 1-36 and the sat on a scale of 400-1,600
bennett said the graduation rate from public high schools slipped from 71.7 percent in 1985 to 71.5 percent in 1986. no figure was available for private schools
all of this is not particularly good news,'' said bennett, who recently began his fourth year as ecretary of education. but he did find some encouraging signs
last year a greater proportion of students took the act and sat tests and the advanced placement exams than ever before,'' he said. that ``means we are succeeding in keeping scores level despite a larger pool of test-takers.''
the percentage of high school graduates taking advanced placement tests has doubled since 1982, from less than 5 percent to nearly 10 percent. minority participation has grown by 78 percent since 1984, double the increase among whites
test results ``show that poor, black and hispanic children are performing better,'' said bennett, although there is still a wide gap between minority and majority scores on the college entrance tests
bennett said that since 1976 black students' scores on the sat have risen by 42 points to 728, while white students' scores fell eight points to 936
he singled out south carolina as a state that has made progress in setting high academic expectations, holding educators accountable and encouraging parental choice
although south carolina ranks last in sat scores among the 22 states where that is the dominant test, its scores have risen 17 points in two years to an average of 832. 0678</first> germany and to combine with czechoslovakian removal. edits to tighten, no pickup.</note>
soviet troops today began the early removal of nuclear missiles from east germany and czechosolovakia under terms of a new superpower arms agreement yet to be ratified
western reporters this morning saw a train loaded with 32 containers leave bischofwerda, about 20 miles east of dresden
officials at the scene said the containers were packed with parts of dismantled ss-12 rockets and that the train's destination was the soviet union, where the missiles are to be destroyed
in addition to the missile parts, 150 of 400 soviet soldiers stationed at bischofswerda also left on the train. officials at the site said the remaining soldiers will leave by the end of the month
a large banner displayed at bischofswerda's railroad station read: ``removal of shorter-range rockets, a contribution to security and peace.''
a local kindergarten class sang: ``we greet you soldiers, you protect the happiness of children.''
the top communist party functionary of bischofswerda, hannelore strugalla, said ``the first practical step in nuclear disarmament is being accomplished in our hometown.''
the ss-12s are included in the superpower treaty on removal of medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles from central europe. the accord was signed by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev in december
dmitri t. yazov, the soviet defense minister, said monday while secretary of state george p. shultz was in moscow that withdrawal of the ss-12s would begin this month as a ``display of goodwill.''
the treaty is before congress and the nominal soviet parliament for approval
there were five rocket launchers, eight missiles and four practice missiles stationed at bischofswerda, according to officials
removal of the warheads from the missiles was completed one week ago, officials said, and additional rocket parts are to be removed from the site within the next two days
soviet troops were also removing ss-12s today from waren, east germany, where there are 22 missiles, nine launchers and seven training rockets, according to figures released after the superpower treaty was signed
waren is about 90 miles northwest of berlin
the east german government arranged to transport 100 western journalists to the two sites to witness the removal of the rockets
the ss-12s _ which have a range of about 560 miles _ fall under the ``shorter-range'' classification in the superpower arms treaty, which covers rockets with a range from 300 to 3,100 miles
in czechoslovakia the loading was taking place in the moravian town of hranice, the country's official news agency ctk said
according to the report, the missiles were transported during the night from a nearby military zone to the railway station where the loading operation began
ctk added that the first of the missiles would leave hranice for the soviet union this evening
ctk quoted soviet lt. col. vyacheslav granovsky as saying soviet officers, mechanics and drivers who had serviced the missiles being dismantled would leave with the first transport today
granovsky did not say how many rockets and soviet personnel will leave czechoslovakia. he also did not say when withdrawal of all the missiles would be completed, and gave their destination only as ''a predetermined place in the soviet union.''
ctk said the removal of the soviet missiles was being watched by 60 reporters, but it was not known if any western journalists were invited
hranice, with a population of 12,500, has been singled out by czechoslovak officials as the only place in the country where soviet missiles had been stationed
the step of the soviet government, the removal of operational-tactical shorter-range missiles before ratification of the soviet-american agreement, is further proof of the sincerity, concreteness and constructive approach of the soviet peace policy to nuclear disarmament and the creation of a more secure world,'' ctk said
the withdrawal occurs during the 40th anniversary of communist rule in czechoslovakia
a polygamist charged in the bombing of a mormon chapel and a standoff with police has asked that his trial be moved out of state because of publicity and the dominance of the mormon church in utah
the polygamist, addam swapp, and co-defendants vickie singer and john timothy singer also want separate trials, court documents indicated wednesday
mrs. singer and swapp also are asking again to be released from jail. a magistrate ruled earlier that they were unlikely to voluntarily return for trial
a similar request was filed late wednesday on behalf of jonathan swapp, addam's brother, but it had not yet been added to the court file
earlier this month, mrs. singer, 44; john timothy singer, 21; addam swapp, 26, and jonathan swapp, 21, pleaded innocent to charges stemming from the jan. 16 bombing of the mormon chapel in marion and the subsequent 13-day standoff at their nearby farm
the siege ended jan. 28 with the shooting death of a corrections officer and wounding of addam swapp. state murder charges have not been filed yet
mrs. singer is the widow of john singer, a polygamist killed by police nine years ago during an arrest attempt, and the mother of john timothy singer. two of her daughters are wives of addam swapp
addam swapp's lawyers are asking u.s. district chief judge bruce s. jenkins to transfer the trial on the ground that swapp ``cannot obtain a fair and impartial trial in the district of utah.''
defense attorney bill morrison said news coverage and religious prejudice make a fair trial impossible
the atmosphere is charged and volatile and rife with misinformation,'' he said. ``the lds (mormon) church represents a sizable portion of the population.''
