president corazon aquino and thousands of filipinos joined hands today in a ``chain for peace'' to mark the second anniversary of a popular revolution that ended decades of authoritarian rule
the country's leading churchman, meanwhile, warned that the philippines cannot survive with huge gaps between rich and poor. leftists staged protest marches and accused the president of abandoning promises of reform
several hundred followers of former president ferdinand marcos rallied at a downtown manila square, calling for the ousted ruler to be allowed to return. police said the marcos loyalists dispersed peacefully after nearly three hours
about 50,000 people jammed a 1{-mile stretch of epifanio de los santos avenue, or edsa. on that same avenue in february 1986, hundreds of thousands of people formed a human wall for four days to protect mutineers holed up in two military camps from marcos' forces
the civilian-backed military mutiny, popularly called the ``people power'' revolution, forced marcos into exile in hawaii on feb. 25, 1986, after he had ruled for more than 20 years
a philippine air force t-28 airplane swooped low over the crowd, which also participated in a procession of images of the virgin mary, including one borne by an armored personnel carrier
officials said the images were the ones carried by priests and nuns during the 1986 revolt in this heavily roman catholic land
the day began with the pealing of church bells and mrs. aquino clasping hands with defense secretary fidel ramos and chief of staff gen. renato de villa on edsa, in front of the camp aguinaldo general headquarters
the ceremony was followed by a daylong carnival, featuring singing, folk dancing and performances by well-known entertainers
but during an afternoon mass, cardinal jaime l. sin, archbishop of manila, warned that the government must address the urgent social and economic crisis facing this nation. half of the 58 million filipinos live in poverty
the ever-growing gap between rich and poor in our society must be drastically reduced,'' sin said. ``only then can our nation survive and go forward.''
sin said the need for land reform ``hangs over us like a sword of damocles'' and added ``urgent reforms must be taken without delay.'' mrs. aquino ordered a land reform program last july but left details to congress, which has yet to approve the legislation
parades and festivities were held in other major cities across this nation of more than 7,100 islands
but from a shopping center near edsa, about 10,000 leftists marched to the presidential palace, waving red banners, chanting slogans and accusing mrs. aquino of betraying the reformist ideals of the uprising two years ago
on wednesday, about 20,000 leftists chanting slogans in support of communist rebels, marched to the scene of today's celebrations and burned an effigy of mrs. aquino
in 1986, sin called on filipinos to turn out into the streets to back mutineers led by then-defense minister juan ponce enrile and ramos
enrile and ramos had broken with marcos, charging him with fraud in the feb. 7, 1986, presidential election in which he ran against mrs. aquino. the rebels' action galvanized the opposition that began after the 1983 assassination of opposition leader benigno aquino, mrs. aquino's husband
prospects for broad social, economic and political reform since mrs. aquino rose to power have been clouded by a $28 billion debt, a cumbersome legislature and political polarization widened by the 19-year-old communist insurgency and the military's rising clout
as chief of staff, ramos has fended off six coup plots. but social activists fear mrs. aquino's reliance on ramos has lessened the government's commitment to reform
the government so far has not prosecuted soldiers for alleged involvement in several widely publicized killings of civilians. nor has it fulfilled mrs. aquino's 1986 campaign promise to abolish the civilian home defense force, a military-backed militia widely accused of human rights abuses
gunmen today hurled a hand grenade at shiite moslem militiamen searching for a kidnapped u.s. marine in south lebanon. police said eight people were wounded
a police spokesman said two gunmen threw the grenade from a speeding car at an amal militia checkpoint near the inland village of dweir. militiamen at the checkpoint were searching cars looking for lt. col. william r. higgins
the attack coincided with a threat by amal to use force to free higgins. amal also summoned shiite clerics to a meeting to discuss his abduction
six amal militiamen were wounded along with two civilians,'' said the police spokesman. he cannot be named in line with standing regulations
higgins, 43, was abducted feb. 17 near tyre, 50 miles south of beirut. he headed an observer group assigned to a united nations peacekeeping force in south lebanon
the pro-iranian organization of the oppressed on earth claimed it abducted higgins and alleged he was a cia spy. u.s. and u.n. officials denied the accusation
higgins is one of nine americans and 25 foreigners missing in lebanon
the shiite militiamen, the police spokesman said, opened fire at the speeding car, but the two gunmen escaped. he did not elaborate
amal, in a statement, identified the attackers only as ``suspicious elements.'' it confirmed that six of its militiamen were wounded in the blast
dweir, a stronghold of the iranian-backed hezbollah, is 15 miles northeast of the port of tyre
the resort to force to free higgins is not unlikely once we locate the place where he is being held,'' said daoud daoud, amal's military commander in south lebanon
daoud, who has been supervising the search for higgins, said he had ``confirmed information that 25 people specializing in kidnapping have been sent to south lebanon to abduct more foreigners.'' he did not elaborate
daoud's remarks were broadcast by the beirut-based voice of the nation radio. it was not the first statement by amal that it would use strong measures to free higgins, but it was the most clear-cut reference so far to using force
a spokesman for the syrian-backed amal said improved weather conditions ``allowed us to speed up the search'' for higgins southeast of tyre
we believe higgins is still in the area south of the litani river,'' he said. he refused to elaborate on the remark. the litani river is four miles north of tyre
the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said every car leaving the area south of the river was being searched
amal, he said, also summoned shiite clerics in south lebanon to a meeting in tyre to discuss higgins' abduction and its effect on the shiite community
amal has arrested six men it says were involved in the kidnapping. the detainees, however, have not been able to provide information on the whereabouts of higgins and the mastermind of the abduction, who reportedly has fled the area
the detainees, according to the spokesman, include the three gunmen who seized higgins and the three who monitored his movements before the abduction
amal also has arrested the man who was supposed to take higgins to beirut, the spokesman said
the seven detainees are among 42 members of the iranian-backed hezbollah captured by amal in the tyre region in connection with the abduction of higgins
the organization of the oppressed on earth is a pro-iranian underground faction believed linked with hezbollah. hezbollah is believed to be an umbrella for underground factions involved in the kidnapping of the 25 foreigners in lebanon
the longest held foreign hostage is terry a. anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press. he was seized in moslem west beirut march 16, 1985
a former argentine general accused of kidnapping and killing civilians in his country was told his refusal to answer lawyers' questions would harm him in a u.s. civil suit by a former prisoner
u.s. district judge samuel conti told carlos suarez mason on wednesday that if he continued his silence, any fact he was asked about would be considered true for the purposes of the $20 million lawsuit
suarez mason, who is fighting extradition to argentina, defied an order by a federal magistrate earlier this week and refused to answer questions about his alleged responsibility for atrocities in military prisons during the late 1970s
the proposed questions include whether suarez mason had authority to order torture and executions at prisons run by the first army corps, which he commanded from 1976 to 1979
the former general said monday he would not answer questions without having a lawyer. the issue of whether the lawyer suarez mason has hired for the extradition case must also represent him in three civil suits without additional pay is now before the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals
conti told the lawyers to submit written questions and ordered suarez mason to be ready to answer on march 28, a day before the scheduled trial of the civil suit and a week after his scheduled extradition hearing before another judge
suarez mason, 63, is charged in argentina with 43 murders and 24 kidnappings of civilians, allegedly committed by soldiers under his command during the so-called ``dirty war'' against suspected leftists
he fled argentina after a civilian government came to power in 1983 and was arrested in january 1987 at his home in foster city, south of san francisco. he is being held without bail
three civil suits have been filed against him by former argentinians now living in the united states, who say they were tortured or their relatives were killed by soldiers under the general's command. u.s. courts have allowed damage suits for acts committed abroad in violation of international law by a foreigner who is physicially in the court's district
a witness said at the kidnapping trial of abbas hamadi that a lebanese mediator may have been involved in the 1987 abduction of two west germans whom he was reputedly working to free
ronnie andrea klein told the court wednesday that she once lived with the mediator, businessman rashid mahroum, and had last talked with him in november 1987
i had a feeling that he (mahroum) might be involved with the kidnappings,'' she said
mahroum, who now lives in lebanon, has denied any involvement in the january 1987 kidnapping of west germans rudolf cordes and alfred schmidt in beirut
hamadi is on trial in duesseldorf on charges of masterminding the abductions in a bid to win the release of his brother, mohammed hamadi, who is charged in connection with the 1985 hijacking of a twa airliner
the west german government last year arranged for mahroum to act as a middleman with the captors of cordes and schmidt
federal police have said they are now seeking mahroum for questioning in the kidnappings
ms. klein told the court she lived with mahroum in the west german city of fuerth from april 1984 to december 1985, and that the two were still on friendly terms up to late last year
i last spoke to him on the telephone in november,'' ms. klein said, adding she believed he was then in beirut
mahroum traveled to beirut as a mediator in february 1987, returning with a photocopy of cordes' passport and demands by his captors that west germany reject a u.s. extradition request for mohammed hamadi
are you aware if he (mahroum) has any special political or religious convictions?'' chief judge klaus arend asked ms. klein
none that i know of,'' she testified
west german security officials say they believe cordes is being held by hezbollah, or party of god, a radical shiite moslem group with close ties to iran
mohammed hamadi is being held in a frankfurt prison, awaiting trial on charges of air piracy and murder in connection with the june 1985 hijacking. no date has been set for the trial
thirty-nine americans were held hostage for 17 days and a u.s. navy diver was killed during the twa hijacking
west germany last year turned down the u.s. extradition request, saying it would try mohammed hamadi instead
in earlier trial testimony, chancellor helmut kohl's chief of staff, wolfgang schaeuble, said the government was forced into making that decision, fearing for the lives of cordes and schmidt
schmidt and cordes were kidnapped in beirut shortly after the jan. 13, 1987 arrest in frankfurt of mohammed hamadi. cordes remains a hostage in lebanon, but schmidt was released in september
another west german, ralph rudolph shray, was kidnapped on jan. 27 and remains a hostage. there have been no claims for that abduction
abbas hamadi's trial resumes march 1, with further testimony expected about mahroum
the census bureau called today for local govrnment help updating the accuracy of maps to be used in the 1990 national head count
each of the approximately 39,000 municipal and county governments across the nation will be sent a computer-drawn map next month, showing the most current boundaries on file at the bureau
census officials are asking that local government leaders review these maps and make any changes necessary
even if local boundaries have not changed, local leaders were urged to carefully inspect the maps, which are the first prepared by the bureau's new computerized mapping system, said robert w. marx of the census geography office. he said the agency wants to promptly catch any errors that may have occurred in preparing the maps
the bureau estimates that one municipality in five has had some boundary change since the 1980 census through annexations, detachments, incorporation or disincorporation. of snow, negotiators adjourning after marathon session, new comments from federal mediator, transition. pickup 11th graf, `union negotiators...</note>
a strike by public school teachers set for today was put on hold this morning as union negotiators considered the district's latest contract offer and school officials canceled classes because of snow
talks recessed at 6:30 a.m. today when negotiators for the cleveland teachers union agreed to take the school board's latest proposal to the union's executive board later in the day
superintendent alfred tutela called off classes for the district's 72,639 students, citing the weather, although no other area school districts were closed. cleveland received up to 3 inches of snow overnight
the district is ohio's largest public school system
union negotiators had set a bargaining deadline of 3 p.m. wednesday and a strike deadline of midnight, but talks continued into early this morning at a downtown hotel under the supervision of federal mediator jack buettner
union president eugene kolach said teachers would not set up picket lines outside schools because classes had been canceled. he declined further comment
the union's executive board agreed to meet at 3 p.m. today to consider the board's proposal, buettner said. he declined to say whether he believed the proposal could lead to a tentative contract
both sides were probably shooting for higher goals than they were able to obtain,'' buettner said. ``there are several stumbling blocks, and i can't really get into a lot of detail.''
the union, which has 5,093 members, has been without a contract since sept. 1
the school system had planned to close schools if a strike materialized, but continue classes for the district's 3,600 high school seniors
bargainers would not comment on details of the negotiations, but both sides have differed on the issues of teacher salaries and a career ladder system
the latest bargaining session began at 10 a.m. tuesday and continued almost non-stop until 6:30 a.m. today, except for a three-hour break wednesday night. buettner shuttled offers back and forth between the bargaining committees, which were in separate rooms at downtown hotel
tutela last month urged teachers to accept a mandatory career ladder system that would hinge pay raises to performance evaluations
union negotiators have said they want participation in the career ladder to be an option
the union had been seeking a 5.8 percent wage increase this year, while the district was offering a 2 percent one-time bonus payment. union negotiators said the amount of the increases could vary depending on the length of the proposed contract
annual salaries for teachers range from $17,687 for beginners to $37,457 for teachers with a master's degree and 35 years experience. the average teacher pay is $29,000
the union represents classroom teachers, guidance counselors, teacher aides, librarians and reading specialists
about 40 parents and others staged a demonstration wednesday outside the hotel where talks were being held to encourage continued negotiations. the rally was organized by the interchurch council of greater cleveland. court rulings; pickup 6th graf: `falwell stood...'</note>
a u.s. supreme court ruling overturning a $200,000 award won by the rev. jerry falwell against hustler magazine has dashed a legal argument that could have stifled political satire, constitutional lawyers say
the unanimous decision wednesday held that even pornographic parodies about public figures are protected by the first amendment as long as the satire could not be reasonably interpreted as factual
the decision was greeted with relief by first amendment specialists
i've been telling my class, if that one makes it, we're in trouble, the first amendment is in serious difficulty,'' said professor c. thomas dienes of the george washington university national law center
falwell had successfully argued in lower courts that he had suffered emotional distress as a result of an ad parody in hustler's november 1983 and march 1984 issues. the ``advertisement'' had a photograph of falwell and purportedly quoted him discussing a sexual encounter with his mother and describing himself as a habitual drunkard. at the bottom in small print, readers were told that the ad was ``not to be taken seriously.''
the jury in the original falwell suit found that there was no libel, but awarded falwell $200,000 after finding the magazine parody had intentionally caused him emotional distress
falwell stood by his arguments wednesday
i fully appreciate the deep concerns the court has shown for the sacredness of the first amendement,'' falwell said in a statement. ``however, i respectfully disagree with their ruling. just as no person may scream ``fire!'' in a crowded theater when there is no fire, and find cover under the first amendment, likewise, no sleaze-merchant like (hustler publisher) larry flynt should be able to use the first amendment as an excuse for maliciously and dishonestly attacking public figures as he has so often done
i believe the supreme court has given the green light to larry flynt and his ilk to print what they wish about any public figure at any time with no fear of reprisal.''
but first amendment lawyers said falwell's claim of distress as the basis for a libel judgment invited such chaos in the libel field that even such supreme court justices as william rehnquist and antonin scalia, not considered steadfast supporters of press rights, could not accept it
the high court also rejected falwell's claim that the parody was libelous because of its ``outrageousness.''
the concept of outrageousness is so ambiguous that it is just not viable as a basis for first amendment standards,'' said dienes. ``if they allowed that, it would have opened an incredible amount of litigation against the media. just imagine the number of parodies that cause humiliation, embarrassment.''
don gillmor, director of the university of minnesota's silha center for the study of media ethics and law, said the language in falwell's argument actually dates back to an 1897 case in england, wilkinson vs. downston, which held that a statement could be libelous if it was ``extreme and outrageous exceeding all reasonable bounds of decency, leading to emotional distress that is severe and is intentionally reckless.''
gillmor said the high court apparently rejected that theory because it ``opened up indefinition, confusion and even judicial chaos, and (the supreme court) just didn't want to deal with it. even if they didn't like the press protections, this doctrine was just too complex an alternative.''
i think rough-and-tumble should be the rule,'' said a.e. dick howard, a university of virginia law professor. ``i think the opinion is right on.''
iran said today that saudi arabia has forbidden a representative of iranian revolutionary patriarch ayatollah ruhollah khomeini from visiting the country to prepare for the moslem pilgrimage
the official islamic republic news agency quoted prime minister hussein musavi as saying this was evidence of the insolence of the saudi government. the agency did not provide a direct quote
it said the saudis refused to let emam jamarani, khomeini's representative and head of the pilgrimage and religious endowments organization, travel to saudi arabia in preparation of the july gathering
last summer, riots in the holy city of mecca during the pilgrimage left 402 people dead, more than half of them iranians. tehran said police sprayed pilgrims with machine-gun fire. riyadh said the violence was planned by iran and many of the victims died in stampedes
there was no immediate saudi response to musavi's comments
saudi arabian interior minister prince nayef has affirmed that the kingdom will not tolerate a recurrence of last year's ``sacrilegious acts.''
any acts against the safety and security of the pilgrims and the holy sites will be sternly dealt with,'' he said
iran has said it plans to send 150,000 pilgrims this year and will organize ``antipathy towards pagans'' rallies again, similar to the event last year that ended in death
moslems are required to undertake the pilgrimage at least once in their life if they can afford it
robert bork said today the defeat of his supreme court nomination has discouraged lawyers from publishing controversial legal articles and advised future nominees to consider waging a national campaign to get on the court
i think this has been very bad for the intellectual life of the law,'' said bork, who resigned as a federal appeals court judge three weeks ago
his experience has led several lawyers to withdraw articles from legal publications, bork said in an interview on abc's ``good morning america.'' he described the new lawyers' credo as: ``express only noble sentiments and arrive at only noncontroversial results.''
bork said judges who have written less than he has could simply refuse to answer questions about their judicial philosophy at confirmation hearings, but he felt it necessary to discuss issues about which he had written
it certainly will inhibit the development of their thought, and it will certainly inhibit the development of the law's evolving intellectual structure,'' he said
bork said that as a judge he did not think it proper for him to wage a media campaign for his appointment, but said of future nominees: ``i would advise them to think about it because i think the alternative is defeat if this kind of campaign is waged against them.''
bork said he wished the white house had done more to counter the media and mail campaign against his nomination, which was rejected by the senate
the white house was caught flat-foooted by an unexpectedly virilent campaign and just didn't get around to responding in time. i understand that,'' said bork, who is joining the institute for public policy research, an educational and research organization that says it takes no positions on public policy issues. soldiers</head>
police today sealed off a busy street in belfast's main shopping area after a bomb planted by the irish republican army killed two british soldiers and injured two others and a civilian
while police investigated the explosion, a soldier charged in the shooting death of a roman catholic civilian was freed on bail and then turned over to military custody
the ira, which is fighting to end british rule in northern ireland, claimed responsibility for the wednesday night bombing in a telephoned statement to belfast news organizations
police said pvt. james cummings and pvt. frederick starrett, both 22, were killed by the remote-controlled explosive as they locked the steel anti-terrorist gates on royal avenue in downtown belfast. two soldiers and a 57-year-old civilian bystander were slightly injured
belfast police said the bomb probably contained about 150 pounds of explosives. the blast shattered the windows of shops and offices several hundred yards away
northern ireland secretary tom king called the attack ``a carefully planned and very vicious one indeed.''
the anti-terrorist gates are guarded by ulster defense regiment soldiers, who search the bags and other items of shoppers and others passing in and out during the day
police said the bomb went off at 11 p.m. when few civilians were about and that there was no warning from the bombers
the two deaths brought northern ireland's death toll since sectarian and political violence flared in 1969 to at least 2,628
on wednesday, police charged an 18-year-old british soldier, pvt. david jonathan holden, with unlawfully killing an unarmed catholic civilian last sunday. a northern ireland court today turned holden over to military custody on $1,925 bail
the defense said holden will plead innocent to the charge of unlawfully killing aidan mcanespie, 23, from an army observation post at a checkpoint near auchnacloy, half a mile from the irish republic's border. holden's court appearance is set for march 9
mcanespie was an election worker for sinn fein, the legal political arm of the ira. the british army said mcanespie was killed by a ricocheting bullet after a machine gun was fired accidentally
but cardinal tomas o fiaich, roman catholic primate of all ireland, has said he believes mcanespie was murdered. catholic leaders in the province said mcanespie had been regularly harassed by the army
an off-duty police officer shot a man to death early today during an armed robbery attempt in a restaurant after the man reached for a weapon and challenged the officer to shoot him, police say
the shooting was the fifth involving dallas police in less than two months. six people have died, including two officers
shoot me,'' dallas police lt. ron waldrop quoted the man as telling the off-duty officer as he reached for the weapon in his waistband. the officer was not in uniform
the man was shot twice and was pronounced dead at the scene, waldrop said
police withheld the names of the officer and the victim
we are still doing the interviews,'' detective rick silva said. ``more details will be available later.''
the off-duty officer entered a denny's restaurant in southwest dallas to purchase food when he saw that a man had confronted a waitress near a cash register, waldrop said
the officer said he heard the man demand money and saw what appeared to be a pistol in the man's waistband, waldrop said. investigators later discovered that the weapon was actually a knife with a handle similar to a pistol's, waldrop said
the officer displayed his badge and gun and identified himself, waldrop said. it was then that the man went for the weapon and challenged the officer to shoot him
dallas police have come under fire by minority leaders and city hall in the past two years for being trigger-happy when confronting suspects, especially blacks and hispanics
however, tension flared last month after police chief billy prince accused council members of fostering anti-police sentiment that led to the death of officer john chase in a highly publicized shooting jan. 23
witnesses told police that chase was shot by a transient who had wrestled his gun from him and was egged on by some spectators. the transient was later shot to death after firing at police
since then, many rallies have been staged in support of the department. 02-25 0486</first>
president reagan's assertion that secretary of state george p. shultz and former defense secretary caspar w. weinberger did not object to the idea of an arms-for-hostages deal with iran goes against earlier statements by himself and the two cabinet officers
the president, responding to a question about whether vice president george bush objected to the failed policy, said at his news conference wednesday night that he did not ``want to be surrounded by yes men. and yes, there were reservations.''
the president, as in the past, declined to elaborate on bush's role. he then pointed to shultz and weinberger as others who voiced objections _ but he said they were not opposed to the basic policy
they did not object to the idea that we were trading arms for hostages,'' the president said
he said that shultz and weinberger ``knew what we were trying to do'' and implied their main concern was public image
their objection was that, if and when this became known, as it would be, it would appear that we were trading hostages for, or arms for hostages,'' he said
a year ago, after the two cabinet secretaries complained about the tower commission report statement that they didn't fight the policy hard enough, reagan backed their position
both secretary shultz and secretary weinberger advised me strongly not to pursue the initiative,'' he said. ``i weighed their advice and decided in the end that the initiative was worth the risk and went forward.''
shultz, asked about the comments today during a flight to israel, said he had testified ``endlessly'' and that it was based largely on his own records
i am not going to go over it anymore,'' he said. ``i've testified and i really don't have anything to add or subtract because my testimony is based to a very healthy extent on records and notes and so on.''
shultz and weinberger, testifying last summer before congressional investigators, said they were kept in the dark by the white house aides arranging the deals
shultz said he was ``sick to my stomach'' when he first learned some of the details of the policy. he said he fought a ``battle royal'' to make sure reagan was aware of what was going on
both shultz and weinberger said they objected to the plans in 1985 and at a dec. 7 meeting that year ``i made a very strong objection to the whole idea, as did the secretary of state,'' weinberger said
weinberger said he objected because the united states was asking other countries not to sell arms to iran, that there was no one reliable to deal with there, and that if it were an arms-for-hostages deal the government was laying itself open to blackmail. three</head> weight of coins broke through roof of armored truck, other details. no pickup. corrects style of brink's, sted brinks, in 7th graf, bgng `the guard...'; adds byline.</note>
an armored truck hauling $400,000 in coins overturned on a freeway, spilling a torrent of change that broke through the truck's roof and scattered across the lanes, authorities said today
three people were treated for minor injuries
the weight of the coins actually blew the top of the vehicle right out,'' said california highway patrol officer lyle whitten, describing the accident late wednesday on the eastbound pomona freeway
a guard riding in the back of the truck was ejected by the force, but he escaped serious injury
he wasn't buried (in coins), and that's what saved him,'' whitten said
the guard and two other people in the truck were treated and released at queen of the valley hospital for minor injuries, said nursing supervisor terri coleman. their names were not released
i understand they're all ok,'' said bill beamon of brink's inc. in san bernardino
the three-ton armored truck was hauling $400,000 in coins from los angeles to san bernardino-area banks when both right rear dual tires blew out, whitten said
the truck careened out of control and rolled onto its side as boxes of coins knocked the roof off and scattered onto the freeway lanes
brink's and highway patrol officials said they couldn't estimate the weight of the coins, but nelson italiano at the union plaza casino in las vegas said an average weight of the various coins could equal 38 tons
it's approximately a half-million dollars in the no. 4 (lane), the on ramp and the right shoulder,'' said officer richard perez of the highway patrol
most of the money was boxed, whitten said, but about $300 in loose half dollars, quarters, dimes, nickels and pennies rolled across some 35 feet of roadway
sgt. john williams, an off-duty highway patrol motorcycle officer, on his way home from work, saw the accident and stopped to secure the area, whitten said
people had already started to stop, even before he got off his motorcycle ... and he shooed them away.''
another brink's truck carrying paper money stopped to help the victims, whitten said
the highway patrol shut down several freeway lanes as brink's employees gathered the boxed and loose change and loaded it into another armored vehicle, dispatcher sabrina elswick said. most of the money was recovered, officials said
police are everywhere guarding it; you couldn't get near it,'' said los angeles county fire capt. art montgomery
industry is about 15 miles southeast of downtown los angeles. against murphree. pickup 20th graf, `tampa police...'</note>
pentecostal leaders gathered today to deliberate the fate of tv evangelist jimmy swaggart after an admitted prostitute said she performed pornographic acts for him for about a year
the woman's account, in a new orleans television interview wednesday, added to pressures besetting the executive presbytery of the assemblies of god, at its international headquarters here
the nation's largest pentecostal denomination, which gets $12 million a year from jimmy swaggart world ministries in baton rouge, la., reported being swamped with up to 300 calls an hour since the evangelist confessed last sunday to unspecified sexual misconduct
about half of the callers complained that the denomination's louisiana council's recommendation that swaggart be suspended from preaching for three months and receive counseling was too lenient, said juleen turnage, assemblies' secretary of information
a lot of people are unhappy with the initial recommendation,'' said the rev. richard champion, editor of the denomination's weekly, pentecostal evangel. ``many thought it too light. some thought it too severe.''
mrs. turnage said public sentiment would not be a factor for 12 presbyters who planned to convene this afternoon in a closed session to discuss swaggart's punishment
the church's final verdict will be in accord with ``the seriousness of the offense,'' mrs. turnage said
an unwritten church precedent is that those involved in sexual offenses are barred from preaching for at least a year. ``it's never been less than a year,'' she said
church sources raised the possibility that the presbytery could instruct the louisiana district council to reconsider its recommendations on grounds that members of swaggart's board improperly participated and the results were announced prematurely
it created tremendous pressures, appearing that the louisiana district was trying to dictate its judgment,'' said the rev. howard cummings of aurora, colo., a former district presbyter
swaggart, whose ministry brought in $142 million in 1986, is the denomination's most prominent evangelist with fire-and-brimstone broadcasts in more than 100 countries. he has been known for his harsh denunciations of sexual lapses by other preachers, including ptl founder jim bakker
evangelist marvin gorman has a $90 million lawsuit pending against swaggart, claiming swaggart falsely accused him of numerous acts of adultery. gorman reportedly gave the denomination photographs of swaggart entering and leaving a motel room with a prostitute
a woman who gave her name as debra murphree told wvue-tv of new orleans that she had met with swaggart for about a year at various motels to perform pornographic acts
to me, i think he's kind of perverted or, you know, talking about some of the things that we talked about in the rooms, you know, i wouldn't want him around my children,'' murphree told a reporter who traced her to a motel in west palm beach, fla., on wednesday
the station did not say how the reporter tracked the woman down, but said it did not pay for the interview
the station quoted her as saying she was the woman with swaggart when he was photographed last october, and that she did not have sexual intercourse with swaggart
he wanted me to get naked and maybe lay on the bed and pose for him,'' she said
he asked me if he could take me home and get dressed up in a dress or something, you know, no underwear and ride around you know and just, maybe in the evening, and take my clothes off and maybe get out of the car and just get back in and, you know, it sort of turned him on.''
the jefferson parish sheriff, in new orleans' western suburbs, said wednesday that murphree had been arrested for soliciting for prostitution. police in tampa, fla., similarly reported that murphree had been arrested in 1985 and 1986 for loitering for prostitution and soliciting for exposure
tampa police said murphree also was known to them as deborah arlene hedge, 28, a native of princeton, ind
murphree said her trysts with swaggart occurred in motels on airline highway between new orleans and baton rouge. she said swaggart would pick her up once or twice a month in his telephone-equipped lincoln town car
she said swaggart never discussed god or religion with her
the washington post reported today that witnesses said swaggart wore hats, sunglasses and headbands, or combed his hair down in front to help disguise himself
murphree said she was sure her companion was swaggart even though he did not use his name:
oh, i knew who he was.''
a new drug for treating endometriosis may provide an alternative for women unable to tolerate the side effects of the only medicine now available for this common condition, doctors say
a report published today concludes that the drug, called nafarelin, works as well as danazol, the standard medical treatment
about 5 percent of all women during their reproductive years have endometriosis. the disorder occurs when tissue from the lining of the uterus grows in other places in the female reproductive system. symptoms can include back and abdominal pain during or after menstrual periods. severe cases may require drug treatment or surgery
although danazol is highly effective, some women cannot take it because of its side effects. nafarelin also causes some unwanted symptoms, but experts say these may be less offensive to some patients
a report on a comparison of the two drugs in 213 women was published in the new england journal of medicine. the test was directed by dr. milan r. henzi of syntex research, a pharmaceutical firm in palo alto, calif
in my opinion, this is the best-designed and best-executed trial of drug therapy for endometriosis ever reported,'' dr. robert l. barbieri of harvard medical school wrote in an accompanying editorial
danazol is derived from the male sex hormone testosterone. some women who take it complain of weight gain, swelling, acne, hair growth and deepening of the voice, among other side effects. danazol also causes unfavorable changes in blood cholesterol levels
nafarelin, which is given as a nasal spray, does not affect cholesterol levels, but it has other side effects, mainly hot flashes, descreased sex drive and vaginal dryness
in the study, both drugs reduced the extent of the disease in more than 80 percent of patients
barbieri said that for women who cannot tolerate danazol, nafarelin ``represents an important therapeutic alternative.''
the new drug is one of a class of synthetic hormones that temporarily shut off the body's production of sex hormones. nafarelin is also being tested as a treatment for prostate enlargement in men. currently, the drug is approved by the u.s. food and drug administration only for treatment of prostate cancer. protest services; predictions of violence and additional comments from critics. no pickup.</note>
two south african church leaders, including anglican archbishop desmond tutu, today called for nationwide services to protest the government crackdown on 18 opposition groups
i hope our people will still be willing to try non-violent strategies. ... but we have nothing to show for our non-violent approaches. if violence erupts, what will be surprising is that it has taken so long,'' said tutu, who won the 1984 nobel peace prize for his fight against apartheid
tutu met with the rev. frank chikane, general-secretary of the south african council of churches, to discuss a response to the orders banning political activities by the opposition organizations
i would not be surprised if they (the government) act against the church,'' chikane told reporters
the meeting took place at khotso house, the johannesburg headquarters for many of the restricted organizations. black paper was draped at khotso house as a sign of mourning
both clergymen appealed to the black majority not to lose hope, to white voters to disassociate themselves from the government, and to the international community to isolate south africa
newspapers, business leaders and politicans criticized the government, saying the suppression of the major black political groups would provoke violence
in lusaka, zambia, the outlawed african national congress called for ``resistance and defiance.'' the anc is the main guerrilla organization fighting to end white-minority domination in south africa
the organizations and civic bodies that have thus been banned were committed to non-violent forms of struggle,'' the anc said in a statement
it is not advocacy of or engagement in armed struggle that the regime fears, but the very expression of democratic opposition.''
president p.w. botha on wednesday gave law and order minister adriaan vlok the power to prohibit all activity by any organization. vlok immediately banned 17 organizations, including the largest anti-apartheid coalition, the united democratic front, from engaging in political activities
he also prohibited the nation's largest labor federation, the 750,000-member congress of south african trade unions, from engaging in any political activity, including commemorating days of importance to blacks
in addition, restrictions were imposed on the activities of individual black leaders
i regret the further erosion of the rule of law. ... banning and detentions can never be the solution,'' said the rev. allan hendrickse, leader of the mixed-race house of parliament. whites and people of mixed race are represented in parliament, but not the 26 million black majority
colin eglin, leader of the anti-apartheid progressive federal party, said, ``the government was busy turning south africa into a third-grade banana republic where real power is not with the parliament, the courts or the people but in the hands of a restricted political clique.''
gavin relly, chairman of anglo-american corp., the nation's biggest conglomerate, said, ``the curtailment of civil and political freedoms to the interests of public order should be subject to judicial control. yesterday's actions are steps away from the rule of law.''
the new nation, a newspaper for blacks published by the south african catholic bishops conference, was among several observers predicting increased violence because of the regulations, which vlok said were meant to improve the atmosphere of peace and security
trade unionists have warned that by banning the commemoration of days of mourning, the government has set the stage for massive confrontation,'' the new nation said. ``the ban is unlikely to stop workers from observing these days.''
the citizen, a pro-government newspaper, said the government actions were inevitable but added: ``suppression of radical or revolutionary movements does not solve the country's problems. it only provides the space within which solutions can be found.''
the orders ``violate a number of basic freedoms, more particularly the freedoms of association and expression,'' said robert charlton, vice chancellor of the university of the witwatersrand. he said the clampdown would provoke protest and disruption on campuses
the large black political organization inkatha was not among those restricted. but the leadership in the kwazulu legislative assembly, headed by inkatha leader mangosuthu buthelezi, condemned the restriction of black organizations, including those with which inkatha has been feuding
there would be no need for the state of emergency if black democracy was unshackled and if blacks were free to support the leaders and the parties of their choice,'' the kwazulu caucus said. soviet union</head> dishonorable discharge. pickup 3rd graf, `the sentence...</note>
a military judge today convicted an army private who fled his west german post for the soviet union on a charge of being absent without leave, rejecting the more serious charge of desertion
pfc. wade e. roberts received a bad conduct discharge and was stripped of his military benefits, but avoided imprisonment. he could have faced one year of hard labor on the awol conviction
the sentence, imposed by col. earl pauley, brought moans and gasps from those in the courtroom
the military's lawyer, capt. daniel shaver, who prosecuted the case, said afterward he was shocked by the sentence and had expected roberts to serve prison time
roberts and his wife hugged and kissed after the verdict was announced
roberts fled his base at giessen, west germany, on feb. 28 and traveled with his girlfriend, petra neumann, to the soviet union. he returned to west germany on nov. 4, and was arrested the following day
the military had pressed for the desertion charge in the two-day court-martial at fort dix
roberts' attorney, ronald kuby, said pauley's decision showed ``we're not going to have a political trial, we're not going to have a show trial. we're not going to punish people because they make friends in the soviet union.''
roberts testified earlier today that he returned to the west from his eight-month self-imposed exile to the soviet union because he and his pregnant girlfriend became disenchanted with communism and feared being trapped there
i wanted to get out of the country,'' roberts said. ``we didn't like it.''
the riverside, calif., serviceman calmly told the court that he and his girlfriend, whom he later wed, didn't like their work at a soviet snake laboratory. he also said that he feared that if his son was born there, he would automatically be granted soviet citizenship
we felt if he were a soviet citizen, we'd be trapped there, and we wouldn't be able to leave,'' roberts said
on wednesday roberts testified he was told to stop seeing ms. neumann
i was told by my first sergeant i shouldn't see my wife anymore _ at the time, she wasn't my wife _ she was pregnant,'' roberts said. ``i was put on restriction, and i was experiencing some problems with my sergeants
i left, and i went to petra's apartment,'' he added. ``i stayed away for over 30 days, and eventually i ended up in the soviet union.''
kuby, said roberts' actions didn't meet the legal definition of desertion: unauthorized absence with no intent to return to the military
wade roberts panicked,'' kuby said. ``he didn't want to be separated from his wife.''
shaver called more than a half-dozen witnesses to the stand to establish that roberts didn't like his unit, had disciplinary problems and wanted to leave
one witness, alfred santos, a security officer at the u.s. embassy in bonn, said he spoke by telephone to roberts the day of his arrest. santos said roberts pleaded to be allowed to turn himself in to embassy officials
he said ... words to the effect he didn't trust the military ... and that he didn't want to go back,'' said santos
kuby argued that roberts maintained his u.s. citizenship while in the soviet union and kept his military identification card
roberts' attorneys argued he was the target of ``selective and vindictive prosecution,'' and that he was being tried because he fled to a communist country. they asked that the charge be dismissed
kuby said that of the 1,048 awol or desertion cases processed last year at fort dix, fewer than 10 resulted in prosecutions
but shaver contended the army has prosecuted cases like roberts'. he said roberts' choice of the soviet union is a legitimate factor in determining whether to proceed with desertion charges
pauley agreed, and said the defense did not prove their client had been singled out
the case is being heard by a judge because roberts exercised his option not to be tried by a jury of five officers and enlisted personnel
ms. neumann attended the court martial, but refused to answer most questions from reporters. the couple have a 2-month-old son
president saddam hussein pardoned a british businessman sentenced to life in prison for bribing iraqi officials after a plea from british prime minister margaret thatcher, officials said today
a british embassy official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the iraqi president pardoned john smith on wednesday as david mellor, a british foreign office minister, held talks with iraqi officials
in london, the foreign office said mellor delivered a letter to the iraqi president from mrs. thatcher asking for his help in obtaining smith's release
it said 46-year-old smith of hazelmere in lancashire had not been released yet. ``we don't expect it to be too long. there are bureaucratic procedures to complete,'' said a spokesman
the foreign office said smith's release ``is the happy culmination of a number of efforts over a number of years.'' it added that ``no deals have been struck.''
the iraqi officials accused of being involved with smith were tried and executed
smith, managing director of the specialist vehicle manufacturer hestair dennis, was arrested in 1979 while talking with an iraqi official in a park
he was convicted in 1980 of bribing officials and sentenced to life imprisonment, which in iraq means 20 years
at the time he was also accused of ``economic espionage'' but it was not clear whether he was ever formally charged or convicted on such a charge
the iraqis convicted in the case were executed according to an iraqi law that prohibits receiving bribes from foreign salesman or providing them with information related to the state
another british businessman, ian rechter, is imprisoned in iraq after being tried in 1987 and convicted of bribing the mayor of baghdad, who was found guilty of taking bribes from rechter and later executed
mellor also pressed for rechter's release but no decision has yet been taken by iraqi authorities. quote. pick up 9th graf pvs: `one unidentified...'</note>
a bomb exploded near a crowded grandstand tonight as thousands of filipinos marked the second anniversary of the overthrow of president ferdinand marcos, police said
elisa florido, a nurse at the medical city hospital, said 14 people were injured, mostly by flying glass and debris. none was seriously hurt, she said, and there were no reports of fatalities
the blast occurred at about 10 p.m. near the main grandstand set up on epifanio de los santos avenue, or edsa, a broad boulevard between two military camps
it was at edsa two years ago that hundreds of thousands of filipinos came to protect mutinous troops from soldiers loyal to marcos. the four-day standoff culminated in his flight to exile in hawaii on feb. 25, 1986
the blast occurred about five hours after president corazon aquino, manila archbishop cardinal jaime l. sin and other dignitaries attended a mass at the grandstand and prayed for peace in this troubled island nation
none of the dignitaries were believed to be at the scene during the blast
no one immediately claimed responsibility for the bombing
the military had been on full alert in case communist rebels or right-wing dissidents tried to disrupt the celebrations
one witness, monica soliman, told radio station dzxl that she and her family were returning to their car when they saw two men behind the stage tying what appeared to be three sticks
when we reached the car, we turned on the radio and suddenly we heard an explosion,'' she said
one unidentified man, interviewed by radio station dzxl, said the blast occurred during a fireworks display
we were watching the fireworks when suddenly something exploded behind us,'' he said. ``my brother was injured in the back.'' the man said he was about 70 feet from the explosion
the blast took place near the end of a daylong celebration that began shortly after dawn with a flag-raising ceremony and a mass, and continued with singing and dancing into the night
earlier, mrs. aquino, defense minister fidel ramos and gen. renato de villa, the military chief of staff, and other senior officials had joined hands with thousands of people for a ``chain of peace'' along edsa. top 11 grafs, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, robertson said</note>
vice president george bush, answering presidential rivals in south carolina, today rejected ``pure, all-out protectionism'' and said existing trade laws are sufficient to help the state's textile industry against foreign imports
bush raised the subject of textiles a day after republican candidate bob dole campaigned in the state and called for passage of legislation restricting foreign textile imports
republican pat robertson has also backed the textile bill and has declared south carolina _ a state where textiles are an important industry _ a major battleground for his campaign
don't go for this pure, all-out protectionism that may save one job and then throw three neighbors in this burgeoning state out of work,'' bush said. ``that isn't the answer.''
he spoke to several hundred students, teachers and others at an assembly at tri-county technical college. he also spoke briefly with students in an industrial electronics class, accompanied by south carolina gov. carroll a. campbell jr., his state campaign chairman
the textile import legislation has support in south carolina and other textile and apparel-producing states of the south. president reagan vetoed similar legislation after it passed congress two years ago
what i propose is that we enforce the law,'' bush said
campaigning wednesday in vermont, bush demanded an apology from robertson for indicating bush's campaign was somehow responsible for the timing of allegations of sexual misconduct against jimmy swaggart, a television evangelist
robertson, however, suggested in louisville, ky., today that if bush had heard exactly what he said there would be no apology demand
i was, frankly, misquoted in the press,'' he said
robertson _ a former television evangelist himself _ said earlier this week he thought it odd that the swaggart controversy erupted just to weeks before super tuesday, when 20 states will choose delegates to the national party conventions, suggesting that the controversy was timed to embarrass him
robertson said he had no proof of political involvement in the swaggart revelations. but in the same interview, robertson accused bush's campaign of ``dirty politics'' and ``trickery.''
by sundown in the old south, i'd like to see him stand up like a southern gentleman with a little evidence,'' bush said wednesday in burlington, vt. ``i'd like to see an apology or proof.''
bush was campaigning today in south carolina, which holds its primary on march 5, three days before the super tuesday contests in 20 states, mostly in the south
bush also expressed puzzlement over another robertson contention _ that his christian broadcasting network at one point had information about the whereabouts of the american hostages in lebanon and that ``they could have been saved.''
robertson spokesmen later said robertson had been referring to passengers and crew members of a twa flight, who were held briefly in lebanon following a 1985 hijacking
my question would be, how come he didn't get a hold of the proper authorities in the united states government that were working day and night, trying to figure out how they could get those people out?'' bush said at a stop in boston
bush, in appearances wednesday in new england, sought to set himself apart from his rivals _ rep. jack kemp, dole, and robertson
you're selecting a president, not a congressman, not a senator, not a preacher,'' he said
on another matter, the vice president said he expected to win in vermont's non-binding presidential primary next tuesday
bush said he did not think his campaign was damaged by a pair of losses in minnesota's gop caucuses and south dakota's primary, both tuesday. dole won in both states
bush's campaign had pulled resources out of south dakota and minnesota in order to concentrate on the contests of march 8, super tuesday
the vice president said he didn't believe the results had any effect on a subject he ``learned the hard way about in 1980 _ momentum.''
during that election, ronald reagan overcame bush's early primary victories to win the republican nomination
reagan, at a nationally broadcast news conference on wednesday night, took the opportunity to defend bush, who has come under questioning on the campaign trail about his role in secret arms sales to iran. bush has refused to detail his advice to the president on the matter, citing confidentiality, but has said he expressed private reservations
reagan corroborated that, adding: ``i don't want to be surrounded by yes men.''
there were reservations, but i'm not going to go into (them) just as he wouldn't go into the private discussions that we may have had,'' the president said
charlotte porter, an editor on the associated press general desk in new york, has been named news editor in the ap's atlanta bureau
carl bell, atlanta chief of bureau, announced the appointment thursday. ms. porter, 33, succeeds mary anne rhyne, who earlier this month was named chief of bureau in hartford, conn
ms. porter, who grew up in lenoir, n.c., was graduated from macalester college in st. paul, minn., and joined the ap in minneapolis in 1976. she worked in the sioux falls and pierre, s.d., offices before transferring to the general desk in 1979. statements.</note>
secretary of state george shultz said today the origins of palestinian rioting in the israeli-occupied west bank are ``essentially indigenous,'' a statement the white house said was consistent with president reagan's assessment that the riots do not appear to be ``home grown.''
shultz, speaking during a flight to jerusalem, where he hopes to amerliorate the conflict in the occupied territories, said, ``it's fundamental origins are essentially indigenous.''
he also told reporters that ``there is an underlying problem consisting of a large number of people in occupation who haven't had the basic rights of governance.''
hours earlier, reagan said at a nationally televised news conference that ``there is every evidence that these riots are not just spontaneous and home grown.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater, asked about the two men's statements, said, ``those are totally consistent.''
the president said the same thing,'' fitzwater told reporters. ``he just said they (the riots) were partly influenced by outside sources.''
he is saying that it is indigenous in the nature of the political problem there but there has been some outside influence as well,'' the spokesman said. ``he is saying exactly what we have said all along.''
fifty-nine people have died since the rioting began, most of them shot by israeli troops
reagan said, ``we have had intimations that there have been certain people suspected of being terrorists, outsiders coming in, not only with weapons, but stirring up and encouraging the trouble in those areas.''
asked about saying the riots were not ``home grown,'' reagan added:
that isn't something you can go out and say we absolutely know, but certainly the violence is both ways.''
shultz said intelligence showed ``a mixed picture'' with ``interaction with outside force.''
but he said ``there is an underlying problem consisting of a large number of people in occupation who haven't had the basic rights of governance. so we seek among other things consistent with israel's security, to look at things that will help palestinians gain legitimate rights.''
reagan offered no evidence to support his assertion that outsiders and terrorists are to blame for the violence, saying security rules prevented him from doing so
he declined to criticize israel's policy of beating large numbers of palestinians and occasionally firing on the protestors
but he said, ``we don't support that sort of thing and we are trying to persuade all the participants to try to arrive at a solution representing justice for all.''
reagan added that ``we have spoken to the government there and we have also spoken to the palestinian leadership because there is every evidence that these riots are not just spontaneous and home-grown.''
previously, administration officials had not given any indication that any outside involvement was suspected in the rioting
the president said ``it's time for us to arrive at a true peace and recognize the rights of all'' in the middle east
he said peace in the middle east ``would be one of the greatest achievements of this administration.''
reagan did not go into detail about u.s. proposals, but israeli officials have already said they oppose two elements. one part is an international conference in april to seek an interim solution in the occupied territories, while the second is a december date for talks to begin on a final settlement
the president said ``it's time for all parties to rid themselves of old ideas and stances that cannot work and to begin a serious process of negotiation and reconciliation.''
any process that is undertaken must meet israel's security needs and satisfy the legitimate rights of the palestinians,'' he said
india successfully test-fired its first surface-to-surface missile thursday, prime minister rajiv gandhi announced in parliament
the missile has a range of 155 miles, used a computer-aided navigation system and could be fitted with different warheads, the united news of india reported
the new missile _ named ``prithvi,'' the hindu word for earth _ was designed by scientists at the government-owned defense research and development organization, the news agency said
gandhi did not say where the test took place
he said india was the fifth country in the world to successfully develop this class of missile, the others being the united states, the soviet union, france and china
in april, india tested its first domestically produced surface-to-air missile. india exploded a nuclear device in 1974, but says its atomic program is for peaceful purposes
the government destroyed more than 41,000 acres of illicit poppies last year, it was reported thursday
the state-owned working people's daily said the government also seized 3,250 pounds of raw opium, 178 pounds of heroin and 66 pounds of morphine base during 1987
the poppies were destroyed both by hand and by aerial spraying of herbicides, it said
in 1986, the government destroyed more than 40,000 acres of poppies and seized 3,900 pounds of raw opium, 105 pounds of heroin and 63 pounds of morphine base, the newspaper said
the opium is grown mostly by hill tribes in eastern burma and refined into heroin by armed trafficking groups operating along the thai-burmese border
it was one of those days for the daily telegraph
the masthead of the wednesday's editions of the newspaper mistakenly said it was thursday, and it reportedly caused havoc throughout the land
the telegraph reported on thursday's front page that one reader complained he had traveled to birmingham a day too soon after being misled by wednesday's paper
someone else went to the dentist a day early, and some elderly readers went to post offices to collect pensions that normally arrive on thursday
several hundred people called to point out the mistake, the paper said
the majority were puzzled and confused,'' it quoted switchboard operator rita sherman as saying. ``but some were very annoyed and upset, particularly those who had traveled all over the place thinking it was thursday and got there before they found out. but a nice cross-section saw a funny side to it.''
the telegraph said the misprint in 300,000 copies of wednesday's final edition
to all of you _ those who saw the funny side and those who did not _ we offer our humble apologies,'' the paper said
more than 75 percent of the 4.6 million tons in food aid needed this year by sub-saharan africa already has been pledged, but ethiopia remains threatened by famine, a u.n. group said thursday
thirty-five of sub-sahara's 42 countries still have unmet food aid needs of 1 million tons, according to a report issued in nairobi by the rome-based u.n. food and agriculture organization
nine of those countries _ angola, benin, botswana, chad, ethiopia, madagascar, malawi, mozambique and niger _ will require exceptional emergency relief, the statement said
althoe than 1 million of the 1.3 million tons of food aid needed by drought-stricken ethiopia, relief operations there face logistical problems, the report said
edouard saouma, fao director general, appealed to donors to send ethiopia trucks, spare parts, fuel and port-handling equipment. pvs, the opinion</note>
the federal election commission said today it is all right for a presidential campaign to write off half the cost of a tv ad as a fund-raising expense even if the overt money solicitation is only a tiny part of the commercial
in its 4-2 decision, the commission signaled to the presidential campaigns that it will allow a practice that some critics have said is a method of evading the state spending limits imposed on the campaigns
dissenting from the ruling, commissioner joan aikens said the agency was merely ``sanctioning creative accounting to get around the limits.''
i think we are absolutely blowing the state limits out of the water,'' she said
but other commission members said the fec should not be getting involved with scrutinizing every campaign ad to determine what portion contained a fund-raising appeal
commissioner thomas josefiak said that even if an ad appears to be mostly issue-related, as long as it has an overt fund-raising message as well as information on how to contribute _ such as a telephone number to call _ the ad can be considered to have a dual purpose. in that case, a 50 percent allocation for fund-raising would be appropriate, the commission determined
fund-raising allocations are important to presidential campaigns because they are not counted against the federally mandated limits on spending in each state
the opinion comes in answer to a query from sen. albert gore jr., the democratic contender from tennessee, whose staff complained about the approach used in ioa by rivals rep. richard gephardt of missouri and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
the issue involves how much of the costs of tv ads can be excluded from the total that a campaign spends against an expenditure ceiling in each state. fund-raising costs are not counted against the cap, which in iowa this year was $775,000
gore did not mention the other campaigns in his request for an fec opinion, but posed his question as a hypothetical involving a 60-second ad for his own campaign, with a fund-raising appeal in the last three seconds
gore asked if he could count only 50 percent of that ad's cost against the cap. the legal counsel's opinion was that 5 percent would be a more reasonable figure
gore's hypothetical paralleled gephardt's commercial in iowa in which the final seconds contained the request for viewers to ``vote, volunteer, contribute.'' gephardt excluded half the cost from the spending his campaign allocated to iowa
such a practice is valuable in iowa because all of the campaigns wanted to spend large sums to get high visibility in the nation's first democratic caucus
dukakis also ran ads that contained only a brief fund-raising appeal at the end, with the rest of the ad focused on issues, and he counted 40 percent as fund-raising
in response to gore's question, the fec legal staff said that writing off part of the ads as a fund-raising expense is legitimate. but the opinion said the write-off should be generally proportional to the portion of the ad that contains a fund-raising message
the fec opinion by counsel larry noble said that a 50 percent writeoff for that would not be reasonable
given that the only appeal to contribute occurs in the final three seconds of the 60-second spot, an allocation of 5 percent (or less) to the exclusion would be reasonable,'' the opinon said
the gephardt and dukakis campaigns had cited the precedent of sen. john glenn's presidential campaign in 1984, in which the fec allowed a 50 percent fund-raising writeoff for glenn's half-hour tv show
noble's opinion noted that the fec decides such matters on a case-by-case basis
campaigns use the fec case-specific rulings, however, as guidelines for their own activities
president reagan broke his silence about the candidates vying for his job, slapping out at republican pat robertson, defending vice president george bush and ridiculing the democrats, saying, ``the kids will play.''
the president, in fielding questions wednesday night at his first news conference in four months, also gave strong backing to his embattled attorney general, edwin meese, saying, ``i have every confidence in his integrity.''
however, reagan refused to comment on the investigation of meese's role in a proposed middle east oil pipeline. reagan said he had no recollection of knowing about the pipeline deal until recently
a relaxed reagan opened with a smile, saying ``on the networks at last'' _ a gibe at abc, cbs and nbc for refusing to broadcast his feb. 2 speech appealing for contra aid
however, he appeared uncomfortable at times, saying he was not aware of federal reserve chairman alan greenspan's complaint in senate testimony earlier wednesday that the administration was putting too much election-year pressure on the fed to lower interest rates
in his testimony, greenspan was highly critical of a letter sent by assistant treasury secretary michael darby to top fed policy-makers 10 days before they were to meet to set monetary growth targets for 1988
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater, asked today if the administration agreed with greenspan, said, ``yes, we do. we have the highest regard for chairman greenspan and the work he's doing, (we're) very concerned about any pressure being applied to the fed because they are an independent body, doing an outstanding job.''
at his news conference, reagan also contradicted his own previous statements and those of secretary of state george shultz and former defense secretary caspar weinberger by claiming the two had not objected to the secret sale of arms to iran on grounds it was an arms-for-hostages deal
shultz and weinberger have said otherwise, and the iran-contra report issued by two congressional committees said the secretaries ``called it a straight arms-for-hostages deal that was contrary to u.s. public policy.''
brushing aside questions on the seemingly differing statements, fitzwater said today, ``i don't feel they need any reconciliation. these are all matters of interpretation.''
reagan has tried from the start of the political campaign to steer clear of the presidential race, but he suddenly switched course with an open slap at robertson
the former television evangelist had said earlier in the day that his own christian broadcasting network once knew the whereabouts of american hostages in lebanon ``and they could have been freed'' if the united states had acted promptly
in reply, reagan said that if robertson knew where the hostages were being held, ``he kept it to himself.'' the president said it would be ``very strange'' if it happened the way robertson described it
as for the plight of the nine americans now held in lebanon, reagan declared, ``we've never let up, and we never will'' in trying to obtain their freedom
robertson, campaigning in louisville, ky., said today that reporters for his network did have hostage information in 1985, that he offered the information to the major television networks and that he was then contacted by low-level state department officials
reacting to reagan's skepticism, he said, ``i wasn't meaning to start some major confrontation with a person i admire tremendously, but obviously the state department must have dismissed what we had to say, or else they didn't refer it up the line to the president.''
in defense of bush, reagan corroborated the vice president's claim that he had expressed private reservations about selling arms to iran
the president said he put down orders that ``i don't want to be surrounded by `yes' men. and, yes, there were reservations, but i'm not going to go into (them) just as he wouldn't go into the private discussions that we may have had.''
asked about democrats' charges that his administration has been plagued by corruption, reagan sidestepped the question and instead accused democrats of misrepresenting his administration's record on the economy
if anyone listened for more than 15 minutes to their candidates, he would decide that we're in an economic slump, we're burdened by inflation, high interest rates and unemployment when, at the moment, none of those things are true. ..
so, i just think that, you know, the kids will play, and as long as they want to do that, but i hope it'll easily be forgotten.''
reagan's meeting with reporters coincided with shultz's departure for the middle east to try to get arab-israeli peace talks moving
it's time for all parties to rid themselves of old ideas and stances that cannot work and to begin a serious process of negotiation and reconciliation,'' reagan said
any process that is undertaken must meet israel's security needs and satisfy the legitimate rights of the palestinians.''
he said there is ``every evidence'' that outside terrorists have been stirring up trouble in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip. he refused to say who he was talking about. fitzwater today insisted there was no difference between what reagan said and shultz's claim that the problem was largely indigenous
pointedly, reagan passed up several opportunities to criticize israel's crackdown on arab protestors in which more than 50 palestinians have been killed. reagan's strongest statement on the subject was ``we don't support that sort of thing.''
