the world court has elected an argentine judge as its president and re-elected as vice-president a judge from senegal
the court's 15 judges on wednesday chose judge jose-maria ruda to hold the body's highest position until 1991, and re-elected keba mbaye as vice president, said the official
ruda, who succeeds judge naghendra singh of india, has been a member of the court since 1973. mbaye, elected vice president last year, has served on the bench since 1982
the world court, formally known as the international court of justice, is the judicial arm of the united nations. it has has no power to enforce its rulings
its 15 judges serve nine-year terms and may be re-elected indefinitely. presidents and vice presidents are elected for three-year periods
