a swedish court has ordered a prostitute infected with the aids virus to be isolated to keep her from spreading the disease, it was reported thursday
the unidentified woman, also a heroin addict, said she will appeal the ruling. she argued that she has abandoned prostitution and does not pose a health threat
she is under 24-hour guard in a hospital ward for aids patients, and will remain there until the government opens a planned institution for carriers of the disease on an island near stockholm, the newspapers said
reports about the institution last year raised protests of infringement on civil liberties
swedish law allows authorities to restrict the movement of people with contagious diseases who ignore medical advice on how to avoid infecting others
the government is reviewing the law, which originally was aimed at venereal diseases and other maladies that could be cured in a short time, said agneta lagerroth of the social ministry. reagan and shultz statements consistent. pick up 4th pvs, `shultz flew...'</note>
u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz today blamed longtime israeli occupation, not outside agitation, for the violent unrest in the west bank and gaza strip
shultz said, ``its fundamental origins are essentially indigenous.''
president reagan, at a news conference wednesday night, blamed ``terrorists'' and ``outsiders'' he did not identify for the violence in the israeli-held territories, which israel seized in the 1967 middle east war. he cited intelligence reports but gave no details
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said today that the statements of reagan and shultz were ``totally consistent.''
the president said the same thing,'' fitzwater said. ``he just said they (the riots) were partly influenced by outside sources. ... he is saying that it is indigenous in the nature of the political problems there but there has been some outside influence as well.''
shultz flew to jerusalem today with u.s. proposals for an overall mideast settlement
he said intelligence showed ``a mixed picture'' with ``interaction with outside force.'' but he added, ``there is an underlying problem consisting of a large number of people in occupation who haven't had the basic rights of governance
so we seek among other things consistent with israel's security, to look at things that will help palestinians gain legitimate rights.''
shultz defended his decision to stop in syria while in the middle east
in the past, he accused syria of terrorism and said the united states should try to isolate the country. sanctions were imposed in 1986, including a ban on meetings between high-level u.s. and syrian officials
in the first place, the syrian involvement in terrorism seems to have diminished, and we have had some definite moves that have been made that we found encouraging,'' he said
i don't mean to say that the problem is resolved,'' shultz added, but he said the united states had realized how important a role syria plays in the region
so we will go there and hear what they have to say and tell them what we have to say, recognizing their significance,'' he said
shultz also seemed to disagree with reagan over the iran-contra affair
the president said shultz and former defense secretary caspar weinberger had objected to the secret sale of u..s arms to iran, not because it amounted to a trade for american hostages held in lebanon but because it could be perceived that way
shultz, asked about the statement during a refueling stop here on the way to israel, did not directly challenge reagan but said, ``i've testified and i really don't have anything to add or subtract becasue my testimony is based to a very healthy extent on records and notes and so on.''
shultz testified in private and in public that he had opposed the u.s. arms sales to iran because it had amounted to trading weapons for hostages
he said the investigations had not brought out any other argument by him and weinberger against the sale
queen elizabeth ii, whose personal fortune is a closely guarded secret, is britain's richest person worth an estimated $5.87 billion, according to a list of the nation's 200 richest people
the list was front-page news in london on thursday, with racy tabloid headlines ranging from ``filthy rich'' in the sun to ``millionaires galore'' in the daily mail
money magazine, which complied the list, said the second-wealthiest briton as 92-year-old sir john moores, founder of the littlewoods soccer pools empire, a weekly game for small-time gamblers based on soccer results. it estimated his fortune at $2.99 billion
it listed the third-wealthiest briton as supermarket chain owner garfield weston, 60, chairman of associated british foods, with an estimated personal fortune at $2.64 billion
in fourth place is the 36-year-old duke of westminster. his inherited holdings include large chunks of highly desireable real estate in central london, huge tracts of farmland and sweeping acres of remote northern moorland. the magazine said his personal fortune was about $2.46 billion
money magazine says britain has seven billionaires, 18 families and individuals worth more than $440 million each, and 20,000 millionaires as measured in pounds
the magazine's estimate of the 61-year-old queen's wealth makes her the world's eighth-richest individual. it said the world's richest person is the sultan of brunei, with an estimated fortune equivalent to $24.64 billion
the guinness book of records lists the richest person in the united states as sam moore walton, founder of wal-mart discount stores in bentonville, ark., whose personal wealth was estimated in mid-1987 at $4.5 billion ``and rising.''
money magazine said financier sir james goldsmith _ fifth in its list of britain's wealthiest 200 with an estimated $1.76 billion _ was the only british billionaire to have made all his money since the end of world war ii in 1945
the youngest person in the top 200 is 31-year-old sophie mirman, with an estimated $52.8 million. she and her husband, richard ross, created the popular sock shop chain
among the 12 women in the top 200 list are ``dynasty'' star joan collins and her sister, jackie collins, the author of a string of best-selling raunchy novels. it said they are worth an estimated $26.4 million between them
editor sue thomas said it took six months to compile the list, ``consulting public sources of information and talking extensively to analysts in the city,'' london's financial district
the people we did not talk to were the 200 themselves because we wanted to keep the list under wraps until the last possible minute. many of the super-rich are very secretive,'' she said
asked how it estimated the queen's wealth in view of the secrecy maintained by her london bankers, coutts and co., mrs. thomas said: ``we found out as much as we could about the different headings under which her wealth falls _ her castles and other properties, her land holdings, her vast share portfolio, her stamp collection, her art collection, her jewelry collection and so forth and we talked to a lot of people with information
we arrived at what we estimate to be a minimum net worth for all the people on our list.''
it said 53 of the 200 fortunes stemmed from property. five percent of those listed came from abroad and only 15 percent belong to the british aristocracy. the self-made rich outnumbered those who inherited their wealth by 2-1
a french company has ordered american subsidiaries to sell nearly 1 million acres of timberland from maine to new york, officials said today
general occidentale wants to sell 800,000 acres of diamond occidental forest inc. land in maine, as well diamond international corp. holdings totaling 90,000 acres in new hampshire and vermont and nearly 96,000 acres in new york
the asking price totals more than $200 million, said robert whitney, executive vice president of landvest inc., a boston-based timberland broker marketing the land in new york, vermont and new hampshire
it would be the largest such land sale in the region since at least 1960, whitney said
a spokesman for the diamond companies, based in old town, maine, would not comment today on the proposed sale of the maine woodland. daniel christensen did confirm the proposed sale of the new york, vermont and new hampshire land
whitney said the land probably would continue to be used for timbering, and said general occidentale hopes to find single buyers for each of the three packages. the company decided to let its subsidiary market the maine package itself, he said
these 90,000 acres in new hampshire and vermont and 96,000 acres in new york state were too small for them to get involved in marketing directly,'' whitney said. ``they're used to dealing in $100 million transactions.''
the asking prices are $18.5 million for the new york package, $19 million for the new hampshire-vermont land, and at least $170 million for the maine land, whitney said in a telephone interview from landvest's office in portland, maine
he said he expected likely buyers would be pension funds or investment syndicates interested in stable returns from timber sales. congress told</head>
child health in the united states could be improved through a number of steps ranging from an expanded medicaid program to child seat-belt requirements, a congressional report said thursday
the office of technology assessment, which advises congress on scientific matters, also recommended better access to medical care for poor children and pregnant women; newborn screening for several disorders; and well-child care for those up to age 6
ota said other promising approaches are school-based health clinics and visiting nurse programs for families in which there is a high risk of child abuse or the birth of low-birthweight babies
judith wagner, a senior assosciate at ota, told the house energy and commerce subcommittee on health and environment that the united states ranked 17th among industrialized nations in infant mortality, a position that showed no improvement in the past five years
wagner also said more than 20 percent of 2-year-olds were not immunized against measles in 1985. he said poor children bear a disproportionate share of illness and death, and a substantial number of children do not have health insurance
ota said it would be both effective and cost-saving to improve access to early prenatal care for poor women, encourage immunizations and preventive care for young children, and encourage the use of child safety restraints in automobiles
the office said expanded newborn screening and universal medicaid eligibility for poor children would effectively improve child health, although they would not necessarily save money
ota recommended further study of two other approaches it characterized as promising: visiting nurses for high-risk families and comprehensive school clinics that offer family planning services to adolescents at risk of unwanted pregnancy
wagner said studies of two school-based clinics show they have achieved some success in reducing pregnancy and birth rates. she said congress should seek more information on ``this rapidly growing approach to delivering health services to high-risk teen-agers.''
congress has been moving in recent years to include more pregnant women and children in the medicaid system. subcommittee chairman henry waxman, d-calif., said thursday he would introduce legislation next week that includes several of ota's suggestions. leader was armenian. pick up 28th pvs, `a later...'</note>
thousands of people demonstrated today in the armenian capital, yerevan, while the soviet army sent in troops and tanks to quell protests over a disputed area in neighboring azerbaidzhan, witnesses said
armenians in nagorno-karabakh virtually shut down the disputed area with a strike, travelers from the area said. some residents said armenians had been killed
mofses gorgiskyan, a resident of yerevan, said in a telephone interview that more than 1 million people were demonstrating there today, but the report could not be verified. he said they demanded that armenian authorities act on their demand that nagorno-karabakh be made part of armenia
soldiers arrived in the morning and took up discreet positions in downtown yerevan, particularly around key government buildings, gorgiskyan said. they also deployed camouflaged trucks downtown and stationed tanks in outlying areas, he said
gorgiskyan said some azeris, members of the main nationality of azerbaidzhan, threw stones at a bus in an outlying area of nagorno-karabakh on tuesday and killed an undetermined number of armenians. azeris also set fire to a school, resulting in other deaths, he said
gorgiskyan described himself as a 26-year-old member of an underground group called the alliance for national determination
in nagorno-karabakh, virtually the entire armenian population, about 120,000, has been demonstrating in the main city since feb. 13, said a 17-year-old resident
there was no way to verify the reports independently because the government barred foreign reporters from traveling to the area
the resident, a student, also said some armenians had been killed by azeris, but she could offer no details
three-quarters of the residents of nagorno-karabakh are armenians. the demonstrators are demanding that armenia's nominal parliament support demands that nagorno-karabakh be removed from azerbaidzhan and turned over to armenia
the resident, a student interviewed in moscow after flying from armenia, spoke on condition she not be identified. she said she saw a crowd gathered this morning in lenin square in nagorno-karabakh's main city, stepanakert
practically the whole population is there. they've come from all the villages,'' said the student
the student confirmed that authorities brought in extra forces at one point during the 12 days of demonstrations, but she said she believed they were militiamen, not army troops
another armenian interviewed at moscow's vnukovo airport estimated that 1,000 people were demonstrating this morning outside the opera house in yerevan
the demonstrations in nagorno-karabakh were continuing around the clock and schools and businesses were closed in a strike, said the student. ``no one's sleeping. no one is going to work. the only stores open are groceries,'' she said
an official at the armenian representational offices in moscow in charge of internal matters, rudolf khatchyanov, told the associated press that a major demonstration by armenians continued in yerevan. but he said he had no details
repeated calls to yerevan were broken off after only a few seconds or did not go through at all
paruyr ayrikyan, an armenian activist in yerevan, said wednesday that 200,000 people demonstrated in the capital's central square, demanding that the republic's parliament convene to resolve the dispute
armenian officials had proposed annexing the mountainous territory, but the party's national central committee earlier this month decided nagorno-karabakh should remain part of azerbaidzhan
on wednesday, the kremlin named an armenian, genrikh pogosyan, communist party chief in the area
an armenian activist in moscow, sergei grigoryants, praised the appointment, but said it would not likely quell the protests
this was the first test of the ability of the country's leaders to work out a compromise to a difficult situation involving nationalities,'' grigoryants said
but he said armenian demonstrators are angered over what they see as unconstitutional interference by the party
the demonstrators already have deemed this matter outside the party's control,'' grigoryants said
demonstrations by armenians against control by azeris began late last week after the party's decision was announced, ayrikyan said
the soviet army sent in tanks and troops as a show of force, and rumors spread to yerevan that some armenian demonstrators were killed in the melee that ensued, said ayrikyan
tass announced wednesday night that pogosyan had been named party leader in the disputed region. tass said pogosyan was armenian and born in nagorno-karabakh. his predecessor, boris kevorkov, also is armenian
a later tass report said party leaders in yerevan met and voiced support for the central committee decision to keep nagorno-karabakh in azerbaidzhan. the party meeting also issued orders to local officials to take all steps necessary to end the protests
nagorno-karabakh is 1,760 square miles, smaller than the state of delaware. czechoslovakia</head>
communist officials and the state-run press said thursday that soviet troops began withdrawing ss-12 nuclear missiles from this town, where hundreds of people waved flags and showered troops with gifts
women pressed flowers on 150 soviet soldiers and children gave them books, candy and other gifts in an orchestrated, two-hour ceremony at the train station. the troops have been here four years
as the train loaded with 32 canvas-wrapped containers pulled away, the soldiers waved at the crowd and pressed the bouquets to the windows
east german officials at the scene and the state-run adn news agency said the containers held parts of dismantled ss-12 missiles and that the train was headed to the soviet union, where the missiles would be destroyed
western diplomats were skeptical
until the arms treaty is in place, there is no way of confirming what we are seeing, and what we are being told is actually what it all appears to be,'' said one western diplomat, who asked not to be identified
in neighboring czechoslovakia, the state-run ctk news agency said soviet ss-12 missiles were withdrawn from the town of hranice, southeast of prague. it said a train carrying soviet troops and 19 missile launchers left hranice en route to the soviet union
the commander of czechoslovak missile units and artillery, lt. gen. jan krizan, was quoted by ctk as saying that hranice was the only place in czechoslovakia where ss-12s were deployed
the shorter-range missiles, which have a range of 300 to 600 miles, would be the first nuclear weapons to be removed from central europe under terms of a superpower arms treaty signed in washington last december
soviet officials proclaimed the early withdrawal an ``act of trust'' that the u.s. congress would approve the accord
military bands played and more than 1,000 residents waved small east german, soviet and communist party flags in bischofswerda, a city of about 12,000 near the czechoslovak and polish borders
some people carried banners reading, ``an early missile withdrawal _ proof of our will for peace,'' and ``long live the soviet-german friendship.''
fifty-four ss-12 missiles have been based in east germany, at four separate sites, since 1983. they were deployed after nato deployed pershing 2 and cruise missiles in western europe
this is an act of building trust,'' said lt. igor vladimirovich obraszov, soviet commander of one of the missile batteries
scores of east german soldiers were also on hand
thank god they're leaving,'' said one east german army lieutenant, referring to the soviet missiles. ``for the past four years i have had to accept being a possible target of a western attack.''
the soldiers posed for photographers, shook hands with local residents and tried to answer questions in halting english or german
it is always good to be going home,'' said 1st lt. taras durayesky, a career army officer from odessa as he boarded the train. ``this is a good country, but i have been here four years.''
more than 150 reporters watched the ceremony
ctk said 60 reporters were watching the removal of missiles from hranice, but no western journalists were invited
