     ...   with the university of texas as the guest team
it's appropriate that texas be the opponent because the longhorns suffered some deep miseries in the airish, dank building where you could catch a cold even if you had just been cured of one
perhaps the worst night was when mike wacker, center of an unbeaten longhorns' team, slipped on a wet spot and so tore up his knee that it ended any chance of an nba career
like a curse from some egyptian tomb, the voodooed longhorns sank to a miserable season, giving abe lemons' detractors their chance to fire him
the next year when texas visited, one baylor coach wanted to shake the 'horns by putting a black x where wacker fell. but more tasteful and cooler heads prevailed
spooky things always happened at h.o.t. of course, there was the first rain delay in college basketball history this year when the roof leaked, holding up play
but that was small trick-or-treat stuff compared to one game i remember years ago involving the visiting texas a&amp;m aggies
i believe an aggie was at the free throw line when a late-running baylor tuba player crashed his automobile into the power pole outside
it plunged h.o.t into darker darkness
the place had always been so dim that rival coaches threatened to issue their players coal miners' lamps
of course, a&amp;m coach shelby metcalf was fit to be fried. the lights never were restored to full power. the aggies finally agreed to play the game out under eerie, twilight zone conditions. they lost
you had to listen for the swish to know you made one,'' metcalf quipped
powers failures were always numerous in h.o.t
more than one deadline was blown by electrical outages which sent stories to editorial graveyards. one sports writer slam-dunked his chair into the stands in one outage outrage
more recently, the baylor mascot knocked a dallas radio off the air briefly by stumbling over an electrical cord
just getting into the building could be fun. i recall arriving at a game early for prime position on gravel within several blocks of the coliseum on a rainy evening
feeling smug, i advanced to within 25 yards of the building before almost disappearing in a mud hole large enough to lose a shetland pony
baylor always had a big advantage in this ``pit.''
the bears at least knew where the dim rims could be found. crowd seating on the floor also gave the bears a huge psychological edge
but baylor was hurt in the recruting wars because of the decaying coliseum
former coach jim haller always liked to talk about school academics and such on recruiting visits. he knew he was dead if he had to take the kid to the barn
