an 82-year-old house built by an explorer, engineer and naturalist will become the new home of the institute that supports naturalist jane goodall, famous for her 28 years of chimpanzee research
a variance allowing the jane goodall institute to use the house for its offices, a museum and a classroom was approved wednesday by the tucson board of adjustment
the house was built by godfrey sykes, founder of the local desert laboratory. he named it dar es salaam after the east african port city he visited in 1912, said georgiana boyer, sykes' granddaughter. she said the name means ``haven of peace'' in arabic
dar es salaam also happens to be where ms. goodall lives when she's not following chimpanzees in gombe stream national park in tanzania
i was amazed, just totally amazed _ it just seemed unreal _ when i heard that this house was called dar es salaam,'' ms. goodall said in a telephone interview from washington, d.c
the institute functions as goodall's u.s. office and arranges her annual lecture tour
the new headquarters will include a museum and a library featuring ms. goodall's handwritten field notebooks of chimpanzee behavior
commerce secretary c. william verity urged lawmakers thursday to produce a major trade bill but not resort to protectionism, while a senate chairman reported progress in drafting such a measure
i think we should have a trade bill and it should be a good trade bill,'' verity told the house foreign affairs committee. he urged the lawmakers to avoid protectionism and praised them for moving to soften a senate provision that would ban u.s. sales of toshiba products
the senate included its toshiba provision last year following reports that a subsidiary of the japanese electronics producer had sold sophisticated submarine-silencing technology to the soviet union
the administration, however, has been a critic of the provision, and house negotiators have proposed to leave the decision up to the president
we believe that would be the correct approach,'' verity said
senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said house-senate negotiators had dropped ``foreign policy'' provisions from a compromise version of the two chambers' trade bills
he did not specify which provisions that involved, although house negotiators on tuesday proposed to delete a feature that would strip romania of its guarantee of trade relations with the united states that are as good as those enjoyed by any other country. proponents say the provision would prod romania to improve its emigration policies
particular interest has focused on a house offer to drop a provision of both measures that would allow a handful of sugar refining companies to collect from the government $400 million in tariffs paid years ago on sugar imports that since then have been refined and re-exported
among other matters facing the senators is a house proposal to drop import curbs on lamb. the feature, contained only in the senate bill, was sponsored by one of the conferees, sen. max baucus, d-mont., who emerged from the meeting and declared that ``real progress has been made'' but provided no specifics
in other trade action, lawmakers from wheat-producing states sharply questioned agriculture secretary richard lyng and u.s. trade representative clayton k. yeutter at a house agriculture committee hearing
the two secretaries were there to discuss the proposed free-trade agreement between the united states and canada. one provision of the agreement would end canadian transportation subsidies for wheat shipped to vancouver but leave untouched a subsidy for shipments to the big grain port at thunder bay, ontario. transporation costs are a key factor in grain prices
american wheat growers have been complaining that the thunder bay payments also should have been eliminated under the treaty, whose major provisions would phase out tariffs between the united states and canada
lyng and yeutter reiterated previous pledges to consider the thunder bay issue in future negotiations and repeated what they said in earlier clashes, namely that the pact represents an improvement in u.s.-canadian trade relations as well as being the best deal that american negotiators could get
but that did not satisfy some lawmakers
are you still looking after the interests of u.s. agricultural producers?'' said rep. ron marlenee, r-mont
i would give an emphatic yes,'' lyng responded
tibetan buddhists thursday began their most important religious festival, an 11-day celebration that was nearly canceled because of fears of a repetition of last fall's violent anti-chinese demonstrations
foreign sources in lhasa, the capital of tibet, said the start of the moinlam qenmo festival passed without incident, although some monks were reluctant to attend the ceremonies and some people stayed away to avoid possible trouble
an indian tourist guide in lhasa, contacted by phone, said some monks didn't want to participate because they said fellow monks, who led the pro-independence riots in september and october, were still detained by chinese police
the guide, who refused to give his name, said there was division in the tibetan community over whether to hold the religious rites as usual this year. he could not confirm reports that some monks boycotted the festival
china's official media earlier said 80 people, including monks, were detained following the disturbances in which about 14 people lost their lives. official reports said almost all had been released after repenting their actions in the riots
a tibetan-speaking american, who has been in lhasa four months, said the city was ``a little tense'' thursday with uniformed and plainclothes police on patrol. he said he saw police in riot gear at the johkang temple where the main ceremonies for the holiday are taking place
the american, who also refused to give his name, said foreigners have been told to return to their hotels by 10 p.m., and that police have posted signs in english warning foreigners not to photograph or participate in disturbances
the official xinhua news agency reported from lhasa that ceremonies marking the start of moinlam qenmo began when two lamas, or monks, blew blasts on large trumpets from the johkang temple in the center of the city
xinhua said about 1,000 monks gathered at the temple to mark the annual ``grand summons'' ceremony, and that about 1,000 people watched in the square outside the temple
the news agency said that with the blowing of the trumpets dozens of believers threw letters of good wishes tied with silk scarves to the presiding lama and begged him to pray for their happiness
inside the temple, one of tibetan buddhism's holiest sites, thousands of lamps glowed while monks prayed to zong kaba, founder of the yellow sect of tibetan lamaism who started the ceremony in 1409
the panchem lama, tibet's second-holiest man after the exiled dalai lama, revealed last month that officials had considered canceling the festival because of fears that the arrival of thousands of pilgrims from other parts of tibet would lead to a new outbreak of violence
the communists, which took control over tibet in 1950, claims the remote mountainous region has been an integral part of china for centuries
however, there has long been considerable friction between the tibetans and the hans who are the dominant ethnic group of china, particularly as a result of the 1966-76 cultural revolution when leftist red guards destroyed temples, suppressed local customs and language, and persecuted religious believers
china blames the recent disturbances on the dalai lama, who fled to india following an unsuccessful 1959 uprising and continues to speak out against what he says are china's oppressive policies in tibet
the beijign government has also accused the u.s. congress, which has called on china to stop human rights violations in tibet, of meddling in its internal affairs
china has said it made mistakes during the cultural revolution and has tried to make amends by rebuilding temples, guaranteeing religious freedom and paying for development of the region, one of the poorest in the country
the army unveiled plans thursday for cutting officer strength in a budget move, including appointment of a board to select more than 350 colonels and lieutenant colonels for early retirement
the service said it also was beginning a voluntary release program for all officers regardless of rank who wanted to leave the military, and would strictly enforce guidelines specifying the discharge of any first lieutenant who fails for a second time to win promotion to captain
the army disclosed last week in its fiscal 1989 budget proposal that it was cutting active-duty strength by 8,600, including about 1,540 officers. the cuts _ down to a total strength of roughly 772,000 _ were prompted by a deficit-reduction agreement reached with congress last november
earlier this month, the army said it would trim its enlisted ranks through a combination of early discharges for soldiers who were already preparing to leave the service and reductions in recruiting goals
the service said thursday it had now begun focusing on the officer community and hoped the combination of the three new programs would allow it to reduce those ranks without causing undue personal hardship
lt. col. greg rixon, an army spokesman, said the service expected between 750 and 800 officers to resign or retire as part of normal attrition. to make up the difference toward the new target, he said:
_the army will convene a selective early retirement board in may to pick 178 colonels and 181 lieutenant colonels for retirement. these are officers who have already served at least 20 years, and thus are eligible for a pension, but had not planned to retire yet. those selected by the board will have to retire by nov. 30
as of last sept. 30, the army had 4,647 colonels and 11,120 lieutenant colonels
_the army will immediately start a voluntary release program for all commissioned officers. under this program, an officer who decides he is ready to leave the military _ but who still ``owes'' time under a special obligation _ will be allowed to resign or retire anyway
the special obligations involve extra commitments of service stemming from such things as advanced schooling or acceptance of lengthy overseas tours
younger officers who were ``commissioned through a service academy, rotc or officer candidate school may have up to 12 months of their service obligation waived, in exchange for 12 months of commitment in a national guard or army reserve unit,'' rixon added
_strict ``involuntary release,'' or dismissal, for certain first lieutenants no later than sept. 30. rixon said a younger officer who is passed over twice for promotion is normally discharged in any event. under the new program, however, there will be no possibility of a waiver that would allow the officer to remain
president reagan plans to nominate barbara mcconnell barrett of phoenix, ariz., as deputy administrator of the federal aviation administration, the white house announced thursday
ms. barrett, 37, has been a partner in a phoenix law firm since 1985. she was vice chairman of the civil aeronautics board in 1983 and 1984. she is also a former corporate attorney for the greyhound corp
the white house also announced that the president will nominate kenneth j. beirne, a former executive director of the republican party of kentucky, as assistant secretary of housing and urban development for policy development and research
after his service in the party position in 1981, beirne, 41, served in a variety of positions at hud. he has been a free-lance writer since last year, the white house said
reagan will appoint robert b. barker, a former executive of the lawrence livermore national laboratory, to the new position of assistant to the secretary of defense for atomic energy
barker, 48, was with the arms control and disarmament agency from 1983 to 1985 and has been working on atomic energy matters at the pentagon since then. he was at livermore for 10 years before coming to washington
alex r. munson, 46, of saipan, north mariana islands, chief justice of the high court for the trust territory of the pacific islands since 1982, will be nominated as judge of the district court for the northern mariana islands, the announcement said. attack, details on surrender and conditions; no pickup; adds byline.</note>
a man who had been evicted from a retirement home burst into a board meeting at the home with two rifles today and opened fire, wounding four people, authorities said. a fifth person suffered a heart attack
the gunman fled from the room at the masonic home for the aged with one rifle tied around his neck with twine, police spokesman dee anderson said. police captured him after a chase
a woman who was one of the four wounded also complained of chest pain, anderson said
a fifth person, willie joe wright, 67, suffered a heart attack and was in critical condition at arlington memorial hospital, hospital spokeswoman tenya woods said. the other shooting victims were in fair condition, she said
apparently, they had a board meeting and one former resident, who was apparently disgruntled, walked into the board room and started shooting,'' anderson said
anderson said 16 board members were in the room
when the officers went to a kitchen in the rear of the building, the man still had one rifle. he very calmly gave up when the officers asked him to surrender,'' anderson said. ``he did not give any information to police.''
the gunman, whose name was withheld, had lived at the home for three years and ``was aware of the time frame of the board meeting. he had been evicted or asked to leave,'' anderson said
the annual search for the nation's most colossal cockroach is off and scurrying
the combat great american roach-off ii came to the mcnicol middle school wednesday to kick off the contest, which will net the winner $1,000 and a trip to the smithsonian institution's insect zoo in washington to see their roach enshrined
sponsors picked the mcnicol school because last year's winner, laine snyder, who discovered his 2-inch-long entry under a hollywood beach lifeguard stand, attended the school at the time
laine has since moved, but other mcnicol students hope to make their school a winner again, even if it means changing their habits
i just step on them when i see them,'' said eric poirot, 13. ``i guess i better stop stepping on them if i want to win this contest.''
another hopeful is frank alvarez, 11, who let contest coordinator michael ``cockroach dundee'' bohdan place a hissing 3-inch monster from madagascar onto his hand
hey, no problem,'' he said. ``i handle lizards. this is just a cockroach.''
frank plans to go roach hunting as soon as he can
i'd like to get the biggest cockroaches. my mother would scream, though, when i brought it home.''
he thought a moment. ``she sure wouldn't scream if i brought home that $1,000.''
bohdan, a dallas exterminator, started the contest last year to raise awareness about roaches, which he called the most serious pest problem in the country. the makers of combat roach control system joined bohdan in sponsoring the contest
the rules: live cockroaches need not apply. they must be dead, but not squashed. those much smaller than last year's winner, which was more than 2 inches long, won't have a chance
competitions will be held in may in miami, new york, washington, los angeles, san antonio, texas, and louisville, ky. the roach-off finals will be in june in new york
roaches can also be mailed in strong packages _ some got flattened in transit last year _ to bohdan at his pest shop in plano, texas
the california supreme court today upheld the death sentences of two men but reversed a third because the defendant was not given a hearing on his competency to stand trial
the two death sentences affirmed _ one for the fatal shooting of a couple in los angeles, the other for the kidnapping and fatal stabbing of an 8-year-old girl in hayward _ marked the first time in recent years the court has upheld more than one death sentence on a single day
the three decisions were written by chief justice malcolm lucas. the court was unanimous in two of the cases, but split 5-2 in the los angeles murder. the dissenters said the judge should not have told jurors to disregard their ``personal choice'' and consider only the factors listed in the law in deciding on punishment
since last year, when conservatives led by lucas gained a majority, the court has upheld six of the 10 death sentences it has considered
in the case that was reversed, brian darle hale was convicted of fatally shooting two elderly men, robbing one and attempting to rob the other in bellflower and cerritos in october 1980
during pretrial proceedings, the court said, hale said he was ``a president'' and a better judge than the trial judge, said he had ``little speakers in his ears,'' and called the judge ``fatso,'' among other rambling statements. two court-appointed psychiatrists concluded he was incompetent to stand trial; three others disagreed
los angeles superior court judge cecil mills ordered a hearing to decide whether hale was mentally able to understand the proceedings or assist in his own defense. but for reasons not explained on the record, no such hearing was held before the trial in which hale was convicted and sentenced to death
the court voted 5-2 to uphold the death sentence of eric b. kimble for the august 1978 fatal shootings of harry and avonne margulies in the doheny estates neighborhood of los angeles, the rape of mrs. margulies and the burglary of margulies' stereo equipment store
the court unanimously affirmed the death sentence of richard hovey for the march 1978 kidnapping and fatal stabbing of 8-year-old tina salazar in hayward
thousands of people stood in driving snow thursday on the site of a triumphant rally that ushered in communism in czechoslovakia 40 years ago
banners and red flags decorated the central old town square, which in 1948 resounded with the cheers of tens of thousands when the communists took power. thursday's anniversary rally, however, was short and low-key
on feb. 21, 1948, klement gottwald gave a triumphant speech on the square four days before taking over czechoslovakia's first all-communist government
thursday's crowd was subdued. huddled under umbrellas, the number of onlookers appeared to be less than the 80,000 people estimated by the state news agency ctk. the banners hung limp in the snow
dozens of people drifted out of the square after party leader milos jakes began a 20-minute speech recalling the ``victorious february'' of 1948 and czechoslovakia's sometimes troubled history since
president gustav husak, 75, who stepped down as party leader in december, was the first member of the ruling politburo to take the stand where the leadership stood sheltered from the snow
when husak first appeared, nobody cheered or applauded. a few claps were heard in the crowd once he waved
in his speech, jakes remembered what he called ``dramatic moments deciding fateful questions of our life'' in 1948
forty years ago, a political crisis arose when most non-communist ministers in the government resigned in protest at growing communist influence in the security and police forces
five days of well-organized street rallies and fierce political discussions followed, ending with gottwald becoming head of a communist government
the takeover sealed the kremlin's domination of eastern europe, and installed a communist regime that swiftly began stalinist-style purges of opponents and of party ranks
jakes presented the 1948 takeover as a move that ensured the triumph of the working class over the ``oppression'' of bourgeois democrats who ruled in czechoslovakia before world war ii
looking back on the ``prague spring'' reforms attempted under alexander dubcek in 1968, jakes reiterated the hard line voiced in a long speech wednesday at a ceremony marking the anniversary
he again rejected any comparison between the reforms of dubcek 20 years ago and the changes said to be under way now in czechoslovakia following mikhail s. gorbachev's reforms in the soviet union
today's changes aim to strengthen socialism, jakes said. in 1968, he added, ``the revolutionary achievements of victorious february and our alliance bonds with the soviet union and other socialist states were threatened
such is the historical truth and nothing substantial can be changed in it.''
jakes gave little indication he is about to favor the economic and political reforms being tried in the soviet union, poland, hungary and bulgaria. he also ruled out all non-communist opposition
his hour-long speech to 500 party members in prague's hradcany castle did not essentially differ from the cautious conservatism husak displayed during his 18-year tenure
jakes' speech thursday was punctuated by few bursts of applause. once he finished, a loudspeaker struck up the communist anthem, ``the internationale,'' which was sung by some of the crowd and a few leaders on the stand
men in the gray-blue uniforms of the people's militia and soldiers in khaki dress uniforms marched briskly past the stand
in his public appearances recently, jakes has emulated gorbachev's style of chatting to citizens on the streets and in factories. he closed out the brief ceremony thursday with thanks to the citzens for attending and good wishes for their success at work
five minutes later, the square was deserted. television schedules had indicated the ceremony would last 75 minutes, but it was over in half an hour
the federal government's sanitation inspection program for cruise ships, now 13 years old, has made a marked difference in preventing illness among travelers, officials said thursday
the national centers for disease control, which oversees periodic inspections of cruise ships sailing regularly from u.s. ports, reported thursday that the percentage of ships passing inspection rose dramatically over the program's first decade, while the number of intestinal illness outbreaks among passengers declined
despite the positive findings, the cdc has been criticized for reorganizing its inspection program
in 1975, when the program began, cruise ships were reporting 7.7 outbreaks of diarrhea for every 10 million passenger-days sailed, said dr. vernon houk, director of the agency's center for environmental health. by 1985, the figure dropped to 2.7 outbreaks per 10 million passenger-days
a passenger-day is one day spent on a ship by one passenger. the cdc considers an outbreak in progress if 3 percent of the passengers and crew are ill
this has been a cooperative effort between us and the cruise ship industry, and ... (the study) clearly shows it has been working,'' houk said. ``things are going in the right direction.''
only 18 percent of the ships inspected in the first year earned satisfactory ratings, compared with 72 percent in 1985, cdc researchers said
the cdc also presented new findings thursday indicating ``that ships that consistently have the highest sanitation scores are less likely to have an outbreak of diarrheal disease than ships with lower average scores.''
on the average, for every 10 million passenger-days, fewer than two of the ships scoring in the top 20 percent reported diarrhea outbreaks. that compares with outbreaks aboard more than eight of the ships scoring in the bottom 20 percent
the 1975-85 results aside, critics have charged that the program's performance has suffered since a reorganization nearly two years ago. the cdc terminated its inspections in 1986, substituting a plan by which the cruise lines would conduct their own inspections. in 1987, a new plan was imposed, using private inspectors operating under cdc review
according to the cdc's latest summary of the 1987 and 1988 inspections, only 55 percent of the ships regularly sailing from u.s. ports _ 30 of 55 ships _ passed. the cdc has no legal power to block ships from sailing, but does distribute the results of its inspections
critics have said the resent inspection results are not good news for the ``privatization'' plan
thursday, houk said it is ``too early to draw conclusions'' from the initial reports from the revamped program. some ships have not yet been inspected under the new routine
houk stressed that the inspection program is thorough
travelers ought to be aware that these are very tough inspections,'' he said, ``far tougher than the usual restaurant inspections done ashore.''
the cdc inspections act as ``an independent survey'' of how well the cruise lines' own sanitation programs are working, he added
the individual traveler should not look at a single inspection report and make that the determinant whether he'll travel on that ship or not,'' he said. ``it seems to me the useful question is, `what is the past history of this ship?'''
the cdc, in its weekly report, noted that the sanitation inspections monitor water quality, food storage and preparation, potential for food contamination, cleanliness and other factors. foreign policy</head>
pulitzer prize-winning journalist seymour hersh is coming ``because you don't normally get this interesting mix of people.'' former cia director william colby will attend ``because i think someone needs to say a few good words about the agency.''
hersh and colby are among more than 30 experts and commentators who plan to meet friday at tufts university for a two-day forum on the role of covert aid and secrecy in u.s. foreign policy
the panelists include former and current members of the intelligence community, military and defense officials, journalists, educators and legal specialists. they represent opinions ``from the left, right and center of the ideological spectrum,'' forum coordinator sherman teichman said thursday
teichman said the conference, sponsored jointly by tufts, the national security archive, the u.s. department of defense and the center for the study of covert action, will address more than such obvious examples of covert action as the iran-contra affair
it is important to ask if the use of covert actions is a necessary part of dealing with foreign governments,'' he said. ``if it is a necessary evil and used to influence others to our way of thinking, then how does a democracy justify its actions?''
topics at the forum include ``the southeast asian experience: a case study''; ``lessons of vietnam and southeast asia for the 1980s''; ``the iran-contra affair: the hostage ransom, iran-israel arms sale''; and ``contra support: managing and supplying a paramilitary operation.''
also scheduled to attend are bob woodward of the washington post; ``pentagon papers'' leaker daniel ellsberg; thomas polgar, a former cia station chief in saigon; former sen. thomas f. eagleton of missouri; and scott armstrong, executive director of the national security archive
it seems like a rather contentious group of people,'' said colby, now an attorney in washington, d.c. colby said he will defend his opinion that ``covert action is a regular part of american foreign policy. it's perfectly compatible with american democracy.''
eagleton has prepared a paper reviewing the history of congressional oversight of covert activities. he said the symposium is particularly timely because of a pending senate bill that would plug loopholes in existing laws that allowed the reagan administration not to notify congress at the time of the iran arms deal
there can be a time and circumstances where covert action is clearly in the american interest,'' said eagleton. ``but the question is: under what conditions of shared knowledge does our government undertake covert action?''
hersh, with tongue slightly in cheek, said he has split views on the need for covert operations
i have mixed feelings about it because on one hand, people like me get to write books on it and make a lot of money,'' he said. ``on the other hand, i don't see, especially when you're talking about things like chile, what (secret actions) have done for the american people.'' attribution.</note>
