producer aaron spelling and fox broadcasting co. are turning to the time-honored tradition of a nationwide talent search to find the young women who will be television's new ``charlie's angels.''
young women across the country will be offered an opportunity to land one of the four roles in ``angels '88,'' which will make its debut this summer on fox
at least five actresses discovered during the search will be assured of roles in at least one episode of ``angels '88,'' a fox spokesman said
unlike the original series, which ran on abc from 1976 to 1981, the new show will have four angels instead of three. farrah fawcett, kate jackson and jaclyn smith were the original angels, although there were cast replacements during later seasons
the dates and cities for the auditions are as follows: march 3, los angeles; march 4, chicago, boston, dallas; march 11, miami, denver, san francisco; week of march 14, open calls in 50 cities with fox stations; march 18, atlanta, detroit, nashville, tenn.; march 21, new york
finalists will take part in auditions in los angeles march 31 and the new angels will be announced april 6
the talent search is a hollywood tradition that goes back to the search for an actress to play scarlett o'hara in ``gone with the wind'' 50 years ago. at the last minute british actress vivian leigh was selected to star opposite clark gable
the disney studio is also conducting a nationwide talent hunt for youngsters who look like the original mousketeers for a movie about the ``mickey mouse club.'' admitting setting fires, details on charges; picks up 7th graf, `howe's mother ...'</note>
a former firefighter admitted setting a series of arson fires that burned a small town's elementary school and two churches that opened their doors to students, a prosecutor said today
adrian julius howe, 23, of omak will be charged with six counts of first-degree arson, prosecutor jack burchard said. he was held in the okanogan county jail
howe admitted setting the fires, which caused $6.5 million in damage, burchard said. each arson count carries a possible sentence of life imprisonment and a $50,000 fine
officials declined to comment on reports that howe held a grudge against the burned school, north omak elementary school
the six fires that began in december and hit the school twice in eight days led to the creation of a 12-member arson task force and door-to-door canvassing in search of leads. two churches and a church house were also burned; one of the churches was struck twice
howe was arrested wednesday, said mimi curry of the state department of community development's division of fire protection services, who has been appointed spokeswoman for the investigation
the task force, set up tuesday and composed of local, state and u.s. bureau of alcohol, tobacco and firearms agents, was ``at a peak of activity,'' with investigators going door-to-door, ms. curry said
the string of arsons terrorized omak, a placid north-central washington town of 4,000. churches and schools stepped up security, and residents formed night-time patrols
howe's mother, lena howe, 67, said she and her 75-year-old husband, ben, adopted their son at age 2. he had learning difficulties and left omak high school in his junior year, the mother told the spokesman-review in today's editions of the spokane newspaper
howe later got a job on the fire patrol in nearby nespelem, but was not rehired after he lost his driver's license because of drinking problems, mrs. howe said. he now works at a lumber mill on the colville indian reservation, just east of omak, mrs. howe said
colville indian reservation tribal chief harry smiskin said howe was a firefighter for the u.s. bureau of indian affairs' fire control department. he said he gave details of howe's employment to investigators
the washington state house voted wednesday night to include in its $207 million supplemental state budget a $150,000 appropriation to help omak and okanogan county pay for investigation of the blazes
if fully approved, the money would be used for administrative costs to complete the arson investigation, ms. curry said
the (okanogan) county budget is being quickly depleted,'' she said. ``after all, they (county commissioners) didn't plan for this (the arson fires) to happen.''
george bush took on a hot issue in a state that could be a republican indicator for the rest of the south thursday, rejecting as ``pure, all-out protectionism'' efforts backed by rivals bob dole and pat robertson to help the textile industry by limiting foreign imports
bush said he opposed legislation that has been sought by many in south carolina and other textile states as a cure for the industry's troubles. his comments came one day after dole campaigned in the same area and called for the bill's passage
i'm for the textile industry _ not the bill,'' the vice president said while greeting several hundred people alongside a greenwood street. ``there have got to be some changes before i'd be for it.''
don't go for this pure, all-out protectionism that may save one job and then throw three neighbors in this burgeoning state out of work,'' bush said earlier at a technical college in pendleton, s.c. ``that's not the answer.''
bush turned aside most questions about his long-distance exchange with pat robertson over the past two days. but he said the former tv evangelist hadn't responded to his demand for an apology or proof ``by sundown in the old south'' to back up robertson's suggestion that the release of sex-scandal allegations against evangelist jimmy swaggart had been timed to hurt robertson
haven't heard a word,'' bush said. ``i've said all i'm going to say about that.''
robertson, in louisville, ky., said he'd been misquoted and suggested bush wouldn't be asking for an aplogy if he knew what robertson had really said
bush spoke about the textile issue to several hundred teachers, students and others at an assembly at tri-county technical college, on a day when he toured the northwestern corner of south carolina by motorcade and stopped at high schools, colleges and restaurants
dole and robertson support legislation that would place limits on the amount of foreign textile products that could be imported. the legislation is popular in textile-producing areas, but president reagan vetoed similar legislation after it was passed by congress more than two years ago
what i propose is that we enforce the law,'' bush said. ``sometimes we're fighting the bureaucracy in washington. we have the laws on the books _ enforce it, so that the textile industry will continue to profit.''
at evey stop bush underscored the importance he and others attach to south carolina in the race for the republican nomination. the state holds its gop primary on saturday march 5, with 37 delegates at stake. but the state is given broader significance because it comes three days before the rest of the south votes on super tuesday, a day when one-third of the delegates in both parties will be up for grabs
robertson has said he must win in south carolina and has devoted an intensive effort. bush has long considered it one of his best states in the south, since he has broad party support including that of gov. carroll a. campbell jr., who accompanied him at his stops
bush would like a win going into the super tuesday states, after finishing far behind in south dakota and minnesota contests last tuesday, and he was spending two days campaigning here this week
dole, the kansas senator, also contesting here, was accompanied in the state on wednesday by republican sen. strom thurmond
bush dropped in on an industrial electronics class where about 30 students interrupted their final examination to hear him speak briefly and watch as he observed a demonstration of a small, computer-driven robotics machine
he sought to tie himself closely to reagan at his stops in this state where the president has been a popular vote-getter. he said, ``i've taken some shots'' for remaining loyal to reagan, ``but you and i know loyalty is a strength, not a weakness.''
major u.s. oil companies doing regular business with saudi arabia are turning to britain for protection of their tankers against iranian attacks in the persian gulf, shipping executives and diplomatic sources said thursday
the sources said the move by such corporations as chevron and mobil apparently was prompted by loss of hope that the u.s. navy's escort operations would be expanded to cover u.s.-owned or operated vessels that don't fly the american flag. the sources spoke on condition they not be identified
they said chevron and mobil recently registered five supertankers in bermuda under the red ensign, flag of the british merchant marine, and exxon corporation had brought its bahamas-registered esso atlantic out of four years' retirement to carry crude to the united states. the 516,893-ton ship is one of the world's three or four largest
exxon already has about a dozen supertankers flying the british flag, and another five sailing under the french flag
france, britain, italy and the soviet union also have naval escort contingents in the gulf
two chevron-owned vessels, the 413,158-ton chevron south america and the 264,000-ton chevron edinburgh, were shifted from liberian to bermudan registry in december. the vessels routinely operate between saudi arabia's ras tanura terminal and a chevron refinery in pascagoula, miss. the chevron fleet is estimated at 48, mainly under liberian registry
mobil, with a 28-vessel fleet, has transferred three liberian-flagged tankers to bermudan. they are the 277,000-ton mobil falcon, the 280,428-ton mobil petrol and the 138,496-ton mobil acme, which also routinely carry saudi crude to the united states
the u.s. navy's middle east force mainly protects 11 state-owned kuwaiti tankers re-registered last year in the united states. only one of the kuwaiti ships is a crude oil tanker, and none of them sails regularly to the united states, which derives only 6 percent of its oil imports directly from gulf sources
although the navy may escort any u.s.-flag vessel, few enter the waterway, where nearly 500 ships have been hit or damaged since the iraq-iran war began in september 1980 and spread to the gulf four years ago
iran strikes at neutral vessels in the 600-mile waterway in retaliation for iraqi raids on its own tanker routes
following an increase in iranian attacks last year, american shipowners with vessels registered under other ``flags of convenience'' for tax and other purposes, or carrying cargo to and from the united states under other flags, urged the pentagon to let the navy escort their vessels
the pressure increased just before the new u.s. defense secretary, frank carlucci, visited the gulf last month to reassess the navy role
however, the policy of escorting only u.s.-flagged vessels was subsequently reaffirmed, at the same time that carlucci announced a slight cutback in the number of u.s. warships in the gulf and nearby waters
the u.s. escort operations for reflagged kuwaiti tankers have been a success and the americans do not want to spoil it,'' said one of the shipping sources
the u.s. administration apparently has stressed to shipowners that protection would be given only to ships flying the american flag and therefore subject to u.s. taxes and laws requiring american crews. under united kingdom registry, vessels must have british captains but are sheltered from taxation
because britain's gulf force sails only as far north as bahrain, halfway up the gulf, ships it escorts would be on their own if heading to ras tanura, or to saudi or kuwait ports farther north
a knowledgeable shipping source in regular contact with oil companies in saudi arabia said there was ``no need for british escort beyond bahrain'' because saudi arabia's navy had made the area secure. he refused to elaborate. ^by mary sedor</byline>
israel tightened security in its capital thursday for the visit of secretary of state george p. shultz, setting up roadblocks, searching arabs' homes and rounding up scores of suspected agitators
in silwan at the foot of the mount of olives, military police in an armored vehicle searched for palestinians on foot and in cars, pulling vinyl seat cushions out of vehicles and emptying the contents of trunks onto a dirt road
at least nine people were hospitalized with beating injuries after military police sealed off the shufat refugee camp within the city limits and then broke into homes searching for arabs suspected of taking part in disturbances, hospital officials said
five palestinians were detained, according to arab reports
during the operation, an associated press photographer heard the sound of rubber bullets and several rounds of live ammunition being fired in the camp
the security crackdown, which began earlier this week, has sent hundreds of military police into arab villages incorporated into jerusalem after the 1967 middle east war
the army said 114 arabs have been detained in the last four days, including 21 minors
the police force has been doubled to 3,000 and the army was authorized to help enforce order in mostly arab east jerusalem for the first time since it was annexed by israel after 1967, the army and municipal officials said
the people in these villages for the last two months thought they belonged to palestine. we are teaching them they live in israel and they will never forget it,'' a senior police officer said. ``we are throwing the book at them: traffic violations, drug trafficking, not paying taxes.''
in al essawieh, a village of unpaved streets abutting the wealthy jewish neighborhood of french hill, riot police ran checks thursday of arabs entering or leaving and detained those whose names appeared on a computerized list
shafikh ali obeid, 57, said his son, faisal, a 33-year-old taxi driver, was held by police for 24 hours wednesday because he was on the list for not paying last year's municipal taxes
they took the keys to his car and took him away in a police van,'' obeid said. he said his son was released after he paid a $1,500 fine, part of which will be applied to pay his tax bill
obeid said the taxes did not appear to provide services to palestinians. pointing to the garbage-filled streets and a greenish stream of open sewage, he complained of the poor quality of municipal services
garbage pickup service has been stopped since january in al essawieh and other arab villages because residents stoned municipal trucks
it is a very difficult time to pay taxes because most people haven't worked since the unrest began. the israelis know that,'' obeid said
it's another way to put the squeeze on us for adhering to the commercial strike,'' he said. ``the roundups are also a message to us to keep in line during the shultz visit.''
secretary of state george p. shultz urged israel on thursday to negotiate a prompt and final agreement with the arabs about the violence-plagued occupied territories
he said the 21-year israeli occupation of the west bank and gaza strip was the main reason for unrest that has cost at least 65 lives since dec. 8
its fundamental origin is essentially indigenous,'' shultz said on the flight from washington to begin a five-day peace shuttle in which he will present u.s. proposals to the israelis and arabs
shultz would give no details, but said his approach to both sides will go far beyond an interim arrangement for the occupied lands, where 1.5 million palestinians live
egypt, jordan and several other arab nations have told the united states they reject the 1978 camp david formula for self-rule in the territories
president hosni mubarak of egypt called the plan, which helped produce the march 1979 peace treaty between his country and israel, ``a thing of the past whose time has ended.''
on the plane, shultz told reporters ``final status issues'' must be taken up promptly, and ``we have a proposal for that.''
it is understood to be a two-step plan that would loosen israeli controls immediately and lead to negotiations for a final settlement, even palestinian statehood, by december
the secretary said the ``underlying problem'' in the west bank and gaza is that people ``don't have the basic rights of governance.''
president reagan said at a news conference wednesday night some of the violence was inspired from outside. he cited intelligence reports but gave no details
shultz said the intelligence reports provide a ``mixed picture,'' including interaction with outside forces
in order to deal with the main problem, he said, ``we seek among other things, consistent with israel's security, to look at things that would help palestinians gain legitimate rights.''
israeli control does not lend itself to ``a stable situation'' in the west bank and gaza, he said
a ``fundamental touchstone'' of his plan are resolutions passed by the u.n. security council in 1967 and 1973 calling on israel to cede territory in exchange for acceptance by its arab neighbors, shultz said
the secretary said the u.s. package is not like a ``cafeteria,'' permitting the sides to choose elements they like and reject the others
he also rejected a soviet proposal for an international conference in which the superpowers would play an active role, contending such arrangements are not likely to produce ``good results.''
israeli foreign minister shimon peres, who had urged washington for months to be more forceful, greeted shultz at the airport and said: ``there is no better alternative than to make the first step toward the long march to bring peace to our people and our area.''
peres said israelis were in the ``most demanding period in our life.''
shultz responded: ``now is the time to work for peace and i'm convinced i'm bringing with me a workable proposal.''
the big question is what prime minister yitzhak shamir will say to shultz when they meet on friday. until now, shamir has resisted the ``territory for peace'' formula long advocated by the state department
on saturday, shultz goes to amman to see zaid rifai, jordan's prime minister, and damascus for talks with president hafez assad of syria
in the past, shultz accused syria of sponsoring terrorism and said it should be isolated. reagan imposed sanction in 1986, including a ban on meetings between high-level u.s. and syrian officials
shultz explained his decision to visit damascus by saying: ``in the first place the syrian involvement in terrorism seems to have diminished, and we have had some definite moves that have been made that we found encouraging
i don't mean to say the problem is resolved. but that was the basic problem. beyond that, as we try to find our way to something that can be helpful in the region, we recognize that syria is an important state.''
sidney poitier says he has worked hard during his 38-year-career to be considered just an actor, not a black actor
today we have eddie murphy, denzel washington, richard pryor, bill cosby and james earl jones,'' said hollywood's first black leading man
we have a lot of black actors who are working. i am now finally just another actor, and that is a hallowed place to be,'' poitier says in the sunday issue of parade magazine
during an interview on the set of ``shoot to kill,'' his latest film, poitier reminisced about his mother and his poverty-filled youth growing up in the bahamas
when a mother would be giving her son a whipping for one thing or another, she'd say, `don't do that to the boy. leave him alone and let his mind work. that's the way my young sidney was _ and look what happened to him
hearing that was one of the best rewards i ever had,'' said poitier
singer willie nelson will be principal host of the nashville network's viewers' choice awards april 26, the cable channel has announced
the oak ridge boys and tnn's ralph emery will also share hosting duties during the 90-minute live show at the grand ole opry house
tnn viewers are now voting for winners in eight country music categories
nelson is known for such hits as ``on the road again'' and ``always on my mind'' as well as his longtime commitment to helping financially plagued farmers
all eyes were on patsy kensit, lead singer of the british band eighth wonder, when she performed at this year's 38th san remo music festival
at last year's festival, a strap on ms. kensit's dress broke during her number, exposing her breast. this year, her dress stayed put
well, i see your dress didn't fall down this year,'' presenter carlo mazzarini remarked after her performance
foreign talent again dominated the four-day festival, which wraps up saturday. wednesday night's six-hour show featured manhattan transfer, bryan ferry, ben e. king, debbie gibson, def leppard and toto
still to perform were paul mccartney, terence trent d'arby, bon jovi, joe cocker and art garfunkel
ilona staller, better known as cicciolina, the porn star who was elected to pariliament last year, faced new legal problems thursday as prosecutors pressed cases to bring her to trial on obscenity charges
rome chief's prosecutor, marco boschi, announced that he has asked the chamber of deputies to lift ms. staller's parliamentary immunity so she can be tried on charges of conspiring with other people to produce obscene publications and take part in live shows
only parliament can decide whether one of its members can be brought to trial
the rome case is one of three pending against the hungarian-born ms. staller, who was elected on the radical party ticket
earlier this week, a prosecutor in venice sent parliament video tapes of ms. staller riding bare-breasted on horseback through st. mark's square last september. another case regards photos of her in a magazine
ms. staller has often said she would welcome a trial to demonstrate what she calls the hypocrisy of italy's laws defining obscenity
the head of the house space subcommittee said thursday the commerce department may be trying a ``power grab'' by granting a massachusetts company an export license for an experiment that is to be flown aboard the soviet union's mir space station
it's no secret that since space is a sexy subject that the department of commerce wants to get its fingers into the jurisdiction of space,'' rep. bill nelson, d-fla., said at a news conference
is this another power grab of trying to get into the space business?'' an angry nelson asked
nelson said he was angry that commerce granted an export license to payload systems inc. of wellesley, mass., for a protein crystal growth experiment to be carried on the mir without consulting with nasa, the transportation department or congress
the florida democrat said he was very concerned about decisions being made by u.s. agencies ``who may not understand the full implications of their decisions upon the civilian and military space programs of this country.''
he said there are a number of questions that need to be answered about the payload systems plans and added, ``i want the whole process put on hold until those questions can be answered.''
payload systems was granted a license to export an experiment to test techniques for growing protein crystals in weightlessness. such experiments have been conducted on american spacecraft in the past, including the 1986 shuttle flight taken by nelson. but the u.s. spacefleet now is grounded and the soviet spacecraft are the only manned vehicles now available to experimenters
byron k. lichtenberg, who flew on the shuttle in 1983 as a non-astronaut experimenter, founded payload systems and has designed the experiment. the firm contacted the soviets about flying it on the mir in march 1987 and then applied in october to the commerce department for an export license. the license was approved early this month
nelson said that although the commerce department consulted with some people in the defense department, it did not consult with the national aeronautics and space administration, the department of transportation _ both of which have responsibilites in space _ nor with congress
the commerce department's unilateral decision, he said, has ``ominous implications'' for the future of the u.s. space program
nelson released a letter to commerce secretary william verity in which he said the process followed for the payload systems license was ``confusing and must be clarified.'' he asked verity to appear at a subcommittee hearings on the subject, to provide information on specific questions about the license
the federal government last year refused permission for general motors and general electric to launch american-made communications satellites on soviet rockets on the basis that it could result in a technology transfer to the soviets
nelson said he fears that payload systems' protein crystal growth experiment could give technology to the soviets
i understand enough about the (crystal growth) process that i know there are questions that ought to be asked before we start giving away insights into how to do this process,'' he said. nelson said the process may have ``important military applications.''
but payload systems research director anthony p. arrott said sunday that the experiment was to investigate only protein crystals, bits of organic matter that can be used in medical and biological research
neither arrott or lichtenberg were available thursday to comment on nelson's statements. a secretary at the wellesley office said neither man was at the office and that they were not reachable by telephone
a witness instrumental in an indictment of panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega was sentenced thursday to 14 years in prison without parole for his part in a drug-smuggling, money-laundering ring
today i would like to apologize to this court and to the united states for my crimes,'' steven michael kalish told u.s. district judge w. terrell hodges in an hour-long hearing. he asked for a ``compassionate sentence,'' promising he ``would not betray that trust.''
kalish, 35, who told congressional investigators last month he personally handed noriega a briefcase containing a $300,000 payoff, previously pleaded guilty to running a continuing criminal enterprise
prosecutors agreed to a cap of 20 years on what could have been a life sentence without parole during a plea agreement struck last march in the 1984 case, said robert t. kennedy, chief of the criminal division of the tampa u.s. attorney's office. kalish agreed to forfeit $2.8 million in cash and possessions as part of the bargain
without his cooperation, the recent indictment (of noriega) would not have been possible at this time,'' the government said in a sentencing memorandum filed earlier in the week
in court, kennedy acknowledged kalish's cooperation had been substantial, but added that didn't diminish the seriousness of his crimes
hodges said he had ``no difficulty in substantially mitigating the sentence'' because of kalish's cooperation and remorse, but noted a previous conviction in texas and gave him 14 years without parole
a recommendation of where kalish would serve his sentence was suppressed by the court at the request of defense attorneys, who said their client's life was in danger
the danger is specifically that he's testified against panamanian strongma manuel noriega, who is known for having been violent in the past toward people he deems his enemies,'' kalish's attorney, alan ellis, said outside the courtroom
kalish has been in federal custody since his arrest in july 1984. he pleaded guilty to being the field supervisor of a tampa-based smuggling ring founded by leigh bruce ritch that smuggled record amounts of colombian marijuana through panama
ritch was convicted and is serving a 30-year sentence without parole
noriega, who is chief of the panamanian defense forces, and business associate enrique pretelt were indicted feb. 4 by a grand jury in tampa for allegedly taking $4 million in payoffs from kalish and ritch to protect their operation
noriega also was charged with laundering more than $100 million of the ring's profits, partly through a corporation he controlled
the same day, a grand jury in miami indicted noriega on racketeering charges accusing him of taking at least $4.6 million from colombia's medellin cartel to protect 8,800 pounds in cocaine shipments
in january, kalish told the senate permanent subcommittee on investigation that he paid noriega more than $1 million in bribes and agreed to pay $3 million more on behalf of the ring, including leaving a briefcase containing $300,000 in cash the first time he met the general
nbc is sending ``highway to heaven,'' ``a year in the life'' and ``st. elsewhere'' out to pasture and adding three hour-long dramatic series to its schedule, the network announced thursday
in the heat of the night'' will premiere as a two-hour movie march 6 and then move into the tuesday 9 p.m. time slot march 15, replacing ``hunter.''
hunter'' will move to saturday at 10 p.m., beginning march 12, replacing ``j.j. starbuck,'' which is going on hiatus and may return later
a second new dramatic series, ``aaron's way,'' premieres as a two-hour movie march 9, and will appear on subsequent wednesdays at 8 p.m. it replaces ``highway to heaven,'' which will appear at 9 p.m. on march 16, 23 and 30, and then go on hiatus
a year in the life,'' currently showing at 9 p.m. wednesday, will be seen at 10 p.m. march 9, 16 and 23. that time slot will be taken over march 30 by a returning series, ``the bronx zoo.''
the network said it also intends to adds two comedies, ``the days and nights of molly dodd'' and ``beverly hills buntz,'' to the schedule, but those times will be announced later
united airlines inc. has paid an $11,000 civil penalty to settle 1987 charges that it violated federal transportation standards involving shipments of live animals, the agriculture department said thursday
the penalty was assessed by the department in an administrative action stemming from nine shipments of dogs and monkeys in 1985 and 1986. a complaint was filed against united last year by the department's animal and plant health inspection service, which administers the animal welfare act
james w. glosser, acting administrator of the agency, said the complaints alleged that united had accepted dogs in shipping kennels that did not conform to size requirement, and that the airline ``either failed to observe and care for the dogs properly'' or stowed them in cargo space without sufficient ventiliation
two dogs died during shipment and another was killed by highway traffic after it escaped shipment, glosser said. the airline also was cited for having ``allegedly accepted a shipment of 50 monkeys in cages that were not structurally sound'' and had no markings to tell they contained wild animals, he said
other allegations included the company's failure to ``move dogs expeditiously from an animal holding area to an airplane'' and to keep shipping containers in an upright position during unloading operations
glosser said united consented to a cease-and-desist order against future violations of the act and agreed within a year to buy a training film approved by usda and show it to all employees who handle live animal cargoes
the state supreme court refused thursday to allow immediate enforcement of a new california law requiring consent of parents or a judge for an abortion by an unmarried woman under 18
the court's unanimous action apparently means the law, blocked from taking effect jan. 1 by a superior court judge's order, will remain unenforced this year while its constitutionality is challenged
major doctors' organizations and family-planning groups contend the law violates the right to privacy under the state constituion by restricting minors' ability to decide on their own whether to give birth or get an abortion
the law, sponsored by anti-abortion groups, would make it a crime for a doctor to perform an abortion on an unmarried minor living at home who did not have written consent from one parent
as an alternative to parental consent, the minor could get a ruling from a judge, after a confidential hearing, that the abortion was in her best interest or that she was mature enough to make the decision on her own
state officials say about 34,000 women under 18 had abortions in 1985, the latest year for which figures are available. under the old law, which remains in effect, a woman of any age can consent to an abortion as long as her doctor concludes she understands the procedure and is consenting voluntarily
san francisco superior court judge morton colvin issued a preliminary injunction dec. 28 prohibiting enforcement of the new law until a trial could be held on its constitutionality. he said the law would cause irreparable harm if enforced in the meantime, and found a reasonable likelihood it would ultimately be ruled invalid
the state's 1st district court of appeal let colvin's order stand. attorney general john van de kamp, the lead defendant in the suit as the state's top law enforcement officer, then appealed to the state supreme court, asking the court to take over the case and to allow enforcement of the law while the suit is pending
george bush scored political points by depicting sen. bob dole as a supporter of tax hikes, but both republican presidential hopefuls have waffled on this volatile issue in the past
bush acquiesced in the notion of increasing taxes last fall though he said he didn't like it. he now maintains that he, as president, would not raise taxes
dole supported the sweeping reduction in tax rates in 1981, but helped enact a $98.3 billion tax hike a year later. he now bridles at conservative portrayals of him as willing to support tax legislation
dole said bush was ``lying about my record'' in a commercial that said dole would readily raise taxes
the ad damaged dole's chances in new hampshire. dole admitted later that he should have responded. he also evidently harmed himself by brushing aside pete du pont's debate challenge to sign a no-tax pledge
the argument revolves about the murky area of the candidates' intentions with respect to future tax increases, mostly because neither bush nor dole can cite a record of having consistently opposed such hikes
barry bosworth, a brookings institution fellow who once headed president carter's council of economic advisers, said that to the extent bush's commercial raised doubts about dole's tax intentions, voters ``responded because they vote their pocketbook.''
the dole campaign has put forth a truth squad to monitor bush's commericals during the balance of the campaign, and the bush camp continues to deny that it distorted the senator's position on taxes
but the record is full of inconsistencies regarding both general tax increases and the question of imposing an import fee on foreign oil
during the 1980 campaign, bush labeled as ``voodoo economics'' reagan's pledge to restore u.s. military might while cutting taxes and balancing the budget. but the record shows no evidence of a bush dissent from tax increases that reagan has signed in the ensuing years
in fact, the closest bush came to a dissent was when he told a crowd in iowa last november that while he didn't like the tax hikes envisioned in the deficit-reduction package, ``i'll support whatever compromise the president makes.''
bush also slipped last october by launching his presidential campaign with an uncompromising pledge to not raises taxes, only to subsequently leave the door slightly ajar. in an oct. 15 interview on cable news network, bush backtracked from his oct. 12 houston promise
what i have said is, if i were convinced that all spending that could possibly be constrained or cut had taken place, then and only then would i consider a tax increase,'' he said. later in the same day, when pressed for an explanation, bush replied, ``i'm not going to raise taxes, period.''
the record shows that dole supported various deficit-reduction tax hike proposals, including the $98.3 billion package in 1981, a $50.6 billion program in 1984 and the $22 billion in hikes contained in a plan reagan agreed to last nov. 20 in the wake of the wall street crash
but dole and his supporters complained bitterly about the bush commercials in new hamsphire _ ads which sen. warren rudman of new hampshire called a ``misstatement of (dole's) record.''
both bush and dole have made statements which seemed to indicate at least a willingness to consider an oil import fee, although dole says he voted against it five times since 1980, and bush said ``an oil import fee is not the way to decrease dependence'' on foreign oil
bush talks frequently of a need to lessen u.s. reliance on foreign oil, but discusses only generally the notion of strengthening the american petroleum industry. an oil import fee would do that
dole's spokeswoman, katie boyle, recently sought to clarify statements he made indicating he would consider such a fee, saying that it would have to carry a rebate provision for consumers
bosworth said in times of general economic prosperity, candidates for political office score big points by suggesting an opponent would raise taxes
i think dole has probably learned from this (loss in new hampshire),'' he said. ``it appears republicans voted for bush there because he appeared to be more adamant about not raising taxes than dole was.''
larry sabato, a political science professor and presidential scholar at the university of virginia, said ``this (bush) succeeded only because dole chose not to respond to it. it was very uncharacteristic of him.''
bush has no position. dole has a record, which includes revenue increases in concert with the administration,'' said bob mcintyre of the private group, citizens for tax justice
martin anderson, who served as a domestic policy adviser in the reagan white house during the first term, said ``my recollection is'' that bush was an even more ardent supporter of tax cuts than was reagan
in fact, he is pushing more, including seeking the cut in capital gains taxes,'' anderson said of the vice president
outgoing president chun doo-hwan held the hand of his 2-year-old granddaughter thursday as he left the presidential mansion after seven years in power
looking strained, chun shook hands with a long line of aides and officials in the grounds of the blue house. occasionally he flashed a tense smile as he quietly said farewell
less than an hour earlier, chun had sat in front of the national assembly and watched roh tae-woo take the oath of office as the country's new president. the two men then returned to the blue house in the center of seoul for chun's formal departure
it was the first time in south korea's turbulent 40-year history that a president had left power peacefully. officials who arranged the ceremony said it had been a problem working out what to do since there was no precedent to follow
chun, who is to serve as an honorary presidential adviser, was widely disliked for his tough rule and suppression of opposition
it is still hard to believe he is leaving. it is so quiet,'' said one man watching the departure ceremony that was nationally televised
roh watched briefly from the doorway as chun left the mansion and then went inside. chun remained outside for a few minutes shaking hands and then drove off
hundreds of security guards and officials lined sidewalks at the main gate and applauded as chun drove away. he waved back as the car sped past
life at the heavily guarded blue house quickly returned to normal after chun left. squads of soldiers resumed patrolling the mansion and its grounds
chun had said repeatedly in recent weeks that he was eager to leave office after seven taxing years. he said he had no regrets and had never wanted to be president
now is the time for me to leave the stage of history, the time to be released from the bondage of public life, the time to be free from the oppressive solitude of the executive office,'' he said in a farewell address wednesday night
chun, roh and other generals took power in 1980 following the assassination of president park chung-hee. roh was elected to succeed chun in december in the first democratic presidential vote in 16 years
some people cheered the ex-president as he returned to his home in seoul. they waved korean flags and a band of folk dancers performed a welcoming dance
other spectators complained later to newspapers that they had been ordered to take part in the ceremony. suspend agreements, sted of suspended; adds details on other threatened action.</note>
united auto workers union officials today threatened to block special agreements at six chrysler corp. plants in an effort to discourage the sale of the company's parts-making division
in addition, the union threatened to suspend other programs that call for cooperation between labor and management at plants nationwide to persuade the nation's no. 3 automaker to keep acustar inc
about 140 local union delegates and members today approved a resolution calling for the suspension of the team concept operating agreements, under which a single group of workers is assigned to put together parts of a car. the traditional american process involves one worker doing a single task on an assembly line
the union is bound by contract to honor the agreements at plants in huntsville, ala.; indianapolis; newcastle, ind.; newark, del.; trenton, n.j.; and detroit. so far, the agreements are in effect only in huntsville, indianapolis and newcastle
but the union is looking for ways to block the agreements, uaw vice president marc stepp said. he did not elaborate
chrysler chairman lee iacocca said feb. 4 that chrysler was entertaining offers to sell all or part of the $3-billion division, saying the company no longer wanted to invest in the research needed to keep some operations technologically up to date
uaw officials have said they feel cheated by talk of the sale because of concessions they made to help bring chrysler out of past financial troubles
acustar employs about 27,000 workers at more than 24 plants nationwide. it makes car parts and some non-automotive products such as chemicals and vinyl
a three-day student walkout at an academically troubled elementary school ended thursday after the principal compromised on her get-tough decision to demote 250 students to lower grade levels
parents had kept an estimated 400 students out of classes at beethoven elementary school since monday to protest the demotions of students whose reading skills were below grade level on standardized achievement tests
but they ended the boycott after principal grace dawson agreed to return demoted students to their original grade levels if their parents met individually with her and helped teachers devise reading-improvement plans
ms. dawson said thursday most of the school's 830 students were back in class and that about 150 of the demoted students had been returned to their original grade levels
but she said 100 students hadn't been reinstated. in some cases, the parents had agreed to the demotions. in others, she said, the students wouldn't be reinstated until their parents went to the school for conferences
cynthia thomas, whose 10-year-old daughter tamika had been demoted from fourth to third grade, said she thought the boycott had accomplished the parents' goal, but that the children also would benefit
they're going to get some extra tutoring and some extra reading programs for our kids.''
the principal said she ordered the mass demotions because so many of beethoven's students were several years behind in learning to read. most of them live in the nearby robert taylor homes, the nation's largest high-rise public housing project, located in a south side neighborhood rife with crime and street gangs
sometimes drastic action has to take place to break the ice,'' ms. dawson she said thursday
when the demotions took effect feb. 15, students were not shifted to other classrooms, but were taught materials and subjects from the lower grades
in some cases, entire classrooms were taught at a lower grade level, ms. dawson said
ms. dawon said the demoted students scored from two years to four years behind grade level on the iowa basic skills test given last year and on the metropolitan achievement test given in january
i will not be a party to passing students on to the next grade who aren't qualified,'' she said. ``as a professional educator, i will not sit back and say there's nothing we can do. otherwise, the children are the losers.''
the principal said her get-tough policy worked by forcing parents to become involved in their children's education
since wednesday, ms. dawson said she had met with about 60 parents to discuss the demotions. she said about 25 percent agreed to leave their children at the lower gade level for the rest of the year
i'm happy because we can't do anything to improve education without parental support,'' she added
a conservative judicial nominee told senators thursday he would discard his unorthodox views and follow supreme court precedent if confirmed, but the same liberals who opposed robert h. bork expressed doubts that he would keep the promise
in a pledge similar to that made by bork in his tumultuous confirmation hearing, nominee bernard siegan said he would ``observe the law of the land'' and added, ``i would resign'' if unable to do so
siegan, a 63-year-old professor at the university of san diego law school, is president reagan's nominee for the 9th u.s. circuit court of appeals
the circuit, on which new supreme court justice anthony m. kennedy served, has jurisdiction over alaska, arizona, california, hawaii, idaho, montana, nevada, oregon, washington, guam and the northern mariana islands
siegan told the senate judiciary committee, ``there are times i will rule contrary to my own feelings. it would be a direct violation and contrary of my oath to push my position ahead of the supreme court.''
in his confirmation hearings last year, bork was unable to convince senators he would put aside his controversial writings, and he suffered a crushing defeat in the senate by a 58-42 vote
siegan's free-wheeling views do not always parallel those of bork, but he's just as controversial when writing on subjects such as civil rights, economic law, separation of church and state, and equal protection for women
as the hearing ended, people for the american way, which had opposed bork vigorously, attacked siegan in a statement
bernard siegan spent the morning distancing himself from his entire body of legal scholarship,'' the group said. but sen. orrin g. hatch, r-utah, who was one of bork's main supporters, told siegan, ``i hope people will give you a fair shake.''
siegan's testimony did not convince to bork opponents: sens. howard m. metzenbaum, d-ohio, and patrick j. leahy, d-vt
leahy questioned siegan's almost total lack of experience in federal courtrooms. ``the last time you were in federal court (35 years ago) i was 12 years old.''
metzenbaum told siegan, ``i'm concerned that if confirmed, you will find a way to implement your views. circuit courts are often the courts of last resort.'' he said there would be a ``great risk'' if the senate confirmed siegan
responding to leahy, siegan said, ``a circuit court judge is given scholarly duties to see if what the lower court did was right. i have spent 20 years of my life in scholarly activities. even a lawyer with trial experience may not know how to write an opinion.''
among siegan's controversial writings:
he would have outlawed separate but equal schools as the supreme court did in 1954, but would have used a reasoning far afield from that used by the high court in reaching its decision
according to siegan, the court should have based its decision on the right of black students to travel to the school of their choice. civil rights advocates have said travel to a new school would not guarantee pupils a seat inside
siegan wrote that the 14th amendment ``safeguards only fundamental and natural rights from violation by the states. there is no fundamental or natural right to education, nor to an integrated education. each is a political right created by government and is accordingly not within the guarantees of the 14th amendment.''
he wrote that the amendment, which extended federal constitutional safeguards to residents of the individual states, was meant to safeguard religious liberty _ but not separation of church and state
it is that view which led him to say it is ``possible to argue that prayer in school would not be in violation of the constitution.'' the supreme court has taken the opposite view
a woman accused of murdering her husband has given up her fight with his family over his burial, but she will be allowed to arrange a memorial service for him, attorneys said
denise monique horner, 21, is charged with first-degree murder in the contract shooting of her husband, vincent horner, 25, whose body was found feb. 2 in his pickup truck in a mall parking lot
mrs. horner, who is being held without bond at the duval county jail, had arranged for her husband's body to be buried or cremated by a jacksonville funeral home
but the victim's father, burt horner, filed a lawsuit saying that because mrs. horner is accused of killing her husband, she has lost her right to decide how the body should be disposed. he wanted to take his son's body to his home state of louisiana
under florida law, a dead person's spouse has the right to dispose of the body unless the spouse caused the death
circuit judge charles o. mitchell ruled that since mrs. horner has not yet been convicted of the crime, burt horner would have to prove during a civil trial that mrs. horner caused her husband's death
wednesday, however, attorneys for both sides reached a settlement in which burt horner would get custody of the body. he agreed, however, to keep his son's body in jacksonville for 10 days so mrs. horner and her family could hold a memorial service
alan chipperfield, mrs. horner's attorney, said wednesday he hopes to get a judicial order allowing mrs. horner to attend the service in the custody of an officer
prosecutors have said they plan to seek the death penalty against mrs. horner. according to court documents, witnesses told police mrs. horner told them she had arranged to have her husband killed
there have been no other arrests in horner's death.  
a group of house members on thursday condemned south africa's decision to ban activities of anti-apartheid groups and scheduled a stepped-up timetable for action on legislation to impose stricter sanctions on the pretoria regime
several of the members also had strong criticism for president reagan, who in a wednesday night news conference said south african unrest results from ``a tribal policy more than it is a racial policy.''
rep. howard wolpe, d-mich., chairman of the house foreign affairs africa subcommittee, scheduled five days of hearings next month and said he hoped to bring a strong sanctions bill to the floor by mid-april or earlier
additional sanctions are the only peaceful means for the west to hammer home to pretoria that the west will not permit the voices of opposition to expire,'' wolpe said at a news conference
he called the white minority government's decision to outlaw even peaceful dissent ``yet one more step towards absolute totalitarian government control over south africa's non-white majority. the south african regime leaves no doubt of its determination to systematically deny any and all forms of legitimate protest, to criminalize what we in the united states know are basic human rights.''
wolpe noted that south african anglican archbishop desmond tutu had appealed to western nations to step up anti-apartheid sanctions in response to the latest crackdown, and said his committee would begin working on a tough sanctions package sponsored by rep. ron dellums, d-calif
rep. jim leach, r-iowa, criticized reagan's news-conference comment as ``very insensitive and lacking any sense of history. this is an issue of democracy. this administration has to stand up on this issue. it can't just slough it off.''
rep. william gray, d-pa., said of reagan: ``his idea of south africa is that of a 1930s tarzan movie.''
wolpe noted that the state department had protested the latest crackdown on dissent by anti-apartheid groups. but he added, ``the moment has arrived for the reagan administration to back its words with action.''
a cut in a major telephone cable 15 miles south of newark disrupted communications along the east coast on thursday, according to american telephone &amp; telegraph co. officials
bill leach, a manager in the at&amp;t network operations center, said the break occurred at about 9:40 a.m. and resulted in a ``fairly heavy network blockage'' of both voice and data transmissions
about 20 percent to 25 percent of the calls running north and south between boston and washington were answered with a recording that told callers that all circuits were busy, and asked them to try again later
a re-routing scheme whittled down the interrupted calls, and by noon all calls were going through, leach said
private circuits, most of them devoted to data transmission, would take longer to restore, leach said. loops were being arranged to divert those circuits, he said, and work was underway to repair the cable
leach said the cause of the break was unknown
the cut disrupted associated press services, interrupting dispatches from ap bureaus to the cooperative's headquarters in new york as well as news to newspapers and broadcast outlets nationwide
efforts to restore service using backup circuits were held up by the severity of the problem, but ultimately service was restored
shipments of federally inspected reindeer steaks across the country would be allowed under a proposal announced thursday by the agriculture department
there is mandatory federal inspection of cattle, hogs, chickens and turkeys at slaughter plants, which allows those carcasses to be shipped across state lines
in addition, regulations permit the voluntary inspection of certain exotic animals slaughtered for human food. those include the american bison, or buffalo, and the cattalo, a cross between cattle and the buffalo
lester m. crawford, head of the department's food safety and inspection service, said producers of exotic animals have asked that the inspection list be expanded to include reindeer, elk, deer, antelope and water buffalo
this proposal is a response to their request and could facilitate the sale and export of the carcasses, meat and meat food products from these animals,'' he said. ``once the animals and products are inspected and passed, they can be sold interstate or exported.''
producers of the animals would pay fees to receive the optional inspection service. crawford said fewer than 2,000 exotic animals are slaughtered annually at the present time and that the slaughter level is not expected to increase much if the exotic list is expanded
by comparison, he said, annual cattle slaughter has been running at more than 32 million head
public comments on the proposal can be sent by april 26 to: linda carey, fsis hearing clerk, room 3168-s, fsis, usda, washington, d.c. 20250
the federal election commission on thursday sanctioned excluding some tv costs from the state spending limits for presidential campaigns, in what a dissenting member said was ``blowing the state limits out of the water.''
by 4-2, the fec told democratic contender albert gore jr. that it is all right to count half of a television ad as a fund-raising expense _ which is exempt from the spending limits _ even if the overt money solicitation occurs during three seconds of a 60-second ad
commissioner joan aikens objected, saying it is merely ``sanctioning creative accounting to get around the limits.''
i think we are absolutely blowing the state limits out of the water,'' she said
gore, a senator from tennessee, sought the opinion after rep. richard gephardt, d-mo., and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who are among gore's rivals for the democratic presidential nomination, ran ads in iowa and counted up to half the cost as a fund-raising expense. that allowed them to spend more money against the iowa overall limit of $775,000
because of the need to have a good showing in iowa, scene of the first democratic caucuses, candidates try to spend as much as possible there. most of the democratic candidates spent the limit
bob bauer, gephardt's campaign attorney, expressed satisfaction with the fec decision and discounted as nonsense the allegations that the practice was merely a way to overspend
we didn't write the law. we simply read the law ... and interpreted it as the fec has interpreted it,'' he said
gore's spokesman paul risley said the campaign was glad the fec had clarified the issue, but declined to elaborate
the commission majority said the agency's auditors should not have to scrutinize every campaign commercial to decide what portion should be considered fund raising
in arguing the prevailing viewpoint, chairman thomas josefiak said that even if an ad also has other purposes, as long as it contains some obvious fund-raising message and information on how to contribute _ such as a telephone number to call _ the ad can be seen as having a dual purpose. in that case, a 50 percent allocation for fund-raising would be reasonable, the commission determined
the decision rejected the recommendation of the fec legal staff which had held that the write-off should be generally proportional to the part of the ad that contains a fund-raising message
in the case of the 60-second ad proposed by gore, with an appeal for viewers to contribute in the last three seconds, a 5 percent allocation for fund raising would be reasonable, but 50 percent would not, fec counsel larry noble contended
commissioner lee ann elliott, who dissented along with aikens, suggested a flat 10-percent write-off for fund raising should be imposed for ads. she criticized the majority decision as a ``mushy'' one that does not give the campaigns a precise guideline
the law sets a spending cap for each state and an overall campaign spending limit of $23 million, plus another $4.6 million for fund-raising costs. the fund-raising costs can be excluded from state limits as long as the campaign has not gone over the $4.6 million
the fec for several years has asked congress to do away with state-by-state limits as burdensome
gore did not mention the other campaigns in his request, but his aides said the query was an attempt to get an fec ruling on the activity of his opponents
gore's hypothetical case, involving an ad he proposed for colorado's april 4 caucuses, paralleled gephardt's commercial in iowa in which the final seconds asked viewers to ``vote, volunteer, contribute.'' gephardt excluded half the cost from the spending his campaign allocated to iowa
the gephardt and dukakis campaigns had cited the precedent of ohio democratic sen. john glenn's presidential campaign in 1984, in which the fec allowed a 50 percent fund-raising write-off for glenn's half-hour tv show
but commissioners said that example should not be a guideline, because the fec decided the matter well after the election during a routine fec audit of glenn's finances to determine if any of his federal matching funds were improperly spent or if there had been any irregularities
that decision was in the context of negotiation and compromise, josefiak noted, after the glenn campaign had initially tried to count the entire 30-minute show as a fund-raising expense
education secretary william j. bennett gave the states mediocre grades thursday on an annual report card that showed dropout rates up slightly, college entrance test scores level and spending higher than ever
the news is not what it should be. test scores are in a dead stall,'' bennett said as he unveiled two wall charts crammed with statistics ranking the states on tests, graduation rates, teacher pay and other measures
in saying that i am disappointed, i think i speak for the american people,'' bennett told reporters. ``we're paying top dollar to educate our children, but we're sure not getting top return.''
mary hatwood futrell, president of the national education association, the nation's largest teachers union, said in an interview:
the time has come to halt the wall chart charade and for people to sit down and really talk about ways we can improve the quality of education for all young people in this country.''
the chart really doesn't give us a lot of helpful information ... other than to serve as a reminder of what we said a long time ago: if you don't provide the support and the resources, and you raise standards, children are going to fall through the cracks,'' mrs. futrell said
asked if citizens should use the statistics as ammunition to vote down school levies, bennett said that depends on how well the local schools are performing
referring to chicago's troubled schools, which he said recently are in ``an educational meltdown,'' bennett said:
if i were a citizen of chicago and they said, `we need more money to make this school effective,' i'd tell them to take a hike. ... they're spending $6,000 per kid for a 50 percent dropout (rate).''
nationally, bennett said the graduation rate from public high schools in 1986 was only 71.5 percent, down from 71.7 percent in 1985
the graduation rate is up from 69.5 percent in 1982, but it is far short of president reagan's goal of a 90 percent graduation rate by 1990
only minnesota, with a 91.4 percent graduation rate, has bettered that goal. near it are connecticut, 89.8 percent; north dakota, 89.7 percent; nebraska, 88.1 percent; and iowa, 87.5 percent
the worst graduation rates are the district of columbia, 56.8 percent; florida, 62.0 percent; georgia and louisiana, both 62.7 percent; and arizona, 63.0 percent
it was the fifth straight year that an education secretary has released the controversial all charts. bennett's predecessor, t.h. bell, initiated the practice
the class of 1987's scores on the scholastic aptitude test and american college testing program were released last fall. the national average on the sat, scored on a scale of 400 to 1,600, was 906. the average on the act, which has a scale of 1 to 36, was 18.7
bennett provided his own rankings of the states
he singled out south carolina for praise, although its sat average of 832 was again dead last among the 22 states where the sat is the dominant test. he said south carolina has picked up 17 points in the past two years, and he called it a pacesetter in efforts to hold educators more accountable for student performance
bennett also praised california for a tough new social studies curriculum; virginia for efforts to make high school students take rigorous math courses; and new jersey for welcoming non-education majors into the teaching profession
the secretary said 43 states now require entering teachers to pass competency tests, up from 34 last year. they are not required by the district of columbia, alaska, iowa, north dakota, utah, vermont, wisconsin and wyoming
gordon ambach, executive director of the council of chief state school officers, said the graduation rate exceeds 75 percent if high school equivalency diplomas are counted, but he agreed that is not good enough. he cautioned against reading too much into bennett's scorecard
the wall chart listed seven states _ arkansas, georgia, kentucky, new jersey, ohio, south carolina and texas _ with laws allowing state intervention in ``academically bankrupt'' school districts
bennett said nearly 10 percent of high school graduates now take advanced college placement exams, up from less than 5 percent in 1982, and a larger proportion of seniors are taking the act and sat. that ``means we are succeeding in keeping scores level despite a larger pool of test-takers,'' he said
test results ``show that poor, black and hispanic children are performing better,'' said bennett, although there is still a wide gap between minority and majority scores
bennett said that since 1976 black students' scores on the sat have risen by 42 points to 728, while white students' scores fell eight points to 936
he was asked if it troubled him that sat scores rose during the early 1980s, but have stayed flat since he joined the cabinet
i don't take that personally.'' he replied. ``i don't think the children taking these tests are in any particular conspiracy against me. it's more a comment on what was going on in their classroom.''
movie and television writers are conducting whisper-quiet negotiations with producers for a new three-year contract, an uncharacteristic approach for the film capital's most militant union
three years ago, the 9,000-member writers guild of america shuddered under internal strife. one faction contended union leaders had misinformed the membership about the producers' offer and caused an unnecessary two-week strike
the union eventually voted to accept virtually the same contract it had rejected. an organizational shakeup followed
talks for the 1988 contract with the alliance of motion picture and television producers are nearing an end, with writers seeking a greater share of foreign market income and producers hoping to restructure residual payments for one-hour syndicated shows
the alliance is an umbrella organization representing about 200 studios and producers. the contract with writers expires at midnight feb. 29, when the producers say they will make their final offer
the union and producers have been discussing their disagreements behind closed doors, and carefully handling their public statements with low-key information campaigns
producers say that despite record box office grosses, the entertainment industry needs a serious cost-control campaign
the union seeks what it calls ``parallel growth,'' meaning more money from areas in which the producers are doing well
guild west regional director brian walton said the union is prepared to strike if necessary, ``but we would first hope to work out the problems.''
herb steinberg, a spokesman for the alliance, has characterized chief producer negotiator nicholas counter and walton as ``very intelligent, bright gentlemen ... there is no sense of rancor or confrontation.''
steinberg said the producers' offer on feb. 29 will be ``firm and final.'' walton said the union has taken precautions to make sure members are kept informed about negotiations, to avoid the confusion and rancor of 1985
since its first contract in 1947, the union has hit the bricks in 1959, 1960, 1973, 1981 and 1985 _ the most strikes by any hollywood union
its west coast members, numbering about 6,500, will vote on the producers' offer on march 1, while 2,000 of the 2,500 east coast members will consider the contract on march. 2. the other 500 members on the east coast are television newswriters unaffected by this contract
in 1987, union members enjoyed an 11.6 percent increase in residual payments, to $57 million, with $39.5 million of that from television. currently, a writer receives $5,100 for a half-hour television script, but experienced writers generally negotiate a substantially higher fee
motion pictures drew a record $4.25 billion in ticket sales for 1987. but producers insist development and production costs are still overwhelming
steinberg and walton both refused to characterize any issue as dominant. but the writers' proposal to increase their residual share of lucrative foreign market distribution income, and the producer's desire to cut residual costs for one-hour syndicated television shows, appear to be the most controversial
writers argue that theatrical and broadcasting product has become one of the largest u.s. exports, registering at least a $4.9 billion trade surplus in 1986. producers say looking at individual growth areas without paying attention to rising production costs is unrealistic
producers have asked writers to drop the fixed residual rate for hourlong television shows and accept a sliding scale of residual payments tied to the show's syndication licensing success
few shows these days turn a first-run profit. the deficit for a one-hour show in 1986-1987 was $370,274, producers have said
while shows for prime-time television have long been deficit-financed, producers used to make their money back with lucrative syndication deals for reruns. but new made-for-syndication shows have hurt that market
the one-hour show syndication market has dried up,'' alliance spokesman steinberg said. ``some deals are possible, if we could bring the price down.''
walton has said the producers' proposal is not in parity with the deal movie and television directors got last summer for accepting the same formula
the union said its analysis showed the producers' figures are derived from the 15 most expensive action-adventure shows. ``also, they are still producing and developing these hourlong shows,'' walton said
producers also want to raise the minimum for defined ``low budget'' movies and television shows. writers take a substantial cut in fees for a defined ``low budget'' work
writers once again are seeking residual increases for videocassette movies, noting directors received an increase in their 1987 contract
among the other 107 demands from the guild are increased affirmative action hiring for women and minority writers; increased health fund contributions by management; and creative rights for scriptwriters
a non-profit group on thursday announced a new loan service that will allow colleges and universities to borrow up to $100 million at below prime interest rates
the capital access trust will make loans to institutions with good credit for new buildings, renovations or for operating money
it is the latest undertaking of university support services inc., a non-profit corporation started in 1986 by business and academic leaders to lend money to students from families that do not qualify for financial aid
the rev. john p. whalen, president of university support services and former president of the catholic university of america, said more than three-quarters of the nation's campuses will need to undertake renovations or new construction in the next five years costing millions of dollars
he said the trust is ``a major new source of capital ... in amounts ranging anywhere from relatively small loans to upwards of $100 million.''
he claimed it will be able to make the loan commitments in just 45 days at rates more favorable ``than any source of borrowing we know, except tax-exempt financing.''
the trust is funded by the sale of university support services commercial paper notes, backed by a bank line of credit and underwritten by shearson lehman hutton inc
the interest rate is tied to the commercial paper note rate quoted in the wall street journal, which whalen said is significantly lower than the prime rate
whalen said that if a college borrows $50 million from the trust for three years instead of borrowing from a bank at the prime rate, it could save $250,000 to $350,000 in interest
university support services' student loan program, called consern, lends individuals from $1,500 to $25,000 a year for private school or college costs. the interest rate varies; it is currently 10.44 percent
a man and woman were charged thursday with trying to sell their 3-month-old baby girl after they allegedly offered to trade the child for a car to drive to mexico, authorities said
a car lot worker told police that the woman said she and the man wanted to trade the baby for an ``old junker'' to go to mexico because they could not afford to keep the baby
detective kevin foster said alicia rodriguez, 31, and porfirio noriega, 23, both of fort worth, were charged with the sale or purchase of a child. they were held in the tarrant county jail in lieu of $1,000 bond
a man and woman at the car dealership refused to make a trade for the child, foster said, but did offer to adopt the baby and sell the couple a car on credit
the child is in the care of the department of human services, foster said
rising floodwaters forced the evacuation of more than 10,000 people and have inundated 1,500 houses this week in the central part of the country, officials said thursday
at least 16 deaths have been reported since monday in floods along the orange river in the orange free state and have since spread to the northern cape province
rail traffic has been knocked out and the main highway between johannesburg and cape town is reduced to one lane. twenty-five magisterial districts have been declared disaster areas and farmers are harvesting their crops 24 hours a day to save something from the encroaching rivers
the strongly flowing orange river, fed by the vaal and modder rivers, has risen more than 6{ feet in two days, the south african press association reported
half of the town of douglas, 50 miles west of the historic mining town of kimberley, was underwater thursday and hundreds of residents had been evacuated to a nearby hill, sapa reported. in the towns of prieska and upington, another 200 miles west along the orange river, residents began loading furniture into trucks in preparation for the wall of water expected to hit them by saturday
local police said the flood line is already higher than the level reached in 1974, when the orange river rose more than 32{ feet, destroying 70 percent of the crops in the central part of the country and leaving hundreds homeless
the minister of national health, willie van niekerk, estimated damage to the road and rail network at about $10 million, and damage to bridges at $3 million. crop and housing damage could not be estimated until the waters subside
clean water is still scarce, telephone lines are down, and mail is being delivered by boat in areas of the orange free state
flooded roads, washed-out homes and inundated cropland have also been reported in lesotho, swaziland and mozambique, but no deaths have been reported. heroin</head>
two recently slain drug agents may have been victims of a war pitting old-line dealers and government agents against asian gangs who are importing ``golden triangle'' heroin into california, officials said thursday
emerging thai, cambodian and laotian drug rings will likely clash with existing hispanic, black and white gangs, opening the way for street wars like those in miami in the 1970s and '80s, said john hensley, the top drug enforcement officer for the u.s. customs service on the west coast
if the asians start mixing it up with the mexican and black gangs, we may see the gun battles and murders that marked the old colombian `cocaine cowboy' wars in miami a decade ago,'' hensley said. ``with the kind of money involved, either side could do the shooting.''
two drug enforcement administration working undercover to crack an alleged taiwanese heroin ring were gunned down in pasadena earlier this month. two alleged traffickers also were killed
investigators have said the alleged drug dealers were unaware they were dealing with federal agents and had set up a drug purchase with plans all along to rob and kill their ``customers.''
such violent confrontations are typical of the turf wars waged by smugglers and sellers, hensley said
in miami during the late 1970s and early 1980s, ``i was there during one turf battle between colombians and cubans and we (federal agents) were the only ones without automatic weapons,'' he said
we saw the turf wars there. if we don't get a cap on it now, it will become a reality here and we don't want it to be a reality,'' he said
the amount of golden triangle heroin, named for the fertile opium-growing area where thailand, cambodia and laos meet, arriving in california during the last two years has increased dramatically. three years ago, only about 15 percent of the heroin smuggled into the state was of the asian variety, said dea spokesman roger guevara
we now estimate that southeast asian heroin represents 50 percent to 80 percent of all the heroin coming into the country. it's a huge influx for los angeles, and it has turned los angeles into a major transshipment center for new york,'' he said
the asians, including the taiwanese, have a ready supply and the potential growth of asian gangs in heroin distribution can lead to more violence,'' guevara said. ``on the other hand, the blacks, mexicans and the whites have always controlled the street heroin market.''
it will cost some more lives to stop the war, the men agreed. agents dealing with drugs and gangs are always more at risk than other agents, hensley said
they aren't wearing body armor. undercover you never know when you're being burned and the backup isn't always that great,'' he said
heroin is more appealing to dealers than other drugs for several reasons, hensley said
because of several national programs, including big anti-drug pushes by the sports and entertainment industries and anti-drug messages by stars, use of cocaine and marijuana has stabilized, he said
heroin is different. users don't look at michael jackson as a role model. the heroin user group is growing slightly, even though there is a turnover because as new users come in, others overdose and die out.''
and heroin brings a distributor a much higher price than a like amount of cocaine, hensley added, in part because it ultimately can be diluted to as low as 3 percent for street sales
a pound of heroin sells for about $50,000, and a kilo, 2.2 pounds, for between $90,000 and $200,000, ``depending on the purity and the dealer,'' he said
agents used to concentrate on couriers who brought in a few pounds of heroin on ships or international flights, he said
but now, heroin has started arriving in the mail, hensley said. ``about two weeks ago, we seized about 45 pounds at the mail facility in oakland.''
we have to look everywhere now,'' he said
the environmental protection agency on thursday unveiled a draft policy that could let states decide when, where and how to use pesticides which could contaminate groundwater
states would get such powers by adopting pesticide management programs approved by epa. otherwise, epa would forbid use of the pesticide in states or counties with high potential for groundwater contamination
without a state plan, ``the risk-benefit determinations underlying these epa-determined geographic prohibitions will be rather crude,'' the agency said
with a plan, states could employ more detailed land and water data than epa would have available. ``where found appropriate, epa would consider modifying the federal registration to accomodate the state program,'' the agency said
epa published the policy as a draft, asking for comment from the public over the next four months
a single national approach ``is going to over-protect, or possibly under-protect'' in specific areas, said john a. moore, assistant administrator for pesticides and toxic substances, at a news conference
soils and groundwater vulnerability vary greatly even within counties, and at the county level and below ``epa's ability to do something ... is not very good,'' moore said
but that does not mean ``epa would walk away from these pesticides.'' in deciding whether to license a chemical, or re-license it, epa has been considering groundwater in deciding whether to impose national conditions, he said
also, the contamination standards the states would be obliged to observe would be set by epa _ existing drinking water standards for chemicals that don't cause cancer, and for cancer-causing chemicals, a concentration that would yield a one in a million chance of cancer for someone drinking from the aquifer over a lifetime
pesticide contamination of groundwater is a relatively new issue. the first examples were found in new york and california in 1979
epa expects to complete a survey in 1990 on the extent of contamination. two years ago, the agency said 19 pesticides had been found in groundwater in 24 states. now, said patrick holden, team leader of the groundwater project in epa's pesticides office, 50 to 60 different chemicals have been found in wells in 30 states. iowa has found pesticides in half the wells serving cities
pesticides are not the only thing that contaminates groundwater, source of drinking water for half the population and for 97 percent of people living in rural areas. fertilizers, waste disposal wells and leaking underground tanks all can contribute substantially
states may get federal aid for setting up wellhead protection zones, and soon epa expects to adopt a groundwater strategy that would require states to classify aquifers under a three-part scheme for high priority protection, drinking water sources and water unlikely ever to be drunk and thus needing little protection
this strategy has been opposed by many environmentalists as writing off what could a substantial fraction of groundwater supplies
sen. david durenberger, r-minn., said thursday in introducing a bill calling for minimum federal standards for all aquifers, ``i cannot agree with it.''
we have no right to come in on this slice of the world or life in 1988 and say we are just going to abandon these resources,'' the senator told a news conference about his bill, at least the 10th dealing with groundwater this session
the senator said he would have to study epa's thursday proposal for the states, though his bill would permit states to go beyond federal standards
democratic presidential candidate michael dukakis called rival richard gephardt a ``flip-flopper'' as tensions ran high between the two at a long-term health care forum on thursday
dukakis warned gephardt against turning the campaign negative, but gephardt said he thought it was important to highlight differences on issues and experience
dukakis and gephardt are struggling for stature as the calendar winds down toward the super tuesday round of primaries and caucuses in the south. each has won two contests to date
earlier in the day, dukakis said he learned a painful lesson about negative campaigning when he lost a 1978 re-election bid as massachusetts governor and ``it's not going to happen again.''
he went on to say in boca raton, ``i don't think this `prince of darkness' routine is going to sell'' and that he would not stand for gephardt attacks
in the hour-long health care session here, dukakis and gephardt largely agreed on the need for a national long-term health care program. but dukakis bristled when a question suggested he was flip-flopping on the role of private insurance for long-term care
this is the flip-flopper over here; i'm not the flip-flopper,'' dukakis said, looking at the missouri congressman, whose record has been criticized by other candidates as inconsistent
both strongly supported the proposal by rep. claude pepper, the 87-year-old miami democrat, to guarantee home health care for the elderly and chronically ill. pepper's bill didn't come to a vote last year as some congressional democrats worried about a potential cost in the tens of billions of dollars
pepper's plan would lift the 45 percent cap on income subject to medicare payroll tax, and both candidates agreed that extra revenue should be able to get the program started
it's the old-fashioned american way of taxing on the ability to pay, which is what we ought to do,'' dukakis said
we're not doing it right today,'' gephardt said of government-provided health care. ``it doesn't have to cost a lot more money.''
dukakis said health care presents a fundamental difference between the democratic and republican parties and he called health care an american birthright
if you lose your health, nothing else matters,'' gephardt said to loud applause from the audience at a retirement community
dukakis said he dominated gephardt in working-class areas of new hampshire and minnesota, both contests the massachusetts governor won, then warned that a negative campaign would hurt the democrats and also that gephardt's record was vulnerable
people in glass houses shouldn't throw stones,'' dukakis said after the senior forum here. he said gephardt shouldn't attack the establishment and then accept corporate political action committee funds
something could be said for consistency,'' dukakis said
gephardt denied his campaign was negative
i am trying in this campaign and will continue to try to outline what i think are the differences,'' gephardt said. ``let's have a discussion of the issues.''
dukakis scoffed when told gephardt said he wasn't being negative
everybody knows what he's doing. when you're behind you attack,'' dukakis said
on wednesday, gephardt gave a speech in waco, texas, that harshly criticized dukakis. ``the candidate with the most money has the least message,'' gephardt said
mcdonald's has decided the british spud is a dud when it comes to french fries, and its plan to switch to american potato varieties has created a flap among some patriots
the fast-food chain plans to use british-grown potatoes of the north american variety called the russet burbank. for years, it has used british-grown potatoes of the british pentland dell variety
a company spokeswoman said thursday the decision to make the change in the british mcdonald's outlets was made ``basically because the russet burbank has got a better flavor and texture.''
it is a more suitable potato for our requirements,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity in accordance with british custom
she said british farmers have been contracted to grow the american variety
mcdonald's is a big customer of the british potato farmer. it needs 55,000 tons of potatoes a year to keep its 263 british outlets in the chips, as the french fry is called here
the american variety produces french fries that hang tantalizingly over the edge of their packets without breaking in the middle, farmers told the today newspaper
but agricultural expert michael shaw, who isn't happy about the switch, told the newspaper, ``mcdonald's is so powerful in the fast-food business that they are killing off the great british chip.''
conservative lawmaker ann winterton agreed
my primary interest is promoting food which is grown in this country. potatoes is a crop we grow particularly well. there are many varieties of excellent qualities.''
she said it would suprise her if the american variety was better
another tory member of parliament, jerry wiggin, chairman of the house of commons select committee on agriculture, said: ``judging from the fantastic support from my own children, mcdonald's doesn't appear to be doing badly using british potatoes.''
mcdonald's conducted tests with the russet burbank on farms throughout the country during the past eight years, according to the daily telegraph
this year, production of the russet burbank, which was developed in california 112 years ago, is in full swing on about 4,000 acres, the daily telegraph said
britain's potato marketing board is not opposed to the switch
the amount of potatoes being taken up on the processing side is increasing and obviously, if growers want to take advantage of it, obviously they have to grow what the buyers want,'' said a board spokeswoman, who didn't want to be identified further
there is not going to be an en masse switch to russet burbank with everyone growing nothing but that,'' the spokeswoman said
mcdonald's main rivals say they are sticking with their british spuds
john shedden, a spokesman for burger king, said the british variety meets all of burger king's requirements. burger king has 18 outlets in britain
wimpy, a british fast-food chain, operates 400 restaurants that fry about 8,580 tons of potatoes a year. it uses the british pentland dell variety, as well as another british variety called the maris piper and a dutch variety called bintje
a wimpy spokeswoman said the type of potato used has less to do with the chips' flavor than the fat or oil used to fry it
wimpy says its uses vegetable oil. mcdonald's says it uses a combination of cottonseed oil and beef tallow. burger king won't say
polish authorities are blocking solidarity leader lech walesa and three top aides from traveling to australia to attend an international trade union congress, a spokesman for the banned union said wednesday
the authorities are trying to block the procedure at every possible stage,'' said solidarity's national spokesman janusz onyszkiewicz, in a telephone interview. ``they are trying to play formal, bureaucratic tricks ... without actually refusing to grant them passports.''
walesa and three other solidarity leaders are trying to obtain passports to allow them to travel to australia to attend the march 14-18 world congress of the international confederation of free trade unions in melbourne
they were invited by the australian confederation of trade unions
lech wants to do everything possible to go there, as this is a congress of a trade union organization of which solidarity is a member,'' said bogdan olszewski, a walesa aide, contacted at the union leader's gdansk apartment
walesa has not left poland since the december 1981 imposition of martial law that suppressed solidarity
walesa applied 10 days ago for vacation leave from his job as an electrician at gdansk's lenin shipyard, but so far he has not received any response from shipyard authorities, olszewski said
poles must have the approval of their workplace in order to file an application for a passport, which then can take two to four weeks to be processed
walesa expected the shipyard would delay its decision until it was too late for him to make the trip, olszewski said. walesa once earlier tried to obtain a passport to travel to italy, but was refused leave from the shipyard
wladyslaw frasyniuk, the wroclaw solidarity leader, said the local passport office refused to accept his passport application on thursday, claiming his invitation was invalid because it was not issued by a private individual but an institution
bogdan lis, the gdansk solidarity leader, said he would try to apply for his passport friday, while union adviser bronislaw geremek of warsaw has filed his passport application and is waiting for a decision
polish government spokesman jerzy urban told a news conference tuesday that if walesa is granted a leave from work his request for a passport ''will be examined in accordance with the existing regulations, as is the case with every other polish citizen
a secret presidential study harshly criticizes state department officials, the american ambassador and marines for neglecting security at the u.s. embassy in moscow where a sex-for-secrets scandal erupted last year
a fundamental reorientation of the way we do business in the soviet union is critical,'' according to the report by a blue-ribbon panel that president reagan appointed last spring
the report scores the ambassador for his ``aloof'' management style, calls working conditions at the embassy a ``national disgrace,'' and says marine guards ``tolerated'' and then ``covered up'' incidents of misconduct, including sexual activities, drunkenness, brawling and currency manipulation
many share responsibility for the security vulnerabilities that existed and in some cases still exist,'' said the panel, headed by former defense secretary melvin r. laird
the so-called laird report was submitted to the state department, which has refused to release it. charles redman, a department spokesman, said the report has not been made public because it is a confidential document for secretary of state george p. shultz
laird urged release of an unclassified version of the document, but said he could not talk about its substance unless the department unseals it. there is also a classified version of the report containing more sensitive information
the associated press was shown a copy of the report, the result of the panel's work from may 7 until july 17
since the panel finished work, one marine has been convicted of spying. but some of the more sensational allegations _ such as reports that kgb agents were allowed to prowl the embassy's top-secret areas _ have been discounted
the report said what happened at the embassy ``may never be known,'' and it added: ``our investigation has revealed that a situation existed ... that would have permitted the incidents to have occurred as alleged...''
robert e. lamb, assistant secretary of state for diplomatic security, said gaps existed in the embassy's security program in the past. ``there were some holes and we have moved to fill them,'' he said
efforts have been made to upgrade security and add more personnel to the counterintelligence staff, he said
some of the findings in the laird report are new; others repeat concerns raised previously about the embassy. here is a sampling:
_laird called the embassy a ``pigsty,'' and the report said it was a fire trap. last week, fire broke out in a section of the embassy
corridors were cluttered with papers, books and personal effects; stairwells and hallways were ``strewn with broken equipment and machinery parts awaiting repair and disposal,'' the report said
those assigned to moscow find themselves working in a seedy, disgraceful facility with inadequate support from washington,'' the report said
_it is ``possible that some marines who had discipline problems elsewhere were assigned to moscow as punishment,'' and the situation was ripe for exploitation by the kgb, the soviet spy agency
_the panel reserved ``special criticism'' for the marines in the guard detachment as ``their misconduct and failure to perform their duties in a prescribed manner led to increased vulnerability in the mission's security,'' the report said. some embassy staffers also violated regulations
_confusion marked policies barring marines from fraternizing with soviets and reporting their contacts. the policies ``obviously were not taken seriously enough to provide security,'' the report said
_the state department's counterintelligence staff was so overworked _ only 11 of the 27 authorized positions were filled _ that ``only the most rudimentary investigation was conducted on the most pressing cases.''
the gross neglect of the state department's counterintelligence may be germane to the alleged security breaches in moscow,'' the report said
_some of the soviet citizens working at the embassy were ``known to be kgb operatives,'' and were ``accorded far too much access to americans.''
the americans had ``ambivalent and contradictory'' attitudes towards the soviets, who worked in a variety of administrative, clerical and support jobs such as cooks, drivers and baby-sitters. the soviets removed their nationals from the embassy in october 1986
_the ambassador ``employed a management style that remained aloof until a specific event occurred and required his attention. ... this was clearly inadequate.''
arthur a. hartman, the u.s. ambassador in moscow from 1981 until 1987, did not return telephone calls placed to his house and his office. he has maintained that earlier reports about the embassy's security problems were overblown
sgt. clayton j. lonetree, an embassy guard in 1985 and 1986, was convicted of espionage for giving the kgb the identities of cia agents and the floor plans to the u.s. embassies in moscow and vienna
but government prosecutors dropped charges against lonetree and cpl. arnold bracy that they permitted kgb agents to roam the embassy. another marine was convicted of dereliction of duty
the naval investigative service says eight other espionage-related cases involving marines remain open as a result of polygraph tests administered after lonetree's confession
besides laird, the panel included richard m. helms, a former cia director; gen. john w. vessey jr., former chairman of the joint chiefs of staff; and diego c. asencio, former ambassador to brazil
also thursday, the office of rep. dan mica, d-fla., made available copies of a preliminary general accounting office inquiry into reports of espionage by marines. mica had disclosed details of the report last week
among others things, the gao _ the congressional watchdog agency _ said ``coordination and cooperation'' between the state department, the marines and the naval investigative service was ``less than adequate.''
for instance, the gao said the state department did not always turn over to the nis for further investigation reports of possible criminal or counterintelligence activity
the value of u.s. agriculture exports is expected to rise to a four-year high of $32.5 billion this fiscal year, the agriculture department said thursday
spurred by recent heavy sales of grain to the soviet union and china, partly under a special export subsidy program, the new 1988 forecast is up $500 million from $32 billion indicated on dec. 17
the new export forecast came just as the department announced another cash sale of corn to the soviet union, the second in two days
overall, with a shipment value of $32 billion, exports in the fiscal year that began oct. 1 would be up 16 percent from $27.9 billion in 1987 and up 24 percent from a decade low of $26.3 billion in 1986. agricultural export were valued at $31.2 billion in fiscal 1985 and $38 billion in 1984
most of the increase (from the earlier estimate) stems from additional wheat sales under the export enhancement program ,'' usda said. ``since the december forecast, eep offers were announced for 2 million metric tons of wheat to the soviet union and 1.2 million tons to china, among others.''
under the eep arrangement, private exporters get free surplus commodities from the agriculture department as subsidies so they can sell grain and other products overseas at reduced prices
on the basis of actual volume, 1988 exports were indicated at 142.5 million metric tons, up from 141 million forecast in december and 129.2 million tons shipped last year
the u.s. share of the world market, particularly in grains and cotton, is rising,'' officials said in their report. ``relatively low world prices and improved u.s. competitiveness through lower (price support) loan rates, the eep and a lower dollar have reduced production incentives for foreign competitors.''
meanwhile, private exporters reported the sales of 601,600 tons of corn for delivery to the soviet union this year under a long-term supply agreement between the two countries
on wednesday, the soviets bought 350,000 tons of corn, the first substantial amount since last october. corn sales are not qualified for eep subsidies, however
no selling prices or other information about the corn sale were disclosed. when subsidies are involved, the exporting firms, quantities and amounts of eep payments are shown, but not when straight cash deals are involved
a metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. the 601,600 tons of corn would be about 24 million bushels, having a farm value of around $44 million at recent prices of about $1.82 per bushel
the corn is part of the grain the soviet union is committed to buy during the fifth and final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual purchase of at least 9 million tons of u.s. grain. the pact expires sept. 30
according to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. the soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent
with the latest purchases, the soviets now have bought more than 2.6 million tons of corn, or two-thirds of the minimum of 4 million tons specified by the agreement
by comparison, the soviet union has bought more than 6.3 million tons of wheat at subsidized prices, plus 800,000 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal for delivery this year
military medical officials said thursday that improvements are needed in battlefield health care but conditions have improved greatly since five years ago, when only one out of 10 casualties could expect adequate care
we have to spend either dollars or blood, and we prefer to spend dollars,'' navy surgeon general james a. zimble told a house armed services subcommittee hearing
zimble said congressional support will be needed for a plan to attain wartime medical readiness by 1992
dr. william mayer, assistant secretary of defense for health affairs, said that five years ago adequate medical attention would have been available to only 10 percent of battlefield casualties. after a year, improvements increased that figure to about 20 percent, mayer said, describing condition as ``still grossly unacceptable.''
he said no comparable figures are available for present conditions but more facilities are still needed abroad. he said there is no funding for 41 overseas army hospitals, in addition to three for the navy and two for the air force
mayer said the u.s. military can now mobilize about 60 percent of the medical personnel and facilities needed in the event of ``general war.''
i'm very comfortable that we're most of the way toward being able to respond adequately today in ways that we couldn't have dreamed of five years ago,'' he told the subcommittee on medical personnel and compensation which is examining military medical care readiness abroad. the panel has scheduled a similar hearing on domestic military medical facilities for march 8
mayer said there is a danger that if improvements in health care for the armed forces do not continue, it could become ``a national scandal.''
air force surgeon general murphy a. chesney said he has purchased 75 percent of the hospital beds that would be needed overseas in wartime but there is no money to obtain the other 25 percent
he said that with the growth of soviet offensive capabilities, u.s. air force bases have to be considered ``first-strike targets.'' he said in 1979 it was concluded that potential casualty rates at air bases were 17 times those previously predicted
since then, he said, the value of medical facilities has grown from $17 million in 1978 to an expected $450 million when all funded work is completed. but that still leaves the air force needing 10 more hospitals with 500 beds each, he said
army surgeon general quinn h. becker said, ``although we have achieved admirable progress in correcting our medical readiness shortfalls, critical equipment and personnel deficiences remain.''
a student was shot in the head and critically wounded by another male student thursday in a courtyard of bristol high school, police and hospital officials said
according to witnesses, the victim was shot while pulling off his jacket to fight with the other student, said mike slocum, a senior at the school
the two youths had been fighting for weeks, said kate meyer, a freshman
the 15-year-old was in critical condition with a single gunshot wound in the head and was taken into surgery at rhode island hospital, said spokesman rick piester
police detective richard almeida said the shooting took place in a school courtyard shortly after noon. authorities reportedly had at least one suspect in custody and have recovered a small-caliber handgun
neither almeida nor superintendent gerald p. bourgeois could furnish the identities of either the shooting victim or suspect
slocum said about 30 people were in the courtyard when the shooting occurred
several students interviewed said they did not witness the shooting but saw the victim sprawled on the floor seconds later
gloria meola, a freshman, described herself as a close friend of the victim. ``i saw him lying on the floor ... all that blood,'' she said, wincing. ``i saw him on that floor, and i freaked out.''
meola said the suspect ran into the school and, with the help of another student, escaped through a window
slocum and several other students described the shooting suspect as a student who was frequently teased. ``the truth is, he was a geek,'' he said
meola said that after the shooting principal edward l. jawor told students over the intercom not to talk to reporters, ``like we're going to act like it's a normal day and our close friend just got shot in the head.'' built</head>
television evangelist jimmy swaggart's admission of moral failure isn't expected to hinder development of a $2 million canadian headquarters, says his representative in canada
the rev. norman maclaren, who has headed swaggart's canadian operation since 1983, said he was planning a new building for his 200-member congregation in niagara falls 10 months ago and decided to make it large enough to serve also as the canadian headquarters for jimmy swaggart ministries
a foundation has been laid for the building, which will include a 1,300-seat sanctuary. the building is expected to be finished by nov. 30
maclaren said his church is a member of the pentecostal assemblies of canada, which is affiliated with the assemblies of god denomination of which swaggart is a member
asked if the tv evangelist's temporary absence from the pulpit and othe4r disciplinary action by the denomination will affect the local plans, maclaren said ``we trust it won't.''
between 35,000 and 40,000 canadians subscribe to swaggart's evangelical magazine, he said. this is the group that will be served by the headquarters in niagara falls
being the swaggart headquarters means handling all canadian distribution of the evangelist's music, tv tapes and literature and processing all incoming mail, maclaren said
