we talked about his las vegas years,'' newton said of his conversation with the president. ``i didn't sing for him and he didn't sing for me, and i think we'll probably keep it that way.''
reagan worked briefly as a night club master of ceremonies in las vegas after his movie career faltered and before he entered politics
a grand jury may investigate possible criminal wrongdoing stemming from a black fbi agent's claims that he was the victim of racial harassment by fellow agents, a government lawyer said thursday
justice department attorney david m. glass told the judge who is hearing a civil lawsuit brought by fbi special agent donald rochon that the department was conducting a criminal investigation of the case
there has been some consideration of criminal proceedings,'' glass told u.s. district judge charles r. richey
glass made the statement in response to the plaintiff's request to examine fbi documents and investigative files to prepare for the case for trial
glass contended that opening the files to rochon's lawyers could interfere with the investigation being conducted by the criminal division of the justice department's civil rights division
rochon, 37, charged in the lawsuit filed last fall that fellow agents in omaha and later chicago waged a three-year campaign of harassment that included a letter threatening death, mutilation and sexual assault of his white wife
an fbi agent was suspended for two weeks for forging rochon's name on an application for an insurance policy covering his death or dismemberment and another for burial benefits, according to the lawsuit
a department source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said investigators are examining letters containing threats to obtain corroboration of rochon's charges
the letters are being examined to determine if the mails were illegally used to harass rochon, the source said
rochon also claims the fbi retaliated against him for complaining by transferring him to chicago and placing a letter of censure in his personnel file. the lawsuit also charges that fbi officials deliberately ignored his allegations to suppress them
on his first day on the job in chicago, rochon says agents placed chocolate in the earpiece of his telephone so that it would come off on his ear when he used the instrument
during a four-day period in the spring of 1985, rochon says he received a letter threatening him with violence, mutilation and death as well as sexual assault of his wife, susan. the letter contained a picture of a mutilated black man, the complaint says
four days later, rochon received a bill for an insurance policy for death and dismemberment that had been taken out in his name
the lawsuit states that fbi officials in chicago gave agent gary miller a 14-day suspension after determining that he had forged rochon's signature on the insurance application and on another for death and burial benefits
but the fbi did not report miller's actions to prosecutors ``although he clearly violated federal and state criminal laws,'' the lawsuit said
the lawsuit charges that in 1986, the justice department's civil rights division deliberately shut down the equal employment opportunity commission's investigation of allegations of harassment in chicago, saying it was conducting a criminal investigation
rochon's lawsuit charges that even though the justice department notified the eeoc of the criminal investigation, it did not interview rochon or agents suspected of wrongdoing until last summer
last summer the eeoc ruled that rochon was unfairly disciplined in omaha and transferred to chicago. the eeoc ordered the fbi to allow rochon to be transferred to any office of his choice within the agency
eeoc also ordered the fbi to lift the 1984 letter of censure, which rebuked rochon for failing to report that he was the victim of possible housing discrimination
the eeoc examiner determined that rochon was the only fbi special agent ever censured for failing to report a legal violation of which he was the victim
the eeoc also ordered fbi training sessions for the agents involved in the racial harassment to ensure such conduct would not be repeated
during the hearing, the judge urged the justice department to find a way to settle the lawsuit to avoid lengthy court proceedings. say</head>
authorities have seized the home of a 90-year-old woman and evicted a family they say terrorized and beat her and stole thousands of dollars from her over the past few years
the retired teacher, whom authorities declined to identify, has cancer and was taken to a nursing home several days before police moved in. she has not been told about the raid and eviction, officials said
eight district attorney's investigators, two police lab technicians and two patrolmen raided the house tuesday night after relatives became alarmed and called authorities
they evicted the live-in housekeeper and her son and daughter-in-law
we have evidence at this point of emotional, verbal and physical abuse _ things that really make you angry to hear about,'' said dave heckenbach, chief deputy district attorney
like smacking her when she doesn't move fast enough, pushing her down when she doesn't drink her fluids fast enough, bruises on her body, bumps on her head, yelling at her, screaming at her, threatening her,'' he said
no charges had been filed as of thursday
we recovered numerous documents that we will have to go through before charges can be filed,'' said diane balkin of the district attorney's office
the woman's troubles began in early 1985 when she advertised for a live-in housekeeper and hired lois hicks, 62, authorities said
ms. hicks took control of the woman's finances and ``substantially depleted her money,'' said heckenbach
we don't know the totals yet,'' heckenbach said, but financial documents were seized when the house was raided. he said that just two bank withdrawal slips that he saw showed withdrawals from the woman's account of $15,000 and $22,000
and they seized many more than what i saw,'' he said. ``i can say easily that we are into the many tens of thousands of dollars that these people took from this lady.''
two years ago, officials said, ms. hicks' son, john hicks, 34, and his wife, cheryl hicks, 35, moved into the house with their eight cats, a dog and a ferret
heckenbach said both john hicks and his wife are ex-convicts. cheryl hicks was convicted of voluntary manslaughter and murder in georgia, and john hicks was convicted of aggravated robbery in georgia, he said. the two met in a halfway house and had been out of prison a short time when they moved into the elderly woman's home, said heckenbach
the family hired their own housekeeper and bought three cars, said heckenbach
heckenbach said that last october, lois hicks told the teacher's lawyer that the elderly woman wanted to change her will
the attorney, to his credit, refused to change the will because his assessment was that she was not mentally able to make a voluntary decision at that point,'' he said
he also told us he saw fear in her eyes and terror in her eyes,'' heckenbach said. ``it was his distinct impression she was being intimidated by lois hicks.''
john hicks was out of town, but lois and cheryl hicks were at the house when officials seized it. they were allowed to take some clothing and toiletries before they were locked out, officials said
barbara cook will not appear in ``carrie,'' a musical version of the stephen king novel, when it arrives on broadway in april, a spokesman for the show said thursday
miss cook, who was the original marian the librarian in ``the music man,'' will withdraw from the show after it completes its pre-broadway run in stratford, england, on march 5, said the show's spokesman jim baldassare
in the musical, miss cook plays carrie's mother. the title character, a teen-age girl with telekinetic powers, is played by a 17-year-old english actress named linzi hateley
miss cook's decision to leave the show was based on consultations between the actress, director terry hands and producer friedrich kurz, baldassare said. several performers are under consideration to replace miss cook but no offer has been made, the spokesman said. the show was to have been miss cook's first appearance in a broadway musical in 17 years. her one-woman show had a short run on broadway last spring
carrie,'' which also was turned into a brian de palma movie starring sissy spacek, has music by michael gore and lyrics by dean pitchford
the show is scheduled to begin preview performances at the virginia theater on april 12 and open on may 1
two common antibiotics used against traveler's diarrhea helped a group of aids patients live longer by preventing the pneumonia that is a leading cause of death from the disease, a study found
the drug therapy gives doctors an important new weapon in the fight against aids, a fatal, incurable immune disorder, one of the study's authors said thursday
if we intercede early with medications that may prevent life-threatening infections, that will prolong life and improve the quality of life,'' said dr. margaret fischl, lead researcher on the study published in friday's journal of the american medical association
the two antibiotics, trimethoprim and sulfamethoxazole, prevented 30 patients with early stages of aids from developing pneumocystis carinii pneumonia while they remained on the drugs
the patients also lived much longer than 30 similar patients who did not receive the drugs, said ms. fischl, an associate medical professor and director of aids research at the university of miami school of medicine
the patients each had been newly diagnosed as having kaposi's sarcoma, a skin cancer that afflicts aids patients. but they hadn't developed pneumocystis carinii pneumonia or any of the other opportunistic infections that eventually kill aids victims, the study said
more than 50 percent of patients with aids develop pneumocystis carinii infection and, despite therapy, more than 20 percent die with overwhelming infection,'' the study noted
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the body's defenses against disease, leaving its victims prey to infections and certain cancers
the patients were studied between january 1984 and june 1985, and were re-examined in june 1987
sixteen of the 30 patients who didn't receive the antibiotics developed the pneumonia, the study results showed
none of the 30 patients taking the antibiotics developed the pneumonia while they received the drugs, the study said
but half of those receiving the drugs had side effects such as nausea and skin rashes, the study said. five had such severe reactions they had to stop taking the antibiotics, it said. four of the five developed the pneumonia within four or five months after the treatment was halted
during the study, 28 of the 30 patients _ 93 percent _ not receiving the antibiotics died, compared with 18 patients, or 60 percent, in the group that took the drugs
ms. fischl estimated that 40 percent of the patients who took the drugs remain alive today. only one patient who wasn't given the drugs is still living, she said by telephone from her miami office
a study published in the new england journal of medicine in 1982 found that the same two prescription antibiotics were effective in quickly relieving the misery of travelers' diarrhea, a disorder common to visitors of latin america, the middle east, the far east and the mediterranean
ms. fischl recommended thursday that all patients with aids and aids-related illness, a condition called arc, be considered for therapy with the two antibotics
similar tests are being conducted on other antibiotics to see if they also may be effective in preventing aids-related infections, she said
ms. fischl speculated that the medical technique known as chemoprophylaxis _ trying to prevent infections with low doses of antibotics _ may become a major weapon against aids and be used in conjunction with other drugs, such as azt
azt, or azidothymidine, has been shown to prolong the lives of aids patients by reducing the frequency and severity of opportunistic infections, like the rare pneumonia
perhaps the combination of chemoprophylaxis with azt will improve the outcome better than either alone,'' said ms. fischl, who also has directed studies of azt
the virus that causes aids is believed to be passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during birth
a 17-year-old student athlete became a hero for the third time in his life when he went to the aid of a man whose van had plunged into a canyon, giving the man his jacket and shirt to ward off hypothermia
duane duffy was on his way home from a school club meeting in colorado springs on tuesday night when he saw a strange light in the trees in the canyon 300 feet below the road
i knew it wasn't the moon,'' duffy said. ``most people would drive right by, because if you didn't know any better you wouldn't have noticed it.''
but duffy drives the road every day, so he stopped to investigate
peering over the precipice, he saw the headlights of a smashed van and heard a weak cry for help
tom dize, 44, of denver, had slipped off the road into the canyon while attempting a u-turn
duffy went off and called for help, then returned to climb down the nearly vertical dropoff. he found dize in bad condition
i thought he was really getting close to hypothermia,'' or low body temperature, said duffy. ``he'd been out there 15 to 20 minutes, sprawled in the snow, and it was really deep. he was shaking and shivering. he was all wet and white, and breathing heavily. it really freaked me out.''
i knew i was going to die,'' dize recalled from his hospital bed
duffy helped dize walk to the road, then took off his jacket and shirt and wrapped the injured man in them and in blankets from his car. he waited with dize until an ambulance arrived
if it hadn't been for him, i might not have made it,'' said dize, who was in satisfactory condition at st. anthony hospital central in denver, where he was recovering from internal injuries
he put the blankets on me, comforted me, stayed with me. i owe my life to him, really.''
duffy's father, duane duffy, said his son had rescued a brother and sister years earlier
when he was 12, he saved his 10-year-old brother from drowning during a fishing trip. two years ago, he treated his 3-year-old sister after she ate rat poison, making her drink milk to coat her stomach and calling paramedics
like every teen, he's rebellious,'' said the father. ``but being the oldest of seven children, he's assumed a lot of leadership. you can criticize kids from day to day, get down on them, and you forget to look at the basic things. we've tried to teach the kids good values, and it looks like i've gotten some reward for that.''
reps. charles e. schumer, d-n.y., and joseph p. kennedy, d-mass., introduced legislation thursday designed to aid consumers in their dealing with banks
schumer and kennedy, both members of the house banking committee _ joined by a coalition of representatives of consumer groups, including activist ralph nader _ told a news conference they hoped their measure would be included in major legislation to restructure banking regulations
as the bank and securities industries argue about how to divide up the goodies of the financial system, congress must make sure that consumers get a fair shake,'' said schumer. ``whether or not congress grants banks any new powers, congress must address the concerns of consumers and communities.''
kennedy said that no matter what congress does on the glass-steagall law, which restricts the role of banks, ``local communities and consumers deserve to have their rights under the law enforced.''
schumer and kennedy said their legislation will offer an opportunity for every person to have a bank account, establish community organizations to monitor bank performance and will provide better information about the credit given to businesses in poor communities
the measure requires that banks make available basic checking accounts to all consumers for a minimal initial deposit. these accounts would be free of all fees and charges for a limited number of checking services
it also will require regular disclosure of where banks are lending their depositors' money, giving consumers a better picture of whether the banks they patronize are serving the community which supports them, according to schumer
a third provision would establish a system of state-level organizations to inform and represent consumers' interests before regulatory authorities, courts, legislatures and other forums
southeast asian heroin importers have supplanted the mafia as the largest supplier of the drug in new york, vastly increasing their share of the illicit market since 1983, authorities said thursday
however, investigations of the drug rings have led to major recent seizures of new york-bound heroin in thailand and chicago, said robert strang, spokesman for the federal drug enforcement administration here
five years ago an estimated 4 percent of the heroin reaching new york was from southeast asia and the remaining 96 percent was from iran, afghanistan and pakistan, where the mafia dominated the distribution network, strang said
now, an estimated 70 percent of the heroin comes from southeast asia _ principally thailand, laos and burma _ imported by gangs based in hong kong and bangkok, while the share from iran, afghanistan and pakistan is down to 30 percent, he said
officials are unsure of the reason for the decreasing role of organized crime, but they speculate that one factor is retrenchment and disarray in the mafia ranks caused by recent successful prosecutions of mafia leaders in new york
the southeast asian heroin has an average street-level purity of 45 percent, compared with 15 percent for heroin from iran, afghanistan and pakistan, strang noted. nonetheless, wholesale prices have remained level, ranging from $75,000 to $150,000 per pound, he said
the dea responded to the increasing role of bangkok and hong kong heroin gangs by forming a special investigative group 1{ years ago, strang said. the group led to seizures of 180 pounds of heroin in new york in december, 165 pounds this week in chicago and nearly 1{ tons in thailand earlier this month
a bomb exploded near a crowded stage late thursday and wounded 14 people at the climax of celebrations marking the second anniversary of the popular uprising that ousted president ferdinand e. marcos
brig. gen. rodolfo biazon, chief of the national capital region defense command, told the associated press there was no indication who planted the homemade device, and no one claimed responsibility. the military had been on full alert in case communist rebels or militant rightists tried to disrupt the celebration
biazon said the bomb went off during a fireworks display at the end of daylong celebrations marking the feb. 25, 1986 ouster of the marcos administration
elisa florido, a nurse at medical city hospital, said no one was seriously hurt. she said most of the injured suffered cuts from flying glass and debris
the blast occurred at about 10 p.m. near the main stage set up on epifanio de los santos avenue. seven stages were erected along the highway, known as edsa, for religious services and performances by filipino entertainers
two years ago, hundreds of thousands of filipinos swarmed onto edsa to form a human wall shielding troops who mutinied against marcos after a fraud-tainted election. the uprising swept corazon aquino into the presidency
during a mass attended by mrs. aquino thursday, cardinal jaime l. sin, archbishop of manila, appealed for land reform and warned that the country cannot survive if it does not narrow the gap between rich and poor
we have to bring about a more equitable distribution of wealth throughout our land,'' sin said. ``only then can our nation survive and go forward
it (land reform) can no longer wait. many believe it is already too late. the insurgency, now so much advanced, is at the gates.''
more than half the nation's 58 million people live in poverty that has fueled the 19-year-old communist rebellion
mrs. aquino ordered land reform last july but left implementing details to congress, where the bill has bogged down because of resistance by landowners
during the mass, mrs. aquino made no speech but offered a prayer:
lord god, you helped us on edsa two years ago, and we thank you for helping us all through these difficult two years. ... we believe that you led us out of bondage. we believe that it was you who made us free.''
about 10,000 leftists marked the day with a march and rally, at which speakers claimed mrs. aquino had abandoned the reformist goals of the 1986 revolution. hundreds of marcos supporters also rallied to demand his return from exile in hawaii
in honolulu, marcos said that after two years in exile, he considers himself a prisoner in the united states. he vowed to continue his fight to return home, though he said he expects to be killed by his enemies
u.s. officials will not allow marcos to return to the philippines because the aquino government believes he and his wife would disrupt the country's political stability
the explosion thursday night was the only incident that marred the celebrations in manila, in which tens of thousands of filipinos returned to edsa for a carnival of religious processions and street dancing
the celebration began with the pealing of church bells across the nation and a flag-raising ceremony at camp aguinaldo military garrison. mrs. aquino joined thousands of people outside the camp to hold hands in a 1{-mile-long ``chain for peace'' down edsa
it was at camp aguinaldo where former defense minister juan ponce enrile and lt. gen. fidel ramos, then the vice chief of staff, announced they were breaking with marcos and backing mrs. aquino
the mutiny galvanized opposition to marcos which swelled after the 1983 assassination of mrs. aquino's husband, former sen. benigno aquino jr
mrs. aquino promised broad social and economic reform, but critics complain she failed to meet the goals because of strong opposition from conservative groups within the military and the elite. chief</head>
