tougher federal laws are needed to stem the dramatically increased rate of indian artifacts looted and vandalized in the southwest, a house subcommittee said thursday
a report by the house interior and insular affairs subcommittee on general oversight and investigations, capping a four-month probe, said up to 90 percent of the archaeological indian sites in arizona, colorado, new mexico and utah may have been vandalized
the subcommittee called it an ``extremely serious problem which threatens our national heritage.''
the 73-page report, issued by rep. sam gejdenson, d-conn., chairman of the panel, said vandalism reports have increased by 1,000 percent since 1980 on the navajo reservation alone
if the rate of looting on other indian lands is as serious ... the looting problem on indian land is reaching crisis proportions,'' the subcommittee concluded
looting in the southwest is especially severe because of the value of certain artifacts. for example, an indian basket and its contents were sold by a dealer for $180,000
the panel recommended revising a law currently in effect that separates misdemeanors and felonies by a $5,000 threshold on the artifacts stolen or destroyed. instead, the report suggested making digging for artifacts a felony and ``surface collecting'' a misdeamanor
the $5,000 threshold causes many problems as it is extremely difficult to quantify the value of damage to archaeological sites,'' the report said. ``this is a clear distinction, which juries and judges can understand without the assistance of an expert.''
the subcommittee also said the law should be changed to make it a crime to attempt to loot or vandalize archaeological sites on federal lands. now looters have to be caught in the act
the panel wants to have the law apply to artifacts that are at least 50 years old, instead of the current 100-year-old standard
in addition, the lawmakers called for more undercover operations and patrols, including patrols at archaeological sites that are important but not protected under the national historic preservation act
the subcommittee said the government should focus on education and advertising efforts, noting that while many looters are seeking a profit, some are just archaeology enthusiasts unaware of the need to protect the artifacts
the key to protecting archaeological resources is to convince the general public of their value,'' the report said. picking up in 7th graf pvs, during his</note>
two top strategists for republican presidential candidate bob dole were fired thursday in the culmination of an apparent power struggle that erupted as the kansas senator was grearing up for the single biggest day of the 1988 campaign
consultants david keene and don devine left dole's campaign in florida, according to campaign manager bill brock
we're in the process of trying to tighten up on resources,'' dole said, but he also acknowledged, ``there is tension in any campaign.''
brock said he decided on the firings and notified dole wednesday night
we don't have any philosophical differences,'' said brock, a former senator from tennessee. ``we're in a different kind of campaign at this time.''
brock said other changes were forthcoming, adding that some dole personnel in the national headquarters would be asked to go into the field for the kansas senator
keene and devine flew with dole on the candidate's chartered plane when he headed south from minnesota on wednesday after his victories in the south dakota primary and minnesota precinct caucuses
devine, in a telephone interview, said brock had called them tuesday night and ordered them off the plane
both refused, saying they worked for dole
brock joined the entourage thursday in orlando, fla., after a day of campaign stops in south carolina and florida. and devine said that while dole was delivering a speech, a photographer asked brock and keene to stand together for a picture
according to devine, as the two men stood together, brock leaned over and said to keene, ``we're going to cut the string on you right now.''
then he looked at devine and said, ``i might as well do both of you together.''
devine said the dispute flared when brock advised dole not to go to south dakota and minnesota tuesday night, despite indications the senator would carry both states
keene and devine argued that dole should go and the senator agreed
during his appearance before the jacksonville chamber of commerce, dole said he considered the republican race a two-man battle between himself and vice president george bush
i've got a feeling we may be headed all the way to new orleans,'' said dole, referring to the republican national convention in august
aiming his remarks at conservative republicans in a city that hosts three huge naval bases, dole praised president reagan's leadership and pitched his remarks toward strong support of the strategic defense initiative. but he also urged resolving the federal budget deficit
the biggest single threat in america ... in my view, is the deficit,'' said dole. ``you have a right to insist we deal with the deficit.''
dole said the country needed to control wasteful pentagon spending with an inspector general ``meaner than a junkyard dog,'' but said he would not compromise on defense
if i'm going to make a mistake on defense, i ant to be sure i've spent enough,'' said the senator
dole also spoke before the florida association of counties mid-year legislative congress and attended a rally on his behalf before flyig to texas
florida and texas are the two largest of the 20 states that have contests on march 8, known as super tuesday
earlier, at an orlando campaign stop, dole told reporters that bush had brought a disinformation campaign to florida
dole complained that tv ads now running in miami, which were also used by the bush campaign in new hampshire and vermont, distort dole's views on several issues
he said the ads say that ``dole can't wait to raise your taxes, then there's something about import fees and something about the inf (nuclear missiles) treaty _ all of which is totally inaccurate.''
later, posing at the universal studios construction site with cartoon and movie characters woody woodpecker and frankenstein's monster, the kansas senator quipped that ``we have a broad-based campaign. ... it's reaching new heights.''
