this is the right time,'' cavaco silva told the national press club. ``if the agreement is not obtained, it is my opinion, in the next four months, perhaps it will not be achieved in the next two years.''
the main factor, he said, is next november's u.s. elections and the change of administrations
perhaps the next administration will take some time, perhaps two years, to make a new assessment of foreign policy in relation to that area,'' cavaco silva said. ``and it would be a pity because the suffering of the people will continue, and the opportunities of economic recovery will be lost.''
cavaco silva said he had discussed angola with president reagan on wednesday and also with secretary of state george shultz and chester crocker, assistant secretary of state for african affairs
crocker has been conducting talks with the angolan government for much of the reagan administration to try to arrange a pullout of some 40,000 cuban troops from angola, which would be coordinated with south africa's granting independence to south-west africa, or namibia
the government of angola is experiencing big difficulties _ economic difficulties of the decline in oil prices,'' cacavo silva said. it also has suffered a setback in recent fighting with unita rebels, in part because of the intervention of south african troops, he said. government troops ``are on retreat now,'' he said
the united states administration is in a position to achieve a retreat of the cuban troops and to explain the arrangement to the south africans ... and to force the necessary steps for the independence of namibia,'' cavaco silva said
he said his government has urged angola to reach an agreement now and that the angolan government has accepted the principle of the total withdrawal of the cuban troops. ``the difficulty is to fix the timetable,'' he said
it is necessary to have in mind that that agreement afterwards has to be negotiated with south africa,'' cavaco silva said. ``and south africa this time has been openly involved. for the first time, they say that the african troops are there.''
he said he was less able to see any quick resolution to the fighting between the angolan government and unita
four current and former employees of northrop corp. have filed a lawsuit accusing the aerospace giant of overcharging the government by more than $1 billion for development of the radar-dodging stealth bomber
the pentagon is investigating the allegations in the latest in a series of inqueries involving alleged mishandling by northrop of military programs
the stealth is northrop's ``crown jewel,'' accounting for about half of its net income and a third of its workforce
last month, the air force confirmed it had awarded a $2 billion contract to northrop in the first infusion of regular production funds for the plane. only northrop got a contract, despite arguments by critics that the air force should seek a second source for the planes because of northrop's problems
in the 1990s, the pentagon is expected to deploy 132 stealth bombers at a cost of $36.6 billion
the plane, designed to be difficult to detect on enemy radar, is under development at northrop's plants in pico rivera and palmdale
the investigation by the air force and the pentagon inspector general's office was revealed wednesday after a u.s. district court suit was filed by the one current and three former employees under the federal false claims act
under that act, citizens are allowed to sue on behalf of the government and share in any damage award
the government must routinely investigate allegations in such suit, and the justice department must decide within 60 days if there is sufficient evidence for the government to join the suit or seek its dismissal
northrop spokesman tony cantafio refused comment, citing company policies against responding publicly to lawsuits and against making statements regarding the super-secret stealth bomber
the suit, which was sealed under procedures followed in such cases, accuses northrop of double-billing, false billing and misrepresented charges, said robert kilborne, the attorney representing the plaintiffs
kilborne identified his clients only as an internal auditor, a former controller, a former avionics engineer and a former test equipment engineer
the suit alleges that northrop destroyed internal audits that turned up evidence of $400 million in improper charges on development of the bomber, predicting that such overcharges may actually total $1 billion
wednesday's suit is the fourth such action brought by kilborne or his law partner, herb hafif, against northrop. the other suits involved northrop's work on the mx missile program
in october, the justice department moved to dismiss one of the earlier suits on grounds that there was insufficient evidence to substantiate the allegations. ^panama city: delvalle said.</head>
