an off-duty police officer shot and killed a man who challenged him to fire and reached for a knife thursday, police said, bringing to six the number of people who have died in dallas police shootings in less than two months
the shootings have exacerbated racial tensions in dallas. two of the police department's most vocal critics are black members of the city council, who contend department's deadly force policy hurts minorities
both the officer and the slain man in thursday's shooting were black
according to police, the man ordered to waitresses to empty a restaurant cash register, and was confronted bu officer cloyce addison shannon
go ahead and shoot me; shoot me,'' the man told shannon as he reached for a weapon tucked in his weapon, police reports said
shannon, 29, shot the man twice in the chest. he was pronounced dead at the scene, police lt. ron waldrop said
the officer was under the impression that the weapon was a gun, but it turned out to be a long-bladed knife with a handle similar to that of a pistol, waldrop said
the dallas county medical examiner's office identified the victim as robert keith johnson, 30, of dallas
six people have died in five shootings involving dallas police this year, including a black transient slain by off-duty police after he killed a white officer in a downtown parking lot as some members of a street-corner crowd cheered him on
the department has come under fire for its use of deadly force and has been criticized as being out of touch with the minority community
police capt. rick stone, who helped write the department's deadly force policy, said the use of such force is limited to the defense of life
officers are prevented from firing warning shots and are prevented from using deadly force to protect property interests alone,'' he said. ``in essence, the officer must feel that either he or another individual is in imminent danger of death or serious bodily injury.''
police chief billy prince, who issued no statement on latest shooting, was criticized by city officials last month for blaming the death of officer john chase on council members. prince said some members' criticism of the department created an environment of potential violence
price was criticized again wednesday by mayor annette strauss and city manager richard knight for comments concerning the department's affirmative action program, implemented following chase's death
prince said the new policy forced him to promote a black officer who had scored one point lower on a civil rights exam than three white candidates
fueling the racially tense atmosphere were plans by the ku klux klan to march saturday
the kkk is abhorrent to the dallas police department,'' prince said in a statement. ``we did not solicit and do not want their support
we regret the organization's plans to demonstrate in dallas saturday and strongly urge them to abandon the planned demonstration.''
in the other police shootings this year, officer james joe was shot while off-duty as he investigating a burglary at the apartment complex where he lived
the other two victims were shot by police last week. one was black and one was white
the sudden change of currency to combat runaway inflation, accomplished largely by lopping zeros off the old one, has caused confusion, shortages of staples and some cheating
we are in a horrible crisis,'' said julia duarte, a fruit vendor at the open-air eastern market in managua. ``we don't have rice, beans, and people are going hungry.''
president daniel ortega, citing a yearly inflation rate of 1,500 percent, announced feb. 14 that the cordoba currency was being revalued at 10 to the dollar. at that time a dollar was worth 20,000 cordobas on the legal rate and 50,000 on the black market
his government said the new currency would end the black market, foil a cia plan to flood the country with the old money, and deprive the u.s.-supported contra rebels of nicaraguan bills supplied by the cia
after ortega announced the change, the opposition private enterprise council predicted it would drive real prices higher
the black market has continued, despite threats that participants would be arrested, and the contras claimed they got $1 million worth of the new money by downing a sandinista helicopter carrying the cash
store owners said they were bewildered by the change in money and many closed for several days. rice and beans, staples for nicaraguans, disappeared from store shelves
the intercontinental hotel, unsure of how the new system worked, charged $46 for breakfast, and $16 for a chicken sandwich
nicaraguans had three days to trade their old money for new. those who were out of the country or otherwise missed the deadline found the old bills worthless
prices set by the government have increased sharply in objective terms. on a dollar scale, a dozen eggs went from just under $1 to $2.50, an average restaurant meal featuring beef went from under $10 to $25, and gasoline rose from about 60 cents a gallon to $1.50
a new scale set monthly wages from $50 to $753. at a store recently, the cost of a shirt was $33 and jeans were marked at the equivalent of $66
la prensa, the opposition newspaper la prensa said in an editorial that the daily wage in 1979, when the cordoba was last valued at 10 to the dollar, was $15.20 and now it is $16.66. it also noted that meat cost $7.22 a pound then and is $35 now
the leftist sandinistas overthrew president anastasio somoza in july 1979, ending a family dynasty that had been in power 42 years
a few days after the currency change, police swept through the eastern market, broke some wooden stalls with clubs and confiscated goods sold by vendors operating without licenses
the government said more than 3,000 vendors at the market had been operating illegally
the police come, they push out some of the vendors, and they take and resell the stuff,'' said mrs. duarte, 60, sitting in front of large straw baskets filled with golden mangos and green oranges
we have to work harder than ever,'' said a nearby vegetable vendor, miguel sanchez sales. ``this new money isn't worth anything either. we used to eat on 10 cordobas a day. now we're lucky if we can get by on 100.''
a request from columnist jack anderson's associate to cabinet officers to tell all about vice president george bush got a brusque reply thursday from secretary of education william j. bennett
dale van atta, co-author of the anderson column, wrote all 34 present and former reagan cabinet members who have served with bush, asking them to rate him as presidential timber
calling bush ``a mystery to the voters,'' the columnist asked for instances where bush influenced policy decisions or actions, and warned that a failure to reply ``may send a negative message about mr. bush.''
bennett's wrote back that it was ``nonsense'' to call bush a mystery to the voters. he also said he would not violate the confidentiality of cabinet discussions, or ``the president's injunction to all his cabinet members to stay neutral in the presidential race.''
finally, and most incredibly, you threaten that you will construe a refusal to accede to your demands as sending `a negative message about mr. bush.' i cannot believe anyone will credit such a perverse interpretation,'' said bennett
i am confident that the american people will judge the vice president's distinguished record of public service on its merits.''
bush has said repeatedly on the campaign trail that he wants to be known as ``the education president.'' bennett has been mentioned as a possible running mate for whoever wins the republican nomination
american schools are still having trouble trying to make good readers out of poor ones, according to a federal released thursday
the report from the government-backed testing program, the national assessment of education progress, said poor readers are left at a disadvantage by teachers who help them figure out hard words but neglect to make them discuss the meaning of the entire passage
american schools continue to have difficulty in narrowing the performance gap between better and poorer readers as they progress through school,'' said the report, ``who reads best?'' the study was based on an analysis of reading tests the national assessment gave 35,000 students ages 9, 13 and 17 in 1986
the national assessment, run under a federal contract by the educational testing service, refrained from making any comparisons between these test results and such assessments of reading in 1984 and earlier
ets officials revealed last month there were sharp, unexplained declines in reading scores among the 9- and 17-year-olds in 1986. they suspect something went wrong in the test itself, not the students' performance
there were no sharp declines in other subjects tested in 1986, they noted
the new report said there is still no explanation for the ``precipitous declines'' in reading, which it called ``simply not believable.''
the national assessment switched to a different scale to report the 1986 test results. but officials expressed complete confidence in the conclusions reached in ``who reads best?''
the report suggests teachers use the same ``thought-stretching activities'' for poor readers that they routinely employ with better readers
students had ``particular difficulty with tasks that require them to elaborate upon or defend their evaluations and interpretations of what they have read,'' it said
poor readers report doing less independent reading than good readers,'' it said. ``poor readers report that their teachers use a narrower range of (instructional) approaches than are used with better readers.''
they focus more on decoding strategies than comprehension and critical thinking, it said
in the elementary grades, teachers of better readers are more likely to preview reading material and read new parts aloud to the class _ both activities which emphasize the meaning of the selection,'' it said
at the high school level, better readers reported more previewing of material, while poorer readers indicated their teachers more frequently pointed out the hard words and read new parts aloud.''
younger students and those in the bottom quarter of reading scores generally were exposed to fewer instructional strategies, while older students and those in the top 25 percent reported engaging ``in more before-and after-reading activities.''
they were ``more likely to be asked to engage in thought-stretching activities after they have finished their reading of the text,'' the report said. noriega. no pickup.</note>
the president on thursday ordered the removal of gen. manuel antonio noriega, the panamanian strongman who has been accused of illicit activities and indicted in the united states on drug trafficking charges
in a nationally broadcast message, delvalle said he had asked noriega several days ago to step down voluntarily so that an investigation of charges of illicit activities could be launched. he said the general declined
there is no other alternative but the use of the powers that the constitution gives me, to separate general noriega from his high command and to encharge the leadership of the institution to the current chief of staff, col. marcos justine,'' delvalle said
there was no immediate indication of whether noriega would comply with the order or if it would be carried out by his officers
the military has long been regarded as the real power in panama, with its chief considered the de facto ruler of the country
the reagan administration has been calling on noriega to step down since his indictment by a federal grand jury in miami on drug trafficking charges on feb. 5. the two indictments portrayed noriega as a key member of an international drug trafficking conspiracy
demonstrations against noriega broke out in panama last june after the military chief's recently retired second in command publicly charged the general with illicit activities ranging from drug trafficking to electoral fraud and the assassination of a political opponent. the military chief said he was innocent
delvalle talked to u.s. authorities last wednesday at an unannounced meeting in miami
reagan administration officials said they received discreet inquiries about u.s. willingness to drop federal drug charges against noriega
in his speech thursday, delvalle said: ``panama currently is experiencing one of the most difficult and dangerous moments of its history.''
he added that he reached his decision because of the ``immense seriousness'' of the situation and ``the fruitlessness of my efforts.''
delvalle said he ordered noriega out as chief of the defense forces of panama ``to allow justice to continue an impartial course without pressures of any kind.''
delvalle was inaugurated in september 1985 after elected president nicolas ardito barletta resigned in a dispute with noriega. delvalle previously was a little known civilian who had run for first vice president on the official party ticket
ardito barletta had been the first elected civilian president to take office in panama in 16 years, although the 1984 vote was marred by charges of vote fraud engineered by the military
noriega and his supporters have said those criticizing the military leader are trying to break the panama canal treaty, under which the united states agreed to cede control of the canal on dec. 31, 1999
noriega has recently criticized the u.s. southern command, headquarters for all u.s. military activities in latin america
the pentagon and the white house interpreted his remarks as a call for the transfer of the 10,000 servicemen and their 20,000 dependents from panamanian soil
washington rejected such a move, saying the american troops were legally in the country and would remain in panama to protect the canal until it is handed over to panama
in washington, a pentagon spokeswoman said thursday that the u.s. southern command had not been put on any type of alert as a result of delvalle's action
everything is normal,'' said capt. nancy laluntas, the spokeswoman. ``they might be advising (personnel) to avoid demonstrations, but the command is on normal status at the moment.''
noriega attended a military college in peru on a scholarship, then entered the panamanian national guard in 1962 as a lieutenant. he quickly became acquainted with a rising young officer named omar torrijos
torrijos took power in panama in a 1968 coup and less than a year later named noriega, then an obscure major in charge of the country's northernmost province, as his chief of intelligence with the rank of lieutenant colonel
the job put noriega in touch with u.s. intelligence agencies interested in any potential threats to the security of the panama canal, a vital shipping link between the atlantic and pacific oceans
when torrijos died in an unexplained airplane crash in 1981, noriega was well placed to shoulder his way to the top command ahead of several more senior officers. he took power in 1983
during his birthday speech earlier this month, noriega declared: ``if they want me out, they'll have to kill me.'' 11th graf, robertson did</note>
pat robertson defended himself against president reagan's critical comments thursday, saying his christian broadcasting network did give the administration information on american hostages in 1985. robertson said he mentioned it wednesday merely as ``a throwaway line.''
reacting to reagan's public skepticism, robertson said at a louisville campaign stop, ``i wasn't meaning to start some major confrontation with a person i admire tremendously, but obviously the state department must have dismissed what we had to say, or else they didn't refer it up the line to the president.''
later, at a stop in birmingham, ala., robertson said of his statements about having known the hostages whereabouts, ``i used that as a throwaway line'' to illustrate that the nation needed to improve its methods of dealing with terrorists
he said it was ``hard to understand why there has been such an incredible flap.''
state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said she had no immediate response to robertson's newest comments about having giving information to the department but would look into the matter further
reagan, during his nationally broadcast news conference wednesday night, questioned robertson's contentions that in 1985 he had known the whereabouts of hostages in the middle east ``where they could have been rescued.''
it'd be very strange if he actually did have information as to the location of those hostages,'' reagan said. ``isn't it strange that no one in our administration was ever apprised of that?''
if he thought that he knew, he kept it to himself,'' reagan added
robertson, campaigning in louisville on thursday, complained that what he had said about the hostages ``was, i'm afraid, misinterpreted.''
in atlanta on wednesday, the republican presidential candidate had said, ``we identified in our news department at cbn the location of those hostages in lebanon very shortly after they were taken, and they were in a position where they could have been rescued. they were in beirut, and they could have been freed.''
robertson did not say which hostages he was talking about
nine americans are in captivity in lebanon, including marine lt. col. william r. higgins, who was captured last week. terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, is the longest-held captive; he was kidnapped on march 16, 1985
a cbn spokesman, benton miller, later said the former television evangelist's comments pertained to hostages who had been taken from twa flight 847 in beirut in june 1985
one passenger, navy diver robert stethem, was killed after the plane was hijacked. the passengers kept as hostages after the plane landed in beirut were later released
the state department, from what my staff tells me, did inquire of us concerning what knowledge we had of that twa hijacking,'' robertson said thursday. ``our reporter did identify the names of the captors and identified them as being close to nabih berri and what is called hezbollah.''
we knew the captors and we had the basic area of beirut where they were being held,'' he said
a state department expert on terrorism has said such information probably would not be enough to mount a rescue effort
robertson's comments on wednesday were criticized by two of his republican presidential rivals, vice president george bush and rep. jack kemp of new york
bush, said, ``my question would be, how come he didn't get hold of the proper authorities in the united states government that were working day and night, trying to figure out how they could get these people out?''
kemp, in a statement, called robertson's statements irresponsible and said he should ``apologize to the families of the hostages whom he has needlessly hurt in an attempt to gain publicity.''
while jimmy swaggart contends with the fallout from his self-confessed moral lapse, his ministry is battling litigation involving taxes on a church radio station and allegations he skimmed ministry profits
one case concerns the tax status of the station, kjoj-fm in shenandoah. the louisiana-based ministry sued county authorities over their denial of a tax exemption for the station, which the ministry contends is a place of worship
in two other cases, city and school authorities are seeking more than $130,000 in delinquent taxes and other claims involving the christian station
an attorney for the ministry, james w. bradford jr., did not immediately return telephone calls thursday
russell r. graham, an attorney for the montgomery county appraisal district, said the station does not meet the legal definition of a place of worship. the agency denied the station tax-exempt status in 1982
he said the agency's defense in the ministry lawsuit had been hampered by the ministry's reluctance to reveal financial information. but he said the county has received ``considerable cooperation'' from the ministry since the county agreed to a judge's order in july sealing further filings in the case until the april 4 trial
in motions filed last year, the ministry revealed it collected $455.8 million in contributions and sales of religious materials from 1979 to 1985. contributions rose about 25 percent annually since 1979, financial statements show
the ministry had claimed the operation did not make a profit, but a 1982 financial statement showed $11.9 million classified as ``excess revenues'' after expenses
graham, in a letter to the judge obtained last year by the texas lawyer magazine, had complained that the ministry would not provide detailed accounting of millions of dollars in ``excess profits.''
tax officials ``believe that further discovery will reflect that jimmy swaggart retained these funds for his personal use,'' the letter said
the texas statute on exemptions provides that not only does the use of the property have to fit the narrow definition of what is exempt, but you have to use income for accepted purposes under the statute and avoid a situation where anyone receives any private gain,'' graham said
ministry lawyers have denied that swaggart skimmed ministry profits
hinging on the outcome of the montgomery county suit are tax cases against the ministry by the city of shenandoah, set for a march 21 trial, and by the conroe independent school district, for which no trial date has been set
shenandoah claims the ministry owes nearly $60,000 on the station from 1980-87 and on its equipment from 1981-87, city attorney michael j. darlow said
the school district claims it is owed more than $70,000 in back taxes from the radio station, its contents and a broadcast tower, said school attorney robert a. mott
the legislation that has snarled the senate in a filibuster is a democratic response to the escalating cost of getting elected to congress
the bill, being pushed heavily by the self-described citizens lobby, common cause, has 52 co-sponsors, all of whom are democrats except robert stafford, r-vt., and john chafee, r-r.i
it would set up a system to encourage senate candidates in general elections to voluntarily observe spending limits ranging from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population
in 1986, the average cost of winning a senate seat was $3 million, a fivefold increase from 1976. in larger states, the cost in 1986 often exceeded $10 million
under the democrats' plan, a candidate observing the state spending limit would be allowed to put no more than $20,000 in personal funds into the campaign
in an effort to curb the growing role of political action committees as a source of campaign money, a participating candidate could get no more than 20 percent of his or her money from pacs. in 1986, pacs provided more than half the money spent by more than 200 house and senate candidates
a candidate observing the limit would be eligible for campaign money from the treasury if an opponent did not adhere to the limit. tax dollars also would be awarded in cases in which a participating candidate was the target of heavy spending by independent groups
a participating candidate also would be eligible for reduced mailing rates. the bill would require radio and television stations to charge the candidate the ``lowest unit rates'' for advertising
campaign ads by candidates not observing spending limits would have to carry the disclaimer, ``this candidate has not agreed to abide by voluntary spending limits.''
most of the nation enjoyed mostly sunny skies thursday thanks to a large high-pressure zone, while snow fell over parts of the midwest and new york state
the snow, ranging from flurries to major accumulation, fell from lower michigan across the eastern great lakes to upstate new york, with heavier snow squalls near lakes erie and ontario
up to 17 inches was dumped on pulaski, n.y., overnight thursday, and up to 8 inches fell at oswego, n.y., between midnight and 7 a.m. est
three to 5 inches of snow fell thursday morning in ohio's geauga and lake counties, while 2 to 3 inches covered downtown cleveland
light rain fell in northwest washington state, and a trace of rain fell in parts of the texas rio grande valley
temperatures remained low in the northeast, with midday readings mostly in the teens and 20s from the upper mississippi valley across the great lakes and northern sections of the ohio valley to the northern and central appalachians. winds of 10 to 20 mph produced wind chills in the single digits as far south as bluefield, w.v
temperatures warmed into the 60s, 70s and 80s across the desert southwest. readings in the 60s were also common across the southern plains, louisiana and southern and central florida
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 14 at gunnison, colo., to 87 at palm springs, calif. the early-morning low for the nation was 18 below zero at gunnison
for friday, sunny skies again were expected across most of the country, while snow was forecast across the great lakes region and scattered snowshowers over the central appalachians and northern maine. light rain was expected along the northern pacific coast, while clouds should increase across southern texas. much of the nation will have highs in the 40s or 50s. highs will be in the 20s and 30s from eastern north dakota across the great lakes region and the upper ohio valley to the northern two-thirds of the atlantic coast. temperatures will reach the 60s and 70s over the southern tier of states as well as over arkansas, oklahoma, kansas, western nebraska and parts of nevada, with readings in the 80s over portions of the desert southwest
albania said wednesday it was breaking out of its isolationist shell to build better relations with its neighbors, but bitter differences between turkey and bulgaria showed the region is still rife with disputes
albania's presence at a three-day conference of six balkan states was its first appearance at a regional forum after a decade of spurning invitations to attend low-level balkan gatherings
development of relations with neighboring countries constitutes one of the priorities of the foreign policy'' of albania, foreign minister reis malile told his counterparts from greece, turkey, yugoslavia, romania and bulgaria
not only do we not hesitate to cooperate with others. on the contrary, we want this cooperation and consider it a factor which contributes to our internal development,'' he said
but the conference, the first high-level gathering of balkan nations since world war ii, was marked by turkey's indirect denunciation of bulgaria's treatment of its turkish minority
attempts to alter the cultural and religious identity of ethnic minorities can neither be reconciled nor coexist with the new beginning we all seem desirous to make here in belgrade,'' said turkish foreign minister mesut yilmaz
relations among most balkan countries are still strained by bilateral quarrels over ethnic minorities that date back to the late 19th century when much of the region belonged to the ottoman empire
yilmaz did not assail bulgaria by name nor mention its estimated one million ethnic turks specifically, but the minority issue is the primary point of contention between the two countries
a campaign forcing turkish citizens to change their names was begun in 1984. it was first reported by turkish newspapers and later confirmed by western diplomats in sofia and by the human rights group, amnesty international
bulgarian authorities, who have so far denied the existence of a self-contained turkish minority, said the decision to adopt bulgarian names was voluntary and no pressure was exerted
the turkish foreign minister's comments were expected to be cause tension during the three-day meeting
he expressed his satisfaction about the ``common understanding'' he reached with his bulgrian counterpart peter mladenov in signing an agreement tuesday that he said would establish a mechanism for the settlement of the existing problems between the two countries
but yilmaz added that ``anachronistic policies cannot be either defended or ignored,'' a reference to bulgaria's policy toward the ethnic turks
asked to comment on yilmaz' speech, mladenov said he would comment on it only after reading it
a member of turkish delegation, asked why the turkish foreign minister decided to criticize bulgaria even after the protocol was signed, said: ``we are seeking a mechanism to solve our problem. but we have yet to see whether it will work.'' kentucky; picks up 5th graf pvs, bgng ``in louisville''</note>
jesse jackson mined for votes in eastern kentucky coal country thursday, the first democratic presidential candidate since 1968 to campaign in this area where he said the land is rich but the people are poor
jackson visited a strip mine site near hazard, then went to a rally that drew about 3,000 people
right down here in appalachia, the land is wealthy _ the people are poor,'' jackson told a crowd in the hazard memorial gymnasium
jackson, campaigning for support in kentucky's march 8 democratic presidential primary, said miners, farmers and factory workers must forge a coalition to battle abuses of large corporations which he said pay few taxes and hold down wages
jackson drew the most applause when he discussed coal-related issues. it is unfair, he said, when big coal companies pay almost no taxes. he also said: ``what good is land if it is stripped from beneath your feet?''
earlier, in louisville, jackson stressed his southern roots and his record. ``i return to the south as a son of the south,'' jackson said
i have given 25 years of national and international service,'' jackson said. ``my track record on national service is more substantial than my opponents. i know foreign policy better than my competitors.''
jackson, a baptist minister, addressed the 44th annual black baptist pastors' conference in louisville before flying to eastern kentucky
no other democratic presidential candidates have ventured into eastern kentucky this year _ or in any year since robert f. kennedy made a campaign trip to the kentucky mountains in 1968

in louisville, jackson said his southern credentials and campaign message will carry him through the super tuesday primary march 8
i return to the south as a son of the south,'' said jackson, who was born in south carolina. ``i helped make the new south better 25 years ago, and now i want to make it even better by focusing on the agenda of today.''
jackson said that agenda includes improving day care, attaining equal rights for women, increasing the minimum wage, increasing aid to education and stopping a loss of jobs
we must care about the family and working people,'' he said. ``we can't be a great nation if we abandon those whose shoulders we stand on.''
asked about his chances on super tuesday _ when democrats go to the primaries and caucuses in 20 states and american samoa _ and, in particular, about how he will do in the balloting in kentucky, jackson said:
i'm not projecting a certain number. those who support me feel i can win. i know i can win.''
jackson, who carried louisville and lexington in 1984 democratic caucuses, made a plug for campaign contributions in his address to the ministers
he later discounted claims that a lack of money will keep him from waging an effective campaign
i cannot buy the nomination. i will outwork my opposition,'' jackson said. ``i come to the south with a message and a track record, not money and television commercials.''
cbs and pat sajak insist they won't be gunning for nbc's ``the tonight show starring johnny carson'' when their new talk show premieres next january, despite its time period opposite the late-night king
cbs made a formal announcement of the signing of sajak, well-known as the host of ``wheel of fortune,'' at a news conference wednesday
cbs entertainment president kim lemasters said the show would be 90 minutes instead of carson's hour and would premiere on jan. 9, 1989
there is no attempt on our part here to compete with johnny carson,'' lemasters said. ``mr. carson is a tradition, he is much-beloved and a brilliant performer in what he does, and that's not our aim. our aim is that the environment in late night can stand more than just one talk-show format.''
if you're going to do a late-night show, that's a fact of life, that mr. carson is going to be there. we can't worry about that. we have to worry about doing the best show we can,'' said sajak
carson, who has been host of ``the tonight show'' for a quarter-century, last year signed only a two-year extension of his contract with nbc, but both sajak and lemasters said they did not plan on carson retiring
i have been hearing johnny carson is retiring for literally 20 years,'' said sajak. ``it wouldn't shock me to be having the same conversation in 10 years, that johnny carson is retiring in a couple of years.''
there's no name yet for the new show yet, though sajak joked, ``we're thinking of the wilton south show,'' a reference to the quickly canceled fox late-night show ``the wilton north report.'' he added, ``perhaps the name pat will be in the title.''
sajak will continue as host of the syndicated nighttime version of ``wheel of fortune,'' which is the no. 1 syndicated show. his contract for the nbc daytime version of the show expires in december
lemasters said cbs would have launched a talk show years ago ``if we'd had the personality.'' he said the network chose sajak because ``we were looking for someone intelligent, which pat is, well-read and with the ability to attract guests. and he's cute.''
lemasters said cbs might put its current schedule of late-night original dramas, ``adderly'' and ``night heat,'' in the 1 a.m. time period instead of canceling them
former secretary of state henry a. kissinger called on the european members of the nato alliance wednesday to unify their military defenses against the soviet union and to coordinate british and french nuclear forces as an important first step
kissinger also suggested that western europe and the united states present soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev with a comprehensive plan to reduce nuclear and conventional arms simultaneously
i am convinced that he has the intelligence and the imagination to make an intelligent response,'' kissinger told the senate armed services committee. ``and if he refused, we would at least understand the nature of the challenge better than we do now.''
kissinger said the western alliance will work better if europe sheds much of its military dependence on the united states and develops ``a capacity for independent action'' based on ``a rational balance of responsibilities.''
as it stands now, he said, the 16 european members of nato often go along with u.s. military decisions for lack of a better alternative. the result is not consultation or a mutual decision-making process but merely a u.s. ``briefing'' on already decided u.s. actions
under conditions of relative prosperity, kissinger said, europe's military dependence on the united states ``can breed guilt, self-hatred and a compulsion to display independence of the senior partner whenever doing so is safe, especially with regard to third world issues, the middle east and some aspects of east-west relations.''
for those reasons, he said, the united states has a positive interest in encouraging the evolution of a more independent european voice in defense matters
kissinger said that while some fear that military independence might weaken europe's military ties to the united states, ``the opposite is almost certainly the case.''
there is no foreseeable east-west conflict in which europe will not be better off with american support,'' kissinger said
this is why, if the british and the french can agree on coordinating their nuclear forces, the united states should encourage it as an important first step toward a greater european role in a joint nuclear defense,'' he said
above all, the united states should make clear that european union on defense matters will be viewed as strengthening, not weakening atlantic ties,'' he said
a european military union, he asserted, would ease west germany's fears of isolation and help overcome a ``logistical nightmare'' caused by the effort of each european nation to ``stretch already inadequate defense efforts across the whole panoply of weapons.''
kissinger said that divisive trends within the alliance have been magnified by the successful ratification of the new treaty eliminating medium-range u.s. and soviet nuclear-armed missiles in europe and elsewhere
he repeated recent statements that the treaty strains the alliance by making the nuclear defense of europe dependent largely on nuclear weapons located not in europe but in the united states or on submarines at sea
many europeans are convinced a gap is being created that in time will enable the soviet union to threaten europe while sparring with the united states,'' he said
here are excerpts of the government's new regulations banning political activity by major opposition groups:
if the minister (of law and order) is of the opinion that it is necessary for the safety of the public, the maintenance of public order or the termination of the state of emergency, he may, without prior notice to any person or without hearing any person, issue an order ... prohibiting an organization ... from carrying on:
_ any activities or acts whatsoever
_ activities or acts of a nature, class or kind specified in the order
the order said an affected organization will not be barred from:
_ preserving its assets
_ keeping up to date its books and records and performing administrative functions in connection therewith
_ complying with an obligation imposed on it by or under any law or court
_ taking legal advice or judicial steps
_ carrying on such activities or performing such acts as the minister may have consented to
no consent ... shall be granted by the minister unless he is convinced that the granting of such consent will not result in the safety of the public or the maintenance of public order being threatened
the order listed the following organizations as being affected by the new restrictions:
azanian people's organization
azanian youth organization
cape youth congress
cradock residents association
detainees parents support committee
detainees support committee
national education crisis committee
national education union of south africa
port elizabeth black civic organization
release mandela committee
soweto civic association
soweto youth congress
south african national student congress
south african youth congress
united democratic front
vaal civil association
western cape civic association
more than 100 ungraded results from an upper-level law exam were accidentally shredded, leaving washington university officials with red faces and some students furious
it seemed to be just a matter of time before a huge administrative error occurred,'' maia brodie, a third-year law student and president of the student bar association, said of the shredding, which was revealed last week. ``some students want their money back, they're so furious.''
school officials said a student working without supervision in the registrar's office accidentally shredded both the questions and answers to a three-hour exam that was given in december
the exam was to provide the sole basis for the grades of 116 students who were enrolled in the evidence course
the shredding occurred two weeks ago. law school dean dorsey d. ellis jr. gave the bad news to the class in a memorandum dated feb. 16
school officials decided to give each student in the evidence class a ``credit'' that will have no bearing on grade-point averages
one student studied nearly full-time for five weeks in hopes of raising her grade-point average through the exam, she said. moreover, minor differences in grade averages can ``make the difference between a $26,000 job and a $40,000 job,'' brodie said. bgng: give us; editing in 11th pvs, bgng: senate majority</note>
a weary senate ended 53 hours of continuous and sometimes cantankerous debate over campaign finance thursday, leaving democrats no closer to victory than when the filibuster began tuesday
by agreement between majority democrats and stubborn republicans, the talking stopped about 7 p.m., setting up a friday vote on a democratic cloture motion to force a vote on their campaign legislation
democrats have the votes to pass the bill, but they had virtually no hope of mustering the 60 needed to win friday's cloture roll call. the expected loss could scuttle the divisive issue for the 100th congress
as the filibuster wound down, majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., made a final pitch for voluntary spending limits to counter the escalating cost of getting elected, with increasing amounts of money coming from special-interest political action committees
the senate should not be owned by an aristocracy of money,'' byrd said. ``campaign reform gives the little guy an equal share. ... this business of the golden handshake _ nobody likes it. senators don't want to spend all their time going from fundraiser to fundraiser with their hand out begging for money.''
another advocate of spending limits, sen. david boren, d-okla., conceded that ``negotiations have fallen apart'' because of gop opposition to proposed voluntary spending limits on senate campaigns
give us a chance!'' boren shouted, urging his republican foes to join in shutting off debate and allowing a floor vote on the campaign finance measure, which democrats have the votes to win
boren promised that if gop senators switched sides and provided the winning margin to invoke cloture, the democratic bill would be open to all ``legitimate, relevant'' amendments the republicans might propose to reach a compromise
but gop senators made clear their fears that the spending limits proposal disguises an attempt to reinforce the democrats' election advantage in large, heavily democratic states and to perpetuate their majority control of the senate
sen. warren rudman, r-n.h., called it the ``incumbent protection act'' and said it would work against election challengers with little name recognition or financial support
everyone in politics knows that with these (spending) limits, what we absolutely say to most challengers is, `you've had it,''' rudman said
we've heard a lot of accusations on this floor that this bill is designed to end the republican party,'' rudman said. ``i don't believe that ... but to many of us on this side of the aisle it kind of feels that way.''
the senate will vote at 10 a.m. friday on whether to invoke cloture, or halt further debate on the bill
the measure has 52 co-sponsors, more than the majority of 51 senators necessary for passage, but democratic strategists say they are still short of the 60 votes required to invoke cloture and proceed to a floor vote on the bill itself
byrd lost a record seven cloture votes on the bill last year, and the lack of any significant weakening in gop determination to block the measure made it likely that byrd would lose again friday morning
he hasn't said what would happen to the bill after the expected cloture defeat, but democratic aides said privately that it would be shelved
byrd, who once threatened to continue round-the-clock filibustering through next week, relented wednesday night and announced agreement with the gop leadership to end the talkathon late thursday afternoon
byrd spokeswoman linda peek denied that the agreement represented a democratic defeat. ``the defeat is for the republicans who are consistently against the campaign spending limits and are afraid to vote on the bill,'' she said
the measure calls for voluntary ceilings on senate campaign spending that range from $950,000 to $5.5 million, depending on a state's population. participating candidates would be eligible for treasury funds if their opponents exceed the limits or if independent groups spend large amounts against a candidate observing the restriction
the bill also would prohibit a participating candidate from receiving more than 20 percent of campaign funds from special-interest political action committees. in 1986, more than 200 house and senate candidates _ most of them incumbents _ received more than half their campaign money from pacs
republicans argued that spiraling campaign costs, rather than spending, should be the primary issue
sen. ted stevens, r-alaska, said the only compromise he would accept would be to allow candidates in individual states to agree on their own spending limts. rudman argued for reallocating contributions under a formula that would allow 50 percent to come from individuals, 30 percent from the political parties and 20 percent from pacs
the debate thursday was much calmer than the day before, when republicans angrily denounced byrd's successful motion to have the senate sergeant-at-arms, henry k. giugni, arrest absentee republicans and force them to return to the chamber
under giugni's direction, armed plainclothes capitol police broke into the locked offices of sen. bob packwood, r-ore., and carried him feet-first onto the senate floor. packwood's arrival provided the 51st senator necessary to constitute a quorum or majority of senators on the floor
byrd hoped to embarrass the republicans by focusing attention on their stalling tactics, and without a quorum to keep the filibuster alive, the senate would have been forced to adjourn
before he arrested packwood, giugni reportedly approached sen. lowell p. weicker jr., r-conn., in the russell senate office building. but weicker, a large man known for his hot temper, refused to submit and giugni left without a protest
afghanistan's communist government said thursday a guerrilla proposal for an interim government while soviet troops withdraw was a ``hysterical'' dream, but a u.s. envoy called it a good idea
undersecretary of state michael armacost, visiting pakistan, said the plan announced this week by the seven-party guerrilla alliance was a ``very welcome step toward the resolution of the afghan problem.''
the alliance, led by yunis khalis and based in pakistan, proposes an executive council of all seven guerrilla leaders to preside over a 28-member cabinet of rebels, afghan refugees and ``moslems presently living in kabul.''
soviet military forces entered afghanistan in december 1979 and an estimated 115,000 now are in the country helping fight the guerrillas
about 3.5 million afghans have fled to neighboring pakistan. most live in border cities and camps that serve as bases and supply points for the guerrillas
thursday's editions of the afghan communist party newspaper anis said the plan ``resembles more a hysterical and disturbed dream,'' kabul radio reported
it is clear that this void and unfounded plan has no legitimacy and therefore is unacceptable,'' the paper said, adding that the insurgent proposal was like the ``story of sharing the wolf's prey.''
the radio also broadcast a foreign ministry statement that ``there is only one legal government in afghanistan, which has been recognized by 80 countries in the world.''
armacost arrived wednesday to discuss progress toward soviet withdrawal. he met with president mohammed zia ul-haq, and a u.s. embassy official said he also had ``frank and open'' discussions with leaders of the moslem guerrillas
mikhail s. gorbachev said feb. 8 that soviet troops will start pulling out may 15 if u.n.-sponsored talks in geneva between afghanistan and pakistan bring a settlement by march 15, and complete the withdrawal in 10 months. the talks are to resume wednesday
pakistan demands a military settlement be accompanied by a political one to ensure transitional stability. washington, which supports the guerrillas, has devoted most of its effort to obtaining a withdrawal
a doctor with aids once ordered to stay away from patients at cook county hospital was guaranteed full medical duties under an agreement approved wednesday by a federal judge
the consent decree signed by u.s. district judge john a. nordberg ensures that the neurologist will be able to examine patients, draw blood, perform spinal taps and handle other procedures included in his speciality
the cook county board restored most of those duties last september after the doctor filed a lawsuit, but nordberg had suggested the board could again reverse itself and asked for a formal agreement between the doctor and hospital
a year ago, the board, which governs the hospital, barred any contact between patients and the doctor
in july, the board said the doctor could see patients, but could not puncture the skin or come in contact with body fluids of patients
the american civil liberties union, acting on behalf of the doctor, filed a lawsuit a month later seeking the return of full medical responsibilities for him
we're all gratified that the cook county hospital has agreed to follow medical evidence that a doctor with aids can continue to practice,'' said aclu attorney ben wolf of the agreement worked out between the aclu, the hospital and the board
he will follow centers for disease control guidelines, which require gloves when certain procedures are performed,'' wolf said. ``he has even agreed to wear double gloves in certain instances.''
wolf said complications from aids have caused the doctor to miss some days of work
when his health permits, he's practicing. he's had some tough times,'' the attorney said
a spokeswoman for the hospital, wanda robertson, forwarded all calls to hospital director terrence m. hansen, who did not return messages requesting comment
under the decree, the doctor is not required to tell patients he has aids, wolf said
the decree said the doctor would not perform muscle biopsies or cerebral work, but not because he has the fatal disease. neurologists have not handled those procedures in years, wolf said
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, destroys the body's defenses against disease, leaving a person prey to life-threatening infections and certain cancers
the virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is believed to be passed mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during birth
nasa chief james fletcher said wednesday that the civil space program is the key to questions ``about where this civilization is going'' and should not be allowed to suffer from the shortsightedness of ``naysayers.''
we need to adopt a rigorous space agenda beyond the 1990s and stick to it,'' fletcher said in a speech before the national space club
he said american technological leadership will ride on the consistent and longterm national support for the space policy recently announced by president reagan
the stakes are very high,'' fletcher said. ``the soviets have let it be known that they are in space to stay. .... leadership (in space) is not just who is ahead, but is a sustained and consistent effort toward goals over a long period of time.''
he said reagan's space policy affirms the nation's commitment to the space station and to human exploration beyond earth orbit, such as to mars. the policy is supported in the president's budget presented last week to congress
the program presented to congress is the right policy at the right time,'' fletcher said. ``we now need to rally national support to it through the various congressional hurdles.''
the civil space program is key to the much larger questions about where this civilization is going,'' he said. ``we can't let the program founder through shortsightedness.''
the nasa administrator cautioned that some oppose the space program and that public support is needed to overcome these objections
it's surprising how many naysayers there are in and out of congress,'' he said. ``we have to guard against the naysayers.''
the national space club is an organization of industrial, military, congressional and governmental supporters of the u.s. efforts in space and rocketry. word `disputed,' subs 6th graf pvs: `a member ... to insert word `non-voting</note>
armenians demanding annexation of part of a neighboring republic massed by the thousands in two cities thursday, and red army troops and tanks were sent into one area as a show of force, witnesses said
a senior official was quoted as saying there were ``human victims'' of the unrest
demonstrations in the armenian capital of yerevan appeared to be the largest unsanctioned gatherings in soviet history, according to eyewitness accounts. some witnesses said more than 1 million people participated in protests and strikes. there was no official estimate of the numbers
the demonstrators were demanding that the nagorno-karabakh region, now part of the republic of azerbaidzhan, be annexed to armenia
in addition to the territorial dispute involving the 1,760-square-mile autonomous region in the caucusus mountains, the people are divided by religion. armenians are predominantly christians, and most azeris, the dominant ethnic group in azerbaidzhan, are shiite moslem
a non-voting member of the ruling politburo, vladimir i. dolgikh, said in a television broadcast wednesday night from yerevan that there were ``human victims'' of the unrest, according to an armenian telephone operator in yerevan
the operator said dolgikh did not provide details
an armenian nationalist activist said he heard rumors that azeris had stoned a bus in nagorno-karabakh, killing an undetermined number of armenians. the activist, mofses gorgisyan, said he also heard that azeris set fire to a school, resulting in other deaths
in glendale, calif., apo boghigian, editor of the armenian newspaper asbarez, said he spoke by telephone wednesday to hovig vassilian, a newspaper editor in yerevan. boghigian said vassilian described the demonstrators in yerevan as ``very peaceful'' but said clashes elsewhere had resulted in deaths
four victims were to be buried thursday in askeran, an armenian village of about 1,000 people, boghigian said
in nagorno-karabakh's main city, sepanakert, about 120,000 people have demonstrated daily since feb. 13, said one resident
the 17-year-old student, interviewed in a moscow airport after arriving from armenia, said some armenians had been killed by azeris in the region, but she had no details
the official tass news agency said a deputy prosecutor from the central government was sent to azerbaidzhan, indicating serious concern over the unrest
tass quoted the prosecutor, alexander katusev, as saying: ``all sorts of rumors and inventions that are being circulated mostly outside of the nagorno-karabakh autnomous region and for which gullible people often fall are groundless.''
he acknowledged, however, that crimes were committed and promised to investigate
there was no way to verify the reports independently because the government barred foreign reporters from traveling to the area
gorgisyan, interviewed by telephone, estimated there were more than 1 million demonstrators in yerevan. a telephone operator said that figure seemed accurate
soldiers arrived thursday morning and took up discreet positions in downtown yerevan, particularly around key government buildings, gorgisyan said. they deployed camouflaged trucks downtown and stationed tanks in outlying areas, said gorgisyan, a 26-year-old member of an underground group called the alliance for national determination
the soldiers did not try to stop the demonstration, and gorgisyan said the protesters were trying not to provoke the troops
we're trying not to break any laws. the demonstration is very well organized and orderly,'' he said
he said businesses and schools were closed in the city and in many other parts of the armenian republic, the smallest of the soviet union's 15 republics and home to 3.4 million soviets
in nagorno-karabakh, the student said she saw a large crowd of demonstrators thursday in lenin square in stepanakert
practically the whole population is there. they've come from all the villages,'' said the student, who spoke on the condition of anonymity
the protests were continuing around the clock. ``no one's sleeping. no one is going to work. the only stores open are groceries,'' she said
an official at the armenian representational offices in moscow in charge of internal matters, rudolf khatchyanov, confirmed a major demonstration by armenians was going on. he said to call authorities in yerevan for more details, but telephone calls to police in yerevan did not go through
the communist party's national central committee this month decided nagorno-karabakh should remain part of azerbaidzhan. radio moscow said armenian authorities planned to ask the central committee to reconsider its position
the demonstrations in the region began after the party's decision was announced, ayrikyan said
tass announced wednesday night that an armenian, genrikh pogosyan, had been named party leader in the disputed region. he replaced boris kevorkov, who also is armenian
prosecutors said thursday it may take up to a month to decide whether to file charges in the death of a woman whose head was cut off and frozen in hopes of bringing her back to life someday in a new body
the riverside county coroner's office this week ruled the death of 83-year-old dora kent a homicide caused by a lethal dose of barbiturates. she died in december at the alcor life extension foundation cryonics laboratory
assistant district attorney jay thompson hanks said the decision to bring charges could take up to a month ``only because there are other questions to be asked and answered, and other pieces of evidence we want tested or examined.''
thompson said ``a wide range of charges'' is being contemplated. those under investigation include ``everyone associated with the death,'' he said
mrs. kent's son, saul kent, 48, is a supporter of the cryonics movement, which freezes bodies or heads in the belief that science will advance to the point where they can be brought back to life
on dec. 9, mrs. kent's physician determined she was gravely ill. her son then removed her from a riverside nursing home and brought her to alcor
kent says his mother was maintained there briefly on a respirator before dying dec. 11. her head was surgically removed
the coroner's office investigated because no doctor was present when mrs. kent died
the coroner asked to examine the head, but kent has refused to give it location. a judge blocked the coroner from disturbing any of the frozen remains at alcor
mrs. kent's son said barbiturates are used after death to slow brain damage caused by lack of oxygen. but the coroner's investigation concluded that mrs. kent was alive when drugs were administered
reagan administration officials were led to believe they had to keep dealing with iran or american hostages could be killed, former white house chief of staff donald t. regan said in a deposition released thursday
regan's account of the arms-for-hostages program was revealed in depositions taken last summer by the congressional iran-contra committees
regan said that at first he supported the idea of allowing israel to sell u.s.-made weapons to iran in september 1985 in return for freeing american hostages held by pro-iranian terrorists in lebanon
i thought it was worth pursuing,'' regan said of the initiative. ``it was an opening. i thought we should explore it.''
by december, regan said he had changed his mind. another shipment of weapons was sent to iran in november, but only one hostage _ the rev. benjamin weir _ was freed in the fall of 1985
asked why, regan said: ``well, the thing had been a fiasco up to that point, in my judgment it had not worked. we were dealing with some very unusual people
we were fooling around for the better part of six months with very little results to show for it, and i couldn't see the value of pursuing that avenue any more. i thought we were dealing either with the wrong people or in the wrong way.''
but regan said john m. poindexter, the former national security adviser, convinced him to go along with the more shipments. poindexter told president reagan and regan that ``there was a whole new lead and a whole new plan and that it might turn thing around.''
in addition, regan said the president, vice president george bush and poindexter received some unsettling news from robert f. mcfarlane, who had been poindexter's predecessor at the national security council
mcfarlane, who continued to work on the hostage project after his resignation from the nsc, traveled to london in december to meet manucher ghorbanifar, a middleman in the u.s.-iran relationship
regan was asked whether on his return mcfarlane indicated that if discussions with the iranians were terminated, the hostages could be killed
yes,'' replied the former chief of staff
this was becoming increasingly evident, that unless we got on a new tack, we would (a) probably never see our hostages; or (b) the whole project would end in dismal failure,'' regan said
in january 1986, the united states began shipping weapons directly to iran. the project ended in november after revelations that profits from the sale of weapons to iran had been diverted to the nicaraguan contras. nine americans remain hostage in lebanon
when majority leader robert byrd forced the senate into its night-and-day campaign spending filibuster on tuesday, he said he wanted to expose republican stalling tactics to the american public
the public got a show, but it was not quite the one the west virginia democrat was looking for
overshadowing the lesson in how a senate minority can use the debate rules to thwart the will of the majority was a late-night cops-and-robbers show produced by the democrats
the climax came early wednesday when a plainclothes police posse led by sergeant-at-arms henry giugni, acting on orders from democrats, pushed through the office door of sen. bob packwood, r-ore., arrested him and carried him feet first into the senate chamber
packwood's commanded performance gave byrd the quorum he needed to keep the filibuster going. it also gave angry republicans a rallying point to shift the focus away from their refusal to let the senate vote on a democratic bill with 52 co-sponsors from the 100-member chamber
illegal, unlawful, null and void,'' snarled arlen specter, r-pa
the former philadelphia district attorney said packwood's apprehension ``really constituted false arrest of a u.s. senator. ... there is a sense that the senate is falling apart, that the senate is disintegrating.''
specter complained that his colleague was treated like a ``common criminal,'' subjected to police-state measures appropriate to ``nazi germany and communist russia.''
banana republic,'' snapped orrin hatch, r-utah. ``the tyranny of the majority,'' said acting minority leader alan simpson, r-wyo. ``demeaning and humiliating,'' was the verdict of malcolm wallop, r-wyo
democrats responded that packwood _ and other absent republicans who escaped the posse's clutches _ had it coming
after all, they said, democrats were only forcing the gop to do something that voters sent them to washington to do: answer the bell and vote
in the span of 45 minutes, the entire republican party in the united states senate, with the exception of one, the designated (floor) leader, vanished into the night,'' said sen. john kerry, d-mass
like most filibusters, this one was a game of chicken. which side would cave in? would the senate compromise over the central question of setting spending limits for senate races?
democrats insist that limits are crucial to any legislation to curb the escalating cost of getting elected
but republican leaders held fast that limits were not negotiable
after vowing to keep the senate in continuous session at least through the end of next week, byrd agreed late wednesday to bring the filibuster to a close at 5 p.m. thursday, get a night's sleep and vote friday on a democratic motion to shut off debate and bring the bill to a vote. it finally ended at 7 p.m., two hours past the original target
byrd will probably lose that cloture vote, just as he lost a record seven cloture votes last year, never getting closer than 55 of the 60 votes needed to end the debate that has consumed 30 days since last june
republicans, outnumbered 54 to 46, have made opposition to spending limits a party issue. so far, only three gop senators have broken ranks and supported cloture: bill co-sponsors robert stafford of vermont and john chafee of rhode island and non-sponsor nancy landon kassebaum of kansas
one key to the eventual outcome is a handful of other republicans who are known to support some form of spending limits but who thus far have stayed loyal to their party's line
democrats had hoped to pick up support for cloture before they had to concede defeat and pull the bill from the floor. the necessary crossovers never materialized, leaving campaign finance a very sick, if not dead, issue for the 100th congress
david goeller has been covering capitol hill campaign finance issues for the associated press since 1983. charges</head>
if panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega left panama because of attempts to oust him from power, ``we would attempt to extradite him like any other dope dealer,'' a federal prosecutor said thursday
there is no consideration whatsoever to dropping this indictment,'' said richard gregorie, chief assistant u.s. attorney in florida's southern district. ``i have not been asked by anybody to do that.''
noriega was indicted in miami with 15 others feb. 4 on charges of taking at least $4.6 million to protect shipments of colombian cocaine, launder money, supply drug laboratories and shield drug kingpins. also charged were medellin drug cartel leader pablo escobar gaviria and a top noriega aide, capt. luis del cid
gregorie, the lead prosecutor in the noriega drug case, said panamanian president eric arturo delvalle made a ``pretty gutsy move'' thursday in ordering noriega out of his post and named a replacement
assuming he does step down, he's going to be like any other citizen,'' gregorie said, ``and i would assume there might be a great likelihood that he would leave the country and go somewhere where we'd have a chance of getting him.''
in tampa, a grand jury feb. 5 indicted noriega and panamanian businessman enrique pretelt on marijuana conspiracy and importation charges
a 1904 treaty between the united states and panama does not oblige either state to extradite its own citizens
the indictment alleged that noriega allied himself with the medellin cartel and once enlisted the help of cuban leader fidel castro to mediate a dispute with the cartel over drug money
castro said in an interview with nbc news aired thursday that jose blandon, former panamanian consul general in new york, lied about castro's role as a mediator for noriega. castro was named in the indictment, but not charged
u.s. attorney leon kellner charged at the time of the indictment that noriega used his position of power in panama to ``sell the country of panama to drug traffickers.''
if noriega is ever brought to trial and convicted of all charges, he could face up to 145 years in prison and fines of more than $1.1 million, prosecutors say
a defendant in the miami indictment, brian alden davidow, 26, of miami surrendered to authorities and pleaded innocent a week ago
ambler moss, former u.s. ambassador to panama, said thursday that delvalle's move was unlikely to bring noriega to trial
it's highly unusual because the military in panama has dominated politics there for a very long time,'' said moss, ambassasor from 1978 to 1982. ``it's very unusual that he would even dare try to separate the head of the armed forces from his powers
it's a very courageous act, although we don't know whether some deal was worked out in advance,'' he said. ``i doubt this would ever result in his standing trial in the united states.''
gregorie held a glimmer of hope. ``if mr. noriega chooses to come here tomorrow morning to be arraigned, he will receive discovery immediately,'' he said, ``and we will be prepared to go to trial in 60 days.''
in a major reassessment of nikita khrushchev, a prominent writer has said the former soviet leader deserves praise for ending stalin's cult of personality and introducing economic reforms
the article was the most wide-ranging appraisal of khrushchev in the official media to date
fedor burlatsky said khrushchev should be praised for putting an end to the cult of personality that surrounded his predecessor, josef stalin, and for improving the economy and bringing modern technology to the country
burlatsky also believes, however, that khrushchev did a bad job of managing the vast soviet bureaucracy and was not completely candid about the nation's problems
now that we are guided by the experience of glasnost, we can see clearly how little was done to inform people about the past, about real problems, about planned decisions,'' burlatsky wrote in an article published wednesday in the literary gazette newspaper
khruschev ruled in 1953-1964 and declared that the soviet union would bury the west, but he was later removed from the leadership in disgrace
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has encouraged a review of history in his campaign for ``glasnost,'' or openness in some matters
numerous articles have appeared about stalin and his excesses but burlatsky is the first to take a detailed look at khrushchev. the journalist and playwright, who was an aide to khrushchev, said the former leader's name was taboo for nearly 20 years until gorbachev mentioned him nov. 2
a wind of change swept the country, the people's spirits rose, they took heart, became bolder and more confident,'' gorbachev said, and praised khrushchev for ridding the country of stalin's cult of personality
burlatsky, 61, picked up that theme in his full-page article
the main significance khrushchev gave to the ideological side of matters was ... unmasking the cult of personality, to speak out the truth about the crimes of the 30s and other periods,'' he wrote
he praised khrushchev for such technological achievements as putting the first man in space and reviving soviet agriculture
khrushchev was not candid in revealing his actions under stalin, however, because ``many in the party knew about the role that he played in persecuting'' people, burlatsky wrote
he also faulted khrushchev for using ``traditional administrative and even bureaucratic methods'' that ruined what began as bold reforms in agriculture and the overall economy
khrushchev was ousted from the leadership in october 1964 by a ``strange symbiosis of political forces'' ranging from conservatives and stalinists to reform-minded officials, burlatsky said
after the fall, khrushchev sank into obscurity. he died in 1971 and the government of leonid i. brezhnev ordered that he be buried in moscow's novodevichy cemetery, second in importance to the kremlin wall
rumors have been circulating that his remains might be moved to the kremlin, where the nation's other top leaders are buried
in a telephone conversation from his newspaper office thursday night, burlatsky said he had not heard any proposals for moving the body
maybe some informal group is talking about it, but it's certainly not a firm proposal among party members,'' said burlatsky, who is a member of the communist party
basque separatists appear to have broken a 60-day truce they offered the government by kidnapping 58-year-old businessman emiliano revilla sanza, officials said thursday
deputy prime minister alfonso guerra told reporters the government considers the kidnapping an attack by the basque separatist organization eta and will not pursue contacts begun with the organization ``because we don't talk with terrorists.''
rafael vazquez, a spokesman for the revilla family, said there had been no contact with armed kidnappers who seized revilla at 11:30 p.m. wednesday outside his home in central madrid. he said the family did not know the identity of the three men and a woman witnesses saw forcing revilla into a car
the kidnapping of the well-known madrid real estate developer occurred after reports that the government had resumed contacts over the weekend with eta members in exile in algeria
eta, whose initials stand for basque land and liberty in the basque language, has taken responsibility for killing more than 600 people in a 20-year campaign for independence in spain's three northern basque provinces
during his annual address to parliament on wednesday, prime minister felipe gonzalez said spaniards should not lower their guard against terrorism despite optimism created by reports of contacts between the government and eta
gonzalez said his government had agreed to resume talks only if the organization respected a 60-day truce offer it made jan. 28
the government broke off preliminary talks with eta in algiers after the group claimed responsibility for the dec. 11 car bombing of a zaragoza civil guard barracks in which 11 people were killed
since 1977, eta has kidnapped 63 people, most of them basque businessmen, to raise funds for its operations. news conference to wednesday; picks up 11th graf pvs bgng, `if anyone'</note>
the u.s. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent annual rate from october through december, the fastest pace in almost two years, the government reported thursday
the growth in the gross national product, the broadest measure of the economy's health, was revised up from an original estimate of 4.2 percent made a month ago
the reagan administration said the growth rate showed the economic recovery, now in its sixth year, a record for peacetime, was suffering no ill effects from the october stock market collapse. however, private economists said they were still concerned about the lopsided nature of the growth
the rapid expansion in the fourth quarter occured without a pickup in inflation. a price index tied to the gnp rose at an annual rate of 3.7 percent from october through december, little changed from a 3.4 percent increase in the third quarter
three-fourths of the growth last quarter came from a buildup of business inventories which was occurring at the same time that consumer spending was plunging 3.1 percent, the biggest spending drop in more than seven years
the last such sharp drop in consumer spending occurred in 1980 during the brief recession that year which helped doom president jimmy carter's re-election bid
many economists believe that growth will slow substantially in the first half of this presidential election year, but in what could be good news for republican chances to hold onto the white house, they are not forecasting an outright recession
some analysts said the revisions made in the new gnp report made them more confident that a recession can be avoided
as we move into 1988, there has to be a slowdown to work off excessive retail inventories, but it will be a pause and not a recession,'' said allen sinai, chief economixq
released, hinted at his press conference wednesday night that the figure would be a good one and he attacked democratic presidential candidates for misrepresenting his administration's economic achievements
if anyone listened for more than 15 minutes to their candidates, you would decide that we're burdened by inflation, high interest rates and unemployment, when at the moment none of those things are true,'' reagan said
analysts said they were encouraged by the new gnp report because it showed that consumer spending, while falling sharply, was not as weak as previously believed. the report also increased the estimate of business investment spending, another area of expected strength in the new year
the economy is better than most people think. consumers are not fizzling out,'' sinai said
on the basis of the revised gnp figures, sinai said he had boosted his estimate of growth in the current quarter to between 1 percent and 2 percent, up from an earlier prediction that growth could be as low as 0.5 percent in the first three months of this year
james cochran, an economist with texas commerce bancshares of houston, said that the new gnp report ``confirms that we will have positive growth in the first quarter. it won't be fantastic, but it will be positive.''
some economists had been so concerned that the huge buildup in inventories would force widespread factory layoffs, that they were predicting possibly one quarter of negative gnp growth. a traditional recession is defined as two consecutive quarters in which the gnp declines
the 4.5 percent increase in economic growth followed a gain of 4.3 percent in the third quarter and was the fastest advance since a 5.4 percent rise in the first quarter of 1986
the fourth-quarter gain boosted growth for the year to 3.9 percent, when measured from the end of 1986, up slightly from the 3.8 percent estimate made a month ago. growth when all four quarters of the year are averaged together showed a 2.9 percent increase in 1987, the same as 1986
the reagan administration is forecasting that growth this year will slow to a rate of 2.4 percent. many private economists believe even this scaled-down figure is too optimistic given the huge overhang of inventories that will slow production in the early part of the year
the administration believes the country will get half of its growth this year from an improving trade deficit as american manufacturers continue to benefit from the decline in the value of the dollar
that trend was evident in the fourth quarter as the country's trade deficit, after adjusting for inflation, shrank by $2 billion as exports shot up by 15.1 percent, outpacing a 9.7 percent rise in imports
the various changes added $42 billion to the total gnp in the fourth quarter, leaving it at an inflation-adjusted $3.88 trillion
here is the text of president eric arturo delvalle's nationally broadcast message ordering gen. manuel antonio noriega removed from his post as military chief, as translated from spanish by the associated press:
panama currently is experiencing one of the most difficult and dangerous moments of its history. it really is lamentable that after having achieved in a few years, with international help and support, success in the struggle for its sovereignty, and after having begun a transition toward a promised democracy and even more recently having started its stalled economy, today the country finds itself virtually at siege economically by external pressures and tensions, in its international prestige as a nation
what has been able to take us to such a terrible crossroads in such a short time?
certainly a dose of unawareness from many, exaggerated ambitions from some and a great lack of understanding from others have contributed decisively to placing us in such a severe as well as critical situation
i should confess with honor that in my unchangeable desire to achieve my goal i have been able to commit some mistakes, but it is even worse to be a victim as i have been of so many misunderstandings without allowing that they might change my way of acting, as i am doing with deep love for my country
i must consider with sadness that many of the successes that have been obtained have been vanishing in the past eight months
this has converted my concerns into fruitless yearnings
what is certain is that the mistaken positions, the unconsulted actions and the mistakes committed, now or in the past, have led to acts of extreme significance, such as those that represent the noticeable paralysis, the rhythm of social and economic development that we have experienced since the midway point of last year
the pressures and tensions of which we are an object and the serious accusations of the grand jury of florida against noriega, accusations which have been gathered and spread by the international press, have damaged the image and prestige of panama
these actions which u.s. officials have taken on the basis that the country is not moving toward a true democracy and the accusations against noriega, are starting to be reflected in an unfavorable international attitude toward the panamanian nation that is financial as well as diplomatic
that situation places the republic before a very serious risk in which the present and future well being of the panamanian people is found at risk
facing this enormous responsibility as a leader, several days ago i decided that i should suggest, and that's what i did, to gen. noriega that he voluntarily step aside from his high command until the charges that had been raised against him might be investigated, and that would reflect highly on his own good and the health and tranquility of the republic
i have not had evidence that the healthy purposes that motivated my suggestion in the sense expressed have had any impact whatsoever. i decided that it was prudent to wait some days so that he might have sufficient time to meditate on the seriousness of the situation to which he is exposing himself and to which he is submitting the country
for all that might be deduced that the accusations against gen. noriega have a political nature, the internal situation of panama cannot be ignored. each day it becomes more complex and dangerous and there will not be peace nor liberty nor progress in panama nor will be be able to perfect or consolidate our democratic system, unless we overcome the passions that have been unleashed and we clarify the deeds beyond all doubt
to find solutions to the serious crisis that affects institutional life and economic stability, it is indispensable that as soon as possible the country might return to the climate of peace and tranquility
the reasons that might take us to fiscal and economic imbalance and that might push thousands of panamanians to unemployment, misery and despair cannot persist
the causes for which the international credit agencies and the international banking community, which always have collaborated with us, might turn their backs to us, worsening our already weakened and precarious situation, cannot persist
the attitudes and conduct that might justify friendly nations to adopt positions that isolate our country and reduce the prestige of our nation cannot persist
we cannot persist in incubating our own disaster, whatever might be the motive, reason or justification that any entity, group or person might brandish, because nothing or no one comes above the nation.''
a mistrial was declared thursday after a jury deadlocked in the case of a former california highway patrol officer accused of murdering a motorist he had pulled over at an isolated freeway exit in 1986
it does not seem to me that any further deliberation is likely to produce a verdict,'' superior court judge richard huffman after seven days of deliberation in the case against 37-year-old craig peyer of poway
peyer was accused of strangling cara knott, a 20-year-old san diego state university student. the 13-year chp veteran was the second officer in the agency's 58-year history to be charged with killing a motorist while on duty
jury forewoman walnetta lenhardt said that after three ballots, jurors deadlocked 7-5 in favor of conviction
i have always thought he was innocent. it's in god's hands. it always will be,'' peyer's wife, karen, said outside court
steve casey, a spokesman for the district attorney's office, said no decision had been made on whether to retry the case against peyer
we're tough. we'll do it for cara. we're going to see it through for cara,'' said a tearful joyce knott, the victim's mother
peyer has been free on $1 million bail throughout the trial. first-degree murder carries a sentence of 25 years to life in prison
peyer was fired by the highway patrol in may after an internal investigation
the prosecution in the trial that began jan. 19 alleged that peyer, patrolling interstate 15, stopped knott because of a defective tail light and forced her to drive down a dark, isolated offramp
knott's white volkswagen was found abandoned in a cul-de-sac near the bottom of an exit, and her body was found at the bottom of a nearby 65-foot highway bridge
twenty-two women had testified during the trial that peyer pulled them over on i-15 and directed them down the same isolated ramp. state officials closed the ramp for safety reasons soon after knott's killing
prosecutors presented blood and fiber evidence that they said linked peyer to the victim, as well as two surprise witnesses who said they saw a chp unit pull over a light-colored volkswagen on i-15 the night knott was slain
the defense argued the blood and fiber evidence was flimsy and unreliable and accused the two witnesses of lying, noting both had waited a year before coming forward with their stories. with comment from governor's spokesman on effect of vote and cubs statement about installation of lights.</note>
the city council voted thursday to lift a ban on night games at the only major-league ballpark without lights, signaling a likely end to a 72-year-tradition of daytime-only baseball at wrigley field
the vote was 29-19 in favor of lights
the tribune co., owner of the chicago cubs, has threatened to move the team out of chicago if lights aren't allowed at the venerable, ivy-covered ballpark
a state law limiting noise at night effectively banned night games at wrigley. the law was suspended last year for post-season nighttime play, and similar action may be needed to allow regular-season night games, some officials said thursday
alderman bobby rush, chairman of the committee that held hearings on the city ordinance, said state legislators have agreed to follow the city in rolling back the ban
they may have to make some adjustments, but there won't be any snags,'' he said. ``the cubs will probably proceed with lights as soon as weather permits.''
jim bray, a spokesman for gov. james r. thompson, said the effect of the council vote was uncertain
there's always been a question whether the original legislation ever would have been able to prevent night games if the cubs wanted to and did install lights,'' bray said
the cubs said after the vote that the club would install a $5 million lighting system that should be ready in four to six months
the proposal approved by the council and endorsed by mayor eugene sawyer would allow eight night games this season and 18 each of the following years until 2002 at the ballpark
at the team's mesa, ariz., training camp, pitcher rick sutcliffe said, ``i think the night games will give us a chance to rest up during the day after coming off long road trips
a lot of times we don't get home from road trips till 2 or 3 in the morning, and only get about four hours of sleep before heading back out to the ballpark,'' he said
wrigley field, a neighborhood landmark since 1914, is bordered by small apartment houses where residents can sit on the roof and watch the action for free. many residents of ``wrigleyville'' are vehemently opposed to night games, anticipating rowdy crowds and parking problems
league owners voted earlier thursday to play the 1990 all-star game at wrigley field if the city lifts the ban on night games
by playing during the day only, club executives say, the team misses out on lucrative revenue from tv networks interested in airing evening baseball
if the cubs made the playoffs while the night-game ban was in force, the team probably would have to play elsewhere, they say, because playoff games are scheduled to accommodate network requests for prime-time exposure
the cubs finished last in the national league east last year
opponents say night games in wrigleyville would mean boisterous fans pouring out of bars in the wee hours, limited parking for residents returning from work, and littered lawns and streets
i have no objection to people having a good time, but they just don't respect the neighborhood,'' said dwight guyer, who can hear the roar of the crowd from his home a few blocks away. ``i don't like people urinating in my yard. i don't like to wake up to trash.''
the chicago tribune, also owned by the tribune co., entered the fray last week with a lively editorial that said aldermen opposed to lights at wrigley field were ``boneheads'' and ``political lightweights.''
state sen. william marovitz, a chicago democrat, said the state noise law could prevent regular-season night games at wrigley
if the noise from wrigley field violates the decibel limit, a resident might file a lawsuit,'' said marovitz, who represents wrigleyville and is against the lights
but rep. john cullerton, another chicago democrat, said city council approval clears the way for regular-season night games without further legislative action
if we did nothing, they could play night games,'' said cullerton, who also represents wrigleyville
a bomb in a taxicab exploded wednesday outside the building housing the greek embassy in west beirut, killing a street vendor and a passenger in the car, police said
the cab driver and three passers-by were wounded when the bomb, hidden in the trunk of the moving taxi, blew up
police said the bomb exploded at 2:40 p.m. in front of the sadat tower, a building that also houses offices of the embassies of finland and mexico
police said there was nobody at the greek embassy at the time of the blast. no arrests were made
the finnish and mexican missions have been closed since april 1986, when most foreigners left moslem west beirut after a wave of assassinations and kidnappings involving foreign nationals
the bomb turned the white mercedes taxi into a pile of twisted metal. no group claimed responsibility for the bombing
syrian troops, who were deployed in west beirut to restore security, blocked off the site for half an hour after the explosion
more than 100,000 people have been killed since lebanon's civil war began in april 1975. druse, shiite moslem and christian militias have done most of the fighting
a former firefighter accused of setting a $6.5 million string of fires reported the first blaze to police and helped authorities erect barricades at the second fire, a prosecutor said thursday
adrian julius howe, 23, will be charged friday with six counts of arson, said okanogan county prosecutor jack burchard. he was ordered held on $250,000 bail. each count carries up to life in prison and a $50,000 fine
howe, arrested wednesday, reported the first blaze dec. 6 at an elementary school, helped set up barricades at a dec. 14 fire, and was seen by police at three other blazes, burchard told superior court judge james r. thomas
the fires began in december, when omak north elementary school was hit twice within eight days. two churches in omak and a church parsonage there also were burned in a week's time earlier this month
howe lived in a trailer court across the street from the school in december, then moved to an apartment across from one of the churches before the february fires, burchard said
howe, who sheriff jim weed said had experience fighting wildfires, was arrested by investigators of a special 12-member arson task force and confessed to all six fires, burchard told thomas
burchard and weed said there was no apparent motive for the fires. investigators have no reason to believe howe, a high school dropout, had any animosity toward the elementary school he attended, burchard said
the investigation depleted the small rural county's coffers, prompting the county to declare an emergency and request state help. the washington house voted wednesday to appropriate $150,000 to help cover the investigation costs
a lifelong resident of omak, a town of 4,000, howe was employed at a lumber mill on the colville indian reservation. friends who knew him from several bars he frequented described howe as a loner who used to get into fights
i don't think that he had anything to do with it,'' said brian marbach, a friend of howe's for 19 years
howe, who spent time in the army, recently had been trying to reconcile with a girlfrend by whom he had a young daughter, marbach said
world production of sugar in 1987-88 has been revised upward to an estimated 101.9 million metric tons, a 1 percent increase from the previous forecast of 100.8 million tons made last october, the agriculture department said wednesday
the department's foreign agricultural service said the revision ``reflects changes in several key countries'' since the october estimate
regionally, the new figures showed increases in raw sugar production for north america, 10.92 million tons, compared with 10.71 million forecast in october; the european economic community, 13.85 million tons, compared with 13.43 million; and the soviet union, 9 million tons, compared with 8.3 million
despite the larger estimate, this season's global sugar production still is expected to trail the 102.8 million tons produced in 1986-87, the agency reported. of weapons, date of his eviction, comment from administrator of his current home. picks up 9th graf pvs, `several women ...'</note>
a elderly man with two rifles burst into a board meeting at a retirement home where he once lived and opened fire thursday, wounding four people and sending a fifth into heart failure, authorities said
the 79-year-old gunman fled the meeting room at the masonic home for the aged with one rifle tied around his neck with twine but surrendered moments later, said police spokesman dee anderson
the four people struck by gunfire suffered minor wounds, she said. however, willie joe wright, 67, who suffered the heart attack, was in critical condition at arlington memorial hospital, said spokeswoman tenya woods
apparently, they had a board meeting and one former resident, who was apparently disgruntled, walked into the board room and started shooting'' at the 15 to 16 people there, anderson said
the assailant, whose identity was not released, had lived at the home for about three years before being evicted in september for breaking rules, anderson said. he knew when the monthly board meeting was to be held, she said
when officers confronted the man in a kitchen in the building, he calmly surrendered and gave them his rifle. both weapons were .22-caliber semiautomatic rifles, anderson said
he did not give any information to police,'' anderson said
officials at the man's current residence, the arlington villa retirement home, said they were shocked to hear of the shooting. ``he is a good resident, very congenial and sociable,'' said administrator gennie pace
officials of the masonic home refused to comment on the 11 a.m. shooting and put the buildings and grounds of the home off limits to visitors
several women gathered outside the home after hearing of the shooting to make sure their relatives, residents of the home, were safe. one woman, who declined to be identified, said her mother had lived there for the past 13 years and called it ``a wonderful place.''
of the shooting victims, eldon brooks, 54, was in fair condition with a gunshot wound to the left thigh, ms. woods said, while frank smith, 77, was in good condition with a gunshot wound in his back
john thompson, 49, was in fair condition with a gunshot wound to his right arm and was later transferred to harris methodist hospital in fort worth
dorothy heath, 67, received a gunshot wound to her thigh and complained of chest pains. she was in fair condition
an employee at the retirement home who would not give her name identified ms. heath as the home's administrator
the state department on wednesday suggested that americans planning trips to rio de janeiro consider postponing their travel because of torrential rains and flooding that have killed 300 people and left thousands homeless
no formal travel advisory was announced, but ruth van heuven, a department spokeswoman, said people who called to check on conditions in the brazilian resort city were told they ``may wish to defer their trip until the local situation improves.''
the department said rains were expected to continue indefinitely, city services were strained, some areas were without electricity and water and several tourist areas were inaccessible
seven people were convicted wednesday on federal racketeering charges for taking part in the violent activities of a murderous gang known as the westies, which terrorized manhattan's hell's kitchen neighborhood for 20 years
an eighth defendant was acquitted of all charges as the five-month trial ended
in addition to the racketeering convictions, some of the defendants, including reputed westies boss james ``jimmy'' coonan, were found guilty of crimes ranging from attempted murder and loansharking to drug dealing and tax evasion
but the key verdict was the jury's decision that the westies did exist, that it constituted a racketeering enterprise and that the convicted defendants had participated in its activities to further the gang's criminal goals
defense lawyers had contended that there was no such organization as the westies. even former gang members testifying for the prosecution said the name ``westies'' was created by the police and the news media to describe irish-american hoodlums on manhattan's west side
prosecutors mary lee warren and david brodsky had contended the six men and two women on trial were the violent core of the westies, which they said seized control of the neighborhood once known as hell's kitchen and maintained their rule ``with horrible and ghoulish acts of murder.''
witnesses testified that in at least three murders, the victim's body was cut up and disposed of in what ms. warren called ``the nightmarish signature crime of the westies.''
there was also testimony by several witnesses that the westies had forged an alliance with the gambino organized crime family, said to be the largest and most powerful mafia group in the country
the key prosecution witness, former no. 2 westie francis ``mickey'' featherstone, said the gang had even shot a union leader as a favor to reputed gambino boss john gotti
but the defense attacked the credibility of featherstone, an admitted three-time killer, and other informants who testified for the government in return for leniency
featherstone, who said he had been coonan's ``right-hand man,'' admitted that he had lied under oath in other cases, had been in and out of mental institutions, suffered delusions and was a former abuser of alcohol and drugs
the racketeering charges alleged eight murders, four murder conspiracies and three attempted murders. to be convicted of racketeering, each defendant had to be found to have committed at least two of the 28 racketeering acts cited
the verdict came on the eighth day of jury deliberations
coonan, 41, was found guilty of attempted murder, murder conspiracy, loansharking, extortion and income tax evasion among other crimes
his wife, edna, 44, was convicted of loansharking and tax charges
in addition, the jury found coonan participated in most of the racketeering acts charged against him, including seven murders
a trial on any single act in this indictment would have resulted in an acquittal,'' said coonan's lawyer, gerald shargel. ``it's just a matter of the government, piling it all together. that's the nightmare of rico (the racketeer influenced corrupt organizations act).''
as the courtroom deputy, bernard wasserman, read out the verdict against william ``indian'' bokun, his father swore audibly
don't tell me to shush!'' john bokun angrily told a marshal. ``that's my son there.''
the younger bokun, 30, of manhattan, who was convicted of drug dealing as well as racketeering, tried to comfort his weeping, cursing father
don't worry pop, i'm all right,'' bokun shouted across the courtroom before being led back to jail
only one defendant, john halo, was acquitted on all charges
in addition to the coonans, both of hazlet, n.j. and bokun, the others convicted of racketeering and racketeering conspiracy were: james ``jimmy mack'' mcelroy, 42; richard ``muggsy'' ritter, 50; thomas collins, 53, and his wife florence, 52, all of manhattan
knapp scheduled sentencing for april 18. all defendants face up to 20 years apiece on both racketeering and racketeering conspiracy
a publishing company's plan to offer a new series of magazines just for doctors' waiting rooms with the requirement that the physicians limit purchases of other magazines has rival publishers furious
the constitution says congress shall make no law abridging freedom of speech,'' said george green, a vice president and group publisher of new york-based hearst corp. ``i guess the man from tennessee has his own agenda.''
whittle communications expects to put its six quarterly magazines in the waiting rooms of pediatricians, gynecologists and family practitioners this fall, said patti carr, the company's corporate marketing associate
whittle is targeting 15,000 doctors' offices its first year, and about half already have signed up, said spokeswoman sara fortune. eventually, whittle hopes to capture 40 percent of doctors' offices in the top 125 markets in the country, she said
under the subscription agreement, doctors cannot have more than two non-whittle publications in the waiting rooms, she said
in return, doctors get magazines at a reduced price, free monthly replacement of worn magazines and an agreement that there will be no ads for unhealthy products such as alcohol and cigarettes, said ms. fortune
the six magazines, collectively called ``the whittle family system,'' will cover beauty and health, living, family life, fiction, gossip, entertainment and sports
each one is designed to be read in 20 or 30 minutes, the time you usually spend waiting for your doctor,'' said ms. fortune
ms. carr predicted it would be ``the largest launch in the history of magazines.'' first-year revenues are projected at $37 million, she said
most publishers find this whole method unacceptable and are not going to sit idly by and let it happen,'' said michael luftman, a spokesman for time inc. in new york
whittle publishes special-interest magazines for such groups as students, restaurant workers and medical personnel
a hepatitis epidemic in shanghai has killed seven people, but the number of new cases has dropped considerably, the pro-beijing hong kong newspaper ta kung pao reported wednesday
it quoted wang daomin, director of the shanghai public health bureau, as saying health officials verified seven deaths. previous reports did not mention deaths
the viral disease, commonly spread in food and water, causes inflammation of the liver, nausea, vomiting and fever
wang also was quoted as saying the number of new cases of hepatitis a had dropped 80 percent from the height of the epidemic
shanghai officials earlier put the number sickened in the 2-month-old outbreak at 16,000. western doctors there said the number could be as high as 40,000. the epidemic was blamed on contaminated clams harvested from polluted coastal waters
china's official english-language newspaper china daily said beijing health authorities launched a city-wide sanitation inspection
in canton, capital of southern guangdong province, health officials warned people to refrain from shaking hands, to wash their hands when visiting others and to avoid eating river snails
weather experts failed to forecast britain's worst weather disaster in nearly 300 years because they stuck too rigidly to computer forecasts, an official report said wednesday
the oct. 16 storm killed 17 people and changed britain's landscape forever as winds gusting up to 120 mph toppled an estimated 15 million trees
homes were wrecked, cars smashed and many parts of britain suffered the worst power failures since the world war ii blitz. insurance claims totaled $1.46 billion
the report to defense secretary george younger came from the state-run meteorological office, under the defense department, and from an independent panel which studied that report and made its own inquiries and recommendations
it said weather experts failed to predict the storm's severity because they followed computer projections ``too closely'' and ``too rigidly'' and did not take into account other factors
the report recommended stepping up the warning system when bad weather is on the way and giving forecasters the scientific background needed to recognize poor computer predictions
compared with the french forecasters, the training which ours receive is shorter (and therefore cheaper) and lays less emphasis on meteorological theory,'' the report said
the defense secretary announced he had accepted the recommendations
the meteorological office apparently had no formal system to allow the senior forecaster to consult more widely when faced with uncertain or severe weather, the report said
it said television forecasts ``played down'' the wind even more than the meteorological office, but in view of the briefing tv weather experts received, they were not to blame
while the report said forecasters shouldn't rely totally on computers, it said the meteorological office must have the most powerful computer available. it noted a new model will be installed in june
the worst storm to hit britain was in 1703 when 8,000 people were killed
district of columbia police chief maurice turner said wednesday he intends to arm up to 1,000 civilian volunteers as part of an effort to fight a crime spree in the nation's capital
volunteer reserve officers, who currently lecture neighborhood groups on crime control and help city residents burglar-proof their homes, will get guns and full police powers, turner said in a statement issued by the police department
they'll serve in support positions augmenting the city's 3,880-member police force, accompany officers on regular patrols, and have the power to make arrests, he said
twenty-one members of the 175-member reserve force were selected for an extensive training program similar to training given full-time officers. turner said ultimately he hopes to expand the reserve corps to 1,000 officers
the trained reserve officers will carry a gun while on duty, but will be required to turn it in the end of their shifts, said turner, who originally disclosed his plan in an interview with the washington times
the chief's announcement came amid a surge in crime, particularly drug-related violence. fifty-two people have been murdered in washington so far this year, compared with 33 at this time last year. police say nearly three-quarters of the murders are drug related
turner said earlier this week that about 100 officers working at desk jobs will return to patrol work after civilians are found to fill their positions. last week, turner said he was replacing officers' six-shot service revolvers with 9mm semiautomatic pistols in an effort to counter the increasingly sophisticated weapons wielded by drug dealers
mayor marion barry has said there are enough officers, but police union officials said 500 more full-time officers are needed
turner did not say when the new program would go into effect, or where the reserves would be deployed. with comment from attorney general's office; adds one graf with suspect attempting suicide, in good condition.</note>
a grand jury should require tawana brawley and her family to cooperate with authorities investigating the teen-ager's alleged kidnapping and sexual assault by six white men, gov. mario cuomo said wednesday
the continued refusal of the girl's lawyers to allow her to discuss the case with investigators is fostering ``a disrespect for the process of law,'' the governor said at a news conference
miss brawley was found wrapped in a plastic garbage bag and covered with feces, with ``kkk'' and ``nigger'' scrawled on her body, after being missing for four days last november. she said she was assaulted by six white men, one of whom flashed a police badge
a grand jury will convene monday in poughkeepsie to investigate the case
cuomo said he'll ask state attorney general robert abrams, the special prosecutor in the case, to ask the grand jury to compel miss brawley and her family to cooperate
the way the investigation is not proceeding now _ and it's not proceeding as it should _ is bad for tawana, is bad for the state, is bad for the system of justice. and i want to change it,'' cuomo said
the lawyers for miss brawley and her family, c. vernon mason and alton maddox jr., did not return calls to their new york city offices
nancy connell, a spokeswoman for abrams, said that ``we're fully in agreement with the governor's statement.'' but she would not say what abrams will recommend to the grand jury
mason and maddox have advised miss brawley not to cooperate, have called for abrams to be removed from the case and for cuomo to create a permanent special state prosecutor for racial cases
the naacp lawyer who initially represented miss brawley before being replaced by mason and maddox said the two lawyers were using the girl as a pawn to achieve political aims
the politicizing of the case in the manner it has been allows for a lot of speculation and detracts from the genuine sympathy and outrage this case should have,'' attorney george hairston told the albany times union
the rev. al sharpton, a pentecostal minister from brooklyn who has also been advising the brawley family, said that because abrams maintains a residence in dutchess county he has a ``relationship'' with sheriff frederick scoralick. sharpton said scoralick was a ``suspect'' in the case
