contra rebels damaged a microwave repeater tower in northern nicaragua overnight, cutting off telecommunications with northern central america and mexico, the defense ministry said wednesday
the brief defense statement said the tower was at mesa de las lagunas, outside the provincial capital of esteli, 90 miles north of the capital of managua. it did not say how the rebels damaged the tower or give other details
in guatemala city, bosco matamoros, a spokesman for the u.s.-backed rebels, said the contras blew up the tower at 1 a.m. wednesday
nicaragua is isolated,'' he said. the contras, he said, want to hinder communications between the country and the rest of central america
nicaragua could communicate by microwave with panama and costa rica but not with honduras, el salvador, guatemala and mexico. satellite communications were not affected
the rebels blew up a microwave repeater tower last october at laguna de santa clara, east of esteli, and destroyed another one in november at las cuchillas hill in chontales province, 90 miles east of managua. that sabotage also caused widespread outages
the rebels have been fighting for more than six years to oust the leftist sandinista government in nicaragua. the sandinistas came to power in july 1979 at the end of a revolutionary war that ended 42 years of rule by the rightist, pro-american somoza dynasty
an airline ticket agent suspicious about a man carrying two big suitcases for a three-hour visit to michigan tipped off police wednesday to what turned out to be an $11 million cocaine bust, authorities said
the man, who was arrested after his plane's arrival here, had bought a round-trip ticket in los angeles from the united airlines agent, said narcotics detective lt. gene wriggelsworth
he paid cash for his tickets,'' wriggelsworth said. ``he fit the drug smuggling profile.''
the detective said 14 kilos, or about 30 pounds of cocaine, were confiscated, ``the biggest we've ever had.''
a drug-sniffing dog was ready when the flight landed at capital city airport for the scheduled three-hour visit and singled out two large suitcases, wriggelsworth said
police then watched as the man claimed the suitcases and met two people. all three were arrested, and a car and $4,000 in cash were confiscated with the cocaine
the three were being held in the clinton county jail on drug-possession charges. their names were not released
the name of the united agent was not immediately available
a jury on wednesday acquitted a police officer of manslaughter in the shooting death of an unarmed black teen-ager last year, a case that sparked accusations of racism in the montreal police department
the nov. 11 shooting of 19-year-old anthony griffin had prompted three inquiries _ by the quebec human rights commission, the quebec police commission and the 4,500-member montreal police force
a black community leader, ronald rock, said wednesday that blacks will march in the streets following the acquittal of constable allan gosset, 38, a 16-year veteran of the department
gosset, who said the shooting was accidental, rolled his eyes, sighed and slumped in his chair when the all-white jury of seven men and five women handed down the verdict after deliberating 16{ hours. the trial lasted four days
griffin's mother, gloria augustus, wept as she left the courtroom, and exclaimed: ``you want us to trust the justice system? what kind of a justice system do we have?''
rock, executive director of the black community council of quebec, said, ``i'm very disappointed. this has set relations with the montreal police back 15 years. we're going to have to hit the streets again.''
gosset said he will have to await police chief roland bourget's decision on whether he will return to work
i think i should be reinstated,'' he said
griffin was brought to a police station in a patrol car by gosset and his partner last november, according to testimony. he bolted in the parking lot but obeyed gosset's shouted order to stop
griffin turned around and gosset shot him once in the forehead with his .38-caliber service revolver, testimony showed
gosset said griffin turned to face him, went into a crouch and began weaving from side to side. gosset said he feared griffin planned to confront him so he drew his gun to intimidate him and it went off, although he did not recall cocking it
defense lawyer serge menard told the jury it was obvious gosset's actions were not motivated by racism, because griffin was being detained on the basis of an arrest warrant
crown prosecutor rene de la sablonniere said gosset was irresponsible and should not have pulled his gun because his life was not in danger
on wednesday, griffin's mother told reporters she was ``shocked and saddened'' by the verdict and promised to pursue the case. lawyers for the family said they filed a wrongful-death lawsuit for $850,000 tuesday against gosset, the police department and montreal's regional government
most of canada's estimated 400,000 blacks are west indian immigrants. the largest black communities are in toronto and montreal. further comment from student protest leader, background on dakin house, deleting some detail to tighten. no pickup.</note>
leaders of 100 minority students occupying a hampshire college building handed the school's president a list of demands wednesday and settled in for what they predicted would be a long siege
we're a little disappointed. they wouldn't even talk to us,'' said dean of students trey williams after a morning meeting with the protesters was cut short
we felt that they needed to take time to look at the demands,'' responded anita fearman, a student from los angeles and a protest leader. another meeting was scheduled for thursday
some 50 black, hispanic, asian, indian and other students, or nearly half the minority student population at the 1,100-student private liberal arts college, took over dakin house on tuesday to protest what they described as the administration's indifference to their longstanding complaints
another 50 minority students from nearby smith, amherst, and mount holyoke colleges and the university of massachusetts joined the protesters wednesday, said ms. fearman. umass was the site of a similar protest that ended last week
about 300 sympathizers, most of them white, accompanied the negotiators to the meeting with administrators wednesday in a library building, where the demands were given to president adele simmons
the crowd marched through classroom and administration buildings on the way, chanting, ``racism has got to go.''
a protest leader, penny predmas, predicted: ``this is going to take a while.''
among the dozen demands of the group, students of underrepresented cultures, were calls for money for third world speakers and publications, the hiring of a racial harassment officer and the drafting of a racial harassment policy
williams, who is black, said school officials were worried that students might be seeking attention rather than results by delaying negotiations
usually building takeovers are the last resort,'' he said. ``i don't know why the students feel they have no other recourse.''
the takeover followed the six-day occupation of a building at nearby umass. that occupation by 125 students ended feb. 17 with an agreement to increase minority recruitment at the 25,000-student campus
the problems (at hampshire) are the same, although the sizes of the minority communities are different,'' said ms. fearman. ``there's a general feeling here that we've been more or less pushed under the rug.''
dakin house contains living quarters for two staff members, an office and meeting space used by minority students. the staff members are being allowed to use their living quarters during the occupation
a free-lance writer from oregon paddled his teakwood boat into bangkok wednesday, the 55th day of his solo exploration of the effect of rivers on thailand's history and culture
two dozen thais greeted an exhausted and tanned steve van beek, offering him food and soda as he pulled into a pier near the foot of the memorial bridge
van beek, 43, of portland, ore., said he expected to complete his nearly 600-mile journey on saturday, when he is scheduled to reach the gulf of thailand at samut prakarn province just southeast of bangkok
van beek paddled his 11{-foot-long boat by day, seeking shelter with local residents at night and listening to their stories of the river and its effect on their lives. he sampled what he called a ``whole new experience'' of food, including raw fish with rice, pig's blood and boiled eel
he said the beauty of the countryside and the hospitality of the thai people have impressed him
how many other places could you walk up to someone and say, `i'm paddling a boat. i need something to eat, a place to stay, something to eat in the morning,''' he said. ``these people, they just opened up their entire houses.''
water, he said, ``permeates every aspect of life in thailand. it is in rites of passage, festivals. fish and rice are both grown in water, and they are the principal sources of food here.''
i lived on the edge of the river for 11 years,'' he added. ``i always wondered where it came from, so i decided to go find out.''
van beek hired a village builder to fashion the flat-bottomed boat
he started his trip in meaja, about 60 miles north of the provincial capital of chiang mai. he followed the ping river south through five provinces, after which it joined the chao phraya river
van beek spent three years in a village in nepal as a peace corps volunteer before arriving in thailand in 1969. he worked on english-language newspapers and magazines before 1977, when he became a free-lance writer and film maker specializing in thailand's art, history and culture
a man was convicted of manslaughter wednesday in the snakebite-death of a girl around whose shoulder he had draped a rattlesnake
district judge j. philip eves announced the verdict against darrell wessendorf in the non-jury trial
wessendorf, 24, had been charged with second-degree murder in the death last year of 21-month-old stevie luren kirkwood of la verkin. he had pleaded innocent by reason of insanity
the judge said that he found wessendorf guilty of the lesser charge because the defendant hadn't been aware of the possible results of his actions
wessendord, who was renting an upstairs apartment from the child's mother, jeri ann kirkwood, at the time, testified that he found the 5-foot rattlesnake on a road and was trying to show the girl that that it would not hurt her
he said he had partially wrapped the snake around the child's shoulder when mrs. kirkwood entered the room and screamed, causing him to flinch and the snake to bite the child
sentencing was set for april 11. manslaughter carries a one- to 15-year sentence. second-degree murder would have brought five years to life
defense attorney j. macarthur wright had claimed that only 0.2 percent of those bitten by rattlesnakes die and called on the judge to ``make a distinction here on what constitutes a grave risk of death.''
people bitten by rattlesnakes are often not even treated,'' he said
prosecutor o. brent rowe argued that wessendorf's actions were intentional and malicious
earlier wednesday, a psychologists, george dunford, said that wessendorf suffered from mild schizophrenia and that he did not believe the defendant understood he was endangering the child
an expert on snakes, james glenn, testified for the defense that the snake is one of the least aggressive types of rattlers and that the hospital did not give the girl enough anti-venom
col. ali saibou, military ruler of niger, has granted what amounts to a pardon for people who attempted two coups against his predecessor
the pardon took the form of a general amnesty for those convicted of crimes against state security, according to broadcasts wednesday by the west african country's official radio
such an amnesty would free officers and civilians involved in attempted the coups against maj. gen. seyni kountche, who died in a paris hospital nov. 10 of what was believed to be a brain tumor. the radio said the amnesty bars those released from holding government jobs except after official review
excluded from the pardon was amadou oumarou, a wealthy businessman and former close adviser of kountche, who failed in a third coup attempt oct. 6, 1983. he was said to be living in belgium
most of the plotters and other political prisoners are held in the arid northeastern part of the country or exiled to their villages, and some fled the country. the radio did not say how many people were involved
in january, saibou granted a partial amnesty to military personnel convicted of lesser crimes, except for those who violated ``morality and honor,'' an apparent reference to convicted coup plotters. the january decision also commuted to life imprisonment all death sentences announced before 1988
hamani diori, niger's first president after independence from france in 1960, was given his freedom from house arrest early in 1987. kountche overthrew diori, now in his 80s, in 1974
niger, part of the drought-stricken sahel region, is one of the world's poorest countries with a population of 6 million and a per capita annual income of about $250. the government said in january it needed 274,000 tons of grain to avoid food shortages for 1.4 million people
health officials wednesday battled an outbreak of disease after rains, floods and mudslides killed at least 277 people in rio de janeiro state
the rio state health secretariat is promoting a vaccination campaign against tetanus, hepatitis, typhoid fever and leptosipirosis caused by rats and contaminated water
the most serious outbreak was of leptospirosis, an infection caused by rat urine and droppings in water. the often fatal disease produces high fever, vomiting, diarrhrea and sometimes paralysis of the kidneys
the health secretariat said wednesday that 223 cases of leptospirosis had been registered, with 15 deaths. most victims were from the low-lying slums north of rio hit hardest by the flooding, which began feb. 2
health workers urged people to boil drinking water and use chlorine to treat water stored in cisterns. rio residents were urged not to walk barefoot through flood water, because the disease can be contracted through tiny cuts and breaks in the skin
foreign countries have donated or pledged about $2 million in money, food, medicine and equipment. japan promised to send vaccine. west germany planned to donate 1 million disposable syringes and needles and $300,000, civil defense officials said
rescue workers kept digging for bodies in mud and rubble left by a violent downpour that began friday and lasted three days. at least 81 rio residents were killed by floods and mudslides in the past three weeks
firemen and civil defense workers recovered a 12th body from the ruins of a hillside clinic for the elderly that collapsed under a mudslide. officials say 15 more bodies could still be under the tons of mud and concrete
president jose sarney visited the worst hit regions tuesday and allocated $2 million for repairs. but rio mayor roberto saturnino braga said the city would need at least $100 million
in washington, the state department on wednesday suggested that americans planning trips to rio consider postponing travel there, though no formal travel advisory was announced
a mixture of cleaning chemicals sent fumes through a school wednesday, sickening at least 149 people, most of them students, authorities said
a 12-year-old girl with a history of respiratory ailments was admitted to holy family hospital in des plaines for observation, said spokesman frank buccitelli. the other victims were treated at hospitals and released
most of those affected by the fumes at thomas junior high school complained of dizziness, nausea and shortness of breath
maintenance men were cleaning a drain,'' said police cmdr. jay plaisted. ``they used a degreaser and a drain opener, and the two together gave off a noxious odor
they opened a window to try to air out the fumes, but the mixture had already moved through the pipes into other rooms in the school,'' plaisted said
before noon, state environmental officials declared the school safe and classes resumed for most of the 700 students, said assistant principal al swanson
two women handcuffed together in a practical joke had to search the city for the prankster when police couldn't unlock the cuffs
ann bishop, 53, and her cuffmate, stephanie henson, 30, showed up at the public safety building close to midnight monday, seeking release from the cuffs
the women said they had gone to the spokane international airport with about 10 other family members and friends dressed in costumes ranging from maids to punks to meet ms. henson's brother, jimmy skog, arriving from austin, texas
skog ``just grabbed us and put them (the handcuffs) on before we knew what was happening,'' ms. bishop said
after police determined they were unable to unlock the cuffs, the women hit the streets to find skog, she said
we found him down at perkins (restaurant) having some coffee and talked him into setting us free,'' ms. bishop said. ``now we are going to have to think of something really good for him. we'll get him back.''
britain's government and opposition leaders condemned south africa's crackdown on major black organizations wednesday and feared the move would bring the ``frustration and despair'' that breed violence
britain, the staunchest opponent of sanctions against south africa, faced renewed demands from the opposition labor party and the anti-apartheid movement organization that prime minister margaret thatcher approve tough embargoes against south africa
neil kinnock, labor party leader, said the thatcher government ``bears a heavy responsibility,'' for the south african government ban on political activity by 18 major black movements opposed to apartheid, including the united democratic front
because it has been so weak against apartheid, we now have even more vicious jackboot rule,'' kinnock said
foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe said he was ``shocked and saddened'' by the crackdown
we do not see how the suppression of non-violent political activity can possibly contribute to a peaceful solution to south africa's problems,'' howe said in a statement, describing the ban as ``oppressive.''
we are particularly concerned that the black opposition in south africa should not lose hope of peaceful fundamental change. frustration and despair breed violence,'' howe added
sir shridath ramphal, secretary-general of the commonwealth, called on the international community, particularly western countries opposed to sanctions, to show south africa ``in every possible way ... that this repression is as intolerable as apartheid.''
mrs. thatcher regularly has been isolated at summits of the commonwealth, the 48-nation association of britain and its former colonies, for her refusal to impose tough embargoes against south africa, a major trading partner
the anti-apartheid movement planned demonstrations at the south african embassy and said it would join other groups in an ``international demonstration.''
anti-apartheid movement president, anglican archbishop trevor huddleston, said south africa ``is once again prohibiting non-violent resistance to apartheid and has slammed the door on any prospect of genuine negotiation.''
britain and south africa's other major trading partners must act decisively,'' huddleston added, saying he would appeal again to mrs. thatcher to change her stance on sanctions
mrs. thatcher argues that harsh sanctions against south africa will harden white resistance to change, harm blacks most, and be evaded by third party countries which are not now big trading partners
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
tens of thousands of health workers marched in scottish cities wednesday as part of a one-day walkout by 60,000 workers at hospitals nationwide, police and union officials said
the scottish trade unions congress called the strike to protest a government plan to force state-run hospitals to compete competitively with private bidders for auxiliary services
about 15,000 workers marched in glasgow and 10,000 in edinburgh, police said. they estimated about 60,000 people took part in the walkout
a union spokesman said rallies were also held in dundee, aberdeen, inverness, lochgilphead and dumfries
union officials said all hospitals remained equipped to give emergency services, but government officials alleged that even those services were not being provided in some areas
michael forsyth, the british lawmaker responsible for health care in scotland, said in a radio interview with the british broadcasting corp. that he was ``disgusted'' at the lack of care available
he said he would talk with the strikers when ``they stop organizing attacks on the sick and stop organizing disruption in our hospitals.''
the situation caused an angry clash between opposition and government lawmakers in the house of commons in london
conservatives shouted ``disgraceful!' in response to remarks by the opposition party's spokesman for scotland, donald dewar, that the protest was justified
scottish secretary malcolm rifkind said the strike ``has led to operations being canceled in their hundreds, and it will undoubtedly add to waiting lists over the weeks and months to come.''
health workers have staged regional walkouts recently, but tuesday's action was the first nationwide protest
forsyth said the government would not changes its plans, saying the strike pointlessly damaged the national health service, which provides free health care to britons
the scottish action follows the feb. 3 walkout by nurses in london to demand higher pay and more government funding of the health service. automakers and teachers also staged separate strikes this month
u.s. and mexican officials pledged to exchange more tariff and investment information during talks that reviewed a trade agreement last year, the newspaper el nacional announced wednesday
but the two sides reached no new concrete agreements during talks monday and tuesday, officials said
we held informal discussions, nothing more,'' said a u.s. official close to the talks, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``they never were intended to be negotiations.''
el nacional, citing attending mexican officials, said the two sides ``agreed to establish a greater flow of more precise and opportune information in tariff and foreign investment matters.''
the two nations trade about $30 billion worth of goods and services
the u.s. delegation, led by deputy trade representative peter murphy, met with its mexican counterpart, headed by foreign trade undersecretary luis bravo aguilera, at the resort of cocoyoc, south of mexico city
under the nov. 6 pact, mexican and u.s. officials will meet periodically to review progress made in foreign investment, services, patents and copyrights, textiles, steel, electronics, agricultural products and information exchanges
the u.s. trade representative and mexican commerce department reached separate agreements on steel, shoes, beer and textiles late last year
the textile accord, signed by presidents reagan and miguel de la madrid at their feb. 13 summit meeting in mazatlan, permits mexico to increase such exports to the united states by about 6 percent each year. in turn, mexico is opening its domestic market to many finished u.s. textile products for the first time
on other issues, the two sides remain far apart. the united states has pressed for mexico to liberalize its foreign investment law, generally restricted to 49 percent of ownership in mexican enterprises
mexico has resisted tampering with the law, but it did set up task force to look at the issue
another point of friction is mexico's law on patents and copyrights, which u.s. officials consider too weak to permit american manufacturers _ particularly in pharmaceuticals _ to export much to mexico
the united states, mexico's largest trading partner, takes in a third of mexico's exports and provides about the same percentage of its imports. mexico ranks fourth as a trading partner with its northern neighbor, after canada, japan and west germany
the son of former president gamal abdel nasser of egypt will return to egypt to stand trial, a lawyer was quoted as saying thursday
president hosni mubarak said terrorism allegations against khaled abdel nasser will not tarnish the image of the late president
the daily al ahram newspaper quoted ahmed el-khawaga, head of the egyptian bar association, as saying the younger nasser, 38, would return to cairo as soon as the trial starts. the report appeared in the newspaper's early thursday edition
el-khawaga made his comments after returning from meetings with khaled nasser in belgrade, yugoslavia, where the younger nasser and his family live
no date has been set for the trial
khaled nasser and 19 men were charged last thursday in connection with four shootings between 1984 and 1987 that killed two israelis and wounded six others and two americans
he and 10 other defendants face a death sentence. eight defendants face a maximum life imprisonment
el-khawaga was not at his office and there was no answer at his home when the associated press tried to obtain further information about his four reported meetings with the younger nasser
in his first public comment on the indictment, mubarak said khaled nasser's alleged involvement in the attacks ``will not affect the name and history of leader gamal abdel nasser, whom egypt respects and loves and whom the whole world, including the arab world and our african continent, also loves.''
mubarak spoke at a closed meeting with senior officers of egypt's 2nd and 3rd armies, both stationed in the suez canal zone. his remarks at the canal city of ismailiya were distributed wednesday by the state-owned middle east news agency
egypt has said it is attempting to have khaled nasser extradited to stand trial
another defendant is gamal shawky abdel nasser, a nephew of the late president. he is also at large, but he faces lesser charges
nasser, who died in 1970, became president of republican egypt in 1956, four years after leading a bloodless military coup that overthrew the monarchy
a champion of arab unity and an inspiration to numerous african and arab liberation movements, he still is revered in much of the arab world and in many african countries
a worldwide nuclear warning system was tested without a hitch wednesday after an earlier one sparked unfounded fears of a second serious nuclear accident in the soviet union
during the test, attended by reporters, a nuclear plant in west germany transmitted routine meteorological data to the vienna-based international atomic energy agency
sixteen countries taking part in the test confirmed within 30 minutes that they received the information. agency officials hailed the test as a success of the sophisticated new warning system
the system has become extremely important after the cherbobyl nuclear accident, said morris rosen, nuclear safety director for the agency
a test of the warning system earlier this month was misinterpreted, prompting momentary fear worldwide of a nuclear accident in the soviet union
the warning system, called the global telecommunication system, can be picked up at 160 points throughout the world, mostly national meteorologcal centers. it receives information from nuclear reactors worldwide and is expected to become fully operational this summer
the april 26, 1986, accident at the nuclear reactor at chernobyl, about 80 miles north of kiev, was the world's worst nuclear reactor accident. it killed 31 people, hospitalized hundreds and sent a cloud of radiation around the world
a 16-month-old-girl was in extremely critical condition wednesday after being bitten by a swarm of ants in her back yard, a hospital spokeswoman said
tiffany cheatham had stopped breathing after the attack but was revived by rescuers who arrived at her home tuesday in navarre, 20 miles from here, said james chalmers, an emergency medical technician
a witness said a dog had knocked the girl into an ant bed, according to chief don van derryt of the holley-navarre fire and rescue association
there were ants all around all of us,'' said janet streaker, a neighbor who tried to help the child's mother, lynn cheatham, remove the insects. ``the mother is full of ant bites herself.''
she said ms. cheatham took off the child's clothing and put her in the bathtub to try to wash off the ants, which were entangled in the girl's hair
there were lots of them,'' she said. ``there are still ants in the bathroom.''
ann papadelias, a sacred heart hospital spokeswoman, said that she suspected the girl was attacked by fire ants, known for painful and sometimes deadly stings, but that she was unable to confirm that with doctors
a secret presidential report on the sex-for-secrets spy scandal at the u.s. embassy in moscow says the american ambassador, his staff, and state department officials in washington must share the blame along with the marines
the report describes a ``seedy, disgraceful'' embassy marked by confused policies, lax supervision and ``gross neglect'' of counterintelligence efforts
president reagan ordered the study last spring after sensational reports that marines sold secrets for sex and allowed soviet agents into the building. the state department has refused to release the report to the public
people who receive transfusions face a one in 40,000 chance of receiving aids-tainted blood despite screening intended to keep the blood supply clean, according to a federal study published today
the researchers emphasize that despite this ``remote but real risk,'' people who need transfusions should not be deterred from receiving them
the blood supply is relatively safe, dramatically safer than it was before we had any screening,'' said the chief author of the report, dr. john w. ward of the u.s. centers for disease control in atlanta
the u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating medium-range nuclear missiles in europe will cost hundreds of millions of dollars to verify and an additional investment of billions more for non-nuclear weapons, the nation's top civilian and military defense officials warn
the pentagon is seeking $198 million this year and another $148 million in fiscal 1989 to ensure verification against soviet cheating, according to defense secretary frank c. carlucci
that money will go for a variety of costs, including the on-site inspections which are a key feature of the strictest verification standards in the history of nuclear arms control, carlucci told the house armed services committee on wednesday
if it didn't hurt so much, you might be able to step back and appreciate what critics are citing as a monumental example of man's folly _ the tax system
but for most people it probably does hurt too much to look, since they are involved deeply, intricately, confusingly, often desperately and frequently bizarrely
consider: it is entirely possible, says professor robert doyle, for a taxpayer to be actively rather than passively involved in a real estate matter that, by official definition, is a passive activity
a few days ago the internal revenue service tried to explain the riddle, but it is difficult to believe it succeeded in doing much more than adding to the confusion of those who seek to understand
such anomalies aren't uncommon. the latest tax law, for instance, is said to be fairer and simpler. it is neither, says doyle, who helps train chartered financial analysts at the american college in bryn mawr, pa
americans have been ``mugged,'' he says
doyle's comment is one of an almost infinite list of criticisms by an almost endless number of critics, including taxpayers, philosophers, historians and authorities on taxes who previously had thought they were experts
among the criticisms:
_many members of congress didn't even understand what they had done in passing the latest tax bill, having bothered to read only a small part of it
_there has been almost no ``tax policy'' in recent years. in the span between 1964 and 1984, congress enacted 16 major tax bills and dozens of lesser bills
example: the economic recovery tax act of 1981 promised corporate tax reductions averaging $51 billion in the years 1987 to 1989. but by 1986, says the tax foundation, this reduction had become a $20 billion-a-year increase
_under the latest tax laws, individuals are responsible for adjusting their withholding statements in order to avoid underwithholding. in 1987, millions didn't. the internal revenue service forgave most of them
as a consequence, those who had fulfilled their responsibilities were put at a disadvantage: they lost the use of the withheld money. those who failed in their responsibility were rewarded by having the money to use
_in some instances, ``unearned income,'' such as dividends, continues to be treated differently from ``earned income,'' despite the wailing of those who saved their earnings to invest, and thereby earn ``unearned income.''
_nobody knows the answers. varying interpretations of the same information are made by professional tax preparers and even by internal revenue service personnel. as a result, similar tax returns are treated differently
in the view of many critics, the decades of amending, rescinding, revoking, reimposing, reconciling and correcting could be adding up to something far more serious than confusion. it could, they say, undermine faith
that undermining could also be widespread. it could, many believe, destroy faith in the tax system and encourage tax evasion. but worse, it could endanger confidence in government altogether
what can be claimed for the tax system is that it has produced an industry that seems destined to continue growing, perhaps even while other businesses are fighting to remain solvent during times of recession
billions of dollars each year go to accountants, attorneys, tax preparers, investment advisers, tax-guide publishers and others whose products and services are deemed necessary by taxpayers
how much the industry contributes to the productivity and well-being of americans is another matter
