angela sanbrano was a student in law school and working on immigration cases in a legal clinic in 1980. she kept running into women from el salvador who said they had been tortured. ``i wondered how we could try and stop this,'' she says
leslie schuld was a student at the univesity of dayton in ohio in 1981 when she saw a film on the violence in el salvador. she says she started reading the troubled history of that troubled country
jon haines was working as an aide in a nursing home in seattle. ``in 1981, it looked like the united states would be getting more invlved in el salvador, and i was really concerned about that,'' he says
these people were drawn to an organization which was just coming into being at the time _ cispes, the committee in solidarity with the people of el salvador
so was the fbi _ twice. in a case which recalls the excesses of the communist-hunting days of the 1950s that led to restrictions on fbi investigations into political activity, the bureau has come under criticism for the way it infiltrated cispes and employed an informer for more than three years who, the fbi now says, supplied ``disinformation and misinformation.''
the first time the fbi investigated cispes it suspected it was operating as a foreign front. the second time, it suspected cispes was engaging in terrorism and had ``cells'' of members planning to commit violence and sabotage
but the upshot was embarrassment, and a new round of qustions about the bureau's squeaky clean image under former director william webster, now the head of the cia
the senate intelligence committee already has conducted one hearing into the fbi's conduct and the house panel that oversees the fbi plans to hold hearings as well
at issue is whether the fbi went too far in conducting domestic surveillance of cispes, violating the first amendment rights of group members to express their political opinions
or as sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, a member of the senate intelligence committee, put it, ``the issues we're talking about go to the very heart of the confidence the american people have in the fbi.''
why did the fbi conduct two investigations of cispes over a five-year period if, in fact, the group was merely one of hundreds in the united states that work to bring about change in american foreign policy?
the associated press interviewed members of cispes and reviewed the 2,000 pages of fbi documents, many partially or totally blacked out by government censors. they were provided in response to a freedom of information request to the center for constitutional rights in new york. the fbi gave its first detailed explanation of its investigation in a report to the senate intelligence committee on tuesday
the story begins in october 1980, with the founding of cispes at conferences in los angeles and washington
the fbi claims that it obtained a document, reportedly seized from the communist guerillas in el salvador, indicating that the communist party in the united states was involved in the establishment of cispes
specifically, the fbi says farid handal, the brother of the head of the salvadoran communist party, met with sandra pollock, a member of the central committee of the communist party in the united states, in march 1980 to work out a way of getting financial and moral support for the salvadoran guerrillas. cispes was that way, the fbi contends
beth perry, a spokeswoman for cispes who attended the founding conference in los angeles, acknowledged in a recent interview that handal did attend the meeting
people knew he was a member of the communist party,'' perry said. ``handal put out his opinions in discussions. we listened because we were interested in all salvadorans' opinions. but dominating, he wasn't.''
perry said pollock attended the east coast conference in washington, and ``just like farid's, hers was just one voice. in terms of this is the (communist party) line, absolutely not. in terms of what we ought to do, absolutely not.''
at the time, the violence in el salvador was in the news almost daily. one news story at the end of 1980 declared that the civil war in the central american nation had taken 8,500 lives that year
less than two months after cispes' founding, three roman catholic nuns and a lay worker were killed and buried in a roadside grave. the sisters were in el salvador to aid refugees from rural areas who were fleeing the violence between leftist and rightist guerillas
when i was getting the testimony from these people for filing their immigration papers, i learned of what these people had gone through in el salvador,'' said sanbrano, the law student who was working on immigration cases in 1980. ``some of the women had been involved in starting unions. they talked about how they had been tortured, and it really touched me. i wondered how we could try and stop this.''
she joined cispes as a volunteer and worked her way up to southwest regional coordinator in 1983 to national coordinator in 1985. she was re-elected to the top spot in 1987, with the new title, executive director
she said the group has two main objectives _ ``to change u.s. policy in el salvador from a militaristic policy to a political-diplomatic policy and to allow central americans to determine their own destiny.''
being in solidarity with the people of el salvador means we support their struggle for peace and justice and work with them to win that struggle,'' she said. ``solidarity means to take someone else's struggle and make it your own.''
sanbrano, who is of mexican origin, said cispes ``openly supports'' the communist guerillas, known as the frente farabundo marti de liberacion nacional, or fmln. but she said the support is not financial. ``we believe they are a legitimate political organization in el salvador.''
the fbi, in its report on the cispes investigation, says the fmln is responsible for numerous terrorist activities, including the may 1983 assassination of navy lt. cmdr. albert a. schaufelberger, who was the u.s. military adviser in el salvador
perry, the spokeswoman for cispes, agreed that the fmln has killed americans. ``we don't want to see anyone killed, but there's a civil war going on there. people get caught in a war.''
she later added, ``we feel americans should not be there. if the united states got out of el salvador, no americans would be killed.''
no one in cispes interviewed by the ap recalled any violent actions ever being discussed at meetings. all said there no secret ``cells'' of members planning terrorist actions. and all generally gave the same report of activities in their area by cispes, ranging from petition drives to demonstrations to inviting speakers to their meetings. two described their meetings as ``long and boring.''
sanbrano said cispes also does a lot of fund-raising, much of it going to running the group and producing newsletters and other literature. she said she gets a salary of $865 a month, as do most of the full-time workers for cispes
some of the money the group raises does go for humanitarian aid and for agricultural projects in el salvador, she said, ``but we don't fund the fmln.''
although the cispes members interviewed had different reasons for joining the group, all said they joined to bring about a change in u.s. policy in central america
leslie schuld, the university of dayton student, now midwest regional director of cispes, joined the group in 1981. she said the film shown by a local chapter of cispes on the violence in el salvador shocked her. she said she read up on the history of el salvador and on u.s. involvement in central america and went to work as a volunteer for cispes
jon haines, the nursing home aide, joined at about the same time. he said he was growing increasingly concerned about u.s. involvement in el salvador. ``in 1981, it looked like the united states would be getting more involved in el salvador, and i was really concerned about that,'' he said
in dallas, parker wilson was a legal counsel to sears. ``i remember having a general concern about the central america situation and our government's actions,'' he said. he joined the local chapter of cispes, which he described as ``a little, scraggly group'' in the early 1980s. it held meetings in a catholic church
not long after the dallas chapter was formed, the fbi hired a former evangelist from el salvador, frank varelli, to inform on the group. varelli began work on march 10, 1981, according to his testimony last year to the house judiciary subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights
for more than three years, he testified to the house panel, he told the fbi what it wanted to hear. he told the fbi that cispes' activities were being directed by the salvadoran guerillas and that members of cispes were engaged in international terrorism or were knowingly helping those engaged in terrorism
the fbi says it began its first investigation of cispes on sept. 3, 1981, at the justice department's request. in its report to the senate intelligence committee, the fbi says it was asked to determine whether cispes was supplying money and material to the communist guerillas in el salvador and, therefore, should register under the foreign agents registration act
oliver b. revell, fbi executive assistant director, told the intelligence panel, that the probe was ``just a records check,'' and it was closed on feb. 23, 1982
the fbi opened its second investigation of cispes on march 30, 1983, largely on the basis of varelli's information, the fbi says in its report to the senate intelligence committee. this was a counterterrorism investigation, which gives the fbi far more sweeping powers than the first probe. it requires only that there be probable cause to suspect a terrorist threat to justify domestic surveillance
varelli continued working as an informer for the fbi for more than three years, telling it in 1984 that members of cispes were plotting to assassinate president reagan and disrupt the republican national convention in dallas. he stopped working for the fbi in august 1984 and in march 1986 filed suit to get the rest of the pay he felt he was owed for his fbi work. the case is still pending
the fbi closed its investigation of cispes on june 18, 1985, because, revell said, ``we found insufficient evidence to continue. ... part of the reason for that was the disinformation and misinformation supplied by mr. varelli.''
wilson, of the dallas chapter, said he considers the fbi infiltration of the group ``so peculiar. the organization has always been open to anyone who wanted to come. there was no need for infiltration.''
_ best country instrumental performance (orchestra, group or soloist): jerry douglas, ``changing channels''; albert lee, ``gagged but not bound''; bill munroe ``the old county barn''; asleep at the wheel, ``string of pars''; stephane grappelli and vassar clements, ``together at last.''
_ best country song: sanger d. shafer and lyndia j. shafer, ``all my ex's live in texas''; k.t. oslin, ``80's ladies''; paul overstreet and don schlitz, ``forever and ever, amen''; mary ann kennedy, pat bunch, pam rose and todd cerney, ``i'll still be loving you''; linda thompson and betsy cook, ``tellin' me lies.''
_ best gospel performance, female: debbie mcclendon, ``count it all joy''; deniece williams, ``i believe in you''; kathy troccoli, ``images''; debby boone, ``the name above all the names''; terri gibbs, ``turnaround.''
_ best gospel performance, male: dallas holm, ``against the wind''; leon patillo, ``brand new''; larnelle harris, ``the father hath provided''; steve green, ``joy to the world''; wayne watson, ``watercolour ponies.''
