north florida farmer fred williams has an analysis of the super tuesday primaries across the south and elsewhere: ``there are too many hogs in the creek and the water is muddy.''
little more than a week from the regionwide presidential primaries in both parties, his farm analogy remains apt. the picture in both parties hasn't entirely cleared, and the races remain crowded
super tuesday, the closest the nation has ever come to a national primary, could crystallize the nomination races, particularly on the republican side. but there's as much likelihood it won't
pat robertson is a wild card that threatens to confuse the republican race. he has the opportunity to do well, maybe even win, in some small-turnout primaries in areas where he built devoted followings through years as a television evangelist
and if no democrat strongly emerges, that race may not come close to being decided on march 8 and the field will move on to the next round of northern industrial states, still crowded with three or four candidates
super tuesday is not fulfilling the wishes of its founders,'' said university of virginia political scientist larry sabato
twenty states hold democratic primaries or caucuses on tuesday, march 8, and they stretch from massachusetts to florida to idaho; there are 17 gop contests. the day is mainly southern, with 14 contests in southern or border states. democrats also hold a caucus in american samoa
at stake are 1,307 democratic and 712 republican delegates _ about one-third the total in both parties
southern legislators set the whole thing up with the aim of providing a conservative or moderating influence on the democratic nomination process, countering and perhaps stealing the thunder of earlier contests. the gop went along, often because democrats control the legislatures in those southern states
the primary may yet move the democratic nominee to the right. but it didn't diminish the early contests. wins in iowa and new hampshire have helped propel richard gephardt and michael dukakis in polls of the south
and so far no single democrat has emerged with broad appeal across the south _ the region democrats agree they must carry to regain the white house
among the republicans, the south looks like george bush territory. president reagan has always been popular there and the vice president has successfully _ so far at least _ managed to appear the heir. polls show him leading dole two-to-one or better in the region
he has the added benefit of a southern organization regarded as unsurpassed. but all those strengths looked as thin as the paper they were written on when bush appeared on the verge of losing new hampshire to sen. bob dole
bush won, of course, but dole, robertson and new york rep. jack kemp hope to attack bush's base and prove it broad but thin
kemp needs to do well somewhere in the south to be able to sustain his campaign and the argument that he is the conservative alternative
robertson, who became known across the south and elsewhere as host of the ``700 club'' program on his own religious cable network, has drawn a line in the dirt of south carolina. he needs to win somewhere, and he says that's where it will be
south carolina isn't a super tuesday state; its gop caucuses are three days earlier. but it is being watched
bush has organizational and institutional strength there. but robertson contends the state is fertile ground for him too. its gop primary usually has a low voter turnout, and crossover democratic voting is allowed _ a made-to-order formula for robertson's strength based in fundamentalist churches
dole is contesting the state, too, but could finish third. dole must pick his shots and concentrate in areas where he can profit under the gop's winner-take-all rules in many congressional districts and states
should robertson produce victories in the south, the gop race could prove a prolonged and bitter fight with bush, dole and robertson. but robertson must still demonstrate he has appeal beyond his evangelical base and can be more than a disruptive force for the gop
jesse jackson leads in the polls in many southern states and is certain to do well in states with heavy black voting populations. he wants to do well in the south but will go on to the convention in atlanta this summer regardless
he's going to have enough votes to play somebody's fiddle,'' said williams, the grand ridge, fla., farmer who backs jackson. ``they'll trade for votes just like we trade pigs and cows.''
dukakis has run well in some southern polls and has a good organization in many states. as governor of massachusetts, he carries the image of a liberal state that triggers opposition in many southern quarters
there is just an innate fear of somebody from massachusetts,'' said louisiana democratic chairman james brady. ``they're associated with tip o'neill and teddy kennedy.''
but dukakis hopes to win florida, where he has strong support in the southern end of the state, and perhaps texas too. with massachusetts voting that day as well he could be the big delegate winner
sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee has tried to position himself to the right of the democratic field, depicting the rest as liberal ``peas in a pod.'' he must do well across the region, and polls have shown him running as high as second and as low as fourth in the region
rep. richard gephardt, winner in iowa and south dakota, is also attracting conservative and moderate democratic voters in some states with his well-honed appeal to concerns about foreign competition and a message that america is in economic decline
he has shown strength among blue-collar voters, and so far has concentrated his effort in the economically hard-hit energy-producing states of the south, where his call for an oil-import fee is a further boost. a texas poll had him leading that huge delegate state but falling back after dukakis won new hampshire
sen. paul simon of illinois has no visible southern strength. gary hart appears to be fading
with so broad a field and so many contests, how will we know who wins super tuesday?
florida and texas are the big prizes, and if a candidate carries both of those, it will be hard for anyone else to argue they won super tuesday, although some no doubt will
as the nomination race moves on, delegates are what matters. massachusetts has the next biggest democratic total, and dukakis figures to get most of them. jackson, too, will get a big share of southern delegates
still another measure will be the cross-over voting. it is allowed in eight of southern and border super tuesday states _ alabama, arkansas, georgia, mississippi, missouri, tennessee, texas and virginia
a big republican primary vote in those states, at the cost of democratic votes, could be a harbinger for the fall
in the hometown of the 39th president, where politics was once the driving energy, the kountry korner is the place to go for coffee, catfish and gossip
eavesdrop there and you will hear table talk about mildred wise's hand crocheted bedspread, the before-and-after beauty treatment pictures of cathy williams on page 124 in the current ``good housekeeping,'' mayor ralph mcdonald's recent illness, the prospects for bass and bream, and unvarnished views on errant tv evangelists
but if hot insight into the super tuesday primaries is the object of your eavsdropping, you eavesdrop in vain
i don't know why people aren't talking about super tuesday,'' marlene dozier, the kountry korner's chief cook and part owner, was saying the other day.``i suppose they aren't much interested
when is it?''
at least one plains citizen with that famous name knows when it is. in fact, hugh carter, the former president's cousin, has already voted
i'm going to be away march 8 so i went ahead and marked my absentee ballot,'' hugh carter said, bending over a stack of books with a felt tip pen
and?
gore. i voted for albert gore.''
hugh carter, too, has not observed any stirring interest among his townspeople in the primary. none of the democrats seeking the presidential nomination has seen fit to make plains a campaign stop. and jimmy carter, who still maintains a home here, has studiously refrained from saying which of the democrats he personally favors for the presidential nomination
nonetheless, hugh carter believes the turnout of plains' 265 eligible voters will be strong
we have to vote at the same time on a county tax increase. that'll get 'em out.''
hugh carter, seven-term state senator, author, ``antiques'' dealer and worm raiser, is the town's leading purveyor of jimmy carter souvenirs
you can pick up a plains souvenir from the kountry korner cashier, or at the drug store or the peanut gallery, which also sells gas, but hugh carter's emporium, for pure variety of ball points, salt shakers, paperweights and postcards, outdoes anything at the grand canyon or niagara falls
people come to plains they want something to take home, show they've been here,'' he said
the one item he hopes all visitors will take home is a copy of his book about the carter family, ``cousin beedie and cousin hot.'' a huge sign out front promises that every copy will be autographed. he also sells, it appears, every scrap of writing ever written by every carter who ever lived
but business is a far cry from what it once was
before jimmy carter was elected president, his brother, billy, described plains, a town of 687 then as now, as a place where a hound dog could lie down in the middle of main street on saturday night and sleep unharmed at least until monday morning
then, during the early presidential years, visitors came in droves, hordes, sometimes 20,000 or more a day, so many, hugh carter recalls, that they had to hire nine policemen just to direct traffic
now plains is back to three cops, one on duty at a time, and except for an occasional tour bus that hound dog would be safe all week
the old depot, which served as carter's 1976 campaign headquarters, was recently designated a national historic site along with carter's boyhood home and high school. all are models of life in the rural south in another era
we're hoping, of course, that the historic site designation will bring more tourists,'' says annie mae vaughn, a volunteer, putting down her book when a visitor entered the depot. the vaughns and carters have been neighbors for three generations
nothing remotely connected with carter is overlooked as a possible tourist attraction. a self-guided tour booklet lists 25 places of interest: jimmy's church, his former church, the post office where he mails his letters, his mother's home, his brother's home, his grandmother's home, his wife's brother's home, the home where his parents had an apartment when they first married
was that where jimmy carter was born?
no,'' said hugh carter. ``jimmy was born in a hospital. but don't you see? that's where he was conceived.''
back at the kountry korner, which is not on the list but is where every tourist stops, the proprietor had a second thought about the coming primary election
i do remember a lady who was in here the other day and mentioned super tuesday,'' said marlene dozier. ``she was from canada.''
united mine workers president richard trumka says he considers the union's failed merger with the oil, chemical and atomic workers union ``a closed deal'' that won't be reconsidered
ocaw's executive board on tuesday voted 6-2 to reject a merger that would have created the united mine, energy and chemical workers of america from the two powerful unions
trumka said wednesday the ocaw board had left open the possibility of reconsidering the merger, but the umw's board voted wednesday to rescind the approval it gave on sunday
a federal judge has given the environmental protection agency until april 15 to ban the sale and commercial use of products containing an anti-termite pesticide believed to cause cancer
u.s. district judge louis oberdorfer ruled wednesday that the epa had acted illegally by allowing 197 holders of federal pesticide licenses to sell existing stocks of products containing the pesticides chlordane and heptachlor
oberdorfer said epa failed to take into account whether continued sale or use of the products ``would pose any unreasonable risk to man or the environment.''
a new blood test for aids antibodies virtually eliminates the false positive readings that needlessly terrorize healthy people, the test's creator claims
smithkline bio-science laboratories said wednesday it would perform the confirmatory tests at its own lab for $80 apiece, about the same price as the tests they are intended to replace. it said the service was available immediately
doctors familiar with the new test said it was a major advance
a new ``condom for females'' pioneered in europe will be tested this spring in the united states, and developers predicted it would be a major weapon in the fight against aids and other sexually transmitted diseases
the new disposable contraceptive, made of polyurethane, resembles a condom but is worn by women, researchers said wednesday as they unveiled the device
president reagan says the decline in the value of the dollar has opened opportunities for u.s. exporters but they could be undermined by protectionist legislation congress is considering
the fact that the dollar's exchange rate is at a far more realistic level is of great significance'' to the market for u.s. exports, the president said wednesday to members of export now, a public-private group organized by the commmerce department
gold prices tumbled wednesday as traders appeared to take a more optimistic view of chances for continued low inflation. the dollar was mixed in foreign exchange
the stock market was little changed. the dow jones average of 30 industrials edged up 0.83 to 2,039.95
bond prices edged lower. grain and soybean futures settled mostly higher, livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures retreated; and stock-index futures declined
a new test that identifies aids virus antibodies in blood is dramatically reducing the incidence of inconclusive tests for evidence of the deadly disease, its maker says
inconclusive results of aids tests can be terrifying for patients because they raise the possibility of infection, smithkline bio-science laboratories said wednesday in announcing immediate availability of the new test
known as hivagen, the new test also virtually eliminates false positive readings, which are already uncommon under current testing procedures for acquired immune deficiency syndrome, the philadelphia-based company said
this test is a quantum leap forward in aids testing,'' john mills, chief of infectious diseases at san francisco general hospital, said in a statement released by smithkline
mills performed clinical trials on the value of hivagen as a replacement for the western blot assay, the current standard test for blood samples that flunk mass screenings
smithkline said it would perform the tests at its own lab for $80 apiece, about the same price as the western blot assay
false positive readings, even though they represent a small fraction of tests, have become more common because aids antibody testing itself has become more common
about 29 million people will be screened for aids antibodies this year, and about 500,000 will be referred for further tests, smithkline officials estimated. the company said false positive readings might range as high as 5 percent on certain inferior versions of the western blot assay, commonly used for further testing
in response, du pont co. said its own widely used version of the western blot assay produces virtually no false positives because the company has an extremely strict standard for what constitutes a positive reading
smithkline officials conceded the du pont test, the only one licensed by the food and drug administration for blood donor screening, produces few if any false positives
with the hivagen test, false positive readings simply cannot occur, company officials asserted. but some scientists were cautious
it may well be that this represents a substantial advance, but you wonder whether it can really be perfect,'' said dr. klemens meyer, an internist and decision analyst at new england medical center in boston, who said he had no first-hand knowledge of hivagen
the presence of aids antibodies does not necessarily mean a person has the disease. the most recent studies have shown that 30 percent to 40 percent of people with aids antibodies have later developed the disease, although many doctors believe that percentage will rise eventually
smithkline has applied for patents on the synthetic molecules used in the hivagen test, said martin rosenberg, vice president of biopharmaceutical research and development
in tests of more than 2,500 blood samples at san francisco general hospital, hivagen was inconclusive in 2.5 percent to 4.2 percent of the patients, vs. 15.6 percent to 18 percent inconclusive results for the western blot assay, said dr. john mills, the hospital's chief of infectious diseases
in another test of the blood of volunteers, the hivagen test was accurate for all 225 people who did not have the aids antibody and was accurate in 135 of the 136 patients without symptoms who did have the aids antibody. in the lone exception, the test was inconclusive, mills said
other companies also have introduced or are working on better tests for aids, including cetus corp. of emeryville, calif., which is developing a test for aids virus genes, and cambridge bioscience corp. of worcester, mass., which has applied for regulatory approval for an antibody test
the hivagen test does not require fda approval because the technology is not for sale to others, groome said. however, fda officials are aware of the test and have invited a smithkline scientist to speak on the subject at a conference next week in washington, he said
when plans for a national energy union fizzled, united mine workers president richard trumka said he started looking for other ways to expand his union's influence
we're going to pursue a policy of growth for our organization,'' trumka said wednesday after the oil chemical and atomic workers international union and the umw rejected a merger agreement that would have created the united mine, energy and chemical workers of america
i spent four or five hours last night with pencil and paper trying to work out ways to expand our union,'' trumka said
trumka said he considers the failed merger ``a closed deal'' that won't be reconsidered, although ocaw spokesman rod rogers said his union doesn't necessarily agree
it's always possible there could bea resurrection of the idea,'' he said
there were compelling reasons why this merger was a good idea, and those reasons haven't gone away,'' rogers said. ``this particular merger proposal is dead, yes, but we could take action to re-initiate things.''
trumka said he was ready to look elsewhere to expand, however
i'll come back at the next (umw) board meeting and say, `that didn't work; let's try something else,''' trumka said
the proposal for a merger between the two energy unions, which each claim about 100,000 active members, was rejected tuesday by ocaw's executive board on a 6-2 vote, largely because it wanted assurances there would be no dues increase, trumka said. the umw then rescinded the approval it gave sunday
trumka said both unions would continue to work together, especially on negotiations with common employers
while he plans to look for other ways to expand the umw's influence, trumka said, he said he did not consider it good policy ``to merge just for the sake of merging.''
