automaking giant general motors corp., which a year ago was wallowing in lotfuls of unsold cars, is showing signs of resurgence because of higher demand for profitable models and an aggressive sales-incentive campaign
the biggest u.s. automaker announced wednesday that it will add about 130,000 cars and 45,000 trucks to previously trimmed 1988 production plans and recall 8,600 employees at four factories
the expansion will be made via restoration of second shifts at three plants, reopening of a closed plant in framingham, mass., and running some plants on overtime
the strengthening demand for gm vehicles reflects the ongoing product quality improvements resulting from plant modernization and employee involvement programs,'' gm president robert stempel said in a statement
this combined with very competitive retail incentive programs has increased the value of gm products,'' he said
at the three plants where gm had dropped the second shift, workers from both shifts were sharing jobs by alternating between two weeks on layoff and two weeks on the job, gm said
the framingham assembly plant, which gm closed abruptly nov. 30, will reopen may 9 on one shift with 2,000 of its 3,700 workers. the plant will build the oldsmobile cutlass cierra, but will not resume production of the chevrolet celebrity, gm spokeswoman kathy tanner said
gm will restore the second shift at its buick-oldsmobile-cadillac group assembly plant in lansing, mich., april 11, returning 2,000 people to full-time work. the 4,350-worker plant builds the oldsmobile cutlass calais and buick skylark
the second shift at gm's 4,200-worker van nuys, calif., assembly plant will be restored march 14, bringing 1,900 employees back full time. the plant, which is gm's only chevrolet camaro and pontiac firebird source, dropped the second shift last week
gm also will restore the second shift at its oshawa no. 1 plant in oshawa, ontario, bringing back 2,700 laid-off workers on march 21. the plant builds the oldsmobile cierra and pontiac 6000
the company said it would increase production at the cadillac plant in the detroit enclave of hamtramck by running its single shift on overtime, adding 4,700 cars between feb. 20 and june 1
cadillac general manager john grettenberger said the increased production was necessary because dealers need more of the restyled eldorado coupe and seville sedans, enjoying high popularity due to a new engine model
gm's expansion plans contrast sharply to the same time about a year ago, when it suffered slumping sales, a three-month backlog of vehicles and loss of market share to its main u.s. rivals, ford motor co. and chrysler corp
uncertainty over gm's prospects was heightened after the october stock market crash, which raised fears that consumers would buy fewer cars. all domestic automakers trimmed production plans afterward, but pessimism has since been eased by healthy sales
in january, ford motor co., the nation's no. 2 automaker, added 75,000 cars to its plans for the first half of 1987, including 53,000 cars in the second quarter, said ford spokesman raymond windecker
chrysler corp., the no. 3 automaker, announced plans last week to add 20,000 cars to its second-quarter schedule
chris cedergren, an industry analyst with the firm j.d. power and associates, said the change in gm's plans reflect ``a little bit of resurgence'' of sales
he noted that the added cars are high-profit models, an indication that gm's profitability may improve in 1988 after two years of higher earnings by ford
the changes do not affect gm's buick-oldsmobile-cadillac group assembly plant in kansas city, mo., still scheduled to shut down indefinitely on april 15, idling 1,600 workers, gm spokesman tom pyden said. condom</head>
a new ``condom for females,'' pioneered in europe, was hailed by developers as revolutionary, but an independent researcher questioned the device's effectiveness
the disposable contraceptive, made of polyurethane, resembles a condom but is worn by women, researchers said wednesday as they publicly unveiled the device
the developers said the female condom would be effective at preventing pregnancy and predicted it would become a major weapon in the fight against the spread of aids and other sexually transmitted diseases
it takes the advantages of both the male condom and the female diaphragm and gets rid of significant disadvantages,'' said mary ann leeper, head of the research team developing the device for wisconsin pharmacal co., which will market it in the united states and canada
but dr. gerald zatuchni, a gynecologist with 25 years experience in researching and developing new contraceptives, said he saw the potential for ``real problems'' with the device
i have not seen the device nor have there been any published studies that would indicate its acceptability to couples, the effectiveness of the device in preventing pregnancy or any side-effects from using the device,'' zatuchni said
the device, known in europe as a ``fem-shield'' or vaginal shield, isn't sold anywhere yet, but testing has begun in europe and is to start in the united states in march, officials said
the developers said they wouldn't have statistics on how effective the device is in preventing pregnancy or the spread of diseases like acquired immune deficiency syndrome until additional studies are completed
the contraceptive consists of a soft, loose-fitting polyurethane sheath and two diaphragm-like, flexible polyurethane rings, ms. leeper said
one ring lies inside the sheath and serves as an insertion mechanism and internal anchor, fitting against the woman's cervix much like a diaphragm, she said. the other ring forms the outer edge of the sheath and remains outside the vagina
it is no more difficult to insert than a tampon,'' said dr. paul salmon, who helped organize tests of the device at london's middlesex hospital
the company, based in jackson, wis., said the device would provide more protection than the male condom, in part because the material is stronger and covers a larger physical area, reducing chances of infection or exposure to body fluids
it also would be more convenient to use than a diaphragm, ms. leeper said, because it doesn't have to be initially fitted by a doctor and can be inserted ``six hours before the sex act or six minutes before.''
but zatuchni, a gynecology and obstetrics professor at northwestern university medical school in chicago, said the idea of a ``one-size-fits-all'' condom for females ``would be sort of ridiculous because women's anatomy varies so much.''
it would be hard to envision such a device staying on during the act of intercourse,'' zatuchni said
ms. leeper said proper fitting would take place during intercourse
she said the company had no estimate on how much the device would cost consumers
the ``female condom'' was developed by an international group of gynecologists and obstetricians, headed by danish gynecologist dr. erik gregersen and his wife, bente
the device has been tested on 80 couples in the united kingdom, denmark and sweden, and additional clinical trials are continuing in europe, ms. leeper said
the world health organization also plans to conduct clinical trials in 15 countries, including brazil, thailand, singapore and nations battling the spread of aids in central africa
aids, a deadly disease with no known cure, is believed to be spread mainly through sexual intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from infected mothers to their infants at or before birth
in the united states, a first round of 500 clinical tests of the new contraceptive is to begin in march, followed by a second phase of 1,000 tests in may, ms. leeper said
the company hopes to apply to the u.s. food and drug administration this summer for permission to begin marketing the device commercially in the united states by the end of the year
the lawyer for a south american mineral concern suing the hunt brothers of dallas opened his case wednesday by spinning a tale of financial intrigue involving texas oilmen and arab sheiks
minpeco s.a., a mineral marketing company owned by the peruvian government, is suing the three hunt brothers, claiming they conspired to corner the world silver market in 1979 and 1980
named as defendants in the case that opened before u.s. district judge morris e. lasker were: nelson bunker hunt, william herbert hunt and lamar hunt
we will show that they did this using their incredible fortunes with utter contempt for the legal and economic system that was so good to them,'' mark cymrot, attorney for minpeco, told the jury in his opening statement at federal court in manhattan
none of the hunts were present in court and they were not expected to appear until the defense begins its case
other defendants include mahmoud fustok, described as the owner of one of the world's largest thoroughbred stables and brother-in-law of a saudi arabian prince
we will show that they were greedy, power-hungry and unscrupulous,'' said cymrot, adding ``what we intend to show is that these men rigged the silver market.''
he claimed that the hunts and their alleged co-conspirators were responsible for the sharp rise in silver prices from about $9 an ounce to more than $50 an ounce between september 1979 and january 1980
minpeco claims the skyrocketing prices caused it to lose more than $100 million when the world silver market collapsed in march 1980, with prices falling back to about $10 an ounce
six financial institutions accused of participating in the alleged conspiracy have settled with minpeco for a total of $64.6 million
minpeco is seeking about $150 million in damages plus treble damages under both the anti-trust and racketeering laws which it claims the hunts and thier co-conspirators violated
but in his opening argument to the jury, the hunts's lawyer belittled those claims
the defense lawyer, paul curran, said rising interest rates, inflation and crude oil prices, coupled with an unstable world political situation, led to the silver market price rise
he ticked off the iranian revolution, the seizure of american hostages at the u.s. embassy in teheran and the soviet invasion of afghanistan
it was these world and economic events that were the reason for the sharp rise in silver prices,'' said curran
he conceded silver prices went up, but noted gold, platinum and diamond prices also rose during the same period because ``the price of silver has historically fluctuated as a result of events in the market place and in the world.''
the trial is expected to last several months
signs warning of potentially harmful chemicals in everything from foods to workplaces will sprout across california this weekend under a law approved by voters in 1986
warning: this product contains a chemical known to the state of california to cause cancer.'' this sign could be seen on store shelves
warning: chemicals known to the state of california to cause cancer, or birth defects or other reproductive harm may be present in foods or beverages sold or served here.'' this sign could be printed on restaurant menus
warning: this area contains a chemical known to the state of california to cause cancer.'' this sign could be posted on a service station island, along a factory fence or on an assembly line
in addition, there will be labels, newsaper advertisements, letters and telephone hot lines telling people about chemicals in the products they buy and the environment in which they work and live
but there probably won't be any warning signs for the more than 15,000 grocery, drug and cosmetic products bought every day. temporary state regulations say that such products manufactured under existing state and federal rules don't have to contain warnings
the signs will be the first visible result of the anti-toxics initiative approved by voters following a bitter struggle between environmentalists who wrote the measure, including the sierra club and the environmental defense fund, and business interests
proposition 65 will also mean confusion, with businesses responding differently to its warning requirements. and dozens of lawsuits could occupy the courts for years as supporters and opponents continue to quarrel over its intent and requirements
the period ahead will be filled with charges and countercharges, pressures and counterpressures and intense courtroom litigation,'' says assemblyman tom hayden, one of the initiative's major backers and the leader of a star-studded hollywood group that campaigned hard for the measure
there are probably still people who wish the proposition had never happened ... but there are people who have come to grips with it as an expression of people's concern,'' said thomas warriner of the state health and welfare agency, who wrote the regulations
the initiative requires anyone who causes people to be exposed to any of 29 chemicals known to the state to cause cancer or birth defects to issue an advance warning
those chemicals include five that business officials say are present in varying levels throughout society: asbestos, benzene, lead, chromium and arsenic
for example, benzene is in gasoline and most service stations will probably have to post warning signs on their fuel islands. chromium is in stainless steel, magnetic tapes, paint pigments and cement
also, citizens who feel they've been exposed to a cancer- or birth defect-causing chemical can take action if authorities won't and collect 25 percent of any eventual fine
republican gov. george deukmejian, who opposed the initiative, followed issued the list of 29 chemicals ``known to the state to cause cancer or reproductive toxicity'' and has appointed a 12-member panel to study whether more than 200 other chemicals should be added to the list
backers of the plan sued deukmejian, saying the initiative required about 250 chemicals to be on the first list. a superior court judge agreed, but the deukmejian's appeal is pending
the advisory panel has in the past year added almost all the 200-plus chemicals to the list. but adding them later, rather than on feb. 27, means they are subject to the initiative's other requirements at later dates
the initiative requires any business with 10 or more employes to give a ``clear and reasonable warning'' before exposing anyone to any of the chemicals on the list, beginning one year after their making the list
another part of the initiative doesn't take effect until oct. 27 for the first 27 chemicals. that part prohibits businesses from discharging any of the listed chemicals into drinking water sources, beginning 20 months after a chemical's inclusion on the list
henley group inc., rebuffed in its latest attempt to take control of santa fe southern pacific corp., has accepted the rejection quietly
we are disappointed but not surprised,'' said henley spokesman norm ritter
santa fe southern on wednesday turned down henley's bid to buy 44.6 million new shares for $780 million. the offer, made on monday, was conditioned up the company abandoning its ``poison pill'' takeover defense and restructuring a $4.7 billion special dividend to stockholders
the chicago railroad, land and natural resources concern also rebuffed henley late last year when henley offered to buy the entire company for $63 a share, or $8.34 billion
santa fe's directors discussed the latest proposal with their investment bankers and legal advisers and concluded the plan would benefit only henley, santa fe president robert d. krebs said in a letter to michael dingman, henley's chairman
that ownership percentage would transfer effective control of the company without the payment of a control premium to our shareholders,'' krebs wrote. ``in addition, the offer would dilute the interests of all our shareholders except for the henley group.''
henley's proposal would have given it 34.3 percent ownership of santa fe. the la jolla, calif., manufacturing, engineering and financial-services firm currently holds a 15.7 percent stake
santa fe stock rose 75 cents to $24.25 share wednesday in new york stock exchange trading
krebs said in his letter to dingman that santa fe's special-dividend plan represented a better value to shareholders than the alternative proposed by henley
the rejected henley proposal asked santa fe to stop the planned march 1 payment of $5 per share in ``junk bonds'' for each of its 157.3 million shares. santa fe already has made a $25-per-share cash payout as part of the special dividend
henley contends the bonds will leave shareholders with a large tax liability because of the way they are structured
instead, henley proposed that santa fe sell it $780 million worth of new stock at $17.50 per share. proceeds from that deal would have been used to make a one-time $5-a-share cash payout to all shareholders
henley had also asked santa fe to void the poison pill takeover defense it adopted in december
under the defense, if any stockholder's stake exceeds 20 percent, other santa fe shareholders would be permitted to buy new stock at half price, diluting the hostile buyer's stake and making a takeover prohibitively expensive
henley has said the takeover defense restricts the maneuverability of major holders like itself and toronto-based real estate concern olympia &amp; york developments ltd
olympia &amp; york, which is controlled by canada's reichmann family, has a 10.5 percent stake in santa fe. the company last week launched a $17.50 a share million tender offer worth $245 million to boost its holdings to 19.9 percent
olympia &amp; york had agreed to support santa fe's restructuring in return for two seats on the santa fe board
meanwhile, henley is waging a proxy fight in hopes of gaining control of santa fe's board of directors at the company's may 24 annual meeting, and is suing santa fe in delaware, where both companies are incorporated, to block the $4.7 billion special dividend
u.s. treasury secretary james baker said thursday he was satisfied with the current exchange rates between the dollar and the japanese yen, according to japanese officials in seoul
baker reportedly expressed that view when he met with japanese prime minister noboru takeshita in seoul thursday. both were attending the inauguration of south korean president roh tae-woo
efforts to stabilize the exchange rates have been successful,'' a japanese foreign ministry official quoted baker as telling takeshita
the official, haraguchi koichi, said baker predicted that the slumping u.s. economy would recover soon and grow at least 2.5 percent this year. fourth-quarter gnp.; uppicks 3rd graf pvs: exports rose...</note>
the u.s. economy surged ahead at its fastest pace in two years _ a robust 4.5 percent annual rate _ in the last quarter of 1987, the government said today
the commerce department's measure of growth in the gross national product, the total output of goods and services, amounted to an upward revision from a month ago, when the gnp was put at a slightly slower 4.2 percent growth rate
such a strong performance is usually considered good news, but some economists fear this time may be an exception
they note that three-fourths of the $42 billion in growth in the october-december quarter came from a $32.1 billion rise in business inventories, which came as consumer spending was falling at its fastest rate in more than seven years
that means production will have to be cut back sharply in coming months to work down the excess inventories _ meaning the overall economy will also probably slow as well in the first half of 1988
a separate report wednesday offered encouraging news on another front, however, when the commerce department said record exports helped shrink the nation's trade deficit at the end of 1987
exports rose 6 percent as the trade deficit narrowed to $40.2 billion on a balance-of-payments basis in the last three months of the year, the department said. it was the first quarterly improvement since the spring of 1986
we have a genuine export boom going on and i think a lot of people are pleasantly surprised,'' robert ortner, undersecretary of commerce for economic affairs, said in announcing the turnaround
in other economic news wednesday, sales of u.s.-made cars and light trucks jumped 14.5 percent in mid-february in a development that analysts attributed to plentiful, aggressive buyer incentives
the consumer has more confidence in the economy than the analysts do,'' said chris cedergren, industry analyst with j.d. power and associates in agoura hills, calif
the news had little impact on wall street, where the dow jones average of 30 industrials edged up 0.83 point to 2,039.95. the dow fell 1.17 on tuesday
gold prices tumbled on expectations of continued low inflation. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $432.80 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, down $8.70 from tuesday's late level
the dollar, meanwhile, turned in a narrowly mixed performance on the world's foreign-exchange markets. bond prices edged marginally lower as a major new issue of treasury bonds waited in the wings
ortner said further improvements in trade were likely in the months ahead because of the beneficial effects of the cheaper dollar, which has declined sharply in value since late 1985 as part of a reagan administration effort to thwart protectionist sentiment in congress
still, the year finished with a record $159.3 billion balance-of-payments trade deficit for all of 1987, the report said
in volume alone, the trade deficit actually showed a 5 percent improvement from 1986 to 1987. the fact that import prices rose more rapidly than export prices helped mask this improvement, commerce department analysts said
the new figures confirmed an end-of-year narrowing of the trade shortfall that already had shown up in the department's monthly merchandise trade reports. the earlier figures showed a $43 billion deficit for the fourth quarter and a $171.2 billion shortfall for all of 1987
wednesday's figures were smaller because they subtracted factors such as the cost of shipping, insurance and military sales from the monthly numbers. the balance-of-payments deficit is also adjusted for seasonal variations; the monthly figures are not. wires.</note>
the u.s. economy grew at a robust 4.5 percent annual rate in the final three months of 1987, the fastest pace in almost two years, the government said today
the commerce department's estimate of growth in the gross national product, the total output of goods and services, represented an upward revision from a month ago, when the gnp was put at a slightly slower 4.2 percent growth rate
president reagan, boasting about the country's longest peacetime recovery on record, had given a small preview of today's good news during his wednesday night news conference. reagan, who is briefed on the economic figures in advance, said they would contain ``a little good news.''
economic expansion at such a rapid clip would normally bring cheers, but the lopsided nature of this increase is instead raising concern among private economists that the recovery will weaken considerably in the first half of 1988
analysts base this forecast on the fact that three-fourths of the $42 billion in growth in the october-december quarter came from a $32.1 billion rise in business inventories, which came as consumer spending was falling at its fastest rate in more than seven years
this ominous combination means that production will have to be cut back sharply in coming months to work down the excess inventories
a buildup of inventories and weak consumer spending can trigger a recession, but most economists believe that the country will be able to escape a downturn this year although they are forecasting very weak growth during the first six months
the rapid rate of growth in the fourth quarter was accompanied by little pickup in inflation. a price index tied to the gnp was rising at an annual rate of 3.7 percent in the fourth quarter, compared to a 3.4 percent increase in the third quarter
the 4.5 percent increase in economic growth followed a gain of 4.3 percent in the third quarter and was the fastest advance since a 5.4 percent rise in the first quarter of 1986
the fourth-quarter gain boosted growth for the year to 3.9 percent, when measured from the end of 1986, up slightly from the 3.8 percent estimate made a month ago
the reagan administration is forecasting that growth this year will slow to a rate of 2.4 percent. many private economists believe even this scaled-down figure is too optimistic
those analysts think that growth in the current january-march quarter will slow to a barely discernible 1 percent rate _ or even less. they expect a gradual strengthening for the rest of the year as growth in export sales offsets a slowdown in consumer spending
the administration is expecting the country will get half of its growth this year from an improving trade deficit as american manufacturers continue to benefit from the decline in the value of the dollar
the upward revision in gnp growth in the october-december quarter came despite the fact that the shrinking in the trade deficit was not as large as originally thought
the various changes added $42 billion to the total gnp, leaving it at $3.877 trillion after adjusting for inflation
in addition to the big rise in business inventories, other sources of strength included a 13.4 percent increase in government spending and an 8.1 percent increase in housing construction
the trade deficit, after removing the effects of inflation, improved as exports shot up by 15.1 percent, outpacing a 9.7 percent rise in imports
the 3.1 percent drop in consumer spending was the biggest setback since a 5.4 percent drop in the first quarter of 1980, a slowdown that occurred during the brief recession that year and which has been cited as a contributing factor to jimmy carter's defeat
the reagan administration, wanting to keep the white house in republican hands, hopes that the big plunge in consumer spending this time does not signal another recession
david wyss, an economist with data resources inc. of lexington, mass., said he expected the gnp would rise at a sluggish pace of 1.4 percent this year as consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of overall economic activity, slows appreciably
wyss said economic growth in the current january-march quarter is likely to slow to around 1 percent with the second quarter possibly posting a negative number
however, he said the country will probably avoid a recession, which is defined as at least two quarters of negative gnp growth, because continued strength in american exports will offset the weakness in consumer spending
michael evans, an economist for a washington forecasting firm, said he has changed from predicting a recession and now believes the country has a 50-50 change of avoiding a downturn
he said a key bit of evidence will come with next week's release of unemployment figures for february
if we had a big gain in employment in february, then the chances of the consumer leading us into a recession are much weaker than i thought,'' he said
japan's inflation-adjusted consumer spending rose 1.9 percent in december from a year ago, the government reported thursday
meanwhile, the government said the nation's major retailers saw sales climb by 7.1 percent in january over the same month last year on the strength of clothing purchases
the statistics bureau of the prime minister's office said december's 1.9 percent consumer spending gain compared with an adjusted 2 percent rise in november
bureau officials said the december increases came largely in the areas of education, utilities, clothing and entertainment
shareholders of broken hill proprietary co. on thursday approved a major restructuring of australia's largest company, which included the repurchase of most bhp shares owned by its two biggest stockholders
under the plan outlined late last month, broken hill will pay 2.1 billion australian dollars, about $1.5 billion at current exchange rates, to buy back 300 million bhp shares controlled by financier robert holmes a court, a persistent suitor for the company
the buyback will reduce holmes a court's stake, held by his bell resources conglomerate, to 10 percent from 29 percent
broken hill also plans to pay 575 million australian dollars to elders ixl ltd., a diversified company run by entrepreneur john elliott, for a 50 percent interest in an elders unit that owns 19 percent of bhp, reducing elliott's broken hill stake by half
elliott and holmes a court also will resign from broken hill's board of directors
the steel, oil and mining company, which has major holdings in the united states, south america and elsewhere has been eager to reduce the influence of both entrepreneurs, especially because of holmes a court's repeated attempts in recent years to buy control of the giant company
elders had acquired its stake in broken hill in 1986 to thwart a takeover attempt by holmes a court
broken hill also had been concerned that holmes a court and elliott might dump their shares following october's stock market crash, depressing the company's stock price
companies controlled by holmes a court lost about 500 million australian dollars in the stock market crash, the biggest corporate loss in australian history, due to investment writedowns. the financier has been selling a number of assets to help ease cash problems raised by the sharp decline in its market value during the crash
broken hill is selling at least 1 billion australian dollars worth of non-strategic investments and assets to help finance its restructuring, which was expected to cost 2.68 billion australian dollars, about $1.9 billion
sir james balderstone, chairman of broken hill, said the restructuring would not be completed for several months
balderstone said the plan would be completed once the transactions with holmes a court and elliott were settled, broken hill shareholders approved the plan to cancel the 300 million shares acquired from holmes a court and australia's supreme court approved the reduction in broken hill's capital
broken hill's plans received clearance tuesday by australian securities regulators, who said they would not take any action because shareholders of all companies involved were to vote on the proposals. incentives; subs 14th graf to remove first reference to phillippi; picks up 15th graf pvs bg'ng, sales of ...</note>
sales of domestic cars and light trucks in mid-february slowed from early in the month but jumped 14.5 percent over the same period a year earlier, reflecting aggressive buyer incentives offered by automakers
general motors corp., ford motor co. and chrysler corp. wednesday reported healthy sales increases over a year earlier, which were not shared by most foreign makers who build cars in this country
they had a lot of help from incentives. i think that's pretty evident looking at chrysler's numbers. chrysler has had huge incentives,'' said joseph phillippi, an analyst with shearson lehman hutton inc. in new york
total domestic car sales rose 11.9 percent in the nine selling days from feb. 11-20, while domestic truck sales, which increased for all makers, jumped 19.6 percent as the surge in light-truck popularity showed no sign of slowing
the eight companies building domestic vehicles sold 325,422 cars and light trucks in mid-february, up from 284,278 a year earlier _ 210,316 cars and 115,106 trucks, compared with 188,001 cars and 96,277 trucks a year earlier
but mid-february domestic car sales moved at a seasonally adjusted rate of less than 7.8 million a year, down from an 8.4 million rate in early february
the consumer has more confidence in the economy than the analysts do,'' said chris cedergren, industry analyst with j.d. power and associates in agoura hills, calif
all economic indicators point to lower sales for 1988 than 1987,'' cedergren said. ``we do expect the downward trend to continue.''
nevertheless, the big three have shown renewed optimism toward the u.s. economy and vehicle market, increasing planned production for 1988 in reverses of cuts planned after the stock market crash in october
gm announced wednesday it is restoring second shifts at three plants, reopening a framingham, mass., assembly plant on one shift and boosting overtime at other car and truck plants
the increases will put 8,600 laid-off workers back on the job and will add 175,000 cars and trucks to gm's 1988 production schedule
in mid-february, chrysler led the big three in domestic car sales increases with a 21.7 percent boost. chrysler's domestic truck sales rose even further, jumping 47.3 percent over mid-february 1986
gm reported a 16.3 percent increase in domestic car sales and a 21.8 percent boost in domestic truck sales over mid-february a year earlier. ford's car sales rose 2.2 percent and truck sales increased 5.4 percent
ford's share of the domestic car market fell to 28.8 percent from 31.5 percent a year earlier, while gm's share jumped to 50.7 percent from 48.8 percent a year earlier and chrysler's share grew to 15.5 percent from 14.3 percent a year earlier
gains by gm and chrysler were somewhat deceptive because both had weaker sales in mid-february 1986 than ford, and both have needed to use incentives more aggressively than ford this year, phillippi said
sales of u.s.-built cars fell 4.5 percent for honda motor co., 23.9 percent for volkswagen and 10.7 percent for nissan motor corp
toyota motor corp. sales of domestic cars rose 72.2 percent, continuing a buildup from 1987. toyota, like mazda motor corp., has only been building cars in the united states for a short time
mazda began u.s. production in the fall at its flat rock assembly plant
oil prices tumbled substantially today, reflecting growing market nervousness that world supplies are increasing too fast
at midday, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate, the benchmark u.s. crude, stood at $16.03 per 42-gallon barrel, down 43 cents from wednesday's close on the new york mercantile exchange
among march contracts for refined products, wholesale heating oil was selling at 45.45 cents a gallon, down 0.95 cent from wednesday, while unleaded gasoline stood at 45.45 cents per gallon, 0.90 cent lower
peter beutel, assistant director of the energy group at elders futures inc., said fundamental and technical factors were pushing the prices lower, with crude touching as little as $15.98 a barrel at one point before struggling back
opec is producing about 1 million barrels a day more than it was a month ago, and this perception is getting into the market _ which isn't thrilled by it,'' he said
recent estimates have put production by members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries close to 18 million barrels a day
beutel said the slide also picked up after crude broke below $16.37 a barrel, ``which had been seen as a very important support level.''
grain and soybean futures prices opened lower across the board today on the chicago board of trade
new rains in the major soybean-growing region of brazil prompted selling of u.s. soybean futures, analysts said. traders are watching the south american soybean crop closely as harvest time rapidly approaches
the thinking is that inevitably (u.s. soybean) prices will go down as these crops come in, unless we get some major improvement in demand, which is not likely,'' said walter spilka, an analyst for smith barney, harris upham &amp; co. in new york
corn futures failed to follow through on wednesday's gains, which were spurred by rumors of soviet purchases of u.s. corn
the agriculture department announced after the close of trading wednesday that the soviets had purchased 350,000 metric tons of u.s. corn, an amount that spilka said was ``not enough to carry the markets very far.''
wheat futures slipped lower on a lack of fresh supportive news, he said
