a former top editor of one of the world's most powerful newspapers has taken up a new challenge: to send people packing
harold evans, who resigned as editor of the times of london in 1982 in a dispute with owner rupert murdoch over editorial independence, has changed his itinerary to become editor in chief of a new travel magazine, conde nast's traveler
traveler, launched last fall by conde nast publications inc., a division of privately-owned newhouse newspapers, already prides itself in being different from the scores of other magazines aimed at the booming travel industry
it is hard-hitting _ in the tradition of fleet street, not madison avenue _ with pointed writing, vivid photographs, fold-out maps and offbeat humor
evans planned the magazine for conde nast starting in september 1986 _ following stints as editorial director of u.s. news &amp; world report and editor in chief of atlantic monthly press, a publishing company
the 59-year-old ``harry'' evans has put his personal stamp on traveler, which has a full-time staff of around 40 and claims a monthly circulation of some 900,000 copies. for starters, unlike traditional travel magazines, traveler doesn't allow its writers to accept free trips or accommodations
we pay our own way; the plan is to be truthful,'' evans said in an interview in his office on madison avenue. ``we print things without fear.''
that policy has generated, for example, an investigative article on airline safety and a report that 22 of 56 cruise liners failed recent inspections by the u.s. public health service
such ``truth in travel'' has already had repercussions. last november, after traveler printed a summary of a report by the world health organization on air pollution in more than 50 cities around the world, ads for varig brazilian airlines were pulled from the magazine
the advertising agency for varig, jonas berger associates, told traveler it cancelled the ads for brazil's national airline because it couldn't ``understand the logic in your telling your readers about the pollution problem in rio de janeiro.''
evans, in turn, fired off an unrepentant editorial. ``readers are tired of fluff and puff,'' he wrote. ``they know it's a big world where sometimes it's sunny and sometimes it rains. they want to be stimulated, but they want to explore and enjoy with all the facts and insights they can acquire.''
the editor's pull-no-punches approach has led traveler to take other strong editorial stands _ advocating, for instance, efforts to preserve wildlife in africa and natural beauty spots in the united states
the magazine's brash approach may have been emboldened by the built-in circulation it inherited from its predecessor, signature magazine. conde nast, a titan of magazine publishing, bought signature in january 1987 from citicorp diner's club for around $40 million _ then relaunched it as traveler last september
although traveler is a completely new product, it picked up a circulation of around 700,000 copies a month from the defunct signature
in its first four issues (from september through december of last year), traveler carried 198.5 advertising pages, bringing in around $4.2 million in ad revenues, according to figures compiled by the publishers information bureau
ronald galotti, traveler's publisher, said the magazine is aiming for more than 500 ad pages this year, which would translate into $12 million to $13 million in revenues. ``we're running very, very much on target,'' he said
travel &amp; leisure, a magazine owned by american express co. that is the dominant force in the travel field, carried around 1,227 pages last year fetching $38.5 million
evans seems to relish bridging the gap between his hard-knocks newspaper upbringing and the upscale world of magazines. at work, he is a whirling dervish of energy _ talking rapid-fire, punctuating his remarks by jumping up to pull out documents and magazines to illustrate his points, fretting over a technical production problem. he seems to have brought the high-tension level of a big-city newspaper to the normally more subdued environs of magazine publishing
a native of manchester in england's industrial north, he started in 1954 as a reporter for the manchester evening news and later became editor of the northern echo, a regional daily
evans is no stranger to this country. besides his more recent jobs with u.s. news and atlantic monthly, he spent 15 months here in 1984 on a journalism fellowship, advising and working on several small-town newspapers. he also was an adviser to gannett co. inc., which publishes usa today
he has encouraged offbeat humor in traveler _ like a guide to shoe-shopping in paris titled ``confessions of a shoe fetishist'' and a regular feature called ``room with a view'' profiling specific hotel rooms. october's was room 472 in the hotel splendido in portofino, italy, where elizabeth taylor and richard burton stayed in 1976
the magazine's style, with a breezy sophistication bordering on snobbishness, has prompted some critics in publishing circles to deride traveler as ``vanity fair goes to the beach.'' the editor in chief of vanity fair, another conde nast magazine that touts good writing, is tina brown _ who is married to evans. moved in advance.</note>
traveler, a new monthly magazine launched by conde nast publications inc., joins a crowded field of publications aiming to tap the booming u.s. market for travel and americans' growing fascination with jet-set lifestyles
americans spent a commanding $255 billion on domestic travel and another $24.5 billion on trips abroad in 1986, according to the u.s. travel data center in washington, d.c
the dominant magazine in the field, travel &amp; leisure (owned by american express co.), is being challenged by a legion of new or reincarnated rivals for advertising dollars
in the past two years, according to adweek magazine, the new york times has acquired and revamped southern travel, reader's digest has purchased travel@holiday, publishing tycoon rupert murdoch has taken over european travel &amp; life, and cbs inc.'s sale of its magazine division has put adventure travel in the hands of an investor group
other contenders include frequent flyer, connoisseur and national geographic. banana republic, a retail clothing chain owned by the gap inc., plans a safari into the field next month with a ``hip'' new quarterly called trips
foreign bankers are putting the finishing touches on secret bids for bonds offered by mexico in an innovative scheme to get rid of some of its enormous foreign debt of $105 billion
the question for mexico is how many of its approximately 560 creditor banks will submit bids under the program before the deadline at 4 p.m. est friday
the plan was devised by the mexican and u.s. governments to try to reduce mexico's heavy debt burden, the second highest in the developing world after brazil
christine bindert, senior vice president at the investment firm of shearson lehman brothers inc. in new york, said the program ``should be fairly successful with a lot of participation, particularly from european and (u.s.) regional banks.''
the big money center banks in the united states, though, were expected to shun the program
they're bound to get some takers,'' said a european banker in mexico city, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``the question is: how many, and at what price?''
the new program involves exchanging some of the debt mexico owes foreign commercial bankers for new, 20-year bonds that will be issued by the government
the bonds, which will be backed by $10 billion worth of special u.s. treasury securities, will carry a higher interest rate than mexico is paying on the old debt
analysts doubt the government will be able to market the entire $10 billion package. mexican officials, they say, would like to sell at least $3 billion of the securities
the success of the program hinges on the sticky question of how much the banks are willing to take for their old loans. in early february, mexican debt was selling for about 48 cents on the dollar in the secondary market
in the auction, the bankers will try to get as much money as they can for their old loans, while mexico will want to buy the debt cheaply
analysts predict the average discount rate will range from 60 cents to 70 cents on the dollar
some banks have expressed concern about the program because they are unhappy that mexico will still get loans at 100 percent of their value while paying back, through the new program, its old loans at less than that
they also are reluctant to accept losses on the loans and worry about government regulations concerning accounting for the losses on their books
mexico's treasury secretary, gustavo petricioli, recently asked u.s. officials to give ``the most favorable treatment possible'' to banks taking part
the program will let mexico retire part of its foreign debt for less than face value and slice the $8 billion or so annual interest fee on the debt
the banks are submitting sealed bids to j.p. morgan &amp; co., the new york banking company acting as exchange agent for the deal. morgan said earlier this week that it had already received some offers, but it declined to release any details
mexico is expected to announce next week how many _ if any _ bonds will be issued. officials have said that if the offers are not good enough, they may reject all of them
as the deadline neared this week, many bankers were reluctant to say if they would bid
we're still studying the program in terms of our own participation,'' said james h. mitchell, spokesman for bank of america in san francisco
in london, none of britain's big four commercial banks would say whether they planned to bid
we haven't said what we're going to do,'' said an official at lloyds bank. added an official at national westminster bank, ``our decision hasn't been made yet.'' both demanded anonymity
analysts expect smaller banks, worried about holding mexican debt, to use the program as a way to get out of international lending
the chairman of britain's midland bank, sir kit mcmahon, found the plan inappropriate for banks wanting to remain in the business because it involves explicitly accepting that the debt is worth less than its face value, a spokesman said
that echoed comments by john reed, chairman of citicorp, the biggest bank-holding company in the united states. ``we're long-term lenders, and we're happy with our portfolio,'' he said
the bonds being offered are good ideas for banks who want to get out of lending to latin america and provide a good way for those institutions to lower their exposure to third world countries,'' reed told the new york times
however, west germany's largest bank, the deutsche bank, said it would bid for the bonds
there had been so many proposals to solve this problem,'' said spokesman hans dettmar. ``finally this plan comes up. it's a new approach, and we want to see how it works.''
japanese banks also were close-mouthed about their plans
in tokyo, an official of a major bank said no decision had yet been made. ``but i think that even if we do participate, it will not be in a very aggressive manner,'' he said, demanding anonymity
