a conrail engineer convicted of manslaughter after a train crash that killed 16 people said today drug and alcohol abuse are a major problem in the railroad industry and random testing of rail workers is needed
i believe that random drug and alcohol testing is the appropriate response to an industry-wide problem,'' the engineer, ricky l. gates, said in testimony to the senate commerce committee
gates has pleaded guilty to manslaughter in the jan. 4, 1987, crash in which the conrail locomotive he was driving slammed into a crowded amtrak train near chase, md. sixteen people were killed and 175 were hurt in the crash
gates has admitted he smoked marijuana shortly before the accident. the national transportation safety board has said that marijuana use by gates and his brakeman, edward w. cromwell, was the primary cause of the accident
while the act of using the marijuana contributed to his inattentiveness, there is no proof that mr. gates was impaired,'' one of gates' lawyers, donna shearer, said in testimony for the senate committee
i cannot begin to imagine the pain and grief i have caused those touched by the accident,'' said the statement by gates, who faces sentencing march 29. ``i am sorry.''
gates said railroad management ``often looks the other way'' when a worker has a drug or alcohol problem. ``i know this because once when i was called to work ... i told the dispatcher that i was intoxicated and could not work,'' he said. ``i was told if i did not report i would be cited for refusing duty.''
i believe that drug and alcohol use is widespread in the industry,'' gates said
conrail spokesman pat linsky said the railroad was studying gates' remarks, and would have no immediate comment
the senate last year approved legislation that would require various types of drug and alcohol testing of rail, airline, trucking and bus company employees. but the house has yet to act on similar legislation
the most controversial type of testing proposed is random testing of transportation workers. supporters say random testing is the only true deterrent to drug and alcohol abuse, while opponents say such testing is an invasion of privacy and is often inaccurate
earlier this month, a federal court in san francisco ruled that testing rail workers involved in accidents based on a suspicion that they had recently used drugs or alcohol is illegal
sen. ernest hollings, d-s.c., chairman of the senate panel, expressed frustration that the house has so far not approved a bill requiring drug and alcohol testing of transportation workers
no one has a constitutional right to drive under the influence, or fly under the influence,'' he said
