assets of the nation's 418 money market mutual funds climbed $2.56 billion in the latest week to a record high level of nearly $280 billion, the investment company institute said thursday
the rise, to $279.99 billion in the seven-day period ended wednesday, followed a revised $608 million decline in the funds' assets the previous week, according to the washington-based mutual fund trade group
the previous week's decline had originally been reported as $1.19 billion
the latest gain leaves the fund's assets at their highest level ever, surpassing the previous high mark of $278.04 billion in the week ended feb. 10
the investment company institute said that in the latest week, assets of 208 general purpose funds fell $522.8 million to $81.44 billion, assets of 97 broker-dealer funds rose $1.07 billion to $115.52 billion and assets of 113 institutional funds jumped $2.01 billion to $83.02 billion
the seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in the week ended tuesday to 6.16 percent from 6.14 percent the previous week, according to donoghue's money fund report, a trade journal based in holliston, mass
the 30-day average yield fell, to 6.23 percent from 6.28 percent, donoghue's said
the average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 43 days, up from 42 days, donoghue's said
separately, the newsletter bank rate monitor said its survey of 100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield available on money market accounts slipped to 5.75 percent as of wednesday from 5.76 percent a week earlier
the north palm beach, fla.-based newsletter said the effective annual yield available on special savings accounts, called super now accounts, was unchanged from the previous week at 5.17 percent
bank rate monitor said the effective annual yield was 6.88 percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 6.92 the previous week. yields were 7.20 percent on 1-year cds, down from 7.23 percent; 7.62 percent on 2{-year cds, down from 7.64 percent; and 8.08 percent on 5-year cds, down from 8.10 percent
