usg corp. kept quiet thursday about two texas oilmen's $1.96 billion takeover attempt of the nation's largest producer of gypsum, an important building material
at this time, we have nothing to say on any aspect of this,'' said paul colitti, a spokesman for chicago-based usg
desert partners l.p., controlled by oilmen cyril wagner jr. and jack e. brown, said wednesday it would pay $42 a share in cash for at least 21.5 million common shares, or less than half the total shares outstanding
the rest of the shares would be exchanged for subordinated debt securities and warrants valued by desert partners at $42 a share
analysts didn't give the proposal much chance of success because of usg's previously stated desire to avoid dealing with wagner and brown, takeover strategists who have made forays against several companies
some suggested the partners might be seeking a way to increase the value of their 9.9 percent stake in the company, purchased last fall at between $44 and $45 a share, so they could sell it with minimal loss
investor reaction to the bid was skeptical. usg's stock, which rose $4.62{ wednesday to $37 in composite new york stock exchange trading, fell back to $35.87{ thursday
in a letter to robert j. day, usg chairman and chief executive officer, desert partners said it is genuinely interested in acquiring the company and will refuse to accept ``greenmail'' _ the purchase of its usg stock at a premium over the market price _ from usg
the company produces gypsum and gypsum-related products in about 100 plants nationwide. gypsum is a mineral component of plaster and other building materials
we're hopeful, now that we've made a specific proposal, that usg's board, recognizing its fiduciary responsibilities, will give it serious consideration,'' said joel reed, president of a desert partners subsidiary formed to try to acquire usg
in november, usg senior management said it had no interest in participating in a buyout of the company with desert partners
the latest proposal came after a federal judge in chicago on monday blocked usg's request to permanently bar desert partners from buying additional usg shares
last week, mesa limited partners, headed by corporate raider t. boone pickens, disclosed its 1.5 percent stake in usg
several years ago, wagner and brown teamed with pickens in a number of takeover attempts, but desert partners has denied that the parties have joined to gain control of usg this time
in its letter, desert partners said it has invested about $225 million, or about $44.30 a share, to accumulate its stake in usg. the partnership owns about 5.08 million common shares. update on analysts' estimate</note>
eastman kodak co., under fire for purportedly overpaying in its $5.1 billion acquisition of sterling drug inc., said thursday it expects to earn profits ``well in excess'' of the amount predicted by wall street analysts
the effort to whip up enthusiasm fell short. kodak was the most actively traded issue on the new york stock exchange thursday but managed to rise only 62{ cents a share to $42. the stock had traded at $49.12{ just before the sterling deal was announced
analysts had lowered their 1988 earnings projections for kodak by about 35 cents a share since jan. 1, prompted mainly by kodak's announcement last month of the agreement to buy sterling, the new york-based maker of bayer aspirin, lysol cleaner and prescription drugs
based on what we have learned from sterling and what we know about kodak, we believe that reduction can be put back into analysts' estimates,'' kodak president kay r. whitmore said in a prepared statement
we're very optimistic about the future,'' the president added in an interview
kodak did not speak out on sterling until this week because its tender offer for sterling shares was still pending. the offer expired monday and kodak is mopping up the final details of the acquisition
analysts who follow rochester, n.y.-based kodak had continued to cut their earnings estimates as recently as wednesday
on thursday, analyst eugene glazer of dean witter reynolds inc. said kodak seemed to be trying to convince analysts that the company would earn $4 a share or more in profit in 1987. he said he was likely to raise his own estimate of $3.85 a share
last year operating earnings were about $6.31 a share, although various special charges reduced net earnings to $3.52 a share
the heavy load of debt kodak took on to finance the sterling purchase helped convince both standard &amp; poor's corp. and moody's investors service to lower their credit ratings on the company to the lowest levels in its modern history
kodak has run into other troubles recently:
_polaroid corp. disclosed that it is seeking $5.7 billion in damages for kodak's infringement on its instant photography patents
_a federal judge issued a temporary injunction blocking kodak's merger of its photofinishing operations with the colorcraft corp. photofinishing operations of fuqua industries inc
_kodak admitted that its innovative 9-volt lithium batteries, which were supposed to have a shelf life of 10 years, don't last that long
whitmore said the purchase of sterling was consistent with kodak's strategy for chemical sciences, would give the company a ``highly profitable revenue stream'' and offers opportunities for cutting costs by eliminating overlaps
so _ recognizing what we're receiving _ the price we paid is competitive, fair and indicative of sterling's inherent value to us,'' whitmore said in his prepared remarks
we now expect that the earnings we report for 1988 will meet or exceed (wall) street's pre-merger consensus, even after taking into account the dilutive effect of the sterling merger,'' whitmore said
britoil plc on thursday dropped resistance to british petroleum co. plc's $4.4 billion takeover offer for the north sea oil company even though britoil still believes the price is inadequate
britoil's board of directors said it was advising shareholders to accept the offer of $8.80 a share for britoil's 504 million shares outstanding
the britoil board had vigorously opposed the company's takeover by bp, which controls 81 percent of britoil's stock
the government announced on tuesday that it wouldn't use its special share in britoil to block the offer, as long as bp kept promises to meet certain conditions
among them were that bp would maintain the headquarters for some of britoil's operations in glasgow, scotland
the government had retained the special share _ which gives it the veto power over the company's affairs _ when it privatized britoil in two stages in 1985 and 1982
britoil chairman sir philip shelbourne said in a letter to shareholders: ``your board continues to believe that 500 pence ($8.80) represents an inadequate price for an ordinary share in britoil, but there are now considerable uncertainties confronting shareholders who might wish to remain a minority in britoil.''
he said the continued listing of the company's shares could not be guaranteed and that the market value of the shares would likely fall after the bp offer closes
the offer currently is open indefinitely
britoil's shares finished unchanged at 498 pence or $8.76 on the london stock exchange thursday
the nation's basic money supply fell $1.1 billion in mid february, while two broader measures, m2 and m3, rose by $6.3 billion and $11.7 billion respectively, the federal reserve board reported thursday
the fed said m1 fell to a seasonally adjusted $759.9 billion in the week ended feb. 17 from $761 billion the previous week. m1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks
for the latest 13 weeks, m1 averaged $755.4 billion, a 2.1 percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 weeks
since early 1987, the fed has not set a specific target range for m1 growth because of ``uncertainties about its underlying relationship to the behavior of the economy and its sensitivity to a variety of economic and financial circumstances and assumptions.''
m2, made up of m1 and such accounts as savings deposits and money-market mutual funds, rose to a seasonally adjusted average of $2,945.7 billion in the week ended feb. 17. this compared with a revised $2,939.4 billion the previous week, which was originally reported as $2,939.9, the fed said
for the latest 13 weeks, it averaged $2,915.8 billion, growing at a 4.1 percent rate of gain
m3, the sum of m2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000, rose to a seasonally adjusted average of $3,722.7 billion in the same period
this compared with a revised $3,711 billion in the previous week, which originally reported as $3,712 billion, the fed said
for the latest 13 weeks, m3 has averaged $3,680 billion, growing at a 5.1 percent rate of gain from the week earlier, the fed said
the fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for ms and m3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent
analysts warned that it is difficult to draw short-term conclusions about the meaning of the three figures, because they are inclined to be volatile on a week-to-week basis
beth reiners, an analyst at the dean witter reynolds securities firm, said the data were mainly in line with the company's expectations, and had no impact on the bond market
in other reports:
_the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and industrial loans at major new york city banks rose $433 million in the week ended feb. 17, compared with a decline of $368 million a week earlier
_the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal reserve system averaged $132 million a day in the week ended wednesday, down from $254 million in the previous week
_the federal reserve bank of st. louis reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $272.3 billion in the two-week period ended wednesday, up from $272.1 billion two weeks earlier
the dollar turned in a narrowly mixed performance thursday on the world's foreign-exchange markets, slipping against major currencies in u.s. trading after edging up against most of them in dealings in europe
gold prices edged up in new york after falling sharply in europe
republic national bank of new york quoted a late bid price for gold of $433 a troy ounce, up 20 cents from wednesday's late bid
the dollar rose in europe on expectations that the u.s. government would revise its estimate of growth in the gross national product for the fourth quarter of 1987 to 5 percent from 4.2 percent
but the report, released in the middle of the european trading day, put the latest estimate of fourth-quarter economic growth at 4.5 percent
as a result, the dollar turned lower, finishing the day in new york at lower levels than it traded at late wednesday
dan holland, a vice president at discount corp. in new york, said some traders bought dollars before the trade report was released because they interpreted president reagan's comments on the economy at a news conference wednesday night as indicating growth had been stronger than expected
but, he said, once the report was released and the revision was only modest, some dollar traders sold the u.s. currency
jack barbanel, senior vice president at gruntal &amp; co., said the dollar took its cues from the bond market where a rally faltered at midday
there is a considerable amount of confusion in the financial markets'' about the strength of the econonmy, he said
in tokyo, where trading ends before europe's business day begins, the dollar rose 0.05 japanese yen to close at 128.80 yen. later, in london, it was quoted at 128.67 yen. in new york, the dollar slipped to 128.425 yen from 128.82 yen late wednesday
in london, the dollar slipped against the british pound, which rose to $1.7665 from $1.7640 late wednesday. the dollar also slipped against the pound in new york, where sterling rose to $1.76725 from $1.76355 late wednesday
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late rates wednesday, included: 1.6930 west german marks, down from 1.69575; 1.39215 swiss francs, down from 1.39535; 5.7285 french francs, down from 5.7340; 1,247 italian lire, down from 1,248; and 1.26495 canadian dollars, down from 1.26505
late dollar rates in europe, compared with late rates wednesday, included: 1.6945 west german marks, up from 1.6925; 1.3935 swiss francs, up from 1.3908; 5.7315 french francs, up from 5.7240; 1.9020 dutch guilders, up from 1.8990; 1,248.25 italian lire, up from 1,246.25; and 1.2650 canadian dollars, down from 1.2651
gold prices edged up in the united states after tumbling in asia and europe
on the commodity exchange in new york, gold for current delivery rose $1.30 a troy ounce to $433.20
in london, gold fell to $428 per troy ounce from $434.70 late wednesday. in zurich, switzerland, gold fell to $433 an ounce from $434.70 late wednesday
earlier, in hong kong, gold fell $7.85 an ounce to close at $436.35
silver bullion prices fell on the london market where the metal was trading at $6.15 a troy ounce, compared with $6.26 late wednesday
on new york's comex, silver for current delivery rose 5.3 cents an ounce to $6.243
the federal communications commission on thursday signaled to foreign governments that the united states remains concerned about markets that have been closed or severely limited to u.s. telecommunications manufacturers
the fcc stopped short of taking action that would reciprocally exclude or limit foreign-owned companies from participating in the u.s. market, though chairman dennis r. patrick said such measures ``are still very much open, very much alive'' at the commission
the fcc said it needs more information on the trade imbalance and ordered large long-distance and local phone companies to report annually to the agency on big equipment purchases, including switches and transmission equipment
by seeking this information we in no way imply an opposition to foreign participation in u.s. markets,'' said fcc chairman dennis r. patrick. ``we believe in the economic utility of free trade and in the proposition that, through that free trade, consumers in the united states benefit by access to goods and services that are provided by concerns around the world
however, we also believe in the principle of reciprocity and there ought to be equally open markets in other parts of the world,'' he said
the u.s. telecommunications equipment trade deficit is about $2 billion annually, the fcc said
japan, germany and france are among the countries whose telecommunications trade policies have contributed heavily to the deficit
the fcc will require annual reports from the country's seven largest long-distance companies as well as the local bell and large independent companies. it also will require interstate carriers that are 15 percent or more owned by foreign interests to file annual revenue and traffic reports
the reporting requirements were proposed in december 1986 by then-chairman mark s. fowler. at the time, the commission also sought comments on steps the fcc could take in pressuring foreign countries to open their markets
fowler, now in private law practice in washington, said there is no need at this time to change u.s. trade policy in reaction to closed foreign markets, but ``by leaving the question open, there's the spectre of further government action.''
his intention in initiating the proposal was to put foreign governments on notice of the u.s. concerns, he said
the only way we could get some countries' attention was to hit them over the head with a threat,'' he said, adding, ``there's more utility in making the threat than in implenting it.''
northwest airlines and flight attendants bargained intensively thursday to avert a weekend strike, but a union representing the workers said a walkout appeared likely
there's a 100 percent chance of a strike,'' said william genoese, director of the international brotherhood of teamsters airline division. ``as far as i'm concerned we're on a collision course with northwest airlines to strike.''
flight attendants were preparing to strike at midnight friday if an agreement wasn't reached
airline spokesman redmond tyler said progress is being made on some major contract issues. the two sides have been meeting since tuesday at northwest's world headquarters with the assistance of a federal mediator, tyler said
senority wage scales, pensions and work rules are among the major issues in the dispute. former republic airlines flight attendants have been working under their old contract since northwest acquired republic in 1986. the company is trying to bring the workers under one contract
we believe we're making substantial progress at the bargaining table,'' tyler said. ``we're not jimmy the greek, but we continue to believe that we will get this resolved without a strike.''
the national president of the international association of machinists has vowed his union's support of the flight attendants, but stopped short of saying machinists would honor picket lines. officials at national and local iam offices did not return telephone calls for clarification
tyler said machinists are under a contract that forbids them to strike in sympathy with another union. ``we expect our machinists to honor their contract,'' he said
pilots are forbidden from sympathy strikes under provisions of the railway labor act, tyler said
asked if those workers would be lockd out if they walk off their jobs in sympathy with the flight attendants, tyler said, ``we won't address that because we don't want to play that `what if?' game.''
genoese said flight attendants would have the full backing of the international teamsters, which could result in delays of supply shipments from truckers
industry analysts were skeptical of the teamsters power to disrupt northwest. anthony hatch, an airline industry analyst for argus research of new york, said genoese is ``overblowing the role the teamsters play in an airline.''
it's pilots and machinists that shut down an airline and nothing else,'' hatch said
tyler said the airline is armed with about 2,000 management workers who are certified as flight attendants to step if the 6,700 union flight attendants strike
domestic automakers were scheduled to produce 211,513 cars and trucks this week, down from last week's 219,021, ward's automotive reports said thursday
automakers produced 252,785 cars and trucks during the same week a year ago. they were were scheduled to make 126,984 cars this week, compared with 133,536 a week ago and 174,075 in the same week in 1987
truck production for the week was scheduled at 84,529, compared with last week's 85,485 and last year's 78,710
canadian automakers were to build 20,800 cars this week, compared with 22,786 last week and 17,012 in the same week last year. canadian truck production was scheduled at 17,985, compared with 18,385 last week and 17,886 in the same week last year. buyouts</head> pritzker. picks up 15th graf, genoese said...</note>
the teamsters union considers employee-led buyouts of airlines and other companies as part of its ``global strategy,'' but has no concrete buyout proposals, the president of the teamsters airline division said thursday
william genoese, responding to questions at a news conference, said the union was studying the possibility of leveraged buyouts or friendly takeovers of pan american world airways, northwest airlines and usair
but he characterized any employee-led buyouts as mere possibilities under the teamsters' long-term strategy rather than as certainties
also, two investment bankers mentioned by genoese said they were not working on any airline takeover proposals with the teamsters
genoese said discussion of union-led buyouts was not a ploy, but he conceded that ``the threat of it will help you in negotiations.''
negotiations between pan am and the teamsters, which represents 4,500 pan am ground employees in 14 cities, over $35 million in concessions broke down on sunday
although the union had set a strike deadline for that night, its members have continued reporting to work. genoese has said a strike remains possible and has threatened to disrupt pan am ground operations
pan am has said it needed a total of about $540 million in concessions from all its unionized employees during the next three years to ensure its survival
northwest is negotiating with its flight attendants on a new contract an faces a midnight est friday strike deadline. genoese spoke at a news conference about the likelihood of a strike by northwest attendants, who also are represented by the teamsters
genoese said he had spoken recently with experts at the investment firms of salomon brothers inc. and drexel burnham lambert inc. about how to finance airline buyouts
drexel was an adviser to the coalition of four pan am unions that unsuccessfully attempted to find a buyer for the financially troubled airline last year, but says it has not dealt exclusively with the teamsters in that regard
robert salomon, a managing director of salomon brothers, said he was unaware of any contact between the teamsters and salomon regarding airline buyouts
genoese also said he had spoken monday with jay pritzker, chairman of braniff inc., about a possible joint bid for pan am. braniff in january dropped a proposal to acquire major elements of pan am corp., the airline's parent, after the pan am pilots union decided to oppose the plan, which called for $800 million in wage concessions over four years from the company's unions
pritzker, through a spokeswoman at his chicago office, declined to comment
genoese said that by considering employee-led buyouts the union simply was examining the same financing techniques used by wall street takeover artists
you can do the financial end as well as (takeover strategist) carl icahn and be good to the people,'' genoese said. ``you're going to see some of these moves pretty soon in the papers.''
coffee futures prices fell sharply thursday, reversing a five-month trend on speculation that a tight supply situation may soon ease, analysts said
on other markets, energy futures prices dropped; grains and soybeans moved lower; precious metals gained slightly; livestock and meat futures were mostly higher; and stock-index futures retreated
coffee contracts on new york's coffee, sugar &amp; cocoa exchange lost as much as 2.87 cents a pound as the executive committee of the international coffee organzation opened a two-day meeting in london
at that meeting, delegates from consumer nations complained of slow shipments of high-quality beans from producer nations and claimed some producer nations had sold coffee at discounted prices to non-member nations, said sandra kaul, an analyst in new york for shearson lehman hutton inc
the apparent willingess of some producers to sell coffee at a discount, along with news that colombia had begun registering coffee for export in april, suggests an easing of supplies, ms. kaul said
this indicates that the short-term supply situation that pushed the market up so sharply is about to come to an end at the same time that seasonal demand eases,'' she said
in addition, analyst kim badenhop of prudential-bache securities noted that coffee prices were nearing levels that could trigger a relaxation of ico export quotas and increase shipments
coffee settled 2 cents to 2.87 cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $1.3829 a pound
crude oil futures slipped below $16 a barrel while gasoline and heating oil prices fell sharply on the new york mercantile exchange
a department of energy report issued wednesday showing an 8.5-million-barrel increase in u.s. oil stocks triggered the sell-off, said bob baker, an analyst for prudential-bache securities inc
but peter beutel of elders futures inc. linked the price decline to perceptions of rising oil production by opec members
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 40 cents to 50 cents lower with february at $15.36 a barrel; heating oil was 1.18 cents to 1.25 cents lower with march at 45.22 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .98 cent to 1.10 cents lower with march at 45.37 cents a gallon
indications that the brazilian soybean crop may be larger than expected sent u.s. soybean futures prices down sharply on the chicago board of trade. most grain futures declined slightly
soybean futures opened lower on news that rain had eased dry conditions in the soybean-growing region of brazil. later in the morning, the brazilian institute of geography and statistics estimated the impending harvest would yield 19.4 million metric tons, significantly higher than the u.s. agriculture department's latest estimate of 18.5 million metric tons
this estimate was obviously negative for the u.s. market, and it took off any rallying attempt the beans might have had,'' said walter spilka, an analyst in new york for smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
