the precious metals are caught in tug-of-war between bulls who believe inflation is set to rise and bears who feel a recession is near, said jack barbanel, an analyst for gruntal &amp; co
it's a very volatile marketplace,'' he said
gold settled 60 cents to $1.30 higher with april at $434.70 a troy ounce; silver was 4.9 cents to 5.2 cents higher with march at $6.245 a troy ounce
most livestock and meat futures advanced on the chicago mercantile exchange
the cattle market was choppy but ended higher on improved demand from packers, while pork prices rose on expectations for stronger cash markets next week, said philip stanley, an analyst in chicago for thomson mckinnon securities inc
live cattle settled .20 cent to .40 cent higher with april at 72.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .25 cent higher with march at 80.67 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .25 cent higher with april at 44.12 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .12 cent to .60 cent higher with march at 52.57 cents a pound
stock-index futures retreated on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 2.35 points lower at 262.85. the underlying spot index was down 2.86 points at 261.58
hundreds of angry, sign-waving workers protesting the possible sale of chrysler corp.'s parts-making division gathered outside company headquarters thursday shouting ``strike! strike!.'' ``you do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,'' united auto workers union vice president marc stepp told more than 1,000 workers who marched in windy, 20-degree weather for more than two hours
chrysler chairman lee iacocca has said chrysler is considering selling its 28,000-worker, $1 billion acustar inc. parts-making subsidiary and may announce a decision next month
the union is trying to pressure chrysler into retreating from the sale, which stepp said threatens the job security of all chrysler workers and is further damaging chrysler's already injured labor relations
besides potential strikes over local issues at key plants that could shut chrysler down, local leaders said they will stop cooperating in programs aimed at improving quality and efficiency
chrysler spokesman doug nicoll said chrysler had no immediate comment
acustar, which has plants in mexico and canada as well as the united states, represents nearly a fifth of chrysler's worldwide operations, already the leanest among the big three u.s. automakers
chrysler has said it may sell acustar because it doesn't want to invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. chrysler already buys 70 percent of its parts elsewhere
before the demonstration, stepp met in detroit with the 140-member chrysler national bargaining council, which represents all of chrysler's 49 uaw locals, and about 100 others who came to listen
the union cannot legally call a national strike over the sale of acustar. but stepp said he told the council he will authorize locals to strike on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved issues such as health and safety grievances
at least seven chrysler locals already have voted to ask for authorization and one, at chrysler's key 4,000-worker stamping plant in sterling heights, will receive permission as early as next week, stepp said
other locals are gathering grievances and preparing to take strike votes and seek national authorization. if disputes aren't resolved, local unions may strike seven days after they receive authorization
the council unanimously passed a resolution calling for suspension of all joint labor-management programs, including special team-concept agreements at six plants, that require trust and cooperation
workers say they are angry at the possible sale because they made concessions and helped iacocca win loan guarantees from the federal government to rescue the company from the verge of bankruptcy eight years ago
let this be a lesson to all america, to trade unionists everywhere, if you think you can work out some cooperative programs to generate trust with this corporation, forget it, because you can't,'' stepp told the protesters. correct that coniston is a partnership, update with final stock price. picks up 8th graf pvs: analysts believe ...</note>
gillette co. urged its stockholders thursday to resist an attempt by coniston partners to seize four seats on gillette's board of directors
coniston wants gillette to boost the value of its stock, by selling itself to another company, or selling off its assets piecemeal or restructuring its finances. gillette chairman colman m. mockler jr. asked stockholders not to sign proxy cards being distributed by coniston, which controls a roughly 6 percent stake in the consumer products maker
the board of directors believes the stated intentions and suggestions of this group are not in the best interests of your company and intends to oppose the group's actions vigorously,'' a letter from mockler to stockholders said
coniston, a new york investment partnership, announced earlier this month that it was approaching potential buyers of the boston-based company and might take other moves to boost gillette's share price
the firm last week nominated four candidates for the seats on the 12-member board of directors up for election at gillette's annual meeting april 21. stockholders as of march 7 will be eligible to take part in the board vote
this letter is essentially a stop, look and listen letter,'' gillette spokesman dick gauthier said
gillette stock fell $1.37{ a share to $39.87{ thursday in consolidated new york stock exchange trading
analysts believe gillette's recent stock price is well below the high-$40 to low-$50 range estimated as its acquisition value. the company late last year rejected a $47-a-share, $5.4 billion buyout offer from revlon group inc., which has bid for gillette since 1986
the company reported a 12 percent rise in sales and doubling in operating profits last year
gus oliver, a general partner in coniston, said thursday the company stood by its position that the proxy fight was necessary because gillette's takeover defenses meant the board had power to accept or reject any merger offers
he criticized mockler's letter but said: ``i think it's to be expected from this particular management and board of directors.''
the letter said gillette would ``act vigorously'' to resist attempts by coniston to gain a greater stake in the independent company, known for its personal products such as razor blades and pens
the board regrets that a costly proxy contest for the control of the direction of your company may develop, particularly at the time when the company is starting to realize many of the ongoing benefits of its restructuring activity,'' the letter said
coniston sucessfully waged a similar strategy of ``strategic block investing'' last year that led to the break-up of allegis corp
your board of directors believes that this is but a catch phrase for trying to force the sale or dismemberment of companies in which coniston takes positions,'' mockler said
from what little is publicly known about coniston partners, neither it nor its partners have any direct experience in managing or running an international consumer products firm.''
gillette reported net income of $229.9 million on sales of $3.17 billion for 1987 compared with net income of $15.8 million on sales of $2.82 billion in 1986. the 1986 figures included a special charge of $165.3 million
excluding the charge, gillette reported earnings per share of $2 last year compared with $1.42 in 1986
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan has warned the reagan administration that further attempts to pressure the central bank to lower interest rates could boomerang
greenspan's warning came wednesday as the administration sought to dampen its dispute with the fed. beryl sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said the administration is ``delighted with monetary policy.''
at issue is a critical letter sent by assistant treasury secretary michael darby to top fed policy-makers 10 days before they were to meet to set 1988 monetary growth targets
the nation's record trade deficit shrank in the final quarter of 1987 as u.s. exports climbed 6 percent to record levels, the commerce department says
while narrowing just $200 million from the summer, the deficit's decline to $40.2 billion on a balance-of-payments basis marked the first quarterly improvement since the spring of 1986, the department said wednesday
robert ortner, undersecretary of commerce for economic affairs, said further improvements were likely
sales of domestically made cars and light trucks jumped 14.5 percent in mid-february from a year earlier despite cold weather that could have kept some buyers out of showrooms, automakers said
total domestic car sales rose 11.9 percent in the nine selling days from feb. 11-20, while domestic truck sales jumped 19.6 percent, the automakers reported wednesday
general motors corp., ford motor co. and chrysler corp. reported healthy increases in sales, which were not shared by most foreign-based automakers
general motors corp. has boosted 1988 production plans by 175,000 cars and trucks and will recall 8,600 laid-off workers and reopen a temporarily closed assembly plant
the strengthening demand for gm vehicles reflects the ongoing product quality improvements resulting from plant modernization and employee involvement programs,'' gm president robert stempel stated wednesday
gm will increase production by running some plants, particularly for trucks, on overtime; restoring second shifts at two u.s. plants and one in canada; and reopening its closed framingham, mass., assembly plant
santa fe southern pacific corp. has rejected henley group inc.'s latest offer to buy a controlling interest in the company
santa fe said wednesday that the proposal would give henley an effective controlling stake in the company without having to pay a premium to other shareholders
henley, which holds a 15.7 percent stake in santa fe, offered monday to buy 44.6 million new shares for $780 million if the chicago company would abandon its ``poison pill'' takeover defense and restructure a $4.7 billion special dividend to stockholders
dart group corp. says it will continue a $1.03 billion hostile takeover bid for stop &amp; shop cos. inc., which is negotiating with several other potential buyers
stop &amp; shop confirmed wednesday it had begun talks with several parties considering a buyout of the supermarket and discount store chain, raising the possibility it might find a ``white knight'' friendly suitor to thwart dart
sandy bouzoukis, a stop &amp; shop spokeswoman, declined to name the parties interested
the federal communications commission on thursday voted to extend through 1989 american telephone &amp; telegraph co.'s 12.2 percent authorized rate of return on its regulated interstate operations
the fcc also decided to extend the 12 percent rate of return that local telephone companies can earn on the payments they receive from long-distance companies for providing access to the local networks
the fcc had set those rates in august 1986 to cover the calendar years 1987 and 1988. the commission voted 3-0 to extend the rates for a third year because economic conditions are about the same today as they were when the rates were set two years ago
fcc chairman dennis r. patrick said the extension would also add stability to phone rates and give the commission more time to refine the formula for determining appropriate rates of return
gerald brock, the fcc's top telephone staff official, said the action has ``no direct effect'' on the commission's proposal to replace rate-of-return regulation of at&amp;t and the local bell phone companies with a cap on the rates they can charge
the agency proposed a broad rate-cap plan last august and, under pressure from congress, said recently it will propose a more specific plan, probably this spring
under the current form of regulation, the fcc sets the profit level it will allow for phone companies under its jurisdiction and allows that target to be met over a period of time
a federal appeals court earlier this year struck down the fcc's rules for ordering refunds by companies that exceed their authorized rate of return because the rules didn't permit companies that earn less than the allowed rate to recoup any shortfalls
the court invited the agency to fashion a new refund policy, but the fcc has not yet responded
